A9590 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-DEMS-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      08-12 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DEMS-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Will Clinton steal show from Gore?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By DAVID IVANOVICH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the nation's first couple, President Clinton
and his wife, Hillary, have turned heads for eight years, upstaging
just about everybody in their path.
</P>
<P>
   But as the two arrived here Friday in advance of the Democratic
National Convention, critics warned that the Clintons' star power
threatened to steal the attention, confuse the message and even
lure the campaign dollars away from Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to raise millions of dollars in cash for both the Clinton
presidential library and Mrs. Clinton's New York senatorial race,
the Clintons will rub shoulders tonight with Hollywood luminaries
ranging from Cher to Gregory Peck in tony Brentwood, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, they are slated to attend a brunch hosted by
entertainment diva Barbra Streisand, the New York Times and other
news outlets have reported. The brunch, however, does not appear on
the president's official schedule, and White House officials
professed no knowledge of the event.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday evening, Hillary appeared on NBC's Tonight Show with
Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons are demonstrating their well-known fondness for
Hollywood, political analysts say, at a time when Gore appears to
be trying to distance himself from the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's vice-presidential running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., has long been a critic of Hollywood mores, while Gore's
wife, Tipper, took on the entertainment industry back in the 1980s
with a campaign to get record companies to warn parents about their
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the Clintons are luring away money that might come
to the Gore campaign's coffers, while confusing the Democrats'
message just days before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, these two are the very personification of
selfishness,'' said Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the
University of Virginia. ``They have three concerns: me, myself and
I.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Black, a professor of American politics at Rice University,
agreed the Clintons appear to be ``using this as an opportunity to
pursue their particular interests ... rather than letting Gore take
advantage of the opportunities that are presented by his
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart, speaking aboard Air Force
One en route to Los Angeles Friday, tried to downplay talk of
competition between the Clinton and Gore camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a natural shift after the convention by you guys (the
news media) _ not necessarily by us _ that moves to the
candidates,'' Lockhart said. ``We're sensitive to that, but there
(are) still things that we are going to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, both Mrs. Clinton and the president will speak at the
convention. And then on Tuesday, Clinton and Gore will meet in
Michigan for what campaign organizers are calling a ``symbolic
passing of the baton.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane shrugged off suggestions that
Clinton was making it harder for Gore to take full advantage of the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is always in the spotlight. The president is
going to say what he is going to say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato argues that in the Gore camp ``they must be seething. I
suspect many of the Gore team will turn out at the airport to wish
them a fond farewell.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons, of course, are in unique circumstances. Mrs.
Clinton is the first first lady to seek public office on her own as
her husband was vacating the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton did try to deflect criticism of Gore in the wake of
the Monica Lewinsky scandal, telling a group of religious leaders
on Thursday: ``Surely, no fair-minded person would blame him for
any mistake that I made.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all political analysts were so critical of the Clintons'
behavior here in Los Angeles. Thomas Mann of the Brookings
Institution, a Washington-based think-tank, noted that Clinton has
been a sure-fire fund-raiser for Democrats during his time in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Tuesday, Mann noted, ``the convention will be about
Gore and the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no shortage of attention to Al Gore,'' Mann
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter Bennett Roth contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx $$$
</P>
