<HEADER>
A9592 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-P1EGYPTCRASH-HNS &LR;      08-12 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-P1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 EGYPTCRASH-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    EgyptAir crash still a mystery
 &HT;    Co-pilot was accused of sexual misconduct
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By MICHAEL HEDGES
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The crash of EgyptAir Flight 990 last October
officially remained a mystery Friday as federal officials released
FBI findings that a co-pilot initially suspected of forcing the
plane into a suicidal plunge had been investigated for sexual
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   James Hall, head of the National Transportation Safety Board,
said FBI reports that co-pilot Gamil El-Batouty had been under
investigation by New York hotel security officers for allegedly
exposing himself and making unwanted sexual advances were being
made public because they ``may be relevant to our investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Batouty is heard uttering a religious phrase in Arabic
repeatedly as the plane, carrying 217 people, made its fatal plunge
into the Atlantic off Nantucket early last Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   A transcript of what was recorded in the cockpit during the last
minutes of the flight was also released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Capt. Adel Anwar had excused himself to go to the
restroom, El-Batouty is heard saying, ``I rely on God.'' He
repeated that phrase at least 10 times before the plane crashed, a
minute and 58 seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   As the co-pilot repeated that mantra, thumps and clicks were
heard on the recorder, then four beeps from a cockpit warning
device. The precise cause of the thumps has not been determined,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Just 32 seconds before the recording abruptly ended, the pilot
returned and asked: ``What's happening? What's happening?''
</P>
<P>
   El-Batouty continued to say, ``I rely on God,'' and pilot Anwar
shouted ``What's happening, Gamil? What's happening? What is this?
What is this? Did you shut the engine? Get away in the engines.
Shut the engines.''
</P>
<P>
   The co-pilot responded: ``It's shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the last sequence on the tape, the pilot urged: ``Pull.
Pull with me. Pull with me. Pull with me.'' That is followed by
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the crash, U.S. investigators said privately that
they suspected El-Batouty had forced the Boeing 767 into its doomed
descent.
</P>
<P>
   Hall took pains Friday to say that the NTSB had reached no final
conclusion about what led to the destruction of Flight 990. ``I
want to make it perfectly clear that no determination as to the
cause of this crash has been made,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   But there were signs that U.S. officials have ruled out
mechanical failure. Hall said there would be no public hearing on
the disaster, which is mandatory if safety issues remain. Hall said
the board has concluded ``there are no unresolved safety issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall told Congress earlier this year that the way the plane
reacted during its plunge was consistent with a ``deliberate action
on the part of one of the crew members.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the crash, the NTSB had released information from the
flight data recorder that showed the plane's engines had been
turned off, as well as its autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a bitter divide remains between Egyptian official opinion
that the crash was most likely caused by an aircraft failure, and
the American view that no evidence has been found to support
mechanical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Hall said no further safety issues remained, Mohsen El
Missiry, an Egyptian official aiding the probe, said there would be
an additional investigation into ``the design of the Boeing 767's
elevator system.'' The plane's elevators, small wings on the tail,
point the nose up or down.
</P>
<P>
   And EgyptAir issued a news release saying the 1,660 pages of
analysis released by the NTSB on Friday actually supported a theory
of failure by the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing on the cockpit voice recorder or the flight
data recorder to indicate Flight 990 was intentionally crashed into
the ocean,'' said Capt. Shaker Kelada, an EgyptAir official who
took part in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Kelada dismissed the reports of sexual misconduct by El-Batouty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careful examination of FBI interviews indicates the relief
first officer's behavior in a New York hotel is largely
unsubstantiated,'' he said. He called those reports a ``smoke
screen,'' and said El-Batouty had no personal, professional,
medical or financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   EL Missiry said speculation about the co-pilot's behavior,
fueled by the FBI reports released Friday, ``is painful for the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI interviews of employees of the Pennsylvania Hotel in New
York where the EgyptAir crew frequently stayed documented a number
of alleged problems with the 59-year-old El-Batouty, including a
charge that he offered to pay a hotel maid for sex the night before
the crash. That was just the last in a long series of incidents at
the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A hotel employee told the FBI that El-Batouty had been warned
that his behavior would be reported to his employer, EgyptAir. It
was not clear whether the hotel followed through with that threat.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the NTSB would publish a probable cause of the crash
in a final report. He said there was no timetable for the release
of that report.
</P>
<P>
   The flight, which carried 100 Americans, 89 Egyptians, 21
Canadians and seven others, left New York for Cairo shortly after 1
a.m. It crashed into 250 feet of water about 51 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the remains of 19 victims have been identified, and Hall
said medical examiners were continuing a process of comparing DNA
from family members with the victims' remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an immense tragedy experienced by people around
the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
