<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RECORD, BUT THAT'S HIS ONLY PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Lenny Krayzelburg's keenest competition eyed him
like a hawk on Friday. It was an intimidating presence, what with a
wingspan that stretched practically from one wall of the IUPUI
Natatorium to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg could see his most onerous opponent down the stretch
of the 100-meter backstroke final at the U.S. Olympic Swimming
Trials without even having to crane his neck much. It was
!ital!right there the entire second lap.
</P>
<P>
   On this night the USC graduate's most austere adversary won. The
clock beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg was .24 seconds slower than the world record he set
last August in the pool where the Sydney Olympics will take place
next month. Though visibly disappointed, Krayzelburg couldn't
really complain.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he realized his dream: He made the U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   And with plenty of room to spare. The race offered a stark
reminder of how far behind Krayzelburg has left the rest of the
best in the U.S., only the clock remaining to push him.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Walker is the 100 short course meters world-record holder,
but he couldn't offer Krayzelburg a concerted challenge for more
than 50 meters. Walker was Krayzelburg's nearest nemesis and he
finished 1.01 seconds behind Krayzelburg's 53.84.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen-year-old Aaron Peirsol handed Krayzelburg his first
defeat in two years at a low-key meet at USC last month but
couldn't come within 1.3 seconds of him when the pressure was a
hammer pounding on his temples.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Bridgewater won the 200 backstroke at the 1996 Olympics in
Atlanta, but sometime between then and now he became more mentor
than measuring stick. Krayzelburg beat his Trojan Swim Club
teammate by 1.98 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Tate Blahnik has won a national title in the backstroke and he
finished 1.97 seconds back.
</P>
<P>
   The difference? Walker, Peirsol, Bridgewater and Blahnik were in
the event; Krayzelburg is of it.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Mark Schubert noticed Krayzelburg's otherworldly gift
almost immediately after Santa Monica College coach Stu Blomkin _
who also saw something really special _ delivered Krayzelburg to
him in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after they started working together, Schubert took the
Fairfax High graduate aside. Krayzelburg, whose family emigrated to
the U.S. from Odessa, Ukraine, in 1989, remembers the ensuing
conversation as if it were yesterday: ``He said, `Lenny, I think
you could be the best backstroker in the world.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old smiled. ``I think that really stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   His world records in the 100 and 200 tell the story of a
prophesy fulfilled. Not that Krayzelburg will admit to it. Getting
him to brag on himself is harder than beating him in the pool. His
parents reared him to have a small ego and big dreams and he is
nothing if not a dutiful son.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats were smart, they'd collect Krayzelburg, who
became a U.S. citizen in 1995, at LAX when he arrives home next
week and make him the centerpiece of a famil-values platform.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg and Yelena Krayzelburg imbued him with an incorruptible
work ethic. They spawned him in 1975 and they sustain him now.
They're his inspiration and his entourage; Oleg is his son's sports
psychologist and cook and Yelena his protector.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Krayzelburg minces few words. ``My dad's advice to me
is always `Break world records,' '' Krayzelburg said.
</P>
<P>
   Right after he touched the wall and saw his time, Krayzelburg's
eyes moved to the stands, to where his parents were standing.
Predictably, he saw Oleg, his arms outstretched, mouthing the
words, ``What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Before he could mouth a reply, he saw his mother take her
program and swat her husband on the shoulders and head. Krayzelburg
didn't have to be a lip reader to know she was saying, ``What's
wrong with you?''
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg laughed as he finished describing this Kodak moment.
There is nothing wrong in his world. Nothing at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
