<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-1STLD-WR     08-12 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN CHOOSES HARD-RIGHT BLACK WOMAN AS RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Ala.)   (CORRECTS ``Tuesday'' to ``Thursday'' in 6th graf)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY and B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ As the latest twist in a political
convention filled with them, Pat Buchanan on Friday shattered the
emerging image of the Reform Party as a haven for white
conservatives by selecting as his running mate a black woman who
taught public school for years in South Central Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the larger of the party's feuding factions
nominated Buchanan as its presidential nominee. With the smaller
group nominating John Hagelin, the fight over $12.6 million in
federal campaign funds was officially enjoined, to be fought out
over the next few weeks before the Federal Election Commission and,
in all likelihood, a federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's pick of Ezola Foster, whose hard-right views
virtually mirror his own, made her the first black candidate to
seek the vice presidency for what is, arguably, a major party.
(There have been other black candidates for president, including
Shirley Chisholm, a Democratic congresswoman from New York, who
sought the Democratic nomination in 1972.)
</P>
<P>
   In presenting Foster at a midday rally, where almost no one knew
who she was until he introduced her, Buchanan gave no indication
that the ticket would face further obstacles, legal or otherwise,
on the march toward the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this lady will be a tremendous benefit to our cause,
to our campaign and to our movement,'' he said, standing beside
Foster. ``She'll be an ambassador to America for what this party is
all about. This shows that we are a party that is open to
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who has brought new energy to the Reform Party since
Ross Perot's second unsuccessful campaign for president in 1996,
had closely guarded the identity of his pick since the convention
began on Thursday. But even with all the speculation over who it
might be, the rumored names never included Foster. This is a
convention, after all, in which the vast majority of delegates are
white, and most are men.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Foster, 62, a former Democrat and a former Republican who
followed Buchanan into the Reform Party when he left the
Republicans last year, has been known to Buchanan for years.
</P>
<P>
   A public school teacher and administrator for 33 years and a
twice-failed candidate for the California Assembly, she is founder
of a California-based organization called Americans for Family
Values. She was an ardent supporter of Proposition 187, a 1984
California measure that sought to deny aid to illegal immigrants,
before courts struck it down. She favors local control of public
schools and opposes programs in them that promote safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Buchanan named her as a co-chairwoman of his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At her introduction, Foster discounted any role that race might
play in her candidacy, insisting: ``We want to do what's right for
all Americans. We have to stop appeasing one group after another.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she seemed an unlikely choice for Buchanan, whose views
are so far to the right on many issues that he has especially
strong appeal to fringe groups that include white supremacists,
militia members and anti-Semites.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Buchanan, who serves as chief campaign strategist for her
brother, said Foster emerged as the vice-presidential choice over
several others was because she shared Pat Buchanan's views on most
issues and because ``she could hold her own in debates.''
</P>
<P>
   As for any votes and support the ticket might lose because the
vice-presidential candidate is a black woman, Bay Buchanan said,
``If we lose them, then I say goodbye. I'm not interested in them,
and I hope this pick tells them we are not interested in their
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster's selection was also well received by many Buchanan
supporters, who went out of their way to say they did not mind that
she was black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so excited for her, and I'm from Alabama,'' said Sharman
Ramsey, whose husband, Joel, is a delegate from Dothan, Ala.
``We're not prejudiced against blacks. We want competent,
responsible people of any color.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Moore, a Florida delegate said: ``Her selection lends us
more credibility. It puts to bed a lot of the spin about us being a
party of whites, because we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's moment of triumph as a nominee came after delegates
in the faction supporting him voted almost unanimously to throw out
a monthlong primary in which hundreds of thousands had
participated. That vote is being replace in favor of a vote by
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in three presidential campaigns that the
will of ordinary voters, whom Perot had envisioned as holding the
ultimate power, was ignored.
</P>
<P>
   But the move was widely viewed as a way to protect Buchanan
against legal action by Hagelin, who has accused the Buchanan
campaign of election fraud. In a complaint to the Federal Election
Commission filed on Thursday, the Hagelin campaign charged that
Buchanan's supporters sent primary ballots to as many as 500,000
people who were ineligible to vote in the Reform primary.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the primary were not disclosed to the larger
group. They were to the smaller. But even though Buchanan won
49,529 to 28,539, in voting totals that represented just 10 percent
of the ballots distributed, the pro-Hagelin group also voted to
throw out Buchanan's votes as fraudulent and named Hagelin by
acclamation its presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting the nomination, Hagelin called on the feuding
factions and all independent parties to unite as an alternative to
Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of all we cherish has come from third-party
voices,'' Hagelin said. ``This is a powerful, powerful movement. We
should begin the process of healing and rebuilding, putting aside
the small ideas that divide us and replace them with grand ideas
that unite us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
