<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK REVOKES MEDICAL LICENSE OF FERTILITY SPECIALIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York State Department of Health Friday
suspended the medical license of a well-known fertility specialist
with a busy celebrity-favored practice who is facing retrial on
insurance fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   The state health commissioner, Dr. Antonia Novello, deciding the
doctor posed ``an imminent danger to public health,'' suspended the
license of Dr. Niels Lauersen before a state investigative
committee had finished reviewing the complaints against him.
</P>
<P>
   Health department officials said they took the action against
Lauersen, who was already on probation with the state for previous
infractions, because of the nature of the charges against him, and
because he appeared confused and incoherent during several days of
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The report of the department's investiga- tion details numerous
charges of negli- gence, incompetence, fraudulent practices and
moral unfitness involving seven pa- tients. One charge involved a
delivery that left a baby severely brain-damaged; an- other told of
a patient on whom an unneces- sary hysterectomy had been performed.
Lauersen is among the busiest gynecologists in the state, despite a
spate of malpractice lawsuits and government investigations, as an
increasing number of couples seek solutions to their fertility
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lauersen has attracted a following of patients as he moved from
hospital to hospital. While most specialists tend to be discreet
about their celebrity patients, he has bragged about his _ Celine
Dion, Liv Ullmann and Geraldo Rivera's former wife, Kiki.
</P>
<P>
   Novello has increasingly employed what was once a fairly rare
practice _ forbidding doctors to practice medicine while an
investigation is under way. She has suspended the licenses of 31
doctors so far this year, 19 more than in all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lauersen's lawyer, Robert Deutsch, denounced the
health department for the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The denial of a fair hearing, I believe, is merely a
continuation of the department's vendetta against my doctor since
1995,'' he said, alluding to the year in which the state began
investigating Lauersen. Deutsch attributed Lauersen's apparent
incoherence to fatigue brought on by the department's requirement
that most of his hearing occur during 10 consecutive days, with
each session lasting 12 hours. ``This has never before been done in
the history of the department,'' Deutsch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't intend to let this drop here,'' Deutsch said. ``We
are trying to stay the enforcement of this order.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauersen's receptionist said Friday that the doctor would not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Lauersen dismissed the state's previous
investigation as minor, and said he did not know what the state
agency ``really is.'' He also denied that he was currently under
investigation. ``The important thing is that I am careful in
everything I do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lauersen is well known among New York City obstetricians and
gynecologists. In part, this is because of his practice involves
fertility work for patients he then refers to obstetricians. Some
contend part of his notoriety stems from his standards of care
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he pushes the envelope on standards of practice,''
a former colleague said. ``But his patients adored him. He has a
huge following.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauersen is the author of several books on fertility and
gynecological health. But he attracted national attention this
spring, when he was prosecuted by the federal government for a
scheme in which he billed insurance companies for gynecological
cases that actually involved fertility procedures. The case ended
with a hung jury and will be retried this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Lauersen had previously been placed on probation for two years
by the state as a result of an earlier investigation into his
medical competence. The state ruled that his practice should be
monitored by his hospital employers, and that he had to take a
course in medical record keeping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
