<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERRORS, BAD INNING DOOM DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Scientists talked about raising the Titanic but found
it wasn't possible.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should try a test run on the Los Angeles Dodgers'
season, and if they can salvage that, they can move on to the
Titanic. It's debatable which would be a bigger undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to erase memories of a horrid homestand and trying to add
some semblance of order to a season quickly sinking, the Dodgers
bullpen allowed five runs in the bottom of the eighth inning in a
7-2 loss to Atlanta on Friday at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The swirl created by the season quickly vanishing down the drain
also threatens to take manager Davey Johnson with it. His future
with the organization continues to look bleak, especially since the
Dodgers have lost two straight, five of six and are 5 games behind
San Francisco in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, it's not a good feeling,'' Dodgers second baseman
Mark Grudzielanek said. ``We need to try and bounce back (today)
and try to win a game and see what it feels like, and then maybe
try to win two. There's not a good feeling in here, no question.
We'll see what kind of people we have in here, if we're men or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also trail the Mets by eight games in the wild-card
race, and frustration is prevalent in every corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's getting late in the season and it looks like
we're going backward instead of forward,'' Dodgers all-star left
fielder Gary Sheffield said. ``We played seven good innings of
baseball and let it slip away. I could never figure this situation
out. A lot of things happened this year that you would never think
would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustration might best be exemplified by perhaps the worst
offensive game of the season for Sheffield. He was 0 for 4 with
four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game Johnson expressed his frustration with the
club's lack of execution during critical stretches, and he got
another painful chance to witness it against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Tied 2-2 in the bottom of the eighth, the Dodgers _ particularly
third baseman Adrian Beltre _ again didn't make the pivotal plays.
</P>
<P>
   After Chan Ho Park pitched a strong seven innings, Terry Adams
relieved and got Andruw Jones to hit a chopper toward third. But
rather than charge the ball and short-hop it, Beltre tried to field
it on a middle hop and it got away and into left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the balls you have to come in and play the short
hop,'' Johnson said. ``If you knock it down, you can pick it up and
throw him out. If you back up on it, you're going to get a nasty
short hop. He's young. He'll learn.''
</P>
<P>
   It was ruled a basehit, but it was the springboard for a
five-run inning. Worse, it wasn't the only gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones doubled in Jones, Wally Joyner singled in a run to
make it 4-2. It could have stayed there when Adams (4-4) got Javy
Lopez to ground to Beltre with runners on second and third and one
out. But as Beltre went to take the ball out of his glove to throw
home, he dropped the ball. Beltre got Brian Jordan wandering off
second base, but a chance to get pinch-runner George Lombard at the
plate was wiped away.
</P>
<P>
   Adams had been brilliant for a nine-game stretch until this
outing. He had allowed one earned run in his last 15 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell behind a couple guys and got a couple of ground balls I
thought should have been made, but when you fall behind and have to
throw it over, you get hit,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a month and a half left. We need to win
ballgames. That's no secret. We need to get a streak going or we're
going to fall behind because Arizona and the Giants are playing
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
