u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-JAGUARS-NY     08-12 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-JAGUARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG START BY GIANTS WASTED BY LATE FUMBLE
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ In a bizarre ending to a preseason game the
New York Giants had all but won Friday night, the Jacksonville
Jaguars recovered a fumble in the Giants' end zone with seven
seconds remaining to score a touchdown and win, 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' reserve cornerback, Fred Lewis, intercepted a pass
from Jonathan Quinn, Jacksonville's third-string quarterback, at
the Giants' goal line and then ran 1 yard into the playing field.
As he did, Giants linebacker Jack Golden tackled Lewis, apparently
trying to keep him from advancing the football.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis fumbled backward, where the Jaguars' Brandon Christenson
recovered the ball for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The freaky conclusion marred for the Giants, 0-2 in the
preseason, what was an otherwise good game for their first-team
offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   For a second consecutive week, the Giants' starters, led by
quarterback Kerry Collins and running back Tiki Barber, moved the
football. The first-team defense delivered another rugged, steady
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The starters _ for a second successive week _ left the field at
halftime with the lead. For a second consecutive week, the reserves
could not hold on.
</P>
<P>
   Collins completed 10 of 19 passes for 110 yards and a touchdown.
Barber had 83 rushing yards in the half. Wide receiver Amani Toomer
caught just two passes, including a 22-yard touchdown pass, but
continued to establish himself as a big-play threat. And the rookie
Ron Dayne, while again looking dependable in short-yardage
situations, also seemed to get stronger as the game unfolded,
finishing with 66 rough-and-tumble rushing yards on 17 carries.
</P>
<P>
   It was Collins, as he had in the Giants' preseason loss to
Chicago, who made the dominant impression with his confidence and
poise. Collins threw the ball accurately and frequently deep down
the field, and his passing statistics don't reflect three dropped
passes.
</P>
<P>
   On the Giants' first possession Collins, throwing off his back
foot after double-pumping, lofted a perfect pass to Toomer, who
made a spinning catch as he fell over the goal line for a 22-yard
touchdown. It was the kind of bold strike rarely attempted by the
Giants in previous seasons _ and even more rarely executed
properly.
</P>
<P>
   It put the Giants ahead, 7-0, a lead they extended to 10-0 on
Brad Daluiso's 27-yard field goal. That drive was set up by a
55-yard dash around right end by Barber.
</P>
<P>
   Barber, the Giants' most consistent offensive weapon last
season, had a couple of dazzling runs in what has been a
spectacular preseason. Lighter and quicker this year, Barber was
stuffed at the line of scrimmage on his long run, but flashed
outside and raced down the sideline, outrunning all but one
defender.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Giants' remade starting offensive line displayed
the same unity apparent in last week's loss to Chicago. Collins,
who was not sacked, was hit in the pocket after passing just once.
The running backs had holes to work with and time to find them
because the Jaguars' defensive line rarely found its way into the
Giants' backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first half, Collins threw an interception when he
tried to force a short pass to Howard Cross over the middle.
Jacksonville linebacker Brant Boyer stepped in front of the pass
and deflected it to his teammate Michael Swift, who made the
interception.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, led by the reserve quarterback Jamie Martin,
advanced to the Giants' 10-yard line. They were stopped there,
however, by the Giants' first-string defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
