</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-RELIGION-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: HOW RELIGION PERMEATES BOTH GOP AND
DEMOCRATIC  CAMPAIGNS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DON LATTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even in America, where piety and politics shack
up in the strangest ways, it was quite a week.
</P>
<P>
   It began when Al Gore, a Southern Baptist, anointed an Orthodox
Jew as his running mate to help attract Christian voters.
</P>
<P>
   And it ended with Bill Clinton bowing before a mega-church
packed with Christian ministers, seeking post-Monica atonement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's selection of Sen. Joe Lieberman brought comparisons to
the 1960 presidential race, when John F. Kennedy's Catholic faith
became a major campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the reaction to Lieberman's candidacy shows how much
the nation's religious and political landscape has changed over the
past four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's response to ``the Catholic question'' was to stress
his secularism, to emphasize that his policies would never be
compromised by the proclamations of popes or prelates.
</P>
<P>
   It's the opposite today. In breaking this historic religious
barrier to national political office, Gore did not pick a secular
Jewish running mate nor one who attends a mainstream Reform
movement synagogue. Gore went all the way, choosing a political
partner whose Orthodox faith lies at the center of his being, from
the food he eats to how he spends his Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Gore didn't choose Lieberman because he's Jewish; he chose him
because the Connecticut centrist is a man of faith. Gore and his
advisers understand that the theological and political fault lines
in America no longer divide us into camps of Christians or Jews,
Catholics or Protestants, Baptists or Methodists.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a post-denominational world, where the commonalities
of faith overshadow sectarian differences.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a world where Presbyterian churches host Passover
seders, where Pope John Paul II travels to Israel and refers to
Jews as ``our elder brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Evangelicals complain about Lieberman's pro-choice position on
abortion, but they embrace him as a Judeo-Christian brother who
believes in God.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are some Americans on the Christian Right fringe who
won't vote for Lieberman because he's a Jew. But the real
battleground in the Bush-Gore race is for Americans in the middle,
those church-going folks an infamous televangelist once called the
``moral majority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Lieberman is Jewish by birth, but more importantly, he is
seen as a man of faith. He is seen as authentic,'' said Rabbi
Robert Wexler, president of the University of Judaism in Los
Angeles. ``For Christians who are religious, he is a validation
that someone who is very religious can hold that office.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his moral failings, Clinton is one Democrat who
understands the political power of post-denominational
``born-again'' piety. Observers may disagree as to the president's
sincerity, but few can question the fact the he used the rhetoric
of redemption to survive the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   It was on display once again this week when the Southern Baptist
president was interviewed by Pastor Bill Hybels on the stage of the
Willow Creek Community Church.
</P>
<P>
   Willow Creek is one of the nation's best known
``mega-churches,'' a nondenominational congregation that uses
contemporary worship and modern marketing techniques to attract
16,000 worshipers to weekend services. It eschews denominational
ties and focuses on attracting ``seekers'' and other unchurched
Americans comfortable with a moderate, ``user-friendly''
evangelism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke into a cordless microphone, his image beamed onto
two huge video screens in the cavernous church auditorium. Once
again, the subject was ``his terrible mistake,'' the audience was a
room full of Christian ministers, and the message was redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``My spiritual life,'' the president confessed, is ``a work in
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But the strangest event on the politics-and-piety front this
week was neither Lieberman's anointment nor Clinton's confession.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the moral arbiters of political correctness ruled
that Loretta Sanchez, a Latina congresswoman from Orange County,
could not hold a fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion  &UR; and &LR;  speak to
the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1976, when Jimmy Carter confessed to Playboy magazine
that he has ``lust in his heart,'' has Hugh Hefner thrust himself
so forcefully into the rough and tumble of presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   Carter dropped 15 points in the polls after his infamous Playboy
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to choose between the two venues, Sanchez first said she
would appear at the Hispanic Unity USA fund-raiser at the Playboy
Mansion in Los Angeles. But Friday, after the decision drew a
barrage of criticism, Sanchez said she might be willing to move the
fund-raiser to another venue.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the moral of the story is that  &UR; some  &LR; things in American
politics never change. Today's Democrats can embrace an observant
Jew on the ticket and a repentant sinner in the White House, but
they still draw the line at an unrepentant Latina in the House of
Hefner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 0101EDT &QL; 
