A9619 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-REFORM-CONVENTION-SFC     08-12 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUCHANAN WINS NOMINATION, PICKS BLACK WOMAN FOR NO. 2  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH _ Pat Buchanan won both ends of the Reform Party's
convoluted presidential nomination process Friday night, but that
didn't stop breakaway dissidents from choosing their own candidate
for president.
</P>
<P>
   Physicist John Hagelin, who also is the Natural Law Party's
candidate for president, was chosen by acclamation at a rump
convention being held just down the street from where Buchanan was
nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Both Buchanan and Hagelin will send their nomination papers to
the Federal Election Commission, which will be asked to decide
which man gets the Reform Party nomination _ and the $12.5 million
in federal funds that go to the nominee's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be just one more colorful event in the short but
tumultuous history of the Reform Party,'' predicted Russ Verney, a
former Reform Party chair who helped lead the walkout against
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   For Buchanan, last night was more a coronation than a
nomination. To roars and cheers from the crowd, the former
Republican presidential hopeful was the only person placed in
nomination. He named Ezola Foster, a 62-year-old black former
teacher and conservative activist, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   For 45 minutes, speakers hammered on the issues Buchanan
opposes: abortion, illegal immigration, NAFTA and foreign military
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Buchanan will never allow the blood of our children to be
shed where there's no American interest,'' said Jennifer Giroux, a
Cincinnati nurse and mother.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Buchanan was nominated virtually unanimously, with
only a handful of other votes and abstentions. Missing, however,
were about 140 delegates who had made their way to the opposition
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan showed up briefly in the convention hall after the vote
to thank the delegates for their support. He is slated to return
Saturday evening to give his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the national press corps when they wrote us off nine
months ago: `You don't know this peasant army,' '' he told the
cheering, confetti-drenched crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan played some political hardball Friday afternoon to
clear the way for his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   While the convention schedule called for the party to announce,
state by state, results of the party's mail-in presidential ballot,
Buchanan's backers were having none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to do (the mail-in count) for three hours,''
Bay Buchanan, Buchanan's sister and political adviser, said Friday
morning. ``We're going to nominate Pat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the convention overwhelmingly voted to dump the
party's mail-in primary, ignoring more than 78,000 people who had
cast the ballots that were supposed to choose the party nominee.
Instead, the convention, packed with Buchanan supporters, picked
the nominee to chants of ``Go Pat Go.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Buchanan landed 64 percent of the mail-in
vote, which provided the icing on the cake for his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are you going to choose now, Jimmy?'' taunted convention
chairman Gerry Moan, in a dig aimed at Jim Mangia, head of the
dissident group.
</P>
<P>
   For delegates at the rump convention, the answer was easy. They
disqualified Buchanan for allegedly stuffing the mail-in ballot box
and nominated Hagelin, the only candidate left standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results of the mail-in vote wasn't any surprise, since we
knew that Buchanan had sent ballots to 500,000 people ineligible to
vote,'' said Bob Roth, a spokesman for Hagelin. ``That's why we
disqualified him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 900,000 ballots were sent out by the Reform Party. There
is no way to determine how many of the votes returned, if any, may
have come from ineligible voters.
</P>
<P>
   The party dissidents already plan to challenge Buchanan's
nomination. Mangia filed a second suit with the Federal Election
Committee Friday, seeking to deny Buchanan the $12.5 million in
federal funds that will go to the Reform Party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only begun to fight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan demonstrated the control he holds over his half of the
Reform Party's dueling conventions by naming Foster as his
hand-picked running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Foster lives in Los Angeles and spent 33 years as a teacher and
administrator. She was a co-chair of Buchanan's unsuccessful run
for the Republican presidential nomination in 1996 and followed him
into the Reform Party when he bolted the GOP last year.
</P>
<P>
   Describing Foster as a lifelong Christian who wants to bring
prayer back into the schools, Buchanan said that she ``has been
with me through every tough battle and hardship we have had.''
</P>
<P>
   By bypassing Reform Party leaders in favor of his longtime
supporter, Buchanan made it clear that he's the new party boss.
</P>
<P>
   Foster will ``contradict all the myths and nonsense about what
this new party is about,'' Buchanan told reporters at a news
conference with the Queen Mary in the background. ``It is open. We
welcome everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   As a politician, Foster tried twice to unseat then-Assemblywoman
Maxine Waters and was a prominent supporter of Proposition 187, the
1994 ballot measure that sought to deny most state aid to illegal
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to continue our compassion, but cease being stupid,''
said Foster, who has argued that illegal immigration hurts poor
black workers the most. ``We need to protect American people and
American shores.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster also said the ongoing fight over use of the Confederate
battle flag should not be a racial issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Confederate flag is part of our history,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
