r s BC-OLY-SWIMMING-TRIALS-T     08-12 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMMING-TRIALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEDFORD WINS THE 100-METER BACKSTROKE TO CLINCH AN OLYMPIC BERTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ After thrice witnessing her daughter come to the
Olympic trials and fail to make the U.S. swim team, Jane Bedford
decided that this time would be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``She stayed home,'' former Texas Longhorns swimmer B.J. Bedford
said. ``She thinks she's a jinx.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of what happened Friday night, therefore, amid
the giggles and the hugs, daughter Bedford had a happy phone call
to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bbblllhhhrrrmmhhhrrrggg,'' B.J. said, mimicking the likely
conversation. ``I don't know if I'm ever going to get the words
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl who twice missed curfew on road trips and had to leave
the U.S. resident team, the free spirit who shaved her head before
the '96 trials just like the guys do, the college athlete who once
showed up at morning practice at UT wearing her clothes from the
night before because she had just gotten in _ Jane Bedford's jinxed
kid _ at long last made the Olympic team Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when fellow Texas ex Josh Davis set a U.S. record in
the 200-meter freestyle and when America's stars shone as expected,
Bedford won the 100-meter backstroke in 1 minute, 1.85 seconds,
leaped from the pool, and began hugging everything in sight _ a
judge, a stranger, a TV camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't discriminate between animate or inanimate objects,''
Bedford explained with mock seriousness. ``I will hug anybody after
I make the Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 200 free, Davis led from wall to wall and toppled
an American record set by Matt Biondi that had stood for 12 years.
Which was the plan all along, the San Antonio native said later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember watching Matt on TV when I was 15 years old,'' said
Davis, whose 1:47.26 eclipsed Biondi's 1:47.72. ``He was my idol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal was to swim 1:47.5 and to break Biondi's record.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Malchow of Ann Arbor, Mich., set the only other record of
the day when he broke Mel Stewart's Olympic trials mark in the
prelims of the 200-meter butterfly. Malchow, who holds the world
record in the event (1:55.18) swam 1:55.67 to break the meet mark
in the morning and was easily the fastest qualifier (1:56.67) in
the evening semis.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100-meter backstroke finals, Sydney gold medal favorite
Lenny Krayzelburg of Studio City, Calif., was first in 53.84,
finishing just ahead of Texas ex Neil Walker (54.85).
</P>
<P>
   Confident 16-year-old Megan Quann of Puyallup, Wash., who broke
the American record in the prelims, won the women's 100
breaststroke in 1:07.26, ahead of California-Berkeley's Staciana
Stitts.
</P>
<P>
   Davis won three gold medals at the Atlanta Games, but this
clearly will be a different Olympics. His wife, Shantel, is
expecting the couple's third child during the same September week
when the Olympic team is supposed to head for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's provided a lot of incentive,'' he said, ``because I
have a lot of diapers to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis plans to return to Austin on Sept. 4, when doctors will
induce labor. He will rejoin the team after the baby is born.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford, meanwhile, is 27 and planning a wedding. Her fiance,
Tom Sorensen, just heard the disappointing news that he would be an
alternate on the U.S. Olympic volleyball team and would not be
competing in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   For Bedford, an admitted chronic worrier, it was not a good way
to launch the week. Though she is a 13-time gold medalist in
international competition, Bedford had always come up short at the
Olympic Trials, including 1996 when she shaved her blonde locks
clean.
</P>
<P>
   She said it grew back like a fuzzy tennis ball.
</P>
<P>
   While on one trip with the U.S. swim team, she missed a 10:30
p.m. curfew, arriving at 7 a.m., she explained, because she was
visiting a friend and didn't want to wake her roommate. She
eventually left the resident team in Colorado Springs, Colo., she
said, ``because people come to little gerbil windows each day and
watch you. They can't have people screwing up on that team, and
that was me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke the rules. I served my time. But I'm a good girl
now.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
