<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASTORY-AMBASSADOR-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTEL THAT ONCE STOOD FOR GLAMOUR MAY SOON FALL IN COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Once a playground for Hollywood's glitterati,
L.A.'s Ambassador Hotel was a fabulous night spot where you might
bump into Charlie Chaplin one night or F. Scott Fitzgerald the
next.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was the site of a tragedy that shook the nation: On
June 5, 1968, Sen. Robert F. Kennedy, fresh from a stunning victory
in California's Democratic presidential primary, was assassinated
at the Ambassador by Sirhan Sirhan.
</P>
<P>
   The image of RFK dying on the kitchen floor was indelibly burned
into the American psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a national shrine to Bobby Kennedy's memory or a
symbol of the glamorous past in Los Angeles, the Ambassador is a
vacant eyesore - a symbol of the city's political paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually since it was closed 11 years ago, the Ambassador has
been the object of a complex series of legal battles on one front
between the Los Angeles Unified School District and a group of
private developers that once included Donald Trump and Magic
Johnson. On a second front, preservationists and the local business
community have been fighting about it.
</P>
<P>
   The site hasn't become a high school campus in an area with the
most severely overcrowded schools. And it hasn't become a retail
complex in an area badly in need of economic development. And, of
course, the building hasn't been torn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible shame,'' said Margaret Burk, author of an
Ambassador history and its publicity director for 22 years. ``That
hotel I believe at one time in its life was better known than any
other hotel in the world. There were princes and kings and queens
and potentates and maharajahs, the emperor of Japan and presidents.
Everybody came to the Ambassador.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel spawned many legends - as when Albert Einstein called
the front desk to complain about the couple fighting next door:
boxer Jack Dempsey was trying to throw his new bride out the
window. Numerous careers were launched at the hotel's Cocoanut
Grove nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   But after the RFK assassination, guests canceled en masse. It
became known morbidly as the place where Bobby Kennedy was killed,
the place where the dreams of millions of Americans were shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Among the millions stunned that night was a 26-year-old Yale law
graduate named Joseph Lieberman, who had been inspired by Kennedy
and had become chairman of his Connecticut campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, of course, is heading to Los Angeles as Al Gore's
choice for vice president. The 1968 presidential campaign still
holds a place in his heart. ``It was probably the last campaign I
really felt passion about,'' he was quoted as saying two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There were some attempts to revive the hotel, located in the
3400 block of Wilshire Boulevard two blocks east of Normandie
Avenue, but the owners didn't put enough money into modernizing,
according to former employees. And the gradual shifting of the
luxury hotel market west to Beverly Hills was the final blow. The
hotel closed in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, the Ambassador became a stepchild to downtown
development.
</P>
<P>
   The latest twist came earlier this week when bankruptcy
protection was sought by the owners who bought the 23.5-acre site
after the hotel closed. They turned to bankruptcy court and
restructuring not because they'd run out of cash, but as a tactic
to prevent foreclosure by the school district.
</P>
<P>
   The LAUSD became involved in 1990 when, needing another downtown
high school, it placed a $48 million deposit on the property to
begin eminent domain proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But when the real estate market collapsed in the early 1990s,
district officials backed off, hoping to get it at a cheaper price.
Later they changed course and decided to build the nation's
costliest school, called the Belmont Learning Center, but abandoned
this half-built blunder after spending $175 million because of
serious environmental problems. This week, district officials tried
to foreclose on the Ambassador property and force a sheriff's sale
to recover the deposit - which the developers spent to pay their
mortgage - plus interest. The owners filed for restructuring the
day before the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The owners say they need to demolish the hotel and create new
commercial and residential development on the entire site so they
can repay the school district, whose officials claim the debt is
more than $70 million including interest.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   That upsets Los Angeles preservationists, who see no reason why
the hotel building can't be used as part of a new development. It
could easily be converted into housing for senior citizens or even
a school, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned and very opposed to (demolition),'' said
Ken Bernstein, director of preservation for the Los Angeles
Conservancy. ``We've worked very closely with the developers and
the school district on those various options.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope that a plan would emerge from the bankruptcy
court that would respect all three goals - that would enable
sensible community development to proceed on the site, that would
enable the school district to proceed with a much-needed school on
a portion of the property and that would preserve one of our city's
most historic buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Not likely, according to the developers, who say their hand was
forced by the school district. They were ready to compromise and
build a middle school on a portion of the property, but officials
say they need a high school, which is opposed by many local
businesses and would take up more of the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reusing the hotel is probably not as effective as full-site
development,'' said George Host, vice president of S.D. Malkin
Properties, one of the lead developers. ``Our focus is completely
on repaying the school board. It's unfortunate they pushed it to
this point.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials point to a desperate need for classrooms in an
area many students must leave aboard buses to attend high school.
They are willing to settle for a 12-acre portion of the property,
but say this campus must be for a high school, which developers and
the business community call incompatible with retail development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they kick out the kids, the kids are going to have to go to
another site,'' said Caprice Young, the school board member whose
district encompasses the hotel. She said sites are hard to find in
a densely populated area.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, she remains hopeful that bankruptcy court can
provide sort of an independent arbitrator, open to proposals for a
school there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Young said. ``But what I've discovered in this
whole process is if anything can go wrong, it will.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate and the likely demolition leave nothing but memories
for those who witnessed the heyday of the Ambassador Hotel and the
Cocoanut Grove.
</P>
<P>
   Like Marshall Wright, 82, who was the hotel's residential
manager during the early 1950s. He recalls a constant flow of
celebrities and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Among numerous anecdotes, he remembers being drafted by gossip
columnist Louella Parsons to serve as an escort on the town for
Marilyn Monroe on nights when she was fighting with Joe DeMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louella told me to take her (Monroe) home, and I was leaving
the hotel with her,'' Wright recalled about one night. ``Just as I
go down the steps, I see - in the mirror - the reflection of Joe
hiding behind a pillar. I just stopped right there on the stairs. I
said, Good night, Marilyn. I wasn't about to tackle Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMaggio remained friendly with Wright. ``We had drinks and
talked about that later,'' Wright said, ``and he laughed. He was
terribly jealous of her. He died still loving her.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright went back and visited the hotel about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke down and cried in the lobby. They asked me why I was
crying. I said if you had the memories I have of this hotel, you
would cry, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a crowning thing in my life. I had bigger jobs in my
life after that, but nothing could ever surpass working at the
Ambassador.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
