r s BC-CAR-PETTY-DAUGHTER-TE     08-12 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PETTY-DAUGHTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KYLE PETTY'S DAUGHTER CARRIES FAMILY'S COMPETITIVE FIRE ATOP REAL
HORSE POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Pattie] Petty fills with emotion as her
daughter enters a plush press room at the American Quarter Horse
Youth Association World Championship Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``See,'' Pattie says, ``this is the type of place where your
daddy goes to every week.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a familiar place to the Pettys, a place of comfort and
accommodation _ computers, phones, faxes and closed-circuit TV to
the oval-shaped arena, a course similar to a racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Montgomery Lee Petty's arena. While her patriarchs
made a dynasty of the family name by racing cars in circles at
nearly 200 mph, the family's youngest member is earning her spurs
by riding horses in circles at less than 10 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of life's lessons that you have to learn out
there and you have to make your own way,'' Pattie Petty said. ``Our
last name opens doors sometimes and other times it shuts them right
in our face. Montgomery Lee has to learn that. She has to learn the
balance of not expecting doors to open for her because of who she
is. She's got to work very hard to prove herself separate from her
last name.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a family name that has seen its share of sorrow this year
with the deaths of Montgomery Lee's brother Adam and
great-grandfather Lee.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the 14-year-old daughter of NASCAR Winston Cup
driver Kyle Petty is the center of attention at John Justin Arena
in Fort Worth, where she competed this week in the world's toughest
youth equine competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the difference in what I do and what Montgomery Lee
does is that I try to go as fast as I can and she goes as slow as
she can,'' Kyle Petty said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery Lee Petty is a star in this arena, having won the
youth quarter horse all-around championship for North Carolina in
1999 and earning her first berth to the Fort Worth championships.
Quarter horses are the world's largest breed, and Montgomery Lee
excels in one of its toughest disciplines: Western Pleasure. At
this week's championships, she reached the semifinals in the event,
in which horses are judged how smoothly they, walk, trot and gallop
around the arena.
</P>
<P>
   She] competes in a sport that includes youth from other affluent
families, and some parents hire adult trainers to ready a horse for
competition. Not the Pettys. Montgomery Lee has trainers and plenty
of horse power, but she insists on preparing her horse, and
practices the same strenuous work ethic that made the Pettys NASCAR
royalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what you do, whether it's horses or auto racing, you
should work for your win and you should really deserve it,''
Montgomery Lee said. ``I don't think that it's fair for me to get
up at 5 o'clock in the morning to get ready for a show and other
kids sleep until noon, and then win the class. When that happens, I
think, `Whoa!' When I compete on my pleasure horse, I'll go out
there and work him for five hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery Lee rides on a picturesque, 400-acre spread of wooded
rolling hills near Greensboro, N.C., where she grew up. She has
trainers, Stacy Hullett, who lives on the family farm, and Mitch
and Jennifer Leckey from Florida, and two expensive horses with
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until Montgomery Lee began rising before dawn and
tending to her horses two years ago that her parents purchased
veteran show horses for their daughter. Until then, she rode horses
that weren't hitting on all cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as she works at it, we'll give her the tools that she
needs,'' Pattie Petty said. ``Her dad is in racing and he knows
that winning depends on having the right equipment. It's the same
in horses, if you don't have the right equipment, all of the work
in the world won't get you in the ring. As long as Montgomery Lee
is diligent and humble, we'll give her what she needs.''
</P>
<P>
   While her brothers Adam and Austin grew up with wrenches and
grease, Montgomery Lee preferred hay and bridal bits. She began
riding at 3 atop small ponies at the family farm. ``When I was
about 5 or 6], I got drug around by a pony and I was scared of
horses for the longest time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She resumed her riding career at 10 when the family purchased a
golden palomino named Trigger, named after Roy Rogers' horse. She
also learned horsemanship skills on an old cow pony named Kelly
that her mother kept on the farm for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Montgomery Lee has a smoother ride on her veteran show
horses, These Eyes Adore Thee (in showmanship, Western Horsemanship
and trail riding) and Mr. Magnolia Zip, which carried her to the
Western Pleasure semifinals Wednesday in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   When times are bleak, riding also helps Montgomery Lee smooth
rough emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make you feel better about yourself,'' she said. ``When
things aren't going well, Stacy \RHullett\S and I go on a long
trail ride. It's great because my horses can fly. We'll end the
ride with a race back to the barn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pettys are focusing on being upbeat after their son Adam,
19, was killed in an auto racing accident May 12. More than a month
earlier, her great-grandfather Lee Petty died at the age of 86. Her
mother requested that Montgomery Lee, who delivered a moving eulogy
at her brother's funeral, not be asked about the tragedy.
Montgomery Lee wears a necklace with a heart-shaped emblem and
Adam's name.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps her greatest tribute to Adam is competing in the Petty
spirit, which has helped the family triumph and cope with
misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I passed on the `have fun' part to her,'' said Kyle
Petty, who was in Fort Worth this week before leaving for the
NASCAR Winston Cup race in Watkins Glen, N.Y. He says his wife,
Pattie ``is more competitive and Montgomery Lee gets that part from
her mother. I just hope that when she's 35, she remembers that she
came to the Fort Worth youth show at 14 and had a good time, and,
oh by the way, she did well.''
</P>
<P>
   When Montgomery Lee competed Wednesday, she was dressed as
colorfully as her dad at Winston Cup races. Except that her black
suit, with a jagged pink top with silver sequins, wasn't filled
with sponsorship patches.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:30 p.m., she sat in a humid, dimly lit stall walkway
peering into a small mirror. As the buzzing fans blew mist nearby
to cool the area, she put on makeup, and adjusted her black
Stetson.
</P>
<P>
   At 4 p.m., she walked to the arena, chatted with her mother in
the grandstands, and then to a gritty and aeromatic warmup area to
prepare her horse. Two hours later, she showed the animal in the
first round and advanced to the semifinals. Though it appeared she
had a smooth ride in the semifinals, she was denied a final-round
berth.
</P>
<P>
   But she drew plenty of affirmation from her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens, my mom and dad are always proud of
me,'' Montgomery Lee said. ``Daddy always says to me to go into the
ring and smile, and have fun at it, no matter whether I win or
lose.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
