<HEADER>
A9624 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-TEN-TENNIS-LADN-(SLAN     08-12 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNIS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS, DAVENPORT ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ The roles switched and suddenly all
eyes were on Amy Frazier instead of Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, the world's top-ranked player, found herself almost as
an underdog because Frazier had upset her last week in Carlsbad.
</P>
<P>
   So all eyes _ and fans' encouragements _ were on Frazier in
Friday's estyle.com Classic quarterfinal at Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Those well-wishers came away disappointed, as Hingis needed just
53 minutes to dispatch Frazier 6-2, 6-1 and set up a semifinal
matchup today against fifth-seeded and defending champion Serena
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very excited to go out there and play her,'' Hingis
said. ``In a way, I had nothing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's other semifinal, unseeded Elena Demetrieva's
nightmare of facing second-seeded Lindsay Davenport came true.
Demetrieva beat Lisa Raymond 2-6, 6-1, 6-4, and Davenport took care
of No. 8 Sandrine Testud 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better for me to play Testud,'' Demetrieva said.
</P>
<P>
   It was better for Hingis to get another chance at Frazier so
soon. Last week, Frazier shocked Hingis 6-3, 6-3 in the
quarterfinals at Carlsbad, Hingis later saying the loss was a
``wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see if I'm a different player from last week,''
Hingis said. ``I was ready for her game better because I knew a bit
from last time what's her strength and weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   So did everyone. Frazier admits she's a one-dimensional player
who wins or loses by her groundstrokes. Her serve certainly won't
win any raves. Hingis broke her all seven times she served.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Frazier, her groundstrokes also were too
inconsistent, too many going long or wide. Plus, Hingis made fewer
unforced errors than last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, last week was last week,'' Frazier said. ``I've
played her so many times and lost. She didn't make any errors. . .
. She was running down the shots and I found I had to go for the
winner maybe a little too early.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't appear Davenport's victory would come early when the
first game lasted eight minutes and had seven deuces. Davenport had
seven break points before finally winning.
</P>
<P>
   Testud finally broke back to tie the set at 2-2, but by then
Davenport had found her stroke and the shots weren't sailing long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I hit the ball a lot better,'' Davenport said. ``I
was hitting the ball deeper and feeling like I could make shots,
work points a little more and go for the shots. I felt a lot more
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Demetrieva is the lesser-known of the remaining players. While
the others have Grand Slam titles to their credit, the 18-year-old
has never reached a WTA final and has just two other semifinal
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one of those appearances was this year at Indian Wells
(where she lost to Davenport), and she's ranked 32nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to say thank you to Monica,'' Demetrieva said of
Monica Seles, whose withdrawl opened Demetrieva's part of the
bracket. ``She gave me the chance to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying here, however, will be tough. Demetrieva appears
intimidated by Davenport. The two have faced off twice this year,
with Demetrieva never winning more than three games in any set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
