<HEADLINE>
THE SPORTS WORLD AT A GLANCE; THE EYES HAVE IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Combine the end of the week with the end of your rope and,
voila, welcome to Whitt's End.
</P>
<P>
   'Twas the beginning of The End ... when I can see clearly now,
the pain is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Actually during last Thursday's LASIK eye surgery, it was no
pain, mo' gain. Unless of course, you consider pain to be the
queasy discomfort of having your eyelids locked open with a
crowbar, having to focus your dilated iris on a red laser you're
certain is burning your cornea because you can smell it, all while
the surgeon reminds you how ``gravely important'' it is to be
perfectly motionless.
</P>
<P>
   To some, that simple irritating imagery is enough for a lifetime
``I Do'' to contacts or glasses. But to a certain fuzzy-focused
sportswriter who often saw more stars than in tonight's Perseid
Meteor Shower and a handful of precious pupils from Tiger Woods, to
Troy Aikman, to Bob Costas, to Cindy Crawford to even Kurt Rambis
(who traded in his trademark horn rims for 20/20), seeing clearly
is believing.
</P>
<P>
   With LASIK quickly gaining on tattoos, headbands and
breathe-right strips as the hottest novelty in sports, a few
suggestions to 10 blurred athletic eyes that should consider the
10-minute procedure to improve their vision, and their visions:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin: Would be able to see his far-sighted career
plummeting from Dallas Playmaker to Huntsville Platemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Jaramillo: Would be able to see that his leg-kick technique
has prodded Gabe Kapler _ not long ago as blind as his bat _ to
record the summer's most consecutive hit singles this side of
Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Firestone: Would be able to see that his name has been blown
out by recalled tires that are evoking new images of the Rolling
'Stones.
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson: Would be able to see that if he really wants to sell
out even the binocular-enhancement seats in Reunion Arena he can
grudgingly sign three talented local players, The Dixie Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campo: Would be able to see that seemingly cross-eyed
backup quarterback Paul Justin needs his own signature boot out of
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Franchione: Would be able to see that even with Heisman
hopeful LaDainian Tomlinson, Outland candidate Aaron Schobel and
the possibility of an undefeated season, it takes a strong case of
astigmatism to envision national respect in light of a schedule
that ranks 107 of 115 in strength.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban: Would be able to see that acquiring a player like
Shawn Kemp with double-figures in points scored and children
fathered is as near-sighted as banning gun shows at Fort Worth
public facilities.
</P>
<P>
   PGA Golfers: Would be able to see that Tiger Woods' 11 victories
in his past 19 tournaments are more than all but one Rangers'
pitcher (Rick Helling) this season, and likely more than the
Cowboys' upcoming total in 2000, thereby prodding them to start
tours of Hide-n-Go-Seek or Eye Spy.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones: Would be able to see that it is better for one of
his former players to be caught with Nelly Adham, rather than
Nellie a Don.
</P>
<P>
   Don King: Would be able to see that boxing is in hotter water
than the Northwest wildfires when Evander Holyfield is on the verge
of an unprecedented fourth heavyweight title and fans are more
consumed with bidding on Joe Frazier's spit bucket on eBay.
 &LR; subheds:CARNAC THE CRAZY  &LR; body:Answer: Gabe Kapler, Alvin Gentry
and The Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Name a streaker, a bleaker and a weaker.  &LR; subheds:BEST
AND WORST  &LR; body:Best strategy: The Cowboys should re-sign '80s
fullback Ron Springs, the last back to run a successful Dallas
screen pass.
</P>
<P>
   Worst strategy: Democratic presidential hopeful Al Gore
inexplicably tabbed Joseph Lieberman over Nancy Lieberman, a
candidate who would've secured Jewish, female and basketball
voters.  &LR; subheds:WHY DID THE CHICKEN CROSS THE ROAD?  &LR; body:To
figure out why baseball allows managers to run onto the field to
argue judgment calls. (He'd also like to peck around for an
explanation as to why they wear uniforms, but that's for another
crossing.)
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Nellie stopping a Mavericks game to run to mid-court to
dispute a charging call, or Dave Campo jogging into the end zone to
discuss a controversial interference penalty against the Cowboys.
As those two actions would be, managers should be immediately
penalized for their ridiculous wastes of time, matched in futility
only by fighting in hockey. In basketball it's a technical foul, in
football it's unsportsmanlike conduct, in baseball it should be an
automatic out.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, can't managers make pitching changes from
the dugout? Give them bullhorns or flash cards, anything to keep
them off the field.  &LR; subheds:MOVIE SNEAK PREVIEW  &LR; body:The
Replacements: With Keanu Reeves looking like Scott Zolak, Gene
Hackman in full ``Hoosiers'' mode under a straw fedora, and more
gratuitous cheerleader cleavage than a Dallas Cowboys sideline,
this latest dive play into the football flick genre is more corny
than the Fletcher's booth on an October Saturday in Dallas' Fair
Park. Along with the other banalities, eclectic scab players from
Sumo wrestlers to deaf tight ends bond, the old coach gets back his
reputation and the has-been quarterback gets the girl. The only
hint of reality: Washington edges Dallas in the climactic game.
 &LR; subheds:END OF THE END  &LR; body:More dumbfounding: The
Cowboys/Mavericks needing a combined 31 assistant coaches, or the
King of Hearts being the only one without a mustache? ... All those
negative Cowboys losses (Michael Irvin, Daryl Johnston, Erik
Williams, Kevin Smith, Deion Sanders, Toby Gowin, Eddie Murray,
Randall Godfrey, Eric Bjornson and Jason Garrett) are balanced by
one positive departure (Chan Gailey). ... Got this friend who's
always asking to be Frank (Zaccanelli) with me, and he says the
reason the NBA's human logo retired is because the Lakers
transformed Jerry West into Jerry Stressed.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
