<HEADLINE>
AN `AMAZING' REACTION TO LAST-PLACE FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The loudest cheer of Friday's morning 200-meter
butterfly prelims at the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials came not for
one of the heat winners, but for Austin's Isaac Grombacher, who
finished in last place.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Austin St. Stephens, Grombacher went to
Texas and majored in mechanical engineering, but did not swim for
the Longhorns. He stayed in the sport through the Austin-based swim
club, Texas Aquatics.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Grombacher began to experience headaches. A month
later, doctors discovered a brain tumor. Grombacher underwent
surgery on May 8, and though the tumor proved to be benign, he was
paralyzed on the left side of his body for two weeks after the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Since he had already qualified to compete, Grombach said,
``Swimming at the trials became my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   As he swam in his preliminary-round heat Friday, the announcer
at the IU Natatorium told Isaac's story to the audience. What
started out as respectful applause became a roar as Grombacher,
swimming in last place, neared the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I touched the wall, I heard this amazing sound,'' said
Grombacher, whose time was 2 minutes, 14.40 seconds. ``It was one
of the best feelings of my life. The whole time I was in the
hospital, I never dreamed it would be like this. It was just
amazing.'' CRAMPING TORRES WITHDRAWS
</P>
<P>
   One day after making the Olympic team in the women's 100-meter
butterfly, Dara Torres of Palo Alto, Calif., experienced cramping
and was forced to withdraw from the semifinals of Friday night's
200-meter freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dara has a history of severe uterine cramping during long
races such as this one,'' said Dr. Glen Luepnitz of the Stanford
Swim Club. ``The cramping can be debilitating.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres had hoped to finish in the top six of the event in order
to qualify for the 4x200 relay in Sydney. She won her heat with the
morning's fifth-fastest time, 2:01.04, but began to get chills
during her warmdown.
</P>
<P>
   She is expected to still compete in Sunday's preliminaries of
the 100-meter freestyle. The rules allow Torres to petition to the
Olympic head coach for a spot in the relay. The coach happens to be
her personal one, former Texas coach Richard Quick.
</P>
<P>
   Cristina Teuscher, who earned a relay gold medal at the Atlanta
Olympics, also scratched from the 200 free semis in order to
concentrate on the 200-meter individual medley.
</P>
<P>
   The scratches opened up a spot in 200 free semis for Texas A&AMP;M's
Monica Williams. She is the daughter of Boston Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams. A native of Dunedin, Fla., Monica swam 2:03.23 and
finished 14th, failing to qualify for the finals. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
