<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMMIN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAYZELBURG NEARLY TOPS RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INDIANAPOLIS _ When Tom Sorensen was cut this week from the
U.S. Olympic indoor volleyball team, his fiancee could sympathize.
Oh, boy, could she ever.
</P>
<P>
   Twice B.J. Bedford had competed in the U.S. Olympic Swimming
Trials, but she never had made it to the Summer Games. In 1992, the
future Mrs. Sorensen finished seventh in the 100-meter backstroke.
In 1996, she placed third, missing a berth to Atlanta by a single
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the fine china, Sorensen and Bedford figured they'd
be registering for ``gold galore'' this month.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, they got what they wanted: an Olympic place-setting.
Bedford had to pay a hefty price for it physically, but she won the
100 backstroke at the Trials at IUPUI. She threw up before the race
and her fatigued muscles were on fire the last 10 meters. And yet
she somehow managed to stay ahead of Courtney Shealy, 1996 Olympian
Lea Maurer and Irvine's Diana MacManus, all three of whom were
separated by just .28 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to do is look at the clock and see who won,''
Bedford said. ''
</P>
<P>
   It was a pretty safe bet that Lenny Krayzelburg would win the
100 backstroke after he came within .07 seconds of his world record
in Thursday's semifinals. He did indeed win, but his final time of
53.84 was .24 seconds slower than his one-year-old global mark.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg's teammate, Kristine Quance-Julian, had the
ninth-fastest semifinal swim in the 200-meter individual medley and
is the first alternate for tonight's final.
</P>
<P>
   The Granada Hills High product will get one more shot at the
event only if someone ahead of her bows out. (It could happen; Dara
Torres had to scratch from the semifinals of the 200 freestyle when
she suffered severe uterine cramps after her preliminary race.)
</P>
<P>
   Quance-Julian is trying to make her second Olympic team 18
months after giving birth to a son. Josh Davis, who broke the
12-year-old American record in the 200-meter freestyle, is another
1996 Olympian who has become a parent over the ensuing four years.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife are expecting their third child around the time
Davis will be trying to deliver a gold medal to the U.S. in Sydney.
Accordingly, his wife is planning to have her labor induced in
Austin, Texas, in early September, before the U.S. team leaves for
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Shealy knows a thing or two about overlapping schedules. For the
past three falls, the recent Georgia graduate juggled varsity
volleyball and varsity swimming. ``I'm glad I'm 6-3 right now,''
Shealy said after touching out the 5-foot-6 Maurer.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Quann is glad she'll be able to start trimming miles from
her training regimen soon, in preparation for an Olympic
breaststroke competition that will pit her against South Africa's
Penny Heyns, the world-record holder in the 100 and 200.
</P>
<P>
   While the majority of the 1,309 competitors here cut back
dramatically on their training in the days leading to the meet,
Quann bragged about having swum 20,000 meters a day up until her
100 preliminary race.
</P>
<P>
   Quann spoke for every newly crowned Olympian when she said:
``This is the time of my life. I just made the Olympics!''
</P>
<P>
   Then she said something that might come back to haunt her.
Talking as though she was reading from track star Michael Johnson's
Olympic Trials diary for USA Today, she said, ``Penny, she's going
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg can't wait to go Down Under again; last August, he
set world records in the 50 (a non-Olympic event), 100 and 200
backstrokes at the same pool that will play host to the Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   His competitiveness cost him a world record Friday. Runner-up
Neil Walker blasted out of the blocks and Krayzelburg went out with
him, sheepishly explaining, ``I don't want Neil to get to the wall
first, even at the 50.''
</P>
<P>
   After tightening up the final 10 meters, he said, ``It's just a
learning experience for Sydney.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
