<SLUG> BC-PROTEST-DNC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS UNITED IN SEARCH FOR DEMOCRACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JORDAN SMITH 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ They're not making speeches or writing the
Democratic party platform, but the 10,000 to 50,000 protesters
expected at the Democratic National Convention will try to play an
influential role.
</P>
<P>
   And because the West Coast activist community is highly
organized, protesters said, they expect a larger turnout next week
than what showed up in Philadelphia earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   But what, exactly, are the activists protesting?
</P>
<P>
   The days of single issues - like civil rights or anti-war
movements - are over. Today's activists are protesting a long list
of issues from ending the death penalty to halting dam
construction.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one theme unifies them: democracy, they said, has
been taken over by corporate interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real overwhelming issue here is human needs not corporate
greed,'' said Medea Benjamin, founding director of Global Exchange.
``We've got to get the big money out of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Global Exchange, which focuses on fair trade issues and
immigrant rights, is hosting downtown ``Reality Tours'' to point
out the effects of global trade on Los Angeles - from garment
district sweatshops to examples of environmental racism, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Special interests, they said, have overshadowed citizens in the
democratic process, yet this week they'll speak with voices heard
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate interests siphon money from public schools, said Luis
Sanchez of the L.A.-based Youth Organizing Communities, creating
overcrowded classrooms and a scarcity of resources in lower-income
areas, as well as allowing construction of potentially
environmentally unsafe schools - like the Belmont Learning Center,
the nation's costliest school that was abandoned half-built.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what's happening in our schools and who is funding
these campaigns,'' he said. ``There is a direct correlation between
this and the dumbing down of California education.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez and Benjamin said their groups will participate in
nearly all organized marches planned for next week.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Becker of the New York-based International Action
Center, said most groups will participate in the majority of
protests, regardless of whether their individual issues are
directly addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a definite correlation between progress and the
strength of people's movements,'' he said. ``This is the continued
emergence of a new movement started in Seattle and Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparked by concerns over extensive property damage and arrests
in Seattle last fall and in Washington, D.C., this spring, the
D2KLA protest planning group developed a four-part nonviolence
agreement that activists participating in organized events must
sign - the agreement includes a ban on property destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, activists can't control what individuals do on their own,
Becker said, and most protesters distinguish between violence
toward people and property destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking a window is not the same as beating a person, said Han
Shan of the Ruckus Society, the Berkeley-based activist training
group. Equating the two, he said, degrades the value of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Property destruction does scare people, though, and we don't
want people to think this revolution is scary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9632 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ANARCHY-CONVENTION-LA     08-12 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANARCHY-CONVENTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANARCHISTS' CONVENTION OPENS, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The Anarchists Convention kicked off Friday with
security guards on watch for police and about 200 people crammed in
a stifling hot Elysian Park studio.
</P>
<P>
   Blamed for violence and vandalism during Seattle and Washington,
D.C., protests, delegates to the North American Anarchist
Conference meeting in Los Angeles for the Democratic National
Convention started their own convention by embracing each other.
</P>
<P>
   And their first seminar: ``Embrace - Group Affection Workshop.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door, graying anarchist Jay Brophy sat in a wicker chair to
discuss ``Liberation Pedagogy,'' telling the spike-haired, black-
and red-dressed anarchists that ``the schools are where the
potential for doing revolutionary work is the greatest.''
</P>
<P>
   For those with two-wheeled transportation, a fellow who gave his
name only as Randy taught the art of Zen and bike repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to disappoint the corporate media, but all we're doing
is having workshops,'' said an anarchist whose name tag read
``Idiot.'' ``I don't think bike repair is the same as throwing
bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference runs through Sunday and is taking place at 2431
Eads St.
</P>
<P>
   Anarchists insisted they have not planned any ``organized''
protests. They said they plan to participate in nonviolent
demonstrations to protest corporate greed and to advocate their
philosophy, which calls for a radical reorganization of society.
</P>
<P>
   Anarchists believe people should live by principles of mutual
aid and cooperation and that hierarchy and all forms of social
domination are unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz of the convention was over whether the rumors were
true: Would police harass anyone wearing a circle-A anarchist logo
or people dressed in black?
</P>
<P>
   ``They say anyone wearing a circle-A will be stopped,'' he said.
``We're starting a new kind of scare. It's not the red scare. It's
the black scare.''
</P>
<P>
   An anarchist guard, who refused to identify himself in any way,
said security is necessary because ``our movement is extreme - it's
calling to destroy the complacency of everyday people because they
are afraid to embrace the potential of their own autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Brophy, a self-described '70s hippy-turned-anarchist, said
anarchists in Seattle committed acts of vandalism by breaking
corporate building windows only after ``police rioted,'' spraying
people with pepper spray and clubbing them.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects a similar reaction during the convention
here. ``The police will probably riot,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the conference, a La Crescenta mother waited for her
daughter to emerge. She told her mother she`d only go in briefly
but had been gone 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Mom, don't come in. They don't like the
establishment.' I said, oh, that's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
