<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEFEAT AND A SCARE: RANGERS' GLYNN PASSES OUT IN DUGOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers received a major scare last
night, when Ryan Glynn, the most promising of the team's young
starting pitchers, passed out in the dugout after being pulled from
the game in the fifth inning of a 7-3 loss to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn was unconscious briefly on the floor of the dugout at The
Ballpark in Arlington, and was attended to by the team's trainers
before paramedics arrived. He regained consciousness, and was alert
when he was taken to Arlington Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He was admitted to the hospital, and was expected to remain
there overnight for observation and a variety of tests.
</P>
<P>
   No reason was given for his collapse, but the stifling heat is
believed to be a factor. It was 98 degrees at game time, with
little or no breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind,'' manager Johnny Oates said of
the heat being the cause. ``I didn't feel too good, and all I did
was sit there and drink liquids all night.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident happened after right-hander, 25, had pitched the
first 42/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn had little problems in the first three innings, but he
allowed all seven Boston runs in the fourth and fifth. Catcher Bill
Haselman noticed from Glynn's pitching mechanics that something was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see it,'' Haselman said. ``He just seemed to be a
little different after the third inning. He was throwing the ball
around the plate, and then he was nowhere near the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Luis Alicea went to the mound to ask him if he
was OK.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve outfielder Scarborough Green said he noticed something
when Glynn came out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just looked a little wobbly when he came off the mound,''
Green said. ``I remember saying he didn't look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Green watched until Glynn got a drink of water and sat down, and
assumed he was all right, but it soon became obvious he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Frank Catalanotto was sitting to Glynn's left
when the pitcher collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I felt him touch me as he fell,'' Catalanotto said.
``I thought he might have tripped or something, but he was lying
there unconscious. It was really scary for me. I yelled down to the
security guard to radio for someone. It was a scary experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Glynn threw 95 pitches before being relieved. He collapsed while
reliever Doug Davis still was trying to get out of the fifth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have no idea,'' pitcher Kenny Rogers said. ``It's hot
out there, boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength-sapping heat might have been a factor in Glynn's
worst outing in a while. He allowed all seven Red Sox runs (five
earned) on eight hits, including two long home runs by Carl
Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn was 2-0 with a 3.00 ERA in his previous three starts, and
earned accolades from Oates before the game for the way he was
learning to pitch at the major-league level.
</P>
<P>
   He started out strongly again last night, with three shutout
innings, and appeared to be on his way to another effective outing.
</P>
<P>
   He showed some grit by pitching out of trouble after Nomar
Garciaparra doubled to lead off the second and moved to third on a
grounder to second by Troy O'Leary. Glynn stranded him there by
getting Brian Daubach on a foul pop to first, and Ed Sprague on a
fly to right.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth and fifth, the Red Sox began to tee off.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn walked Scott Hatteberg to lead off the fourth, and Everett
followed with his first homer, a shot into the upper deck in right
field. Garciaparra then reached second on an infield single and an
error by third baseman Mike Lamb, and scored on a single by
O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox added four runs in the fifth, when they batted
around. Trot Nixon drove in the first run with a single, and
Everett knocked in the next three with a 418-foot homer to center
field.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn was pulled after getting Garciaparra on a fly to center
and giving up a single to O'Leary. A couple of minutes later, he
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed for 10 minutes while Glynn received medical
attention. He was sitting up when he was wheeled out of the dugout
and taken to an ambulance. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
