<HEADLINE>
SMALLISH COWBOYS LINEBACKER COAKLEY COMING UP BIG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ For as long as he can remember, Dallas
Cowboys weakside linebacker Dexter Coakley has been defined by his
height.
</P>
<P>
   Or lack there of.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley _ generously listed at 5-foot-10 in the Cowboys media
guide, though he is actually closer to 5-8 _ might as well have
added ``undersized'' to his name.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what he did on the football field, the 228-pound
Coakley was never able to escape the stigma of being considered an
oddity because of his atypical linebacker size.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley's 1999 campaign _ a team-high four interceptions, a
second-best 131 tackles and All-Pro honors _ has made him a novelty
no more.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year veteran heads into the 2000 season simply
regarded as a football player. And a very good one at that.
</P>
<P>
   He calls it a dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a definitely a great feeling,'' Coakley said. ``All my
career I've always been dealing with `is he big enough?' and `can
he get the job done?'. I've used that as a burning fire. I used
that as fuel that was thrown on that fire constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've ever wanted was people to accept me as a football
player. It's a great a feeling to know that you are now looked upon
as a football player, not a short guy who is probably not capable
enough to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have never questioned Coakley's ability. After
drafting the unknown Appalachian State product in third round of
the 1997 draft, Cowboys chief scout Larry Lacewell remarked that
the Cowboys got him to play football not ``change light bulbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Coakley has done nothing but play football since his arrival in
Dallas. As a rookie, he won the starting weakside linebacker job
before the team broke training camp. He set a Cowboys rookie record
with 136 stops, earning consensus all-Rookie honors.
</P>
<P>
   He has simply gotten better each year since, culminating with
last season's award-winning performance. Coakley was the first
Cowboys linebacker to play in the Pro Bowl since Ken Norton in 1993
and the first to lead the team in interceptions since Eugene
Lockhart in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys assistant coach Tommie Robinson said skeptics should
have been measuring Coakley's heart and talent instead of his
height.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley, who has exceeded expectations throughout his NFL
career, could be the fastest linebacker in the league. The former
high school running back has run the 40-yard dash in 4.28 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger is not better; better is better,'' Robinson said.
``Dexter is a great football player. He is talented, and nobody
works harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Coakley said he was inspired by Sam Mills and Zach Thomas, two
other small linebackers who have achieved greatness despite their
size. He said he hopes he is an example to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I am,'' he said. ``I hope I'm following in that same
mold (of Mills and Thomas). People told me I couldn't get it done,
and I'm proving them all wrong. I want people to learn from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coakley already has a disciple in Cowboys middle linebacker Dat
Nguyen (5-11, 230), who is facing similar questions about his size
as he heads into his first year as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy who paved the road for myself to get me an
opportunity to have a chance to be where I am,'' Nguyen said.
``He's been going through obstacles all his life. He's definitely a
guy I look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Coakley is pleased with his play last season and his new-found
level of respect; however, he says he is not satisfied. He says he
still has a lot of work to do and goals to reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get back to the Pro Bowl,'' Coakley said.
``Hopefully I can achieve greatness in this league. But I've still
got a lot of improvement to do. This is just the tip of the iceberg
on what I'm capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   What Coakley says he refuses to worry about, however, is owner
Jerry Jones' tradition of not paying linebackers top salaries. A
free agent after the season, Coakley understands that he could be
out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley, who could command roughly $5 million a year on the open
market next season, points to his $1.027 million contract in 2000,
which is the highest for a linebacker in team history, as a glimmer
of hope. He's trusting that his on-field play will prompt the
Cowboys to alter their philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Departed linebackers Randall Godfrey, Dixon Edwards, Darrin
Smith and Norton all thought the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Coakley, however, has made a career out of breaking down
barriers. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
