<HEADLINE>
KAPLER EXTENDS STREAK TO 24 GAMES TO TIE CLUB RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ On a night when he became a part of Rangers
history and also stranded three runners on base for the final out
in a 7-3 loss to the Boston Red Sox, Rangers center fielder Gabe
Kapler was calm in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel comfortable and I feel confident,'' said Kapler, who
tied Mickey Rivers' record for hitting safely in 24 consecutive
games. ``I feel great at the plate. The ball feels like it's coming
in slow motion. I feel no pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last at-bat, Kapler hit a slow line drive to second
baseman Mike Lansing to end the game, but it was his second-to-last
at-bat, a single up the middle, that put him in the Rangers' record
books.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the bottom of the eighth inning, all eyes at the
Ballpark in Arlington were on Kapler. Hitless in his previous three
at-bats, Kapler's 23-game hitting streak was in jeopardy and the
crowd cheered loudly.
</P>
<P>
   They also booed loudly when the count reached 3-0 in
anticipation of what was sure to be a walk and the end of his
hitting streak. But Kapler singled to tie the record and keep the
streak alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately that ball got under \RRed Sox shortstop\S Nomar
\RGarciaparra\S,'' Kapler said. ``But I would have traded a hit for
a couple of RBI in key situations tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler's 24-game hitting streak ties the longest hitting streak
in the major leagues this season and Rivers' 20-year record. Tony
Womack of Arizona also hit in 24 consecutive games from May 2-29
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler ended the first inning on a fielder's choice to
Garciaparra. A slow line drive to right field in the fourth inning
was followed by another ground out to Garciaparra in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Before last night's performance, Kapler was 34-of-93, with six
home runs and 19 runs batted in during his streak. He raised his
batting average from .241 to .281.
</P>
<P>
   After Kapler's single, Rangers first base coach Bobby Jones
tossed the ball into the dugout.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
