<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SLOAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS, SLOAN READY TO FACE ARBITER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stars will venture into previously untested waters this
morning when they meet winger Blake Sloan in a franchise-first
arbitration hearing in the hope of settling a contract impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan filed for arbitration this summer after the Stars extended
him a qualifying offer that would give him a 10 percent raise from
his salary of $357,000 last season if he plays the entire season
with the Stars. But he'd be paid significantly less for any time
spent playing for their minor-league affiliate, the Utah Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   The contract the Stars offered is called a two-way contract.
Sloan wants a one-way contract that would guarantee him his salary
no matter whether he played for the Stars or the Grizzlies this
season. Sloan played 67 of 82 games, all for the Stars, last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clear picture of how we view him as a player as does
he,'' Stars general Bob Gainey said. ``Somebody else will decide
and then we'll move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey said he didn't foresee an agreement being reached before
this morning although both sides have talked.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the decision, the Stars will have a contract with their
last unsigned player from last season within the next 48 hours. The
arbitrator has that long to give a ruling. But Gainey said the
team's roster is in no way finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be looking to add some players,'' Gainey said, noting a
defenseman and at least one more forward, ``sounded right. ... We
told everybody we're in a waiting period until we got all our
players signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the Stars added one new player, acquiring right
winger David Ling from the Chicago Blackhawks for future
considerations. The 5-foot-9, 185-pound Ling, 25, spent the past
two seasons with the Kansas City Blades of the International Hockey
League. He was ninth-round selection of the Quebec Nordiques in the
1993 NHL Entry Draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also have been talking to several free agents _
defenseman Dave Manson and forwards Claude Lemieux, Ted Donato and
Stephane Richer. The Stars' training camp begins Sept. 9 in Vail,
Colo., and their first exhibition is scheduled for Sept. 14 against
Colorado in Denver.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
