<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' GREG ELLIS AHEAD OF SCHEDULE IN RETURN FROM LEG INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cowboys defensive end Greg Ellis is ``one
week ahead of schedule,'' head coach Dave Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, who will probably get in some preseason game work (either
Aug. 19 at Denver or Aug. 24 vs. St. Louis) because of his
progress, returned to team practice this week for the first time
since breaking his left leg in two places eight months ago today.
It was one week earlier than either the medical or
strength/conditioning staffs expected.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing it as a psychological breakthrough as much as a physical
accomplishment, Ellis felt he passed the so-called ``flinch test''
with flying colors.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this week, including team drills during yesterday's second
practice, the third-year player found 300-pound bodies caving in
around his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time it went through my head: `Let's make
sure nobody rolls into it.' It wasn't like I was scared or nothing.
... I pretty much was just being smart about the whole deal,'' said
Ellis, who suffered the career-threatening injury Dec. 12 against
Philadelphia and has a titanium rod in his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is expected to be ready for the Cowboys' Sept. 3
regular-season opener against Philadelphia. He finished the week
with soreness in his leg and throughout his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's to be expected,'' he said. ``Thank God I'm just able to
do everything as if nothing ever happened.'' \Nsubheds:Harris to
hold in a pinch Tight end Jackie Harris yesterday joined Randall
Cunningham as an emergency backup holder to rookie Micah Knorr, who
has the inside track for the punting job. The Cowboys are making
sure they have a holder on field goals and extra points who will be
active each game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got accused of having pretty decent hands,'' laughed Harris,
who says he will take a couple of reps after each practice until he
feels confident. ``I've never-ever in my entire football life done
this.'' \Nsubheds:Justin No. 4 Paul Justin is expected to be the
fourth quarterback to play against the Oakland Raiders tomorrow
night, following rookie Clint Stoerner.
</P>
<P>
   Campo explained that the coaches want to see Stoerner work with
and against something other than bottom-rung players, adding that
flip-flopping the order is not a reflection on Justin, even though
he has six turnovers (four interceptions, two lost fumbles) in two
games.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about job security, Justin, 32, replied, ``I don't
even think about it. I've just got to get going. It's pretty
black-and-white: Eliminate turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Justin's fourth team in four years. He doesn't feel that
he's pressing, although he said he is frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to the guys all the time. Sometimes, I get tired of
talking,'' Justin said. ``We've just got to produce as a group, and
we haven't done that in the first two games.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
