<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARAMILLO HIRING CONTINUES TO BE A HIT FOR OATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It was just supposed to be breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Some bacon and eggs, a couple of slices of wheat toast with a
little strawberry jam. Two or three cups of coffee and a polite,
``Don't call us, we'll call you,'' line to wrap things up.
</P>
<P>
   That's what new Texas manager Johnny Oates was thinking when he
agreed to interview Rudy Jaramillo in October 1994. After all,
Oates already had two other candidates in mind to be his first
Rangers' hitting coach. This would be a simple courtesy meeting to
satisfy a whim of general manager Doug Melvin's.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours later, the Rangers' new skipper had made what might
have been the most fortuitous hire of his managerial career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He blew me away,'' Oates recalled, retelling what has become
an almost legendary story in Rangers circles. ``I had to tip the
waitress for two meals, we were in the (hotel) restaurant for so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Going on six years later, Jaramillo might just be the best
hitting coach in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been six years and the horses keep changing,'' Oates said
before Friday night's opener of a six-game homestand against the
Red Sox at The Ballpark in Arlington, ``but we keep getting the
field plowed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Oates' colorful way of saying that the players come and
go, but the Rangers continue to remain at or near the top of the
American League charts in hitting.
</P>
<P>
   They started play Friday night ranked second in the league in
hitting at .290. If they can catch the White Sox (.293) before
season's end, Jaramillo's hitters will have led the league three
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to spring training this year we'd lost Juan
(Gonzalez), Lee Stevens, Todd Zeile, (Mark) McLemore, (Roberto)
Kelly and (Tom) Goodwin,'' Jaramillo said. ``That was a lot of RBIs
gone, but on the first day I told them I didn't expect any less
from the offense and that the standards were going to stay the same
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's no .350-hitting Pudge Rodriguez and no .340-hitting
David Segui either. No matter. The hottest hitter in baseball
during the past three-plus weeks has been Jaramillo's latest star
pupil, Gabe Kapler.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing gains notoriety for a hitting coach like turning around
a player like Kapler, who hit only .245 last season in Detroit and
fell into a deep slump early this season shortly after belting two
home runs on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   That was the same Kapler who, with an eighth-inning single
Friday night, extended his hitting streak to 24 games, tying Mickey
Rivers' club record and matching the Arizona Diamondbacks' Tony
Womack for the longest streak in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jaramillo who suggested the leg kick that Kapler now uses
to trigger his swing, allowing him to stay back and wait longer on
the pitch before committing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finds different approaches for different hitters,'' Kapler
said. ``The worst possible thing is a guy who thinks there's only
one way to hit. You look around this room and Pudge is successful
in a different way than Raffy is, who's successful in a different
way than Cat (Frank Catalanotto) is, or Luis (Alicea).
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody finds their own way to be successful. If you have a
hitting coach who teaches one way, and your way isn't their way ...
ooh. It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The late Charlie Lau was a huge success in Kansas City teaching
weight shift and power position. Walt Hriniak had success in Boston
and Chicago with his emphasis on keeping the head down and swinging
through the ball, but Kapler says both techniques are universal for
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy never says, `This is the only way to do it.' He says,
`We're going to find a way to make this click and if one way
doesn't do it, we'll try something else.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of a hitting coach among the players shows when
they leave a club for whatever reason but can't wait to re-visit
their old guru.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys who have played here and had success and then left, when
we go on the road they all want to talk to Rudy,'' Alicea said.
``When we were in Cleveland, Segui was saying, ``Ohhh, I need to go
see Rudy.' He can't do anything for them now because they're in
other organizations, but they miss him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo teaches his hitters five basic points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to see the ball, you have to have rhythm and timing,
you've got to separate (the trigger mechanism from the swing), you
have to stay square (to the plate) and you have to transfer your
weight,'' Jaramillo said. ``We feed off those five roots. That's
what simplifies it for the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he the best hitting coach in the game? It's a question the
former Dallas Sunset and University of Texas star outfielder meets
in his typical head-on style.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good hitting coaches,'' he said, ``but I
don't doubt myself in any way. I want to be the best. I strive to
be the best and that's the same attitude I try to give my
players.''
</P>
<P>
   For Oates, it's an easy answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he the best? In my mind he is because I hired him,'' Oates
said, ``and the results speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates might, in fact, want to visit that same hotel restaurant
next to The Ballpark and drop a little more tip money on the table.
</P>
<P>
   It was, without a doubt, the best breakfast-turned-into-lunch he
has ever had. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
