<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-DIAMONDS (Yellowknife, Northwest Territories) _ By 2005,
the Northwest Territories is expected to produce as much as 15
percent of the world's diamonds and Canada will then join the ranks
of the world's top five diamond producers. With this future on the
horizon, officials are taking the lead now to protect the future
image of diamonds by suppressing the trafficking in uncut stones
that helps to fund guerrilla armies in Sierra Leone and Angola. By
James Brooke. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ A look at the maneuvering going on
between Israelis and Palestinians on the post-Camp David prospects
for a new summit; and at Prime Minister Ehud Barak's continuing
efforts to create a new coalition. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Undated) _ With wildfires still burning out of
control across a dozen Western states in what may be the worst fire
season in a generation, a fierce debate in timber politics has
begun to rage over who might be to blame. By Douglas Jehl. 1,600
words.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-STAMPS-STATES (Undated) _ In California, New York and 27
other states, people applying for food stamps are asked if they own
a burial plot. Nebraska and Nevada want to know if applicants have
sold their blood, and for how much. Hawaii demands garage sale
receipts, South Dakota wants documentation of past bingo winnings,
and Minnesota, on page 20 of a 36-page eligibility application,
asks if anyone in the household gets money from a paper route. Food
stamp applications in most states have become so onerous that they
are deterring needy people from applying for the subsidies, the
most comprehensive analysis of the applications has found. By Nina
Bernstein. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY (Undated) _ When top executives leave large corporations
before their contracts are up, the corporations reward or punish
them financially in different ways, depending in part on how well
the officer has done and why the officer is leaving. Given that
Halliburton Co., which Dick Cheney is leaving to run for vice
president, did not do extraordinarily well in his five years there,
what does that say about how Halliburton will treat Cheney's
departure? By Diana B. Henriques, Lowell Bergman and Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ASSESS (Washington) _ News Analysis: The five-party
system of Democrats, Republicans, Greens and two Reform parties is
something new in American politics and right now it's helping Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas in important ways. By Adam Clymer.
(Editors, this story originally budgeted as REFORM-PARTY-ASSESS.)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the
potential impact of the Reform Party and the Green Party on the
political fortunes of the major party candidates. By Adam Cymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JOB-STRESS-UNIONS (Undated) _ Work that makes people feel like
idiots is hardly the stuff that brought organized labor to the
barricades in the past. The famous labor struggles of American
history call to mind collapsing mineshafts and machine gunners
posted on factory roofs, not mandatory telephone sign-offs recited
in attractive, air-conditioned offices. Yet Verizon's customer
service representatives say that even in their comfortable,
well-lighted call centers, stress has become a striking point. And
some observers think the Verizon workers may be making the
complaint at a time of heightened public receptivity. By Mary
Williams Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ During the strike at Verizon
Communications, about 30,000 managers have been filling in for more
than 86,000 unionized workers at Verizon offices from Maine to
Virginia, pinch-hitting on union jobs that range from answering 411
calls to fixing aerial cables. And after several days of the work,
many of them said that while they were not siding with the unions,
they had a new appreciation for the work of their members. By
Edward Wong.
</P>
<P>
   SOROS-CAPITALISM (Undated) _ George Soros, one of the world's
most successful speculators and richest men, has come as close as
anyone to personifying the spread of global capitalism and the
power of international financial markets. So, in 1998, when he
wrote a book predicting the imminent ``disintegration of the global
capitalist system,'' his views caused quite a stir. Two years
later, the global economy is still kicking, and, in a new book,
Soros is taking back his grave forecasts. By David D. Kirkpatrick.
</P>
