r a BC-CLINTON-INLA-LADN     08-12 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT RAISES BIG BUCKS FOR LIBRARY, HILLARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Bill Clinton swept into Los Angeles on Friday to
kick off the Democratic National Convention with a celebration of
his eight years as president and to do what he does best - raise
money and campaign for votes.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop for Clinton was at a fund-raiser for the
re-election campaign of Rep. Xavier Becerra, D-Los Angeles, where
aides estimated more than $100,000 was collected for the Nov. 7
race even as the congressman is planning to run for Los Angeles
mayor next April.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also championed Vice President Al Gore as an experienced
and worthy successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked closer with Al Gore than anyone,'' Clinton said.
``I know this man. He is willing to make the tough decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarred by bitter partisanship during his presidency, Clinton
urged both Democrats and Republicans to take the high road in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say that they are honorable people and treat them
that way. We have to put an end to the politics of personal
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean we can't have an honest debate on our
differences. The other side doesn't want that. They say it's
negative campaigning when we talk about how they voted in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   With thousands of delegates from across the country due to
arrive today for the start of the convention on Monday, the big
events for Clinton and first lady Hillary Clinton, a New York
Senate candidate, are scheduled throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   An event at the home of entertainer Barbra Streisand - at
$100,000 a couple, minimum - is expected to raise some $10 million
for the Bill Clinton Presidential Library.
</P>
<P>
   A second event is expected to raise between $2.5 million and $4
million for first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's bid for the U.S.
Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles and this state have been very kind to me and mine
and my administration,'' Clinton said at one point. Also, jokingly,
he noted: ``California has two women Senators. I think New York
should have at least one.''
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the president's fund-raising during the convention
has raised some concerns among other Democrats about whether he was
taking so much that Vice President Al Gore will be left
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   California Democratic Party chairman Art Torres said he was not
surprised at what Clinton was doing and understood the reasons for
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his last convention and is his only opportunity to
raise the money he needs for his library,'' Torres said. ``Former
President Bush did the same thing. It's what presidents do.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Torres said, California already has been generous with
Gore and will continue to support his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in praise of Gore, as he has in the past, Clinton said
the vice president provided his full backing during difficult
times, such as deciding whether to make loans to Mexico and whether
to get American troops involved in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And the president credited Gore with helping him to guide
economic prosperity that has flourished under his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time we had this sustained level of economic
prosperity was 1960-1961,'' Clinton said. ``Everyone thought we
were on automatic pilot. Well, we weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Republicans, the nation underwent the worst recession
since the Great Depression, he said, as he criticized proposals to
use all of a national projected surplus for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he told the crowd of 400 at the buffet reception for
Becerra, other factors were involved.
</P>
<P>
   If he had a Democratic-controlled Congress, Clinton said he
could have pushed through stronger Social Security protections, a
patient's bill of rights, prescription drug benefits and stronger
gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
