u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      08-12 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANAHEIM'S LEFT-HANDERS DEAL HERNANDEZ DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It was 1998 and the worst start of Orlando
Hernandez's career. It also could have been the best thing that
happened to him. Their lineup stocked with left-handed hitters, the
Anaheim Angels peppered El Duque for 13 hits and 10 runs in 3 1/3
innings here two years ago, incontrovertible evidence that
Hernandez had to change his approach and pitch inside more.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque is having more trouble with left-handed batters lately,
a problem illuminated once more by the Angels, who thumped the
Yankees by 8-3 Friday night. Mo Vaughn and Garret Anderson each had
two-run doubles for Anaheim, and the Yankees' lead over the Boston
Red Sox in the American League East was trimmed to four games.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it seems Hernandez has been unable to pitch inside to
left-handers, rather than unwilling. He threw 71 pitches to
left-handers in the first five innings, and not once did any of the
Anaheim lefties swing and miss. Hernandez (8-9) allowed nine hits
and seven runs in 6 1/3 innings, and he has replaced David Cone as
the Yankees' most notable pitching puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has always been more effective against right-handed
batters than lefties because he can entice right-handers to flail
at his slider. But his slider is not nearly as dangerous against
left-handers, and Hernandez has had to find other ways to finish
them off.
</P>
<P>
   After learning a lesson here two years ago, he starting jamming
lefties with fastballs, mixing them up with changeups and slow
curveballs. Lately, however, Hernandez has struggled to control his
fastball and his changeup when throwing to lefties, and has been
getting knocked around.
</P>
<P>
   When Seattle beat El Duque last weekend, left-handed batters
reached base in 6 of 14 plate appearances; Friday night, lefties
reached base in 10 of their first 18 plate appearances, a .556
on-base percentage. The Angels scored four runs in the first inning
against Hernandez, on a single by Darin Erstad, a walk issued to
Orlando Palmeiro, Vaughn's two-run double, and run-scoring hits by
Garret Anderson and Adam Kennedy _ all left-handed batters. Two
right-handed batters hit in the inning; Tim Salmon and Troy Glaus
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   When the half-inning finally ended, after 30 pitches, catcher
Jorge Posada got a quick lecture from manager Joe Torre and
Hernandez rested on the bench, a white towel draped around his
neck, looking like a boxer at the end of a brutal first round.
Billy Connors, the Yankees' interim pitching coach, played the role
of trainer, standing directly before Hernandez, placing his hands
lightly on each of Hernandez's legs, speaking to his pitcher.
Hernandez sometimes glanced at Connors, but mostly looked away,
frustrated. He pitched inside more often to left-handed batters
thereafter, with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees appeared on the verge of a comeback several times
against Scott Schoeneweis, the Anaheim starter. But they stranded
two runners in the second inning and scored one run and left
another runner in scoring position in the third. Glenallen Hill
rocketed a ball to right-center in the fourth, with a runner at
first, and the ball disappeared into the stands. But Mike Reilly,
the first-base umpire, immediately signaled fan interference,
ruling that an Edison Field patron had reached out from the
grandstand, over the playing field, and pulled Hill's drive into
the stands; the replay showed his call was correct.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had runners on second and third with nobody out.
First baseman Tino Martinez took a called third strike, turned and
argued with the home plate umpire Laz Diaz, who had a number of
exchanges with hitters from both teams. Scott Brosius took a called
third strike, and he turned and gawked at Diaz incredulously. When
Luis Sojo lined out to end a rally that resulted in no runs,
Brosius flung a cup of water and took an angry swipe at a cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams bashed a two-run homer the next inning, cutting
the Anaheim lead to 4-3. The Angels' left-handed batters responded
in the bottom of the fifth: Erstad reached out and poked a looping
double inside the left-field line, and Vaughn walked with one out.
After a fielder's choice groundout, Hernandez got ahead on the
count to Anderson, no balls and two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Needing one pitch to stifle the Angels' rally, Hernandez tried
nicking the outside corner with a breaking ball, but when it
drifted over the plate, Anderson reached out to pull a line drive
to right-center field. As Vaughn rounded third, he waved an arm,
beckoning Salmon to follow, both scoring easily to give Anaheim a
6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees threatened in the seventh. After Williams singled
with two out, pushing Posada to second base, the right-hander Mike
Fhyrie came in to pitch and worked carefully to the right-handed
Jose Canseco, walking the slugger on four pitches. The bases were
loaded, but Fhyrie got out of the inning when Hill flied to right.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad collected his third hit of the game, his 180th hit of the
season, in leading off the seventh with a single. The left-hander
Randy Choate relieved Hernandez with one out to pitch to Vaughn,
and Erstad _ apparently attuned to a scouting report on the rookie
_ stole second and third and scored on a sacrifice fly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
