<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING DIFFICULT ABOUT SPARKS VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The WNBA playoffs are supposed to be tough, but the
Los Angeles Sparks made it look way too easy.
</P>
<P>
   Focused and prepared for a battle, the Sparks did themselves a
favor, first, by jumping out to a big lead over the Phoenix Mercury
to take the fans out of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in front of the Mercury's franchise-low crowd of 6,167
they put on a clinic to take an overwhelming 86-71 victory Friday
night at America West Arena in the opening game of the
best-of-three, first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were totally focused and prepared to play,'' said Sparks
center Lisa Leslie, who hit 8 of 15 for 20 points to go with 11
rebounds. ``It all started at practice yesterday. The game was won
at practice. Practice was harder than the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was hard for the Mercury, which had no answer for
Leslie or DeLisha Milton, who had 19 points on 8-of-12 shooting, or
Mwadi Mabika, who had 15 points on 6-of-11 shooting. Tamecka Dixon
added to the balanced attack with 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks shot 52 percent and outrebounded the Mercury 38-26.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is good ball movement on our part,'' Sparks coach
Michael Cooper said. ``We're a very unselfish team, a team that
loves to pass. It's not about who gets it done as long as it gets
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks led 24-12 midway through the first half and never let
Phoenix get any closer than 11. Each time the Mercury tried to go
on a run, the Sparks kept pulling away.
</P>
<P>
   Tonya Edwards hit a 5-foot jumper and Brandy Reed pulled up for
a 3-pointer to cut the Mercury's deficit to 51-40 with 12:50 to
play. But the Sparks bounced back with Ukari Figgs, Leslie and
Mabika scoring the next six points to rebuild the solid lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a re-adjustment on our part. That's when you can't
make the mental errors that we were making, and I'm glad we were
able to regroup from that,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix was limited to 36 percent from the field to trail at
halftime, 43-24. They finished at 46 percent, but much of their
offense came in garbage time when the game was already decided.
They were 6 of 21 from the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Sparks' fourth win over the Mercury and their third
consecutive in Phoenix. It was the Mercury's worst effort against
the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't shoot the ball well in the first half,'' Phoenix
coach Cheryl Miller said. ``When you play a team like L.A. you
can't afford to get in a hole that deep. L.A. made some key shots,
got the key rebounds and they played extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   The series moves to Los Angeles where Game 2 is Sunday at 2:30
p.m. and Game 3 Tuesday, if necessary. It will be the Sparks first
game in the Forum since July 27. They've been on the road for the
last seven games, going 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper warned that going home is not a guaranteed victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't take for granted that we're going to go back there
and automatically get a win,'' he said. ``We're going to have to
work at it. Even though they lost, the format the way it's set up,
they were looking to steal this one. Well, they have two games to
get back in this one. We can't play around with this team. Even
though we're going home we know the urgency of the situation. We
have to put this team away, and hopefully we can do it Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix got balanced scoring, with Reed leading with 17 points,
Bridgett Pettis contributing 14 off the bench, Michelle Griffiths
adding 13, and Lisa Harrison and Jennifer Gillom getting 10 apiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
