<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Davis sets American record in 200 freestyle
</P>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Josh Davis was a 15-year-old student at San
Antonio's Churchill High School in 1988 when the U.S. Olympic
Swimming Trials were held at the University of Texas. Already
thinking swimming would be his sport, he went to the trials with
his mother and saw his destiny when Matt Biondi set an American
record in the 200-meter freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I got my Matt Biondi tapes,'' he said. ``I watched
them about every day. Then when I got to college in 1990, I lost
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Swimming the same event Friday at the 2000 Trials, Davis starred
in his own short film, four adrenaline-fueled laps of the Indiana
University-Purdue University pool that toppled the record Biondi
set 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a 1994 UT graduate, touched in 1 minute, 47.26 seconds,
besting Biondi's mark of 1:47.72, to win an event that had the feel
of a Longhorns workout. Scott Goldblatt, who is entering his senior
year at Texas, took second, ensuring he will compete in Sydney.
Jamie Rauch and Nate Dusing, both of whom also are due to be UT
seniors this year, were fifth and sixth, respectively, finishes
that likely will lead to relay positions on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be disappointed,'' said Rauch, a graduate of Cy
Creek High School. ``Josh and Scott go one-two, and Nate and I make
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Although only the top four finishers in the 200 freestyle are
guaranteed spots on the team, the fifth-and sixth-place finishers
typically make it as a result of swimmers doubling in various
events.
</P>
<P>
   Two other events Friday added to the UT presence on the U.S.
team. Winning the women's 100-meter backstroke was Texas ex B.J.
Bedford. Earning second in the men's 100-meter backstroke was Neil
Walker, a 1998 UT graduate. Walker finished behind Lenny
Krayzelburg, who won in 53.84, off his 1999 world-record time of
53.60.
</P>
<P>
   For Davis, the evening capped a remarkable series of months. He
has been gunning for the record in the 200 freestyle since winning
the event at the 2000 spring nationals in 1:47.94, making him the
first American to go under 1:48 since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it when it counts,'' he said of his record. ``Not the
preliminaries in the morning. I did it at night, making the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than three weeks away from his 28th birthday, he has
clearly found a gear he didn't have four years ago, when he won
three relay gold medals in Atlanta but finished seventh in the 200
freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   According to Davis, one reason for his improvement is the fact
he has been training in Austin with Randy Reese, former coach at
the University of Florida and the brother of UT men's coach Eddie
Reese, an arrangement, he said, that allows him to ``get the best
of both.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Davis had something extra Friday, going out
fast and holding on at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit 100 (meters), heard the crowd going crazy and figured I
was on record pace,'' he said. ``To break Biondi's record by half a
second, I'm really happy and thankful.''
</P>
<P>
   Rauch said it helped that he and the other UT swimmers in the
200 finals had trained with Davis and become accustomed to his
breakneck early pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been swimming with Josh long enough to know that's how he
does things,'' Rauch said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he believes he can swim at least 1:46.80 and possibly
get within shouting distance of Australia's Ian Thorpe, who in May
lowered the world record to 1:45.51.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to spend the next two weeks working on fitness,''
Davis said. ``I know I can go out. Now I've got to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   He also will have to deal with Olympic preparation at a time
when his wife, Shantel, is expecting their third child _ a boy _
adding to a household that already includes Caleb, soon to turn 3,
and Abigail, 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three kids in three years _ that provides me with a lot of
motivation,'' he said. ``A lot of diapers to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he and his wife are planning to induce labor on Sept.
4, the day after U.S. swimmers are scheduled to leave for Sydney
from their training base in Los Angeles. He said he will return to
Austin for the delivery, then travel to Sydney himself a day later.
</P>
<P>
   After welcoming his son into the world, he said, he will be able
to swim ``with peace of mind'' and make his attempt to challenge
Thorpe on Thorpe's turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Australians, we've really got our work cut out for
us,'' Davis said. ``But I race to win. That's why there's an
Olympic final. Maybe I can get 1:46, and you never know at that
level. Anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
