 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Berkman, Astros rally past Phillies
</P>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Some things are better left unexplained.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, manager Larry Dierker expected the Astros to hit
Phillies starter Bruce Chen on Friday night, but not hard-throwing
reliever Vicente Padilla.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Dierker had it backward.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Berkman had four RBIs, including a bases-clearing double
in a five-run ninth inning, as the Astros rallied to defeat the
Philadelphia Phillies 7-2 in a game between the teams with the
worst records in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   After being held to a run off Chen over the first seven innings,
the Astros finally put together some offense with one run in the
eighth and five in the ninth against the Phillies' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Berkman did most of the damage with a run-scoring double to tie
the game at 2 in the eighth and a three-run double in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou went 3-for-5, which included his 18th home run of
the season, and Julio Lugo had two hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is such an unusual game in the sense that what you
expect might happen sometimes doesn't happen,'' said Dierker, whose
club won for only the fifth time this season when trailing after
seven innings. ``I expected we would start hitting Chen. It didn't
seem he was throwing that hard or he had that great of control. But
we never really did hit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Padilla comes in throwing 96 mph, and he looks
unhittable, and we whack him all over the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros can start by thanking Phillies manager Terry
Francona, who replaced Chen with one out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, acquired from the Atlanta Braves at the All-Star break,
allowed two runs and six hits in 7 innings. He walked four and
struck out four.
</P>
<P>
   No member of the Astros' active roster ever had faced Chen prior
to Friday's game at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla, who stifled the Astros in two relief outings in early
July while with the Arizona Diamondbacks, inherited one baserunner
and promptly ran into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Alou singled, and Berkman followed with an RBI double into the
left-center gap.
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Spiers was intentionally walked, Padilla got out of
the jam when Tony Eusebio bounced into a double play to end the
inning with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Daryle Ward led off the Astros ninth with a pinch-hit single off
Padilla, then was removed for pinch runner Glen Barker. Lugo beat
out an infield chopper to second base, and Tim Bogar reached safely
on an error by Padilla to load the bases. Jeff Bagwell was hit on
the left shoulder on a full-count pitch to put the Astros ahead 3-2
with no outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was kind of an ugly inning,'' Bagwell said. ``It doesn't
matter how the runs come.''
</P>
<P>
   Padilla (2-3), who left the game with cramping in his left side,
allowed four runs, all unearned.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gomes replaced Padilla and recorded two outs before
Berkman added the final touches with RBI Nos. 51, 52 and 53 of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about getting into a comfort zone in big situations
when you've got guys in scoring position and know you are one of
the people the team is counting on to drive in some runs,'' said
Berkman, who batted in the No. 6 hole Friday. ``Chen was tough.
Whenever you face a pitcher like that, you have to hang around and
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Phillies struggled out of the bullpen, Astros reliever
Marc Valdes (3-4) pitched two shutout innings, and closer Octavio
Dotel retired the final three batters.
</P>
<P>
   Astros starter Scott Elarton allowed two runs and seven hits in
six innings. He struck out a season-high nine and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   But the 6-7 righthander said he never felt comfortable with his
delivery Friday night, which led to a high pitch count (119 in six
innings) and an early departure.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies stranded five runners in the first three innings,
including three in the third when Mike Lieberthal struck out and
Travis Lee bounced out to Elarton to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt terrible in the windup,'' said Elarton, who had won
eight of his previous nine starts. ``It seemed like I started every
inning with a runner on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness I felt good from the stretch, because I was
able to pitch out of some jams and keep the damage to a minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``He didn't have his best stuff, but he proved
what kind of pitcher he's becoming by keeping us in the game. The
bullpen came in and did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies took a 1-0 lead in the fourth on Kevin Jordan's
third homer of the season, a shot just into the left-field
bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros tied the game at 1 in the sixth on Alou's homer, but
the Phillies quickly regained the lead in the bottom half of the
inning on an RBI groundout by Tomas Perez. Pat Burrell led off the
inning with a walk and moved to third on a double by Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Eusebio extended his career-high 15-game hitting streak _
the longest in Astros history by a catcher _ with a double in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
