<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9655 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-PICKENS-HNS &LR;      08-12 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PICKENS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy days are here again for Pickens
</P>
<P>
   By JOHN McCLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Receiver Carl Pickens has been spending a lot
of time on his knees lately.
</P>
<P>
   But Pickens isn't begging. He's just thanking the Lord for his
good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   After escaping Cincinnati and signing with Tennessee, Pickens
feels like a political prisoner who has been granted asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Pickens, who grew up in North Carolina, played at the University
of Tennessee and owns a home in Atlanta, left a loser and signed
with a Super Bowl contender desperate for a receiver with his
impressive credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living proof that the grass can be greener,'' Pickens said
Friday during a break at the Titans' training camp. ``There's just
no comparison between them (the organizations). I really feel like
I've been reborn.''
</P>
<P>
   During his eight-year career with the Bengals, Pickens never
played on a team with a winning record. The best they could do was
7-9. The Titans haven't had a losing season since 1995 when they
were still the Houston Oilers, and they are coming off a Super Bowl
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that I've ever been more excited about a season,
except for maybe my rookie year,'' Pickens said. ``People say,
`Have you changed?' and I say, `No, I haven't changed, because who
I was in Cincinnati is not who I really am.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so fired up here, because everything's so positive. They
know what it takes to win. How could you not be fired up to be in
this situation?''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is mutual. The Bengals are fired up about getting
rid of Pickens and called it addition by subtraction.
</P>
<P>
   At times during his career in Cincinnati, Pickens was as good as
any receiver in the NFL not named Jerry Rice. Along the way,
though, Pickens earned a reputation as a malcontent, a troublemaker
who was a bad influence on the plethora of young players the
Bengals kept bringing in every year. They couldn't wait to get rid
of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like losing,'' Pickens said. ``There were times when
I said what was on my mind because we were losing. I just couldn't
accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got criticized for being a cancer on the team. The media
said I was hard to deal with and uncoachable. But I don't know if
you ever heard anything about me not playing on Sundays.''
</P>
<P>
   During a three-year stretch, Pickens was phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   After catching 71 passes for 1,127 yards and 11 touchdowns in
1994, he had 99 receptions for 1,234 yards and 17 touchdowns in
1995. The next season, Pickens caught 100 passes for 1,180 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Carl brings his `A' game, he's pretty much unstoppable,''
Titans cornerback Denard Walker said. ``If he's not the premier guy
in our conference, he's right up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of Cincinnati was a two-year process for Pickens,
who had been designated as the Bengals' franchise player. When he
blasted coach Bruce Coslet near the end of last season and said it
would be a mistake to bring him back, Pickens became persona non
grata with management.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, Bengals owner Mike Brown inserted a clause in
contracts demanding a portion of signing bonuses be repaid if a
player is critical of the team. Some players signed it. Others
didn't. The NFL Players Association has filed a grievance trying to
get the clause _ dubbed the Pickens rule by the media and players _
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the offseason, the Bengals told Pickens to clean out his
locker, that he wouldn't be returning. But they had to get a ruling
on the franchise designation and how it would be interpreted after
Pickens was gone. When the league didn't get back to them quickly
enough, they told Pickens to report. He languished in football
limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really couldn't figure it out,'' he said. ``It's like they
didn't want Pickens in camp because he's the cancer of the team. I
was actually heading out the door on my way to minicamp, and they
said, `We don't want you in camp.' I'm thinking, `Cool, I'm going
to be released.' Then they said, `No, now we want you to come to
camp now.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like, `Make up your mind. Either I'm the cancer of the
team or you want me to come to camp.' You hear about other teams
wanting you, and they wouldn't trade me. They had opportunities to
get draft picks for me and didn't do it. I felt like they were just
stringing me out, trying to make me suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the time came to let me go, probably in hopes of me not
finding a job anywhere else, they didn't do it. I guess they
assumed my reputation would keep teams away from me. But Tennessee
wasn't concerned. Neither were the Jets, Ravens and Saints. But it
worked out for the best. It strengthened me.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his reputation, Pickens figured it was the media's
doing because his coaches and teammates didn't call him a cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that was fed to them by anybody on the staff,
because the staff still wanted me to play,'' he said. ``They paid
me a lot of money to play. Why would you pay a guy all this money
if he was a cancer and a problem in the locker room and his
teammates and coaches don't like him? I couldn't really figure it
all out and who was saying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing that bothered me, that nobody stepped up and
said, `Hey, he's not like that. He's here every day, and he's
working his butt off.' You just never heard any of that from
anybody. I had to defend myself all the time. There were 10 or 15
other guys who felt the same way I did, because I talked with them
about it. But you never heard about it from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickens is having to get into shape, but he caught a touchdown
pass in the preseason-opening victory over Kansas City. Titans
coach Jeff Fisher envisions Pickens and Kevin Dyson as the
starters. When Yancey Thigpen recovers from ankle surgery,
Tennessee could have an outstanding trio.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Yancey's healthy, we'll play the best two,'' Fisher said.
``It's understood by all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickens, 30, has impressed his teammates, especially the
defensive backs who are relieved they only have to cover him in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pickens is smart,'' cornerback Samari Rolle said. ``He changes
his routes. He's a big target, easy to find. He wants the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teams pursued Pickens, who signed as a free agent after
he was waived. After playing at the University of Tennessee, he
found it hard to believe the Titans had captured the interest of
football fans in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really surprised,'' he said. ``To be honest with you, I
didn't know how well the Titans would go over in Tennessee, because
this is Tennessee Volunteer country.
</P>
<P>
   ``But everywhere this side of Nashville and that side of
Nashville, it's Titans this and Titans that. You see the signs,
posters, billboards, the television stuff. Some people say because
it's new it'll wear off, but I don't see it changing as long as
this team continues to win. And I think we will continue to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a sense of direction here. We have leadership. We have
the facilities, the fan base. It's like playing on an all-star
team, because you've got guys at every position who can make big
plays. I love it here because the only thing you have to worry
about is football. Everything else is taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickens has circled Oct. 8 on his calendar. That's when the
Titans travel to Cincinnati to play in the new Paul Brown Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it'll be interesting,'' he said, choosing his words
carefully for the first time. ``That's a team that let me go and
didn't get anything for me. I spent eight years there, and I still
have a lot of good friends in Cincinnati. I don't hate Cincinnati
or management there. We just had to go our separate ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickens believes he has just signed the proverbial new lease on
his football life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to be in a positive, winning situation,'' he
said. ``For now, I'm just happy to be out of Cincinnati. I get a
chance to play on a winning team with a chance to go to the Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
