<HEADLINE>
ANGELS OUTWIT YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels left-hander Scott Schoeneweis
wormed his way in and out of trouble Friday night at Edison Field,
a tease here and there, and, in the end, he thoroughly frustrated
the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Schoeneweis emerged with an 8-3 win in front of
43,169 fans, the third-largest home crowd of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It was Schoeneweis' first win in more than two months and it
provided the Angels with just their third win in nine games while
stopping the Yankees' winning streak at three.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very fine offensive ballclub,'' manager Mike Scioscia
said of the Yankees. ``Scott kept them off balance all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Garret Anderson drove in three of the Angels'
runs with a pair of doubles, first baseman Mo Vaughn knocked in two
with a double and Troy Glaus slugged his 32nd home run.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one of Glaus' homers have come while playing third base,
which established a club record for homers by a third baseman,
breaking Doug DeCinces' 1982 mark.
</P>
<P>
   One downside to the win: Tim Salmon's hitting streak was halted
at 17 games. The Angels right fielder was 0 for 4, striking out
twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels ripped into Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez (8-9) for
four first-inning runs, added two more in the fifth, stole one,
literally, in the seventh, then finished it with Glaus' homer in
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis (6-6) hadn't won since beating Minnesota on May 25.
Since then he'd lost four, had three no-decisions and made an
appearance on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said there wasn't a lot of frustration,'' he
said. ``I'd throw well, but we'd fall behind. I felt I was putting
us in a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis pitched into the seventh, scattering nine hits over
6 innings. But he turned over yet another a precarious situation to
reliever Mike Fuyrie: two on, two out and designated hitter Jose
Canseco digging in at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Fuyrie walked Canseco on four pitches to load the bases. But he
got Hill on a fly to right for the third out . . . and the Yanks
left three more on base.
</P>
<P>
   Fuyrie came out after that, and following the game he was placed
on the disabled list because of inflammation of his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   In one other move, the Angels outrighted outfielder Chris
Hatcher _ who never got into a game in his brief stay in Anaheim _
to Triple-A Edmonton to make room on the roster for Kent Mercker,
tonight's starter.
</P>
</TEXT>
