u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-12 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS GO SEVEN GAMES UP FOR FIRST TIME AS ABBOTT MUFFLES
INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Turn to the standings page Saturday and you'll see an
astonishing sight, even if this fine family newspaper isn't running
that infamous ``Son of the Beach'' ad for ``Bodacious Ha-Has.''
</P>
<P>
   No, this is a simple line of small, sans serif type showing
something truly historic: the Mariners with a seven-game lead. Like
the headline, ``Starbucks drastically lowers prices on its
lattes,'' this is something that has never before been printed in a
Seattle newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   After a 6-2 road trip against the American League's two other
first-place teams, the Mariners returned to a sold-out Safeco Field
Friday night and extended their first-place lead to a
franchise-high seven games _ a full week's worth of games _ with a
7-1 victory over Cleveland. The lead surpasses Seattle's previous
largest, 6{ games during the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's too early to get too excited. After all, as
manager Lou Piniella cautioned reporters, ``It's August 11 _
there's still a lot of season left to play.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, there's a lot of season left to play what,
alas, has become the Mariners' theme song, ``Who Let the Dogs
Out?'' Asked what the over-under is for how many times fans will
hear the song (which is a charitable term) between now and season's
end, pitcher Paul Abbott said, ``I don't know, 1,050 times?''
</P>
<P>
   As often as the Mariners play it, that's probably too low an
estimate for the rest of the weekend, let alone the rest of the
season. But it was about the only time Abbott was off Friday.
Continuing his strong work as a starter, Abbott held one of the
league's best lineups to one run and four hits in 7 2/3 innings,
running his record to 8-4 with a 3.80 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   And to think that just a mere week ago the Mariners' lead was
down to one thin game, with three more games against the Yankees
and four against the White Sox staring at them. Rather than fold,
Seattle won six of those games and carried over that success into
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep go out there and play like it's a one-game
lead, like we did last week,'' Abbott said, adding that playing New
York and Chicago ``was a great chance to show we're one of the
teams to be reckoned with. It's a huge confidence builder. That was
huge for us, to go in there and send a message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but gain confidence from a trip like that,''
said John Olerud, who continued his pursuit of Cal Ripken's record
streak (he's only about 16 years away) when he had to replace an
injured Stan Javier at first base on what was supposed to be his
first night off this season. ``To play the division leaders and go
6-2, that's a big shot in the arm for everybody. Now you feel that
if and when you make it to the playoffs, you have had success
against those teams. And that definitely helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Facing a lineup like that and a pitcher as good as Chuck
Finley, we feel like if we can score a few runs, we've got a chance
to win the way we've been pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much what happened, too. After Cleveland scored
its only run against Abbott in the top of the first inning, the
Mariners tied it with a run in the bottom of the inning and took
the lead with three in the second. Finley, who caught his cleat and
turned his right ankle on his first pitch, allowed five runs and
walked six in 31/3 innings. And that was pretty much that, thanks
to Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   One start after pitching a career-high eight innings against the
Yankees, Abbott held Cleveland to one hit and no runs after the
first inning. With a stiff breeze blowing in most of the evening,
Abbott retired 21 of 23 batters during one stretch before walking
consecutive batters with two out in the eighth and giving way to
reliever Jose Paniagua. Abbott, who pitched briefly for Cleveland
another lifetime ago, is 4-0 with a 0.81 ERA against his ex-team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to win,'' said Abbott. ``And when you expect to win
and then do it, it makes everyone contribute and feel confident.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, things have changed a bit since these two teams
last played.
</P>
<P>
   Decimated by injuries during the first half of the season,
Cleveland has been rallying lately, trimming three games off
Chicago's Central Division lead since the start of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a comment that the White Sox could probably hear
Cleveland's footsteps approaching, Piniella replied, ``I hope they
don't hear them too much. Because we're playing them the next six
of nine games. We want to keep them nice and quiet ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just playing good solid baseball, a combination of good
hitting and good pitching,'' Piniella said. ``And that translates
into wins. We just have to keep going out there and do it one game
at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
