<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1342 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THEATERS-ORNATE-REVIE     08-12 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATERS-ORNATE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF THE GRAND OLD CINEMAS, THE SCIENCE OF THE NEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marcus Loew, who founded Loews Theaters in the early
1900s, once said: ``We sell tickets to theaters, not movies.'' That
was certainly the case when the grand movie palaces of the 1910s,
'20s and '30s lit up America.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the theaters were showy grandes dames. They
flaunted crystal chandeliers, marble floors and architectural
ornamentation worthy of the Sun King. The Loews Paradise in Fordham
in the Bronx was beyond rococo, festooned with statues, elaborate
archways and intricate frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   By the '40s, the golden age of movie palaces was falling into a
decline that, in the '70s, the mall-driven rise of the multiplex
began to counter, only for it to be clobbered again by the VCR
craze.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few years, a new grandiosity has arrived,
inflating cinemas into Brobdingnagian multiplexes that house as
many as 30 screens, the theaters competing with their film
selections in terms of theatricality.
</P>
<P>
   AMC, the national movie chain formerly known as American
Multi-Cinema, has built 11 30-screen theaters in six cities,
including Los Angeles, Chicago, Phoenix, Detroit, Dallas and
Houston. On West 42nd Street in Manhattan, it has erected the AMC
Empire 25, which, as its name suggests, has a mere 25 screens.
There are also four roof decks _ a sublime amenity for stargazers,
sun addicts and smokers. Those who want an unencumbered view of
Manhattan's skyline can choose to look from outdoors or indoors,
thanks to vast banks of windows. At one of six concession stands,
there is cafe seating and several television monitors, which show
coming attractions as well as interviews with luminaries on Cable
News Network. There is also a VIP room for celebrities who don't
want to mingle with hoi polloi.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street is a Loews, with a ceiling fresco in the lobby
and wall murals meant to hark back to the likes of the Paradise.
This cinematic emporium has 13 screens, TV sets at the concession
stands and, like AMC, several talking machines where moviegoers can
purchase tickets. It also has a restaurant that supplies the
concession stands with more than the usual movie fare, reflecting
the fact that more profits are made there than on ticket sales. On
the menu are mini mozzarella sticks ($5.99), chicken quesadillas
($5.99), potato skins ($6.99) and popcorn shrimp ($7.99).
</P>
<P>
   Theater owners pin this bigger-is-better, more-is-more ethos
squarely on the synergy of the booming economy and changing
demographics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times are good,'' said Rick King, a spokesman for AMC.
``People have more disposable income.'' And those people, he said,
include baby boomers who have become empty nesters, and
big-spending teen-agers and young adults, who are savvy and
demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's teen-ager and young adult movie-goers have higher
expectations in a technical sense,'' King said, ``for sound and
picture quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The cinemas reflect the shift. ``We've returned our attention to
film presentation and showmanship in our buildings,'' said Marc
Pascucci, a spokesman for Loews. ``The consumer is a lot more savvy
about the presentation. Entertainment has become news.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, every possible technological advance is being
incorporated: digital sound, bigger screens and stadium seating,
where everyone is on a riser.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what happens is, the moviegoing experience is more powerful
and more consuming,'' Pascucci said. ``What we've found is that
instead of going to an ordinary theater in the neighborhood, people
will go to a theater one or more miles away if it's splashier.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all that focus, the new grandiosity holds little
resemblance to the old. What technology gives now, atmosphere
offered then.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Jones, a senior associate at Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer
Associates, a Manhattan-based architectural firm, said the old
movie palaces, with their mixing of Baroque, Italian Renaissance,
Classical and Moorish themes, were meant for fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were going to a different period of time,'' he said.
``They were taking you to a different place. You were
transported.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's analogy,'' he said, ``is: buy a plane ticket, go down
to Disney World and end up in the Magic Kingdom. It's the wonderful
world of movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The megaplexing trend appears to be going as global as the taste
for American movies. Loews, which has 245 movie locations in 22
American cities, also has cinemas in Canada, Spain, Hungary and
Turkey. And it has plans to build in Italy and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet the new style in megamultiplexing will last as
long as the economy rides high _ or until some unforeseen social
development steals its audience. The grand old movie palaces _ all
set in urban centers _ died out less from the Depression than from
housing patterns that sucked city populations into new suburbs
after World War II, according to Toby Miller, a professor of cinema
studies at New York University's Tisch School of the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The televisualization and suburbanization of American homes
denuded the inner city of its population,'' he said. Modest cinemas
became the norm.
</P>
<P>
   And there's another area of vulnerability. Bigger is only better
until it isn't. Years ago, there was a monopoly-busting Justice
Department decree that forced major movie studios, which used to
control distribution, production and exhibition, to sell off the
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   At AMC Empire 25 last week, the backlash against big was more
personal. Yoland Trevino, who is from Los Angeles, said she felt
like ``a rat in a maze'' trying to find a bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no signs visible from here,'' she said, looking
around in the lobby. ``It's like sensory overload. I'm
overwhelmed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
