<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9667 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SINATRA-WWII-REVIEW-N     08-12 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINATRA-WWII-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM 4F TO ETERNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(editors: please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets) 
 By TOM KUNTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some in Times Square aren't thrilled by Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's plan to erect a statue of Frank Sinatra on the traffic
island at 44th Street and Broadway. Critics say the Crossroads of
the World is too congested for the bronze likeness of a singer with
little connection to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The most historically significant aspect of this proposal,
however, has been overlooked: The monument in front of the armed
forces' busiest recruiting station would honor a man who avoided
the World War II draft and spent much of his life trying to live it
down.
</P>
<P>
   As the historian William Manchester once noted, Sinatra was
``the most hated man of World War II'' because he was getting rich
thrilling American women while their boyfriends and husbands were
fighting overseas. In fact, the site proposed for the 10-foot-tall
statue is almost exactly where in 1944, sailors (captured in a
famous photo) threw tomatoes at the crooner's visage on the
now-defunct Paramount Theater across the street from the recruiting
station, which opened in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra and his family always claimed that he wanted to serve,
but was stopped by a punctured eardrum. It's true that his
exemption was legitimate. But his claim is put to the test by
records of an FBI inquiry into his exemption released after his
death in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra repeatedly said on draft forms that he had ``no physical
or mental defects or diseases,'' as he wrote on one. But when he
arrived at the Jersey City, N.J., induction office in December
1943, he gave Army doctors plenty of reasons to reject him. He told
them that an ear injury at birth and subsequent operations were
still causing ``running ear'' and ``head noises.'' Furthermore, he
claimed to be ``neurotic, afraid to be in crowds, afraid to go in
elevator, ((wants)) to run when surrounded by people'' and had
``been very nervous for four or five years.'' He also complained
that he ``wakens tired in the a.m., is run down and
undernourished.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctors didn't question the implausibility of such a
celebrity being crowd-averse. Instead, they verified that he had a
punctured left eardrum and declared him 4F. (The conservative
columnist Westbrook Pegler dubbed him ``bugle-deaf Frankie boy.'')
</P>
<P>
   As for his other claims, Army doctors concluded he was ``not
acceptable material from a psychiatric viewpoint.'' But they
downplayed this in their official report. A subsequent inquiry
noted that ``inasmuch as the selectee was to be rejected on an
organic basis'' _ the eardrum _ ``the diagnosis of psychoneurosis,
severe was not added to the list. Notation of emotional instability
was made instead ((to)) avoid undue unpleasantness for both the
selectee and the induction service.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI investigated as a result of an anonymous tip (passed on
by the columnist Walter Winchell) that Sinatra bribed his way out
of the draft. Agents turned up no evidence of that. But what the
FBI did find puts the statue debate in a different light.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra spent much of the rest of his life trying to compensate
for not serving. He entertained U.S. troops in Italy at the end of
the war. He recorded special disks just for the GIs on the front
lines. And he tried to entertain the boys in Korea, too, but the
Army refused to give him a security clearance, suspicious that he
might be a communist (which, it turned out, he wasn't).
</P>
<P>
   In a way, a statue on that spot would be more than an honor for
Sinatra. It would be a vindication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1350 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SINATRA-WWII-REVIEW-N     08-12 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINATRA-WWII-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM 4F TO ETERNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(editors: please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets) 
 By TOM KUNTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some in Times Square aren't thrilled by Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's plan to erect a statue of Frank Sinatra on the traffic
island at 44th Street and Broadway. Critics say the Crossroads of
the World is too congested for the bronze likeness of a singer with
little connection to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The most historically significant aspect of this proposal,
however, has been overlooked: The monument in front of the armed
forces' busiest recruiting station would honor a man who avoided
the World War II draft and spent much of his life trying to live it
down.
</P>
<P>
   As the historian William Manchester once noted, Sinatra was
``the most hated man of World War II'' because he was getting rich
thrilling American women while their boyfriends and husbands were
fighting overseas. In fact, the site proposed for the 10-foot-tall
statue is almost exactly where in 1944, sailors (captured in a
famous photo) threw tomatoes at the crooner's visage on the
now-defunct Paramount Theater across the street from the recruiting
station, which opened in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra and his family always claimed that he wanted to serve,
but was stopped by a punctured eardrum. It's true that his
exemption was legitimate. But his claim is put to the test by
records of an FBI inquiry into his exemption released after his
death in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra repeatedly said on draft forms that he had ``no physical
or mental defects or diseases,'' as he wrote on one. But when he
arrived at the Jersey City, N.J., induction office in December
1943, he gave Army doctors plenty of reasons to reject him. He told
them that an ear injury at birth and subsequent operations were
still causing ``running ear'' and ``head noises.'' Furthermore, he
claimed to be ``neurotic, afraid to be in crowds, afraid to go in
elevator, ((wants)) to run when surrounded by people'' and had
``been very nervous for four or five years.'' He also complained
that he ``wakens tired in the a.m., is run down and
undernourished.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctors didn't question the implausibility of such a
celebrity being crowd-averse. Instead, they verified that he had a
punctured left eardrum and declared him 4F. (The conservative
columnist Westbrook Pegler dubbed him ``bugle-deaf Frankie boy.'')
</P>
<P>
   As for his other claims, Army doctors concluded he was ``not
acceptable material from a psychiatric viewpoint.'' But they
downplayed this in their official report. A subsequent inquiry
noted that ``inasmuch as the selectee was to be rejected on an
organic basis'' _ the eardrum _ ``the diagnosis of psychoneurosis,
severe was not added to the list. Notation of emotional instability
was made instead ((to)) avoid undue unpleasantness for both the
selectee and the induction service.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI investigated as a result of an anonymous tip (passed on
by the columnist Walter Winchell) that Sinatra bribed his way out
of the draft. Agents turned up no evidence of that. But what the
FBI did find puts the statue debate in a different light.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra spent much of the rest of his life trying to compensate
for not serving. He entertained U.S. troops in Italy at the end of
the war. He recorded special disks just for the GIs on the front
lines. And he tried to entertain the boys in Korea, too, but the
Army refused to give him a security clearance, suspicious that he
might be a communist (which, it turned out, he wasn't).
</P>
<P>
   In a way, a statue on that spot would be more than an honor for
Sinatra. It would be a vindication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
