<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greens Joke and Reformers Fight
</P>
<P>
   It is easily the wittiest candidate commercial of the 2000
election. In a parody of MasterCard's ``priceless'' television
campaign, Ralph Nader's first spot takes aim at the ways the
major-party candidates finance their runs for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grilled tenderloin for fund-raiser: 1,000 dollars a plate,''
the announcer says. ``Campaign ads filled with half-truths: 10
million dollars. Promises to special interest groups: over 10
billion dollars. Finding out the truth: priceless.''
</P>
<P>
   That last line is narrated over a photograph of Nader as a young
consumer advocate. But the commercial overlooks Nader's latest
public role: professional thorn in Vice President Al Gore's side.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party standard-bearer, who polls show is likely to
siphon off some liberal Gore supporters, was not the only
third-party candidate muscling his way onto television last week:
The Reform Party, meeting to pick its candidate in Long Beach,
Calif., broke into rival conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle was between the conservative commentator Pat
Buchanan, representing a new guard in the party formed by Ross
Perot in 1992, and a faction of party veterans that was backing
John Hagelin, a physicist who has run for president twice on the
Natural Law Party ticket. ``We are going to reach back to the 20
million people who voted for Ross Perot in 1992, the people who are
not looking for a right-wing extremist,'' Hagelin said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan seemed to be practicing his own politics of
inclusiveness on Friday, when he selected as his running mate a
black educator from Los Angeles, Ezola Foster. ``We welcome
everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were other distractions for the Gore campaign. In South
Barrington, Ill., President Clinton faced 4,000 members of the
Willow Creek Community Church on Thursday to speak about his life
after an adulterous affair and the effect that event should not
have on the man he wants to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get enough credit for what we did together that is
good, and surely, no fair-minded person would blame him for any
mistake that I made,'' the president said. _ By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   Tomayto, Tomahto, Potayto...
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists have long assumed that while people in Beijing
might ponder different topics than those in Oklahoma City, their
ways of gathering information and making sense of the world were
indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   New research, however, indicates that people from different
cultures may in fact think differently.
</P>
<P>
   In laboratory studies comparing East Asians and Americans, Dr.
Richard Nisbett, a professor of psychology at the University of
Michigan, and his colleagues uncovered two separate thinking
styles. The Asians tended to be more ``holistic,'' showing greater
attention to context, a tolerance for contradiction, and less
dependence on logic. Westerners were more ``analytic,'' avoiding
contradiction, focusing on objects removed from their context, and
more reliant on logic.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe an animated underwater scene, for example,
Asians were more likely to describe the background and the
relationship between objects. Americans focused immediately on the
largest fish.
</P>
<P>
   Nisbett's work, because it is systematic and repeatable, may
prompt scientists to re-evaluate their notions of what is universal
and what is local. Dr. Susan Andersen is a professor of psychology
at New York University and an associate editor of the journal
Psychological Review, which will publish a theoretical paper by
Nisbett and his colleagues. She said the research ``turns on its
head a great deal of the science that many of us have been doing,
and so it's sort of scary and thrilling at the same time.'
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERICA GOODE
</P>
<P>
   Despite Protests, Another Texas Execution
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Cruz, a mentally retarded 33- year-old with an IQ of 64,
was one of two men executed on Wednesday in Huntsville, Texas.
``The execution of persons who are mentally retarded serves no
principled purpose and demeans our system of justice,'' Martha W.
Barrett, the president of the American Bar Association, wrote to
Gov. George W. Bush. The European Union also had called on Bush to
spare Cruz, saying the execution of the mentally retarded violated
international human rights norms.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz was condemned to death for the 1988 rape and murder of a
24-year-old woman. His last-minute appeal to the Supreme Court was
denied by a 7-2 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing to Muggles
</P>
<P>
   First the magic, now the marketing. Harry Potter merchandise
arrived this month in more than 140 Warner Bros. Studio Stores
around the country. Warner Bros., which owns the rights to the
first two Harry Potter books, is thus far selling relatively few
items, among them T-shirts, backpacks and baseball caps. But the
studio has made more than 40 licensing deals for Harry Potter
products ranging from candy to soap, which will gradually appear
before the first Harry Potter movie, scheduled to open Nov. 16,
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Walking Out Over Wireless
</P>
<P>
   In a dispute over organized labor's future in the New Economy,
more than 86,000 workers went on strike against Verizon
Communications, the nation's largest local telephone and wireless
company. The union wants concessions from Verizon making it easier
to organize in the company's fast-growing wireless division. The
strike affected 25 million people in 12 Eastern states and
Washington, D.C. Verizon was formed by Bell Atlantic's acquisition
of GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SIMON ROMERO
</P>
<P>
   ABC's Inventive News Report
</P>
<P>
   ABC News admitted that a report it showed twice on ``20/20''
challenging the benefits of organic food was based, in part, on
nonexistent evidence. The producer of the segment, David W.
Fitzpatrick, was suspended from his duties for one month, without
pay. John Stossel, the correspondent on the report, was
reprimanded. He was told to apologize. _ By JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   Tire Trouble
</P>
<P>
   They can't find the flaw in the design or the materials or the
manufacturing process, but the makers of Firestone tires say some
of their products are falling apart on the highway. As a result,
they are recalling 6.5 million tires used on Ford SUVs and a
variety of other pickups with 15-inch wheels.
</P>
<P>
   The Bridgestone/Firestone company promises to replace them all _
but only by next summer, a delay that has angered consumers and
politicians. Experts say, however, that the company just doesn't
have enough tires to go around. So while the federal government
investigates 46 deaths and 80 injuries that may have come from the
tires, vehicle owners may wait for nearly a year for replacements.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   Wahid's Last Hurrah
</P>
<P>
   In his state-of-the-nation speech to the Indonesian People's
Consultative Assembly, President Abdurrahman Wahid issued a
tough-minded rebuttal to critics who say he has not done enough to
address Indonesia's many troubles. However, Wahid, who is blind,
fell asleep as the speech was being read by an aide. Other aides
fed him candy to wake him whenever he drifted off. Several days
later, Wahid announced he would cede day-to-day administration of
the government to Vice President Megawati Sukarnoputi.
</P>
<P>
   By SETH MYDANS
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
