</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Jewish Question
</P>
<P>
   After two Jewish cemeteries were desecrated in the western
German state of Rhineland-Palatinate and an explosive device was
found outside a Jewish family's home in Bavaria, German politicians
reviewed a possible ban on the small rightist National Democratic
Party on the ground that it is a threat to democratic stability.
The Constitutional Court, however, has not upheld any such ban
since the 1950s. The government and Jewish leaders said an
advertising campaign for tolerance, called Show Your Face and
featuring sports and entertainment celebrities, would start in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   The National Missile Mess
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton nears a decision on building a national
missile defense, an intelligence report warned that the decision
could prompt China to expand its nuclear arsenal tenfold, while
Russia could take destabilizing steps like placing multiple
warheads on its ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The report could erode support for the administration's proposed
missile shield, which is also facing technological hurdles. Defense
Secretary William Cohen postponed making his recommendation to
Clinton by at least a month, citing ``a number of difficult
issues,'' including the need for more tests and delays in building
a new booster rocket.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
<P>
   The Truth Is Out There
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers this week added nine to their tally of planets known
to orbit other stars, bringing the total to more than 45. Among the
newly discovered planets is one orbiting the star Epsilon Eridani,
located only 10.5 light years from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Epsilon Eridani was one of two stars focused on in 1960 in the
first search for radio signals from alien civilizations _ and the
first false alarm. As soon as a radio telescope was pointed at the
stars, loud, pulsing signals immediately burst from the
loudspeakers, which turned out to be interference from a passing
plane. More recent listening efforts by the SETI Institute of
Mountain View, Calif., have not heard anything.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KENNETH CHANG
</P>
<P>
   Bringing the War Home
</P>
<P>
   Russia's summer lull was shattered by a terrorist bomb that
exploded on Tuesday in a busy pedestrian tunnel beneath Pushkin
Square, killing eight and wounding nearly 100. Within hours, Mayor
Yuri Luzhkov claimed responsibility lay ``100 percent'' with
Chechnya, the breakaway republic where rebel leaders had been
vowing to strike Russian cities. Russian President Vladimir Putin,
however, said it would be premature to blame the Chechens, and
though police quickly rounded up suspects, none was immediately
connected to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PATRICK E. TYLER
</P>
<P>
   Surfer Girl
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in the Internet's brief existence, more women
than men are going online, according to a survey by Media Metrix
and Jupiter Communications. During the first quarter of this year,
50.4 percent of Internet users were women, and there was a 125
percent increase in teen-age girls online. The survey also found
that women, unlike men, don't surf so much as find sites that help
them save time or money, and return to them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
