<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      08-12 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 FOR SUNDAY AMs 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Aug. 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-REUNIONS (Seoul, South Korea) _ Some of the people who
will participate in upcoming reunions that will bring 100 North
Koreans south, and take 100 South Koreans north, recall how their
families were separated by the Korean War and talk about the
uncertainty they have lived with. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-RELIGIOUS-STRIFE (San Juan Chamula, Mexico) _ This rugged
part of Chiapas state has been ground zero in Mexico's lingering
conflict between Catholics and Evangelical Christians. The battles
have blazed on for 30 years, dividing fathers from their sons,
turning violent, and leaving hundreds dead and at least 30,000
displaced in Chiapas alone. But that may be changing. By Ginger
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-VANITY (Caracas, Venezuela) _ When a recent consumer
survey of 30 countries concluded that Venezuelans, men and women
alike, are the most vain people in the world, the results were
considered a bit embarrassing, but hardly surprising. ``Of course
it is true,'' said Marga Bermudez, a salesclerk in a busy beauty
products store at a shopping center in a middle-class area here.
``How could it be otherwise? Ours is a country renowned for its
beauty queens, and so we are always, always worrying about our
appearance.'' By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-ARCTIC-TOURISTS (Yellowknife, Northwest Territories) _
Yellowknife, on the northern tip of the Great Slave Lake, has
traditionally been the Saturday night destination of choice for fur
trappers, gold miners and lonely Mounties. But as evidenced by two
new hotels nearing completion here, a new sushi restaurant with
Japanese-speaking staff, and travel advertisements fattening Up
Here magazine, Yellowknife and Canada's north are undergoing a
tourism boom. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-MUSLIMS (Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) _ Malaysia, with its
large Chinese and Indian minorities, is a model of multiethnic
harmony in Asia. But people here believe the peace is fragile. They
look in fear at neighboring Indonesia and the Philippines, which
are battling Muslim insurgencies. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   LAOS-PRINCE (Undated) _ Nearly 20 years ago, an 18-year-old
prince, heir to a doomed Asian royal line, commandeered a small
boat and sailed unnoticed with his brother and their nanny across
the Mekong River from Laos to Thailand. Laos had become a Communist
nation, and the prince, Soulivong Savang, feared being co-opted or
killed. Two decades later, the prince _ grandson of the last king
of Laos, who died mysteriously in Communist captivity with the
prince's father and other relatives _ is quietly beginning to
reassert his claim of leadership. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-BORDER (Beirut, Lebanon) _ Lebanon's very limited
deployment of soldiers and police into the south, far from
stabilizing the situation along its border with Israel, is raising
new uncertainties. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-FAULTY-CABLES (Undated) _ On May 18, the Federal
Aviation Administration issued what appeared to be an important
safety notice for the world's airlines. Federal investigators had
learned that a manufacturer of cables that work key controls in
many widely used jetliners might not have properly tested its
cables. Samples checked by investigators, the notice said, had
failed to meet minimum requirements for strength. FAA officials
expected the airlines to check their fleets and, if necessary,
replace the cables. But federal prosecutors who were suing the
cable maker said that the system broke down because the critical
information did not reach airlines as intended. By John Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OAK-DISEASE (Felton, Calif.) _ Despite the beauty of the
towering redwoods and bay trees in these mountains some 60 miles
south of San Francisco, it is the more modest tanoak trees that
draw the eye. These tanoaks are falling victim to a new disease.
Scientists call it sudden oak death syndrome, and they are alarmed
by its rapid spread and its ability to kill an ever increasing
number and variety of trees. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-MOVE-AFTERMATH (Philadelphia) _ Gerald Wayne Renfrow
thought the nightmare hit its climax 15 years ago on a gruesome day
when he and his neighbors watched the city police bomb and burn
down his solid working-class neighborhood, killing 11 people in a
confrontation that became a firestorm. ``Now they're bombing us
again,'' said Renfrow, more furious than sad as he girds against
the city's latest attempt at what officials are calling ``closure''
for Osage Avenue. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-REPORT (Undated) _ Almost half the money from federal
education programs is going to the poorest schools in the country,
but those schools continue to lack qualified teachers and
technological resources, including computers with Internet access,
says a new report from the Department of Education. By Edward Wong.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-EXCLUSIVE (Los Angeles) _ Details to come. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BIO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Democratic freshman class
that was elected to the House of Representatives in 1976 was a
remarkable one, loaded with bright and ambitious young reformers
who blended the idealism of their generation with the cynicism bred
by Watergate and Vietnam. Many would go on to bigger things _ Dick
Gephardt to the top of the House Democratic leadership, Leon
Panetta to the White House as chief of staff, Barbara Mikulski to
the Senate. But even in this hotbed of ambition, Al Gore stood out.
By Kevin Sack and Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-DONORS (Washington) _ The Democratic convention starting on
Monday in Los Angeles will be a display of wealth, power and
influence as gaudy as the Republican show in Philadelphia. By John
M. Broder and Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-LOSANGELES (Los Angeles) _ Major public events like the
Democratic convention are opportunities for the host cities to put
a well-scrubbed face forward and for their power elite to stand on
a national stage, displaying a shared sense of civic pride and
identity. But in Los Angeles, a sprawling concatenation of
communities with a restless multi-ethnic character, there is no
single ``face,'' in the usual sense of the word. A surge of
immigration and the rapid shift toward an economy dominated by
small businesses rather than huge corporations have pushed Los
Angeles into a dizzyingly complex transition. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-SECURITY (Los Angeles) _ The police say they are ready.
They've chopped down trees that could be set on fire, uprooted
newspaper racks that could be used as battering rams and fenced off
a good-size patch of downtown Los Angeles with tall, silver swaths
of chain-link in an effort to keep any protests at the Democratic
National Convention from getting out of hand. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Hopping away from Clinton
concupiscence. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ End of the ZIRP _ and possibly the
end of an era. By Paul Krugman. &QL;
</P>
