<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain soaked parts of metropolitan New York on Saturday as
a potent jet stream disturbance spiraled slowly south from Canada.
Sunday, the same disturbance will spawn a low pressure system near
the New Jersey coast, setting the stage for damp weather along much
of the Northeast seaboard. Farther south, partial morning sunshine
will yield to clouds and spotty afternoon thunderstorms in the
southern Middle Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, subsiding air currents associated with high
pressure will bring sunny skies to the central Great Lakes and Ohio
Valley. Meanwhile, isolated storms will form in the Middle West as
an approaching cool front interacts with increasingly humid air.
</P>
<P>
   The West will broil amid plentiful sun, though cooler air will
be found near the coast and in the Rockies where spotty
thunderstorms erupt.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DANCING LIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   A dazzling display of colors emblazoned the nighttime sky across
parts of the Midwest early Saturday. The Aurora Borealis, often
called the Northern Lights, is frequently seen near the Arctic
Circle, where charged particles from the sun collide with gases in
the upper atmosphere. These gases then emit colored light, much
like molecules in a neon sign give off red light after being
bombarded by electrons. A large solar flare on Wednesday increased
the flow of charged particles from the sun, thus setting the stage
for the dancing lights of the aurora over latitudes farther south
than usual. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
