<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PRUDES AND PLAYBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dreaming of a convention gleaming with purity,
Gore aides and Democratic officials bullied and blackmailed Rep.
Loretta Sanchez of California until she tearfully canceled her
fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the shapely former Playmates whom Sanchez hired as
``docents,'' Hef in satin pj's and those bodacious blond twins on
Hef's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Pressuring the spunky lawmaker to switch to a less libidinous
site, the Gore team held hostage her prime-time speaking slot at
the convention and threatened to yank her credentials, fire her as
the Democratic Party's general co-chairwoman and withhold support
for her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a three-month contest of wills, Sanchez caved in
on Friday and agreed to move the fund-raiser if the Democrats could
come up with a place with ``that kind of cachet,'' as she put it,
so all her donors would still show.
</P>
<P>
   That got me thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Where could the Democrats go to raise a pile of dough, a place
with that same louche cachet _ a place associated with a
superannuated roue, young buxom playthings, historic sexual
significance?
</P>
<P>
   A place where Hollywood celebrities like Jack Nicholson and
Leonardo DiCaprio hang? A place where the randy, retro goings-on
have made conservatives screech and feminists blanch?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. What about the Oval Office?
</P>
<P>
   It's perfect, really. Why do the Democrats need the Playboy
Mansion when they already have the Executive Mansion? The party has
used its Pennsylvania Avenue pleasure dome to shake down millions
in the last eight years. Instead of carting her off to Universal
Studios, why not let Sanchez borrow the White House for one boogie
night to raise money to enlist Hispanic voters?
</P>
<P>
   When Al Gore was a senator, he used to give metaphor dinners, at
which participants would ponder the meaning of the metaphor.
Clearly, the vice president has elevated the Playboy Mansion to a
metaphor.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and Joe Lieberman are no longer satisfied with being
hall monitors. The men who want to lead the party of free
expression and civil liberties are scuttling away from the Playboy
in Chief so fast they are charging into Cotton Mather territory.
They are so determined to erase the memory of an X-rated president
that they proselytize for everything to be G-rated.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Gore would be better off if he had held dinners to
discuss the meaning of irony. Then he would understand how risible
this seems.
</P>
<P>
   You can't accept $1,500 in donations from the Hefners and then
get on a high horse when a fellow Democrat wants to use the
Hefners' house to solicit donations. You can't defend Bill Clinton
over a romp with an intern, calling him ``one of our greatest
presidents,'' and then treat Loretta Sanchez like a reprobate. You
can't back Clinton on selling the Lincoln Bedroom to fat cats, and
then mug Sanchez because she tries to lure fat cats with a famous
venue.
</P>
<P>
   You can't fix your problem with women voters by bashing Bunnies.
The president did something lecherous in a staid place; the
congresswoman merely tried to do something staid in a lecherous
place.
</P>
<P>
   Gore may have dragged one congresswoman into line, but he'll
never match W.'s disciplined convention. The Clintons are out of
control, gluttonously and gracelessly gobbling millions for the
Arkansas library and New York campaign that should go to the
lagging Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had been pressuring Clinton to say in his convention
speech that Gore should not be blamed for his wayward ways.
</P>
<P>
   But the president has told friends he wants to make the best
speech of his life, going out like Babe Ruth, who hit three homers
in his last game. So he decided to ``purge'' a few days early and
get that out of the way. But his self-involved, conveniently timed
apologia only served to remind everyone about how the White House
lost its dignity, underscoring W.'s plaints.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Hillary and Bill have begun talking up the idea
that she really was the co-president all along, but they had to
keep it quiet.
</P>
<P>
   So where does all this leave Al?
</P>
<P>
   If Hillary was second banana, was he third? And will he be
relegated to a spot in the lineup behind the Sultan of Political
Swat swinging to knock it out of the park?
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least Gore crushed Sanchez. So he has one good Godzilla
vs. Bambi moment under his belt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
