<HEADLINE>
INSTANT MAKEOVER AWAITS L.A. VISITORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANE ROBISON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Hello, Democrats, ``Destination, Dream Land,''
awaits you.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles welcomes you to the land of make-believe and makeup
tips, tummy tucks and tireless toning.
</P>
<P>
   Bring us your tired feet, your masses of wrinkles and chubby
thighs.
</P>
<P>
   While you're here anointing your chosen candidate, Vice
President Al Gore, we'll remake and remold you, rejuvenate and
restore your every pore during your five days or so in paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Reinvent yourself, just like everyone else in Tinseltown.
</P>
<P>
   You can be whoever you want to be. You can have whatever you
want. This is L.A. and that's our credo.
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to trudge back to Pocatello looking the same as when
he or she came (For that matter, who wants to go back to Pocatello
at all?), when for a mere $2,000 you can plunge into the fountain
of youth and come up looking like Jennifer Aniston, or new hubby
Brad Pitt, or both.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're thinking the next five days isn't enough time to
be totally rejuvenated and completely transformed beyond your
wildest dreams, dear Dem, think again.
</P>
<P>
   You're not in Kansas anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Brush off the dust of Enid, Okla., and discover the true El
Dorado a golden spigot of beauty, youth and oneness with the
universe.
</P>
<P>
   We'll dazzle you with botox injections and tumescent
liposuctions. We'll pamper you with paraffin hand wraps and
detoxifying herbal wraps.
</P>
<P>
   This is the opportunity of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The city where dreams are made and people made up to look like
dreams. And for the dreams that don't work out, L.A.'s the place to
redesign yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lackmeyer didn't exactly reinvent himself. The Cincinnati
native just made the most of an opportunity after his dream of
becoming an Olympic runner didn't quite work out in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   While running at the Santa Monica Track Club, where Carl Lewis
trained, Lackmeyer was approached by a friend and asked whether he
could help get an actor in shape for a role. The actor was Val
Kilmer who was starring as Jim Morrison in ``The Doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Lackmeyer did such a good job, he ended up with a new career as
a personal trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just blossomed after that,'' said Lackmeyer, 41, who now
lives in Agoura Hills.
</P>
<P>
   When women come to Lackmeyer to get in shape they almost always
have an image in mind of who they want to look like - Madonna, he
says. For men, it's Brad Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   So when we asked Lackmeyer, who trains the Marciano family,
owners of Guess? jeans, to develop a workout for visiting
Democrats, he came up with our 5-day Fitness Makeover. And here it
is:
</P>
<P>
   Day 1: Start with the politically correct warm-up: Walk around
Staples Center twice, refusing to take any money from special
interest groups. ``You may have to run,'' Lackmeyer advises.
</P>
<P>
   Day 2: Lieberman Lunges. Keep head up, back straight, feet close
together and step forward as far as possible, being careful not to
step on anyone else's toes or ego.
</P>
<P>
   Day 3: Presidential Push-ups. Kneel on the floor with hands 24
inches apart. Place legs straight behind, back straight and head
up. Place presidential speech on the floor directly under your
face. Keeping body rigid, lower yourself until your nose touches
your speech. Breathe deeply, repeating to yourself, ``I will win
this election, yes. I will win this election ...''
</P>
<P>
   Day 4: Democratic Dips. Hold yourself straight on bars. Keep
elbows into sides, lower your body by bending shoulders and elbows.
Lower yourself down, (Bill can help you if you have trouble with
this one). Pause, then press back to arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   Day 5: Al Gore's Beach Blast Run. Run hard and run long, just
like Al's acceptance speech is likely to be.
</P>
<P>
   Lackmeyer warns that if this doesn't help jump-start your
fitness program, maybe you're not ready for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some Democrats might be too busy partying to fit in a
personal trainer or to work out at one of L.A.'s gyms that have so
many well-toned, sexy members, Congresswomen Loretta Sanchez could
have thrown a fund-raiser and still not gotten Al Gore to show up.
</P>
<P>
   For those Dems, L.A.'s ``Fitness by Phone,'' a training regimen
created by personal trainer Susan Block of Encino, will come in
handy.
</P>
<P>
   Block invented the program to give traveling Hollywood people
the will and the way to stay fit without having a personal trainer
by their side. Instead, they're given a calorie monitor that looks
like a pager and records all their movements throughout the day.
Once a week, they go over the results with a trainer by phone and
set goals for the following week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're empowering people to take personal responsibility,''
said Block, who has 1,000 clients in a business she developed just
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly the kind of trainer that vice presidential
running mate Joseph Lieberman would advocate.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nobody should leave Los Angeles without availing
themselves of all the cosmic opportunities for cosmetic
enhancement.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Los Angeles and Beverly Hills have more plastic
surgeons per capita than any region in the world, according to the
American Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery and the American
Society of Plastic Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   Women have long sought the services of L.A.'s corps of plastic
surgeons. But according to Dr. Les Bolton of Beverly Hills, a
growing number of men are discovering that plastic surgery can give
them an edge in the business world, especially the e-commerce
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more men in their late 40s and 50s are coming in
because they're competing against 25-year-old billionaires in
e-commerce and they want to have an edge,'' Bolton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to stay fit, so they go to the gym. But if they want
to feel vital and vivacious, they go to a plastic surgeon.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the miracles of modern medicine, it's possible to
undergo several cosmetic procedures in the morning and still make
the evening speeches at the convention without any visible scars.
</P>
<P>
   As you sit, carefully, in rapt attention, fellow delegates no
doubt will remark what a wonderful glow you have.
</P>
<P>
   That glow can be achieved with a 30-minute, $100-$250
microdermabrasion that peels fine lines away and rejuvenates the
skin, according to Dr. Debra Luftman, who teaches skin surgery and
general dermatology at UCLA and who has her own practice.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how much can be done in just minutes. Botox
injections to remove the crow's feet around the eyes, collagen
injections that give you the Mick Jagger mouth, and
microdermabrasion, which sounds like something the Ruckus Society
will be staging for maximum TV time, can all be done in less than
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd start with the tumescent liposuction, which
Luftman calls the ``safest and most effective method available.''
The four-hour, $3,000-$6,000 procedure shaves off mounds of blubber
while you're awake with a local anesthesia. No noticeable scars and
by the end of the week, people will notice your too-tight jeans are
a little looser.
</P>
<P>
   However, Luftman warns that the full effects won't be noticeable
until you're back watching corn grow in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The only hitch might be transportation or getting trapped
downtown in demonstration central.
</P>
<P>
   If they were smart, plastic surgeons would park a van just
outside Staples Center and offer a surgical strike team.
</P>
<P>
   If you've followed my instructions, by now it's Tuesday, halfway
through the convention. You've started on your fitness regimen,
you've worked in the plastic surgeon and now you're ready to be
pampered at a spa while protesters lay siege to downtown.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when you'll contact the very serene and soothing
Barbara Gauthier, owner of the Gauthier Total Image Spa in Sherman
Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   A day with Gauthier and her staff will leave Democrats so
relaxed and rejuvenated, they'll swear Al Gore is the best orator
since Oliver Wendell Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier herself is the quintessential L.A. success story. She
arrived in Los Angeles more years ago than she'd care to remember,
but she does remember her first impression looking over the palm
trees as her plane was landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was paradise,'' she said, her eyes still aglow
with excitement. ``I loved this place, all the diversity it had to
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Her road to all things beautiful started out as a simple journey
to buy a washer and dryer. ``I needed the money,'' she said, so she
began selling cosmetics out of a closet in her house.
</P>
<P>
   Today, her business is 15 years old, employees 23 and serves
clients who include movie and TV industry big shots.
</P>
<P>
   People love to feel good about themselves when they're in Los
Angeles. And they love to be worked on by the same people who work
on stars.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't like the term ``makeover.'' It sounds too much like
what it is, a schlep that needs to start over.
</P>
<P>
   She prefers: ``image update.''
</P>
<P>
   Give her three hours and she'll find the real you under those
puffy eyes, swollen ankles, sagging shoulders and clothes that
scream ``Home Shopping Network.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the optimal treatment in the minimal amount of time, she
recommends two people work on you at once. For a mere $250, you
could get a foot reflexology to rejuvenate and balance the body,
followed by a facial, a parafin hand treatment, a haircut and
style, and a manicure while sitting next to the cast of a daytime
soap.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Al's given his acceptance speech. He's gotten a
minibounce in the polls, and you're ready for some heavy face
lifting and breast augmentation Friday, followed by some serious
R&AMP;R in Santa Barbara to recuperate from all the parties and the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But then, once you've discovered the serenity of Santa Barbara,
Ronald Reagan's old haunt, it's doubtful you'll ever make it back
to the Rust Belt or the Snow Belt or the Bible Belt or the Borscht
Belt.
</P>
<P>
   What's a soccer mother or father to do?
</P>
<P>
   File a name change with Los Angeles Superior Court, take your
new face, your buff body and your new personal awareness and open a
little chakra shop on Ventura Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Destination, Dream Land'' is at your feet.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
