<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-GUIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGE SET AT STAPLES CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ It's showtime.
</P>
<P>
   After months of planning, the transformation of Staples Center
is complete, with barely a shred of Lakers purple in sight - just a
whole lot of red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   The 900,000-square-foot sports arena now is draped with the
colorful bunting, swirling lights and electric anticipation that
come with the biggest political parties to hit the nation every
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the future of America when you walk into the door,''
said Luis Vizcaino, press secretary for the Democratic National
Convention Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center has gone from an entertainment and sports arena to
a 21st century convention hall where we will nominate the first
president of the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Intricate plans and calculated designs have been in the works
for months to create a striking experience for the 35,000 VIPs,
delegates and media representatives when they venture onto Ground
Zero.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, they will be treated to a festive atmosphere, with
800 moving lights and dozens of hovering, glowing signs reading
``America 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   But the experience begins even before visitors and delegates
enter Staples Center. As they arrive inside the secured perimeter
of the convention area, they are greeted by tall white metal fences
and tight security.
</P>
<P>
   Even outside, there are ingredients of a festive atmosphere. An
open-air plaza next to Staples Center - at 12th and Figueroa
streets - has been blocked off for music, munching and mingling.
Each afternoon, delegates will be able to enjoy ethnic foods, music
and entertainment in the plaza before heading indoors for the day's
meetings and speeches.
</P>
<P>
   In Staples Center, a carpeted floor has been built five inches
above the arena's cement floor to hide hundreds of cables snaking
across it.
</P>
<P>
   The stage sits on the east side at basketball's half-court line.
The podium is futuristic and festive, silver in color with red and
blue stripes and stars and an 18-by-32-foot projection screen above
it.
</P>
<P>
   The height of the stage - five feet - is a key component to the
elaborate design, planners say. It sits lower than any in
convention history, and speakers will be closer to the delegates
for a more intimate feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to be the most interactive, open and accessible
convention ever,'' Vizcaino said. ``The feel of the hall is of
openness and inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   California delegates get prime seats closest to the stage and
next to delegates from Vice President Al Gore's home state,
Tennessee. Connecticut delegates were hastily moved down front from
the back row after Gore picked Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman as
his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   For delegates, 56 voting stations are set up on the floor and in
the seats. Even the voting stations have a millennial air -
lecterns, each equipped with two telephones and a
futuristic-looking iMac computer.
</P>
<P>
   Looming above the delegates, plush skyboxes have been converted
into television broadcast booths. CNN overhauled three skyboxes to
accommodate equipment and personalities who already have started
broadcasting live from the center.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury suites' hard cherry wood doors have been replaced
with ones made of particle board to minimize damage from media
equipment and harried broadcast technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Looming even higher above are special moving lights affixed to
ceiling trusses. The lights are programmed to focus on speakers or
single delegations, illuminating and highlighting them in the
massive room.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a high-tech sound system was installed for speeches
and music.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging in the rafters are signs of a grand finale - bundles of
red, white and blue balloons, more than 200,000 in all, which will
be dropped after Gore accepts the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   This week, students and adults inflated the balloons and stuffed
them into enormous clear plastic sleeves that were lifted to the
ceiling in anticipation of the big finish.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, there will be confetti - lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 pounds of multicolor, shredded paper - also
stuffed in plastic sleeves - will rain down at the same time as the
balloons during the celebration Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the last balloon falls and the delegates head home,
workers will scurry to clean up the arena and television crews will
move in to tape an episode of NBC's White House drama ``The West
Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to wonder what the plot of that episode will be.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-OAK-DISEASE-ART-4     08-12 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-OAK-DISEASE-ART-480(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGRESSIVE DISEASE FELLS TREES IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FELTON, Calif. _ Despite the beauty of the towering redwoods and
bay trees in these mountains some 60 miles south of San Francisco,
it is the more modest tanoak trees that are everywhere dead and
dying that draw the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Their sheaves of brown leaves a startling contrast to the
verdant forest around them, these tanoaks, like thousands of trees
up and down the California coast, are falling victim to a new
disease. Scientists call it sudden oak death syndrome, and they are
alarmed by its rapid spread and its ability to kill an ever
increasing number and variety of trees.
</P>
<P>
   So many trees began dying this year that scientists began a mad
scramble to understand this syndrome, first seen five years ago in
a single patch of tanoak trees just north of San Francisco. In July
researchers found evidence that the die-off _ which has spread to
three tree species _ had also spread over 350 miles along the coast
from far northern into central California, fueling concerns that
the disease might continue its rapid spread to other species and
outside of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers became even more concerned last month when another
team of scientists discovered that the culprit appeared to be a
previously unknown species of Phytophthora, a notorious group of
funguslike organisms that includes the species that caused the
Irish potato blight and the species now killing oak trees in Europe
and eucalyptus trees in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen anything like this,'' said Dr. Rick
Standiford, associate dean for forestry at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``Oak trees die, of course, but nothing to
this extent. Knowing what Dutch elm disease and chestnut blight
have done to our forests _ chestnuts are basically extinct _
hopefully that doesn't happen with oaks.''
</P>
<P>
   A state of emergency has been declared in Marin County, one of
the hardest-hit areas, and a statewide task force has been created.
Possible federal actions will be considered on Tuesday by the
Department of Agriculture, which has the authority to call
quarantines to restrict the movement of a plant disease.
</P>
<P>
   While describing the disease as having reached epidemic
proportions, scientists note that there are still vast stretches of
healthy oak trees even in affected areas, though how long and how
many of those will remain healthy is impossible to predict.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are predicting, however, that the growing die-off
will have a huge impact on the thousands of animal species that
rely on leaves and acorns from these trees. Concern also is growing
over the fire risk posed by the rapid accumulation of dead trees in
already fire-prone areas. In addition, many homeowners are
panicking over the loss of beloved and valuable trees. In hard-hit
and well-to-do Marin County, for example, a coast live oak tree can
add as much as $30,000 to the value of a property.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The disease was discovered by Dr. Pavel Svihra, a horticulturist
at the University of California at Davis, in 1995 when he was
called by homeowners in the town of Mill Valley to inspect dying
tanoak trees that bordered their backyards. But for years he was
unable to arouse the interest of other scientists, who dismissed
the problem as trivial.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the disease appears to have spread rapidly, showing
up in a variety of forests, from tourist destinations like Muir
Woods National Monument to remote wild lands to suburban backyards.
And it has jumped from attacking only tanoaks, a poorly regarded
species, to attacking prized coast live oaks and black oaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence was so overwhelming that something was going
on,'' said Dr. Brice McPherson, entomologist at the University of
California at Berkeley. ``People just couldn't ignore it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The first symptom of the syndrome is the so-called bleeding, as
wine-red sap oozes from the bark. Later the tree is attacked by
beetles that leave a coating of sawdust on the bark and by fungi,
including one known as Hypoxylon that sprouts black warty growths
on the trunk. When the tree eventually dies its leaves go quickly
from green to brown, hence the name sudden oak death syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers still do not know how the disease moves from tree to
tree or forest to forest. But in the laboratory this summer, Dr.
David Rizzo, a plant pathologist at the University of California at
Davis, and colleagues discovered that the new Phytophthora makes a
spore that can swim. The finding suggests the disease could move in
water as the spores of other Phytophthora species are known to do.
But the disease could also have spores that are moving via soil,
wind, beetle feet, hiking shoes or tires. With the disease
prevalent in state parks, neighborhoods and other areas frequented
by humans, some suspect humans are the real culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does it spread so fast? People visit Muir Woods, get it in
the tires of their car and drive home to Santa Cruz and bingo!''
said Rizzo, whose laboratory discovered that the disease was caused
by a Phytophthora. ``It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists noted that while disease-causing spores are likely to
spread far beyond California, they will only cause trouble _ on the
East Coast, for example _ if tree species in the new areas are
susceptible and if the Phytophthora can withstand a variety of
climates. Researchers are testing both conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are still trying to determine just how far the
disease has spread and how many trees have been afflicted, with
estimates ranging from the thousands to the millions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Maggi Kelly, remote sensing specialist at the University of
California at Berkeley, and McPherson are using aerial digital
photography to search for early signs of the disease. Stressed
trees often reflect light differently and if these researchers can
find such a visual signature from the air, it would allow them to
quickly do large-scale surveys of the spread of the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a team of six students working with Dr. Steve Zack, a
wildlife ecologist with the Wildlife Conservation Society based at
the Bronx Zoo in New York, has done the broadest survey yet,
individually examining 8,000 tanoak trees over a 350-mile span up
and down the coast. They are finding an average of 15 percent of
the trees are infected across the range and as many as 80 percent
are infected in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of all the missing acorns and leaves will probably be
huge, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cascading effect of losing these trees is going to be
awesome,'' Zack said. ``We're just waiting for the other shoe to
drop.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear why the disease is spreading now, whether it
is because this Phytophthora species is an exotic pest that has
just arrived or whether it is because the species is a formerly
benign organism that only recently evolved a virulent form. A few
scientists are arguing that the disease may be a longstanding but
normally milder one that is temporarily flaring up as it takes
advantage of trees stressed by weather or water conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for the disease's spread, many people, in
particular homeowners, are desperate for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of homes, whole neighborhoods are built around these oak
trees,'' said Nicole Palkovsky, oak project coordinator for the
Marin County Cooperative Extension, which provides horticultural
and related advice to residents. ``People are emotionally
devastated when they lose their trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from having a cure, scientists say they are afraid that
current efforts to eradicate the disease may be doing more harm
than good. For example, some land managers and homeowners are
cutting and uprooting diseased trees. If the disease spores move in
water or air or soil or via the tree's wood, such movement could
accelerate the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists also are concerned about the effect on the
environment if homeowners begin applying fungicide, which may or
may not even affect the disease, and insecticide, which is being
used to keep the beetles at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago researchers were reluctant to make
recommendations because so little was known. The severity of the
disease, however, is dissolving the hesitation of even the most
cautious researchers, as scientists have begun calling for action,
including quarantines on the movement of oak wood and living oak
trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much we still don't know,'' said Dr. Susan Frankel,
forest pathologist with the Forest Service and chairwoman of the
newly formed California Oak Mortality Task Force. ``But we all
agreed that we can't wait any longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
