<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OAK-DISEASE (Felton, Calif.) _ Despite the beauty of the
towering redwoods and bay trees in these mountains some 60 miles
south of San Francisco, it is the more modest tanoak trees that
that draw the eye. These tanoaks are falling victim to a new
disease. Scientists call it sudden oak death syndrome, and they are
alarmed by its rapid spread and its ability to kill an ever
increasing number and variety of trees. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   3-graf refer:
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-FAULTY-CABLES (Undated) _ On May 18, the Federal
Aviation Administration issued what appeared to be an important
safety notice for the world's airlines. Federal investigators had
learned that a manufacturer of cables that work key controls in
many widely used jetliners might not have properly tested its
cables. Samples checked by investigators, the notice said, had
failed to meet minimum requirements for strength. FAA officials
expected the airlines to check their fleets and, if necessary,
replace the cables. But federal prosecutors who were suing the
cable maker said that the system broke down because the critical
information did not reach airlines as intended. By John Sullivan.
</P>
