<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9706 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-ART-10     08-12 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-ART-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREANS, DIVIDED BY WAR, AWAIT RELATIVES' RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ In the chaos that was the first few months
of the Korean War in 1950, Kim Hyun-suk, age 14, went off to school
one morning _ and never came back.
</P>
<P>
   His family could only speculate on his fate until, in 1964, they
received word from a neighbor in their hometown that a letter had
come for them from North Korea via Japan, indicating that the boy
who had vanished was in the hermetically sealed communist North.
</P>
<P>
   That ought to have been good news, but it carried its own woe,
for in the dictatorial South Korea of the time, any hint of contact
with the North spelled peril.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor, who had received the letter on behalf of the
family, was so excited that he gossiped about it. So the mailman
who had delivered the letter came and confiscated it, unopened,
before Kim Hyun-suk's father could get back to his hometown to
retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, in 1965, the post office notified the family that
a similar letter had arrived _ but refused to hand it over.
</P>
<P>
   With suspicions aroused about links to the communist North, Kim
Hyun-suk's younger brother, now 59, suddenly found himself without
a job, and he had to get by doing odd jobs that he picked up as he
could. His father, who had owned a photography studio, was forced
to close shop and do various jobs, hiring out a car for use as a
cab and traveling to Manchuria for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspected my brother was in North Korea, but we couldn't
tell even our friends that a family member was living there,'' said
the brother, Kim Hyun-ki. ``That would have caused a lot of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   With that history in mind, the family did not even apply to
participate in the reunions that in coming days will bring 100
North Koreans south, and take 100 southerners north, reassembling
remnants of families separated in a war that has never officially
ended, despite an uneasy truce across the 38th parallel since 1953.
</P>
<P>
   But Kim Hyun-suk did apply to join the reunions _ and his South
Korean family was stunned when the Red Cross called to tell them
their son and brother wanted to come to see them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recently realized that a person I thought was dead is going
to meet me, and I'm overjoyed,'' said Kim Nam-shik, Kim Hyun-suk's
father.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, the school told Kim Nam-shik that his son had gone on a
school trip. ``A war had just broken out, and no one had any time
to look for a lost student,'' the father said. ``We had no one to
turn to. It's hard for me to say that we ever gave up looking for
him, but there was no place to get any information, and the war was
intensifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when they got word of the mysterious letters that came via
Japan, the idea that his son was still alive had a whiff of
unreality. ``We heard about these letters through a third party and
at times I even doubted they existed,'' Kim Nam-shik said. ``I had
lived until then having given up on ever seeing my son again.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife was more hopeful. ``Every day until she died last year,
my mother placed a bowl of clear water in the garden and prayed for
my brother's return,'' said Kim Hyun-ki, Kim Nam-shik's second son.
</P>
<P>
   They cannot imagine what their reaction to the reunion will be
and sometimes still speak of the meeting as if it might not occur.
``So much time has gone by that if I see him, I don't even know if
I'll have any tears,'' Kim Hyun-ki said.
</P>
<P>
   His memories of his brother are those of a 9-year-old envious of
an older sibling. ``I was the ugly duckling,'' Kim Hyun-ki said.
``He was better-looking, very smart, and he was the one who got the
most attention and love.''
</P>
<P>
   The father is so overwhelmed that he does not know what he will
say to his oldest son at Tuesday's planned reunion. ``It's just
unreal that we are meeting, and that in itself is enough,'' he
said. ``I don't know how much longer I will be alive or whether we
can ever live together for a brief period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to have any hope,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Koreans involved in the reunions are at the forefront of the
effort to rebuild a single Korean nation by first mending hearts
broken long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reuniting the separated families is the most important part of
the efforts toward eventual reunification,'' said Lee Sang-man, a
professor at Chung-Ang University who is advising the government on
unification. ``Without a solution to this humanitarian issue, we
cannot achieve anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange of family members separated by the war was given
top priority at the historic summit meeting in June between the
South Korean president, Kim Dae-jung, and the North Korean leader,
Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   There was a similar, albeit smaller, reunion in 1985, but it was
an isolated event. This reunion is intended to be the critical
first step in bringing the two nations together. As the two leaders
acknowledged, without restoring the human bonds torn by the war,
there would be little hope of cultivating the economic cooperation
and reduction in military tension that would form the foundation
for eventual reunification.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a symbolic event,'' Lee said. ``The
government strongly believes that it is a prerequisite to
everything to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The meetings are regarded as the strongest evidence to date that
Kim Jong Il, until the summit meeting a mysterious recluse who
ruled his country with the totalitarian power established by his
father, Kim Il Sung, is committed to rapprochement. Information is
tightly controlled in North Korea, the last bastion of hard-core
Stalinism in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, by allowing North Koreans a tiny glimpse into the lives of
their more affluent relatives in the South, Kim Jong Il is taking
perhaps the biggest gamble since his father's death in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the meetings have been carefully scripted. The
reunions will take place in the tightly sealed environments of
hotels in Pyongyang, North Korea, and Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   The North Koreans visiting Seoul will not even be able to go to
the graves of relatives who died during the separation, a
restriction that is regarded by many in this Confucian society as
more troubling than the inability of the visitors to stay in their
families' homes for the three-day reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the control, nothing can dim the excitement and
tension surrounding the lucky Koreans chosen for the meetings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kim Joon-sup, now 66, left what was then his home in Pyongyang
on July 9, 1950, and headed for his graduation. He was 15 at the
time, and he had no idea that he would not see his home again.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks earlier, the North Korean army had begun the
Korean War, marching south across the 38th parallel. The army
needed recruits, including Kim Joon-sup and his graduating
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother had to go to the church that day and couldn't attend
the ceremony, and my father was working for the railroad and
couldn't come,'' recalled Kim Joon-sup, who eventually became a
prisoner of war in South Korea and stayed on to make his life here.
``So I told my parents goodbye, intending to return after the
ceremony, but 50 years later, I still haven't gone home.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after graduation, Kim Joon-sup's class was herded
onto the school's soccer field and enlisted. ``We never even
touched our diplomas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Kim Joon-sup will go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember playing with my siblings on the banks of the
Taedong River,'' he said. ``We would pan for gold, and in those
days, if you did it all day long, you'd come up with a couple of
flecks.''
</P>
<P>
   He will meet his younger brother, Kim Chang Hyup, and his
sister, Kim Kyung Sup. ``She was only 6 years old when I was taken
away, and I remember that she was really pretty,'' Kim Joon-sup
said. ``But who doesn't think that about their baby sister?''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Joon-sup, like the other South Koreans traveling north, is
an ordinary citizen. Most of those coming south, however, are
believed to be North Korean loyalists who have high-level ties to
the Communist Party and are from academia and the arts.
</P>
<P>
   They will have only limited time to meet with their South Korean
relatives, and they will see Seoul only from the buses that will
take them to various sites, including Lotte World, a shopping mall
and amusement-park complex, and Changdok Palace, the historic home
of Korea's emperors. Oddly, North Korea is rumored to have
requested that the palace be included on the itinerary. ``There is
absolutely zero risk for defection,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   The Unification Ministry put a priority on older people like Kim
Nam-shik but used a computer in an effort to make the selection
process as neutral as possible. Priority was given to separated
spouses, then to parents separated from children, and then to
siblings.
</P>
<P>
   There were inevitable tragedies. Chang I-yun, 71, had been told
his 109-year-old mother was alive in the North, only to get news
that she had died. And one 90-year-old woman died shortly after
receiving word that her son might be selected to visit Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Even Kim Joon-sup, who was kidnapped into the North Korean army,
was rushed to the emergency room with acute indigestion after
hearing that he was to be reunited with his siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Moon Kyung-ja, a life insurance broker whose sister is in the
North, considered herself such a long shot for the reunion that,
like Kim Nam-shik, she did not apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned on the TV and saw my sister's name on the screen,''
Moon said. ``I kept calling the Red Cross but I couldn't get
through. Finally I did get through, and just after I hung up the
phone, a television station called and said they were coming over
with a camera crew. I was out of my mind _ and I have to watch my
high blood pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon's memory of her sister is rooted in a childhood turned
upside down when the war erupted, when Moon was 10. Her father, a
wealthy industrialist with interests in coal mining, fled to a
remote family cottage, and then disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, faced with the alternative of being labeled a
capitalist by the communists who were fast marching down the
peninsula, went to work for them, doing various odd jobs and making
sure she always had one of her children with her so the troops
would leave her alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had to work to support the North Korean troops,'' Moon
recalled, humming a tune the soldiers taught her to sing to keep up
their morale. ``My older sister worked in the canteen and sneaked
rice to us.''
</P>
<P>
   When the tide turned against the North Korean troops, the work
Moon's mother had done for the communists landed her in prison.
Relatives refused to help her or her children. ``My uncle, who was
in the army, moved into our house and refused to give us any food,
even though we begged him to just give us a little something for my
baby brother,'' Moon recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The essentially orphaned children found themselves begging for
food from their former servants, who scorned them. Realizing that
they would die on their own in Seoul, Moon's oldest sister, Moon
Yang-ok, took Moon and her younger sister to live with relatives in
the town of Chi Rae in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Moon Yang-ok returned to Seoul, and then disappeared along with
Moon's second-oldest sister and her brother. Moon's mother had also
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were too scared to talk about them because until the 1970s
any word that you had worked for the North Koreans and you were
severely punished,'' said Moon, who is now 59. ``But we were
desperate for news. We spent a fortune on famous fortune tellers,
and any time we had even the vaguest word that they were sighted
somewhere, we would head off for that city or town, only to be
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   She suspected that her sister was in the North, but she did not
know what to do. Her younger sister, Moon Jong-oh, moved to Los
Angeles, and Moon has not heard from her in two years. ``I am
alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Red Cross called her and brought a passport-sized
photo of a sad-faced woman bearing a remarkable resemblance to
Moon. ``It was like seeing someone from another country,'' she
said. ``It felt very strange. I could tell she went through a lot
of hard times, but the man from the Red Cross, he told me she's one
of the better-off ones.''
</P>
<P>
   She suspects that her sister, one of the seven or eight women
who will come from the North, is married to a high-ranking North
Korean official, but those politics do not bother her a bit. ``I'm
happy about that,'' she said. ``It means she's had a good life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
