<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9712 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-ART-NYT &LR;      08-12 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM PARTY CONVENTION ENDS WITH RIVAL NOMINEES AND LIKELY
LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr. and MICHAEL JANOFSKY  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8
is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Battered and sundered into competing
factions, the Reform Party fought through the final hours of a
bitter national convention Saturday, then limped out of town as two
parties, each with its own ideology and nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Both laid claim to the Reform Party name. But other than that,
about the only thing they shared was a highly questionable future
and the strong likelihood that they would end up in a
campaign-crimping court battle this fall over the original party's
remains and $12.6 million in federal campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   Gone from this raucous four-day affair was the commanding
presence of Ross Perot, who founded the Reform Party eight years
ago and, with his rapid-fire talk of changing the federal
bureaucracy, briefly made it a potent third force in U.S. politics.
A couple of years ago, when he sensed that the country, grown
economically fat and seemingly content, had lost its appetite for
him and political reform, he cut his ties to the party, leaving it
to drift.
</P>
<P>
   It came hard aground here in Long Beach this week and broke in
two. Try as they might, party officials could not put it back
together.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, the hard-right columnist and former Republican
presidential contender, took one part. John Hagelin, a soft-spoken
perennial candidate who usually runs under the banner of the
Natural Law Party, took the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``At long last we have a home of our own,'' Buchanan said
Saturday after his faction chose him as its nominee. ``And this
party we are building together is being built to last.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin struck a similar note in his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your party,'' he told his cheering followers.
``Breathe strength into it. Grow it into America's next major
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the two men agreed on nothing. Rather, they accused
each other of just about every sin under the political sun,
especially of trying to steal the party away.
</P>
<P>
   As Buchanan saw it, when he joined the party last spring, it was
hardly a party at all. He said his presence would reinvigorate it,
dismissing Hagelin as a political nobody.
</P>
<P>
   In Hagelin's view, Buchanan was a brazen opportunist on the down
side of a political career seeking merely to further his own
conservative social agenda. This agenda is crowded with hot-button
issues like abortion, gun control and affirmative action that
Hagelin argued the party had always avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Both men arrived in Long Beach intent on using the dispirited
party as their vehicle to run for the presidency. The nominee would
get $12.6 million in federal campaign money for the fall run,
because Perot had captured more than 5 percent of the vote in his
1996 presidential run, an amount almost beyond comprehension for a
third-party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that many national polls had Buchanan pulling less
than 2 percent of the popular vote and Hagelin less than 1 percent.
Or, as Russell Verney, who helped Perot found the party in 1992,
put it in one of the few humorous moments of the week:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a close one, all right. John Hagelin is within one point
of Pat Buchanan.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition between the two men grew so intense and angry
that they convened separate conventions and nominating processes in
adjacent convention halls.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan ended up with more delegates than Hagelin _ mainly, it
appeared, because he had seized control of party machinery in many
states with the help of the ``Buchanan Brigades'' from his earlier
presidential runs. Hagelin accused the Brigades of having used
everything from fraud to plain sneakiness to take over state
organizations. He filed a complaint with the Federal Election
Commission and said he would go to court if necessary to prove that
he was Perot's deserving successor.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan insisted that his only interest had been in using the
Reform Party to bring about reform.
</P>
<P>
   In the text of the speech Buchanan prepared to give Saturday
night in accepting his nomination, he talked of ``new reforms,''
but they had little to do with changing government. Rather,
Buchanan repeated what he has been demanding for the better part of
a decade _ outlawing abortion, reining in ``arrogant, unelected
judges, ending racial quotas and preferences.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin talked reform and only reform in his acceptance speech.
He also invoked Perot's name, something no other speaker had done
during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept with humility and with pride the mantle of H. Ross
Perot,'' he began. ``He did more to restore government to the
people of the United States than anybody since Abraham Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot is still a hero to many Reformers. But since he cut off
contact with the party _ he has seldom mentioned it publicly in
almost two years _ there has been no grass-roots push to bring him
back. The impression is that many party members are thankful for
his contribution but feel that he has had his run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
