u i BC-LAOS-PRINCE-NYT &LR;      08-12 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAOS-PRINCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXILED LAOTIAN PRINCE SEEKS NEW ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years ago, an 18-year-old prince, heir to a doomed
Asian royal line, commandeered a small boat and sailed unnoticed
with his brother and their nanny across the Mekong River from Laos
to Thailand. Laos had become a communist nation, in the orbit of
neighboring Vietnam, and the prince, Soulivong Savang, feared being
co-opted or killed.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, the prince _ grandson of the last king of
Laos, who died mysteriously in communist captivity with the
prince's father and other relatives _ is quietly beginning to
reassert his claim of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The return of a monarchy, even a constitutional monarchy, to
Laos is at best a remote possibility. Royal families continue to
play a role in Asia, from the Himalayas through Southeast Asia to
Japan, but Prince Soulivong Savang is not focused on those
examples.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in New York on a recent visit to Laotian exile
communities in the United States, the prince, now 37, said that
after years of a European education in law and political science,
he has found a new hero in King Juan Carlos of Spain, a champion of
democracy in a country that emerged from a long dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so interested in the future of monarchy in Laos,'' he
said, speaking in Lao through an aide who interpreted. ``My main
proposal is to restore democracy first. The restoration of the
monarchy would be up to the Lao people.''
</P>
<P>
   He is taking that message to Laotians exiled in the West at a
time of unexpected new unrest in Laos, a country of barely 5
million people. In recent months, bombings in the capital and other
towns, coupled with an apparently reinvigorated rebellion among the
Hmong people in the north, has shaken the last largely
unreconstructed communist government of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Soulivong Savang treads carefully in talking of the
Vietnamese, who had hoped to keep Laos and Cambodia within an
Indochinese federation dominated by Hanoi. The federation was a
legacy of French colonialism, which ended in the mid-1950s. The
French also promoted the modern Laotian monarchy. As its heir, the
prince is portrayed in Laos as a client of the West.
</P>
<P>
   The crown prince, who lives in Paris, has been following reports
of student unrest and a surreptitious return of the Vietnamese
military to Laos. He is also concerned about the domination of Thai
business on the fragile economy of Laos.
</P>
<P>
   With an end to communism, Vietnamese and Thai influence would be
gone from Laos, said his uncle, Prince Sauryavong Savang, who
escaped death because he was in Thailand when the sweep of the
royal family took place in 1977. The elder prince regent also lives
in Paris. The Laotian government has never said exactly what
happened to the rest of the royal family, except to announce in
1989 that King Savang Vatthana was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Soulivong Savang said that he was away at school in 1977,
when his grandfather, father and six other family members were
arrested. He was allowed to remain with his mother, Princess
Manilay Khampane Panya, in the royal capital, Luang Prabang, though
under constant surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   The government arranged his secondary education, which included
large doses of communist doctrine. A cousin of the late king,
Prince Souphanouvong, had become a Marxist, so there was a
precedent. Because the young prince's family had been stripped of
their money and possessions, he learned to grow rice to feed them,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, he said, his friends began disappearing from
school. ``When they stayed loyal to the monarchy they would be
taken away for re-education,'' he said. ``Later I realized that the
government was trying to prevent a group of supporters growing
around me because by the age of 18, I had become a symbol and a
danger. I heard a rumor that I would be sent to a Communist country
for further education. I was obliged to find a way to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   The prince said that he faked allergies that he said needed
urgent treatment by a doctor in Vientiane, now the Laotian capital.
Before his minders could see what was happening, he had fled from
there across the Mekong to Nong Khai, a Thai river port.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand, he and his brother were protected by the Thai royal
family until it was considered safe to arrange the prince's travel
to France. His mother is still alive in Laos, he said. They met
last year in Australia, where the Lao government had allowed her a
visit when her daughter, the prince's sister, had a baby.
</P>
<P>
   The Laotian exile community _ 100,000 in France, 40,000 in
Australia and half a million in the United States _ has been
fractured ethnically between Lao and Hmong. The crown prince said
he tells both groups that a constitutional monarchy is their best
hope of unity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
