</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ARCTIC-TOURISTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE GOLD RUSH: TOURISTS DISCOVER CANADA'S NORTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   YELLOWKNIFE, Northwest Territories _ With tee-off times set for
midnight, the summer solstice golf tournament was fast approaching
when Rebecca Jaud faced an increasingly familiar problem for this
Arctic city: no rooms at the inns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was calling bed and breakfast operators to see if they could
loan camping equipment so tourists could sleep in their
backyards,'' said Jaud, who runs this city's increasingly busy
visitors center. During the first half of this year, she estimated,
Yellowknife's hotels were sold out ``15 to 20 nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Yellowknife, on the northern tip of Great Slave Lake, has
traditionally been the Saturday night destination of choice for fur
trappers, gold miners and lonely Mounties.
</P>
<P>
   But as evidenced by two new hotels nearing completion here, a
new sushi restaurant with Japanese-speaking staff, and travel
advertisements fattening Up Here magazine, Yellowknife and Canada's
north are undergoing a tourism boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just crazy with Europeans,'' Darielle Talarico, manager
of Go Wild Tours, said in Inuvik, a town above the Arctic Circle,
as she prepared to send another group of visitors down the Dempster
Highway to Whitehorse, 1,000 miles to the south. This summer,
weekly flights link Zurich and Frankfurt with Whitehorse, capital
of the Yukon Territory, where tourism has become the No. 1 economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Although Germans flood the Yukon, French flock to Nunavut and
10,000 Japanese tourists come to Yellowknife every winter to view
the northern lights, Canada's northern tourism boom is largely
fueled by Americans, who account for about three-quarters of the
nation's foreign visitors every year.
</P>
<P>
   Much as affluent Americans migrate south in the winter to escape
the cold, more and more Americans now migrate north in the summer
to escape the heat.
</P>
<P>
   In a reversal in 1998, more Americans made overnight trips to
Canada than Canadians made overnight trips to the United States.
With northern tourism growing faster than southern tourism,
American overnight trips to Canada increased by 24 percent in the
1990s, hitting 15.2 million last year, while American trips to
Mexico grew by 14 percent during the decade, hitting 18.3 million
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, Canada rose to 8th place from 11th in the ranking
of popular world travel destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans are lured by the Canadian dollar, which lingers
near historically low levels. But while they may find good prices
on their summer trip, they still find that coming north does not
necessarily mean an escape from global warming. In mid-July,
air-conditioners were going full blast in this city, 275 miles
south of the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Edmonton it was so hot we had to put things under the
kickstands so the bikes wouldn't sink into the asphalt,'' said
Lloyd Schaffer, a retired computer systems analyst who motorcycled
here from Waterloo, Iowa, with a friend. ``We love Canada. The
people are so friendly. The prices are good up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada's three northern territories, home to only 100,000 people
sprinkled across 1.5 million square miles, have traditionally been
seen as a preserve of the Indiana Jones adventure traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with good hotels in every major town and increasingly
reliable, if expensive, air links, it is often older and more
affluent tourists who can be found in northern restaurants,
ordering bowls of caribou stew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it so much that we are going next year on a Russian
icebreaker, from Churchill in the Hudson Bay to Greenland,'' said
Sam Wagonfeld, a retired Denver child psychologist, after spending
a week in July touring Eskimo villages and archaeological sites
with his wife, Sally Allen. The five members of the tour group, who
flew around Nunavut, Canada's new eastern Arctic territory, were
all in their 60s.
</P>
<P>
   For years, one of North America's most fabled drives was the
Dempster Highway, the world's only all-weather road that crosses
the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have five children,'' Betty Veitch, a retired Ontario
schoolteacher, said as she settled into a dinner theater in Inuvik.
``As soon as they heard what I was planning, they said, `Go for
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   At Inuvik, where dust-covered vans and recreational vehicles
line the main street, the visitors center now receives 6,000
visitors a year, largely in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the accessible Arctic,'' said Dennis Zimmerman,
manager of Arctic Nature Tours, an agency owned by the indigenous
Inuvialuit people. ``Mom and pop can go to the Arctic.''
</P>
<P>
   In Yellowknife, where two stuffed polar bears adorn the airport
terminal, arriving visitors often say they are surprised by the
amenities offered by this territorial capital of 18,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Symington, who moved here from Hong Kong to manage the
Explorer, the city's largest hotel, said, ``People say: `You've got
a city here, high-rise buildings. We thought you would be living
out of trailers.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marion Lavigne, publisher of Up Here, which appears eight times
a year, has watched the travel portion of her advertising climb to
60 percent. Noting that hotel rooms are to increase here by
one-third this fall, she added, ``For a town that had zero bed and
breakfasts five years ago, we now how have 20 or 30.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
