u i BC-LEBANON-BORDER-425&AMP;AD     08-12 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-BORDER-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. CRITICIZES LACK OF HELP BY LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Lebanon's very limited deployment of soldiers
and police into the south, far from stabilizing the situation along
its border with Israel, is raising new uncertainties 10 weeks after
Israel ended its 22-year occupation of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Despite weeks of international diplomatic pressure to do so, the
Lebanese pointedly did not put their forces on the border when they
finally sent them in on Wednesday. This has now drawn a rebuke from
U.N. peacekeepers on the ground, who are hinting that their mission
_ begun in 1978 _ could end when its latest mandate expires in six
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Border security is essentially the responsibility of the state
of Lebanon,'' said Timor Goksel, the spokesman for the U.N.
soldiers, who fanned out in force along the border a week ago.
``This is a national, not international duty.''
</P>
<P>
   The border has been quiet except for daily rock-throwing into
Israel at the old Fatma Gate, a major tourist attraction that is
increasingly annoying to the Israelis. Three Lebanese, including
two journalists, were wounded by Israeli gunfire in an incident
last week when a man on the Lebanese side lit and threw a Molotov
cocktail over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   The various forces now in the area include 1,000 Lebanese
soldiers and police, the hundreds of U.N. peacekeepers, Hezbollah
guerrillas maintaining their own observation posts and _ on the
other side of the frontier _ Israeli troops putting up new border
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon's refusal to have its forces go all the way to the
border is widely seen here as a move by Syria, which has virtually
controlled Lebanon for a decade, to maintain pressure on Israel to
return the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   By leaving control of the border uncertain, this line of
reasoning goes, Syria reserved the threat of possible future action
by Hezbollah, or other proxies, such as Syrian-based Palestinian
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government says it will only deploy its troops on
the border in the context of a complete regional peace agreement,
including the turnover of the Golan Heights, conquered by Israel in
1967, and the return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   International donors have insisted on the dispatch of government
troops to the south. Lebanon has said it sent its forces into the
border region only to keep peace among local Shiite Muslims and
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The task force ``is responsible for law and order,'' Lebanon's
interior minister Michel Murr told reporters, ``and not on the
border with Israel. The border is not our concern at this stage.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Lebanese government has also told the U.N. peacekeepers not
to set up at what had been border crossing points. Nepalese
soldiers in the U.N. force were withdrawn from one such crossing.
U.N. officials say privately that they suspect that the orders not
to watch these points originated with Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has repeatedly complained to the United Nations about the
Fatma Gate, where Hezbollah has deposited piles of rocks at
designated stoning points.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli chief of staff, Gen. Shaul Mofaz, warned that
``Israeli soldiers know how to behave'' if attacked, and deputy
defense minister Ephraim Sneh accused the peacekeepers of failing
to prevent violence.
</P>
<P>
   A leading Hezbollah official, deputy secretary general Naim
Qassem, described the stone throwing as ``a way for the Lebanese to
express their rejection of the occupation.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, he dismissed the complaints to the United
Nations. Israel, ``which has not succeeded in getting guarantees
from the Lebanese state _ despite pressures, particularly from the
Americans _ is trying to snatch up guarantees when and where it
can,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, U.N. officials are said to be sharply
pointing out to the Lebanese that the Security Council resolution
that authorized and extended the peacekeeping force in southern
Lebanon, known as Unifil, also calls on the Lebanese government to
extend its authority throughout the region and ``proceed with a
significant deployment of the Lebanese armed forces as soon as
possible.'' The latest resolution, passed on July 27, also looks
forward to phasing out Unifil and replacing it with a presumably
smaller group of observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Lebanese seem to be unaware of is that Unifil's end
is near,'' a U.N. official said. ``Lebanon can't go on indefinitely
ignoring its responsibility for the border and the border region
alike.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
