<SLUG> BC-EDUC-REPORT-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOREST SCHOOLS SHORT ON TEACHERS AND COMPUTERS, SAYS U.S. REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost half the money from federal education programs is going
to the poorest schools in the country, but those schools continue
to be short on qualified teachers and technological resources,
including computers with Internet access, says a new report from
the Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released on Friday, examined six federal programs,
including the Title I program that allocates $8 billion each year
to try to help disadvantaged children get access to teachers and
computers. The report was based on data from the 1997-1998 school
year collected in 720 schools in 180 districts.
</P>
<P>
   It comes at a time when federal education programs are being
hotly debated in Congress and in the presidential campaign. Dick
Cheney, the Republican candidate for vice president, said in July
that ``there ought to be accountability'' with Title I money, which
comes from a three-decade-old program. Earlier this year, former
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, while campaigning for the
Democratic nomination for president, said he would double the
government's Title I allocations if elected.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed that although secondary schools had a third of
the country's more impoverished students, only 15 percent of Title
I money went to those schools. Secondary schools were less likely
to receive Title I funds, and they received smaller amounts than
elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   One of the report's more disturbing findings showed that
teachers' aides rather than qualified teachers were teaching many
students in Title I schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paraprofessionals were used in many Title I schools for
teaching and helping to teach students, although their educational
backgrounds did not qualify many of them for such
responsibilities,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Although almost all of the teachers' aides in Title I schools
had a high school diploma or an equivalent degree, only 19 percent
had a bachelor's degree, the report said. That figure dropped to 10
percent in the schools with the highest poverty rates.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the instructional workers supported by Title I money
were teachers' aides. But 41 percent of these aides said that they
spent at least half of their time teaching students on their own,
without a teacher present.
</P>
<P>
   The report confirmed the existence of a growing digital divide
in the country's classrooms, which keeps students from low-income
families from having more access to computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While federal money paid for almost a quarter of the computers
that schools received in the 1997-1998 school year, ``high-poverty
schools had less access to technology than low-poverty schools in
terms of the quantity, quality and connectivity of computers,'' the
report said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even after using federal funds, the poorest schools had only one
computer for every 17 students, while more affluent schools had one
for every 12 students, the report said. And those computers in the
poorer schools were less likely to be ``advanced multimedia''
computers or ones able to connect to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that only 8 percent of secondary
schoolteachers and 38 percent of elementary schoolteachers said
their students used computers daily. Most teachers said their
lessons ``never'' or ``hardly ever'' required students to use the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Many principals and instructors said that teachers were
responsible for the lack of use of current technology. ``A major
barrier to the effective use of technology,'' the report said,
``was insufficient teacher understanding of ways to integrate
technology into the curriculum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
