<P>
   TRAFICANT-RENO _ Ohio Congressman James Traficant has long used
his mouth as a weapon of destruction, but rarely has his vitriol
been this personal. On a Fox News national news program Wednesday
Traficant levied a variety of sordid allegations against Attorney
General Janet Reno _ from mafia-supplied call girls to substance
abuse _ claiming secret affidavits that he refused to release.
Reno, in an unusually strong reaction, said people in public office
have to endure all sorts of nasty comments, but these are some of
the most nasty, unsubstantiated comments she has ever heard.
Traficant himself has said he is about to be indicted on federal
charges, raising questions about the real reason for his public
broadside against the Justice Department. (Montgomery, Cox News
Service) 30.
</P>
<P>
   CAMILLA-VICTIMS _ Six months after a tornado struck Camilla,
many victims are back on their feet and rebuilding their homes. The
reason for the rebound, victims say, is a rich neighborhood spirit
and the overwhelming kindness of strangers. (Osinski, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-SANCHEZ _ LOS ANGELES _ Democratic officials may have
reached an uneasy truce with Rep. Loretta Sanchez after she agreed
to move a $3 million fund-raiser from the Playboy Mansion, but
questions remain whether the party's strong-arm tactics will damage
its standing with an ethnic group being strongly wooed by both
sides in this year's campaign. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GORE _ LOS ANGELES _ After months of campaigning hard before
an inattentive public, Al Gore will find his spotlight this week at
the podium of the Democratic National Convention. Here's what he
and his party must accomplish this week. (Shepard, Cox News
Service) MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton takes the stage
Monday at the Democratic National Convention with two distinct _
but conflicting _ goals. One is to celebrate his own presidency's
eight years of peace and prosperity and to claim a place in history
on his own terms. The other is proclaim Al Gore as the co-author
and rightful heir to the administration's successful policies while
minimizing his ties to its scandals. (Deans, Cox News Service)
MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-MEDIA _ WASHINGTON _ Story on convention media preparations.
(Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-MONEY _ When it comes to raising cash at their convention,
the Democrats give no ground to the the GOP, though they perform
the money dance a little differently. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-TERRY _ When Democratic convention planners ran into money
and organizational problems, they called in Clinton friend and
prodigious money-raiser, Terry McAuliffe. We spend a few days with
the man said to have raised more money than any political
fundraiser in history as he pulls the convention strings in Los
Angeles. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COOL-TOWN _ PALO ALTO, Calif. _ A recent tour of Cool Town, as
Hewlett-Packard labs here are known, highlighted some of the
high-tech gadgets that will be appearing in our lives soon.
(Geewax, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPES _ BOONVILLE, N.C. _ In the four decades he's grown
tobacco, Frank Hopson never worried about the rising and setting of
the sun. ``Tobacco's a weed,'' and will grow just about anywhere,
he always figured. But now one of a fast growing number of North
Carolina farmers growing grapes to supply area vineyards,
57-year-old Hopson has learned to pay attention to sunshine and
other considerations critical to growing sweet, firm grapes. The
payoff? A crop that agricultural experts say won't replace North
Carolina's embattled, nearly billion-dollar-a-year crop, but one
that is acre for acre as profitable as tobacco. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Burritt with photos, possible list of number of commercial
vineyards in other Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-TOBACCO _ LEXINGTON, Ky. _ Southern tobacco farmers are
nervous. Growers in Kentucky, North Carolina, Georgia, Tennessee
and South Carolina farm 90 percent of the domestic crop. But a $145
billion anti-tobacco verdict in Florida has many wondering whether
this is the straw that's broken Joe Camel's back. Will they turn to
catfish farms and grape vineyards or car sales? We check and see.
Pegged to meeting of big tobacco on Aug. 14. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PYRAMID- MOSCOW _ Looking like something straight from
the X-Files, the cosmic gray three-story pyramid appears suddenly
around a bend off Moscow's northbound highway. Lines outside it
attest to its reputation of a Mecca of the paranormal. According to
its builder, a new celebrity among Russian faith-healers and
astrologists, the pyramid can bring peace and harmony to the world,
can prolong life and heal disease. All you have to do, he says, is
believe. And thousands of Russians, bored or disenchanted with
traditional religions, do. (Coker, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED Wed., Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   COSTARICA-CRIME- SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Long admired as one of
Latin America's most peaceful, prosperous and stable countries,
Costa Rica has hit a bad patch recently with a crime wave that is
threatening its reputation and the peace of mind of its residents.
The murder of two young American women tourists in March captured
international headlines, while a top Costa Rican policeman recently
complained that he doesn't have the resources to fight the growing
problem. We profile the problem and the country. (Williams, Cox
News Service) MOVED Wed., Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COSTARICA-CHILDSEX- SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Apparently the
country has a booming sex-tourism trade, and children as young as
12 and 13 have been selling themselves as prostitutes. (Williams,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS. With information for locator map.
MOVED Wed., Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEMOCRACY-QIUBAN VILLAGE, China _ Just about every single
one of this watermelon-growing village's 444 eligible voters turned
out to cast a ballot for the village chief. They had a choice
between a mini-bus driver, a shop owner and a fellow farmer. That
the election took place in China is a sign to some - especially
those at the Carter Center, who are working with China on
standardizing village elections _ that this communist country is on
a slow but steady course towards democracy. To others, village
elections are but a cynical gambit by the central leadership to
maintain control over the massive rural
</P>
<P>
   population. (Chao, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS. With
information for locator map. MOVED Wed., Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   UPS _ When UPS formed an insurance company in Bermuda in 1983 to
be owned by employees, there was no indication the participants had
any idea they had just set in motion a series of events that would
culminate 16 years later in a punishing U.S. Tax Court ruling that
found UPS had committed a ``sham transaction.'' As a result, the
company may now be forced to pay the IRS one of the largest bills
in tax history - up to $2.3 billion in back taxes, interest and
penalties. UPS has appealed the ruling and the 11th Circuit
considers it next month. (Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MALL-OF-GEORGIA _ ATLANTA _ Mall of Georgia opened with great
fanfare a year ago promising to be the mall of all malls. A year
later, it's still searching for its last anchor and competing in
area that choaking with retail venues. Has it lived up to its
promises. What challenges does it face today? (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PHONES _ ATLANTA _ Local telephone service, the rather boring
plain jane element in communications compared to go-go cell phones
and red-hot long distance services, has suddenly become a new
battleground. Many players are emerging to take on BellSouth, none
more eager than the cable giant, MediaOne, backed by its tentative
parent, AT&AMP;T. Yes, AT&AMP;T, old Ma Bell who used to be everybody's
phone company. The move by the cable company into phones, oddly
enough, is being helped along by BellSouth, mostly in obedience to
federal legislation. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   JOE-MURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I never thought I'd have to
go to Philadelphia to learn about Mexican food. But that's what
happened. In between covering the GOP National Convention and
dodging protesters, I ended up at a wonderful place called
Tequila's in the downtown area, chatting with the owner, David
Suro, 38, on what makes good Mexican food. (Joe Murray,
editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas) Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Before I made that dash
from the air-conditioned office to the air-conditioned car, I
checked my finances. I had 65 cents to my name. I could buy a cold
drink to sip on the way home, or be 65 cents ahead tomorrow. I
decided I needed the change more than the soda. As I pulled out of
the newspaper parking lot, cranked up the AC and headed to the
intersection, I saw her, looking like a frightened rabbit. (Ernest
Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Undermined by votes in the Knesset and betrayed
by a one-time coalition partner in filling the nation's figurehead
presidency, Prime Minister Ehud Barak has been left holding an
empty political bag. The question now is whether Barak, after a
series of political defections, can cobble together a functioning
coalition before the Knesset, on a three-month recess, reconvenes
in October and makes a final decision on its preliminary vote to
call early elections. (Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ ``Is America ready for a Jewish vice
president, only a heartbeat away from the presidency?'' The answer
needs to be a typical Jewish one, a return question: ``Why not?''
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVED Thursday.
