<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Ballpark, hot dogs and Dick Cheney
 &HT;    Why did Bush pick Cheney? Same reason it's called The Ballpark
 &HT;    By GARY BORDERS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE BALLPARK IN ARLINGTON _ This is the house that George W.
Bush helped build. Politics aside, it's such an improvement over
its ugly predecessor as to not be in the same ballpark, so to
speak.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the team, the lowly Texas Rangers, aren't having the
same success as their erstwhile owner. If the Rangers were a
political candidate, they would be the Lamar Alexander of the
American League, finishing behind ``other'' in most political
polls.
</P>
<P>
   To take the political analogy further than it should ride, the
Rangers seem to have never shaken the ghost of their previous
incarnation as the Washington Senators, a team that by the time it
moved to Texas even gave politics a bad name with their ineptness.
While there have been a few semi-successful years _ they made the
playoffs last year and lost in three straight to the Angels _ the
Rangers are a ``wait 'til next year'' kind of team in a town and
state that expects winners, year in and out. The Cowboys, Stars,
Rockets and Spurs all have had championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, the Rangers have a long way to go to match the
futility of my beloved Boston Red Sox, who have every chance of
completing a century without having won a World Series. There's
just 18 more years to go before it's been 100 years since Babe Ruth
pitched the Red Sox to a World Series win, and I've seen nothing to
indicate the losing streak is about to end anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   About the only excitement the Red Sox are providing is Pedro
Martinez who even injured is the best pitcher in baseball. Then
there's Nomar Garciaparra's torrid year at the plate; he's flirting
with .400. Last time a batter topped .400 it was a fellow Red Sox,
Ted Williams in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Rangers, their pitching is dreadful, future
Hall-of-Famer Pudge Rodriguez is out for the year, and the only
reason to head to The Ballpark is that it's a fine venue to watch a
ballgame, even in the dog days of August. At least as long as it's
a night game.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were surprised that W. picked someone as nondescript
as Dick Cheney as his vice-presidential candidate should remember
that, after all, he was one of the partners who picked ``The
Ballpark'' as the name of the Rangers' new stadium. It's a name
that's bland, safe and conservative, like Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   About six years ago, a friend and I made a trip to spring
training in Florida, where we took in games at the Red Sox and
Rangers training sites. Maybe 50 feet away from where we sat,
George W. sat behind the dugout, eating peanuts and occasionally
signing autographs. A man could have made a lot of money at the
time taking bets that this affable man would soon serve as governor
of Texas and then become the GOP nominee for president and, at
least right now, the odds-on favorite to become the next occupant
of the Oval Office. I should have swallowed my pride and asked for
his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Back to The Ballpark. Sure it's got a theme-park look, a faked
old-timeyness that reminds one of those high-dollar subdivisions
where houses look like ersatz Victorian homes ensconced on streets
with names spelled in old English _ Surrey Corner and such. But
there's real grass and few dreadful seats. And there's shade from
the Texas sun, great hot dogs and in the seventh inning, a
impossibly cute little girl sang ``Take Me Out to the Ballgame'' in
a voice clear as a Central Texas river.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lost, 4-3 to the White Sox, who are riding high in
the AL Central, another minor miracle in August. It's not a
terribly exciting game, but it's relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention the hot dog? Grilled onions, mustard, jalapenos
and pickle relish, washed down with a ballpark beer. It was just
lovely. My friends and I gossiped, told bad jokes and draped our
legs over the seat backs in front of us, since there were plenty of
vacant seats. It was a fine night.
</P>
<P>
   My politics and W.'s don't often mesh, but a man who loves
baseball has at least a few redeeming qualities. Can you imagine Al
Gore kicked back watching a game, munching on peanuts? Only if
there was a TV camera close by attempting to prove he's just a
regular guy like the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I hear Ralph Nader loves baseball, too. I figure he's
a Cubs fan.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
