<SLUG> BC-JOE-MURRAY-COLUMN0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Food and politics do mix
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I never thought I'd have to go to Philadelphia
to learn about Mexican food. But that's what happened.
</P>
<P>
   In between covering the GOP National Convention and dodging
protesters, I ended up at a wonderful place called Tequila's in the
downtown area, chatting with the owner, David Suro, 38, on what
makes good Mexican food.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, Suro's restaurant makes really good Mexican food _
not to be confused with Tex-Mex.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 3,000 years of difference,'' said Suro, who grew up in
Guadalajara. ``Mexican food dates back all those centuries and
represents an evolution and blend of cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tex-Mex is basically one, very small segment of the real
Mexican food. But it is food not known in Mexico and is really a
distortion of what Mexican food is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Suro, who settled here after marrying a Philadelphia woman, was
``probably the only Mexican downtown'' when he opened his
restaurant in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have a lot of people working in restaurants. Still, the
professional Mexican community is not as large as in other
cities.''
</P>
<P>
   What there is you'll find well represented at Tequila's, a
gathering spot for writers, poets, artists and academics.
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``Bohemian group,'' said Suro, who includes himself in
that category, ``very interesting people who are trying to fix the
problems of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At least part of the attraction of Tequila's may be that it
lives up to its name, offering some 150 varieties of the fiery
Mexican liquor. Prices range from $10 for a bottle of everyday
brands to $300 for premium selections, which are aged in casks the
same as brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there's the food.
</P>
<P>
   Suro describes Tequila's cuisine as a ``complex and rich variety
of dishes'' with excellent meat and seafood among more than 50 menu
choices.
</P>
<P>
   As for a speciality of the house, Suro will tell you that ``it's
difficult to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But the one he considers ``most important to our cuisine'' is
the mole poblano sauce, which contains 35 ingredients and is made
from scratch at Tequila's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very challenging to reach the optimum in flavor and to
blend all those ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, are the politics at Tequila's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have good friends who are on the right and good friends who
are on the left,'' said Suro, who is a citizen of Mexico with
permanent residency in the U.S. ``We try to get both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only way the conversation has balance. Otherwise, we
would be very boring. It's a good blend.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether George W. Bush or Al Gore would make the best president
from the standpoint of relations with Mexico, Suro wouldn't offer
an opinion _ other than to say, ``It is difficult to say.''
</P>
<P>
   He did allow this much:
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush speaks good Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was quick to add, ``Al Gore tried. He did not do well,
but I have to say, at least he tried.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't take that as a political prediction. You shouldn't
either.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
