<SLUG> BC-BOB-DIARY0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The saga of a journal and one man's undoing
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ My God, what are in those notes?
</P>
<P>
   If George Washington were running for president today, his
political consultants would worry whether Thomas Jefferson's
tediously detailed note-taking would hurt his chances of becoming
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Pity Bob Graham. For more than 20 years, he has written down
every excruciating detail of his life. What time he wakes up. How
much he weighs (``The scale at our Miami Lakes home is the the
best. The one here is off by 3 pounds. The one in the Senate gym is
pretty accurate.'')
</P>
<P>
   What he eats for breakfast, lunch, dinner. If you shake his
hand, your name is in his notebook. He writes even between holes of
golf.
</P>
<P>
   He now has more than 2,500 notebooks stored away. You know the
kind. The little brightly colored spiraled ones that you buy at
Eckerd's and slip in a shirt pocket. Graham buys them in colors _
red, yellow, blue, green. The colors represent summer, fall,
winter, spring. In each notebook, he has blank pages separating
sections and a system for dates that he cheerfully explains in
great detail while standing outside the Senate Hart Office
Building. Trust me, you don't want to know.
</P>
<P>
   He loves talking about his notebooks, and Floridians love his
notebooks. His obsessive record-keeping is a quirky, endearing
trait that also is a tool for helping him keep track of things that
he wants done.
</P>
<P>
   But it was this Jeffersonian penchant for writing down every
minuscule detail that scared Vice President Al Gore's political
consultants. Even the national press wondered aloud if Graham was a
tad too weird.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent ``Meet the Press,'' host Tim Russert asked four
NBC reporters about Gore's list of potential running mates. When it
came to Graham, one reporter worried about Graham's notebooks. They
all nodded knowingly and quickly dismissed Graham's chances.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Graham's word was his own pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a reflection of how frightened we've become of
the written word,'' says University of Florida political scientist
Richard Scher. ``If Thomas Jefferson or James Madison, who both
kept extensive journals, were alive today, they probably couldn't
get on a national ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age where private writings often have been used against
people, ``we've become a shred-the-document society.''
</P>
<P>
   Scher thinks that is a shame. ``If James Madison had not kept
extensive journals, there is a lot we would not know about our
Constitutional Convention,'' he says. ``Someday, Graham's
collection of notebooks is going to be a very valuable resource for
historians.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was on vacation in Wyoming when he got the call from Gore
about his decision to pick Connecticut Sen. Joe Lieberman as his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   It's surely in the notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
