<SLUG> BC-CAMILLA-VICTIMS0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After the storm, community determination restored Camilla
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes, the system does work for disaster victims.
And when it does, it's usually because of the hard work of
goodhearted people.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Valentine's Day in South Georgia began with a
tornado that killed 18 people and destroyed more than 300 homes.
The heaviest concentration of damage was around the McNair Road
area of Camilla.
</P>
<P>
   What had been a modest neighborhood of homes and trailers was
wind-churned into something resembling a small landfill site.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, all the debris is gone. Most of the homes have been
rebuilt or replaced. A few people have even started setting out new
shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   The returning neighbors often help each other with the emotional
part of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Williams, who lost his home to the storm, said the
neighbors gather in small groups, often when one sees another
outside. The storm still dominates their talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tornado did a lot of damage here, but it didn't take away
our hearts,'' Williams said. Most of the framing is finished on
Williams' new house. It will be nicer than his old place, and it
will have a safe room in it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the family next door, where a woman was killed, has moved
away. ``Some of my neighbors, I'll probably never see again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood as a whole, however, is well on its way back.
``We lost a lot of material things, but we've still got our
families. This has pulled us together as a family, as a
neighborhood. We're hangin' in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlyne Jackson said she's anxious to see the work done on a
new home. She's living still in a government trailer on her lot on
McNair Road, while she awaits final approval of a construction
loan. For some of the people who owned homes, the process has been
more complicated than for people who rented, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, moving was never an option, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I own this land,'' she said. ``There wasn't nowhere else I
wanted to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The tornado deposited L.C. Gaines and his 90-year-old father on
the ground outside their mobile home, but neither they nor any of
their relatives who live nearby were seriously injured. Now, Gaines
and his father have a new prefabricated home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The programs worked real good,'' Gaines said. ``We had a lot
of help.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a major understatement.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the storm cleared, battalions of volunteers moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Kip Davis, a consulting engineer for both the city of Camilla
and Mitchell County, was drafted to coordinate the volunteer
efforts. The response from area residents and from total strangers
from around the state was ``utterly amazing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the first weekdays after the storm, there were approximately
400 volunteers per day on the scene. And on the first Saturday,
there were 2,000. For the next few weeks, the volunteer forces
stayed at about half those levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the work of debris removal, volunteers helped with
things the disaster victims were emotionally ill-equipped to handle
at the time, like filling out forms for emergency assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reinstates your faith in humanity,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of the recovery picked up recently, with a
housebuilding ``blitz'' for tornado victims in Camilla. City
Manager Michael Scott said a new subdivision quickly sprung up,
when the city put in utilities and Habitat For Humanity crews
started building 10 new homes at once.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said it's the communitywide determination to put Camilla
back together that has made the recovery successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when these things happen, it's so overwhelming
that some people just throw up their hands and abandon the place,''
Scott said. ``But here, the mindset from the beginning has been,
`Get in, get it cleaned up, put it behind us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
