<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CLIMBING0813-COX     08-12 2128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMBING0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Climbing Fourteeners clarifies mind, spirit
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's hard to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know don't have to say a thing. They know, and that's
enough. But occasionally somebody asks, or the meter hits full and
the feelings from on top have nowhere to go but out.
</P>
<P>
   So they touch their fingertips together to form a peak and
whisper, ``Fourteener,'' a mantra of endless meaning and
possibility. They spread their arms wide like Moses entering the
promised land: the very center of heaven and earth, they say.
</P>
<P>
   They point to their eyes and ears, talking in terms of the
senses _ air so pure, sky so blue, peaks upon peaks upon peaks to
the edge of forever, a view through the heart and into infinity.
</P>
<P>
   Then they laugh and say they climb pretty much for the hell of
it.
</P>
<P>
   And that's about all the explanation there is.
</P>
<P>
   There are 54 14,000-foot peaks in Colorado. People climb up them
for whatever reason and come back down, and they know _ the
planning and preparation, leaving before dawn when the day is
velvety cold, the climbing and climbing, quads burning and lungs
begging for reprieve, above timberline, 500 yards to go, loose rock
and scary parts, ice and wind, and then ... and then, the summit.
Top of the world.
</P>
<P>
   One down, 53 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the word compulsion a lot,'' said Lon Carpenter,
membership coordinator for the Colorado Mountain Club Western Slope
Group. ``Most people don't start out to climb all the Fourteeners,
but hiking above treeline, making it to the summit and the view
from up there ...''
</P>
<P>
   He knows. But it's hard to explain. He talks about a passion and
commitment for climbing, bordering on addiction, and a ``because
it's there'' mind set that focuses not so much on the summit as on
the challenge and joy of the climb. And just a plain ol' love
affair with mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really become mentally stronger,'' said Terry Schmalz, who
with her husband, Mark, has climbed all 54 Fourteeners. ``Mentally
and physically stronger. You have to focus, so it removes you from
the stress of your everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schmalzes are two of a growing group of climbers who have
submitted all 54 Fourteeners, most of whom, like Carpenter said,
didn't start climbing with that in mind. They just wanted to climb.
</P>
<P>
   For Carpenter, the compulsion to climb started five years ago as
a mild mid-life crisis. He and a friend both turned 40 around the
same time and decided they wanted to do something big in their
lives. They decided they should climb a mountain. A year later,
early on a summer morning, they began their climb up Mount
Sneffels.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an ideal day. Carpenter's gloves got wet, he didn't
have an ice ax, his rain gear wasn't heavy-duty enough, he had no
extra socks. He and his friend got back down safely, fortunately, a
lot smarter and, in Carpenter's case, hooked. Now he has less than
a dozen Fourteeners to summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first thing I've had a passion about in my life,''
he said. ``It's given me a respect for people who have a passion
for the things they do in life. Since I started climbing, this is
the most alive I've felt. I can't tell you what I did last week,
but I can tell you what happened every five minutes of a climb.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes something like this: You stand at the trailhead early in
the morning, the sky inky blue and, even in summer, your breath
making puffy clouds. Get your pack situated, your boots tied just
right, everything ready and adjusted, and start walking. At first
you're in high forest, pine and aspen standing like sentries in the
deep morning shadows along the trail, which is spongy with dead
needles and damp earth. The air is so crisp it snaps, so clean you
reach out to grab a handful.
</P>
<P>
   The sky goes from purple to fuchsia to pink to gold as the sun
wakes up. You climb up and up, over rocks, winding around
switchbacks, past streams guarded by wildflowers, gulping water and
air as you stop for rest. Mountain birds warble and a rustling off
in the trees might be any number of animals. A layer comes off as
you warm up. And you keep going up. Plants are getting shorter and
sparser, your legs are feeling warm, you're breathing faster and
you move a little slower so you don't get light-headed.
</P>
<P>
   Soon there are no plants, just a moonscape of gray rock and
patches of snow. Little fires ignite in different parts of your
body as you see the summit and keep climbing up. It's not as close
as it looks and the air is thin. You consider stopping, possibly
turning around as your legs beg for mercy and your lungs threaten
revolt. But you're so close. So you go, and then you're at the top,
a narrow ridge from which the wind blows clouds straight into your
hands. You can turn in a small circle to see a world of peaks and
valleys and, in that instant, they're all yours.
</P>
<P>
   And then you come back down.
</P>
<P>
   And then you're most likely hooked.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Moston knows what that's like. In summer 1957 he climbed his
first Fourteener. He was in Ouray at a geology field camp when one
of his professors from the Colorado School of Mines decided to run
a little extra energy out of the students, so he led them up Mount
Sneffels.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Moston was a smoker, he'd never climbed a mountain
and he had no idea what to expect. They didn't have mountains like
that in Pennsylvania, where he's from. So he just put on his
regular shoes and went, with ``no idea what I was getting into,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   They were on the summit later than they should have been, so a
thunderstorm swooped in and lightning flashed around them as they
headed down. The static electricity stood their hair up straight
and Moston found something he loves. On his days off from working
as an engineer, he climbed. In 1974, he finished the Fourteeners
when he and a friend climbed El Diente, though it never was his
goal to do all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an enjoyment of the outdoors and seeing new
things,'' he said, which he gets to do more often now that, at 67,
he's retired from 33 years as a district engineer for the Colorado
Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Most climbers will say that they learn as they go _ what to do,
what not to do, what to bring, how to behave in the mountains. The
Schmalzes, who both are teachers in School District 51 and spend
their summers climbing peaks, took basic mountaineering and first
aid courses through the Colorado Mountain Club to learn technical
skills like using an ice ax and survival skills such as how to
bivouac.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Colorado's Fourteeners have routes that beginning
climbers can hike up, but often more experienced climbers take
challenging routes that require technical skill.
</P>
<P>
   They learn when to turn around if the clouds look threatening,
how to navigate narrow ridges of rock and not plunge to their
deaths, what weight in the backpack is worth taking and what should
be left behind. They develop opinions about what should and
shouldn't be counted as a Fourteener. They talk in code when they
get together, swapping stories about Little Bear and Redcloud,
Gerry Roach's book, crampons, quad clean-outs, ice and a moose.
</P>
<P>
   On their last climb, the Schmalzes saw a moose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You climb for the experience, what you're going to see,'' said
Bill Hamann, who has been climbing since the early '60s and has
done 52 Fourteeners. He said he doesn't care if he gets the other
two because he climbs for the personal challenge and for the joy of
just being out there.
</P>
<P>
   Many climbers, he said, climb for the lists. They want to get
all the Fourteeners, then the top 100 peaks in Colorado, then the
top 200 peaks, then all 637 Thirteeners, or all the peaks in one
range, or all the peaks in a quadrant of the state, or the highest
points in each Colorado county.
</P>
<P>
   Some climbers branch out to the highest point in each state, or
head overseas to mountains in Peru or Mexico or Nepal. Serious
climbers will say it's in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a focus that washes out your everyday anxieties
and concerns,'' said Allen Conrad, 63, who moved to Colorado two
years ago from California, where he did extensive climbing. He's
getting started on the Fourteeners, but just for the fun of it and
not for a list.
</P>
<P>
   Because, as every climber will tell you, obsessions and goals
and passions aside, it should be fun. Which probably is why so many
people are on Colorado's Fourteeners and why those peaks are in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourteeners are being loved to death, the life stomped right
out of them by crowds of adoring climbers. Several weekends ago,
volunteers with the Colorado Fourteeners Initiative counted more
than 640 climbers on Grays and Torreys peaks on one Saturday, said
Jennifer Tucker, education and outreach coordinator for the
Colorado Fourteeners Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The climbing season is short _ about 100 days in summer _ so new
climbers are coming to the mountains in droves, particularly the
mountains with easy-to-navigate trails that don't require technical
climbing skill. The problem is not only extreme use, but ignorance
of mountain etiquette and leave no trace practices, said Loretta
McEllhiney, Colorado Fourteeners coordinator for the U.S. Forest
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a lot of vegetation loss and a lot of soil
loss,'' she said, citing as an example Capitol Peak, where climbers
have created trails that turned into gullies and rerouted a creek.
``We can't ever put that creek back into its original bed. And the
vegetation loss is serious because we have a lot of sensitive
species, especially in our alpine environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Trails are being trampled through sensitive environments, litter
is being dropped, fire-pits being dug in wrong places, ground water
being polluted, she said. To combat increased degradation of the
Fourteeners, the U.S. Forest Service and the Colorado Fourteeners
Initiative have teamed to study each Fourteener, prioritize the
seriousness of the damage on each one and begin working to remedy
the problems, Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   A project oversight team of biologists, geologists, soil
specialists, environmentalists and concerned citizens analyzed
resource damage, available resources, threatened and endangered
species, rate of change and other factors to prioritize each peak.
The peaks with a high priority ranking for preservation are Torreys
and Grays, Quandry, Blanca, Crestone Needle, Pyramid, Pikes Peak
and Mounts Bierstadt, Harvard, Shavano, Democrat, Bross, Sneffels,
Columbia, Yale, Massive and Missouri Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Once the peaks are prioritized, volunteers set to work. They
reconstruct or build sustainable trails from trailhead to summit,
Tucker said, ``so it will be the kind of trail hikers will stay
on.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, trails have been built or restored on Mount Elbert,
Mount Belford, Humboldt Peak, Huron Peak and La Plata Peak, and
restoration projects are in progress on Mount Bierstadt, Mount
Harvard, Grays and Torreys peaks and Missouri Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   McEllhiney said some climbers have criticized the Fourteeners
Initiative and the Forest Service for building trails, making it
easier for more climbers to use the mountains and ruining the
wilderness experience with a trail, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I very much believe that the reason people are there is
not because there's a trail or a lack of trail,'' she said. ``It's
because there's a mountain over 14,000 feet. The Forest Service
didn't build trails to the top of the peaks because they didn't
know people would be interested in doing that. Now we're doing
crisis management.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Fourteeners Initiative also this summer initiated a
peak steward program in the Clear Creek ranger district, in which
volunteers at the trailheads, on the peaks and along the trails
guide climbers and serve as an education resource about wilderness,
leave no trace climbing, wildlife, alpine ecology and climbing
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to protect and preserve the integrity of
Colorado's peaks and the quality of recreational opportunities they
provide,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the crowds on the Fourteeners, many serious climbers
have turned to other, more remote peaks _ the less-often climbed
Thirteeners, peaks in Wyoming's Wind Rivers or Tetons or
California's Sierra Nevadas, peaks that don't have the reputation
of the Fourteeners but are just as challenging and just as
beautiful, Mark Schmalz said.
</P>
<P>
   But they still nibble at the Fourteeners. They can't help it.
There's just something about those mountains _ miracles of plate
tectonics that call your name and offer whatever it is you're
looking for. Plus a million miles of blue sky.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to explain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
