<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPES0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco farmers turning to grapes
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOONVILLE, N.C. _ In the four decades he's grown tobacco, Frank
Hobson never worried about the rising and setting of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco's a weed,'' the Yadkin County farmer always figured,
and it would grow just about anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as one of a steadily growing number of North Carolina
farmers diversifying into grapes, 57-year-old Hobson has learned to
pay attention to sunshine and other considerations critical to
cultivating sweet, firm grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're growing, I swear,'' said Hobson, holding the tender
green leaves of a Cabernet Sauvignon grape vine in one of his big
rough hands, and a Salem Light in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, in Dobson, officials at Surry Community College
are giddy over grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with classes Thursday, the college will be the first in
North Carolina to offer a two-year degree in viticulture, the study
of growing and marketing grapes. Over the past year, farmers
swelled the attendance of noncredit classes intended to introduce
grapes as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking for years for something new, knowing that
tobacco was waning,'' said John Collins, 56, the college's vice
president for instruction.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics abound, pointing to supposedly promising crops _
such as kiwi fruit in South Carolina and broccoli in Virginia _
that flopped once planted in Southern soil.
</P>
<P>
   Hogs, chickens, strawberries, soybeans and sweet potatoes are
among the many crops farmers raise, but typically not as profitably
as tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Cultivating grapes also requires a greater initial investment
and different growing techniques than tobacco, a crop farmers are
so accustomed to growing they're reluctant to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't see that many farmers, especially the smaller
ones, going into the grape business,'' said Darrell Crisp,
executive director of the Farm Services Agency in Surry County.
</P>
<P>
   But agricultural experts say grapes represent a potentially
profitable payoff for some of North Carolina's 13,000 tobacco
growers.
</P>
<P>
   With annual sales worth $2.3 million, Tar Heel grapes are a long
way from replacing the state's embattled, $650-million-a-year,
flue-cured tobacco crop. But, officials said, in areas such as
these Blue Ridge foothills, where nights are cool, grapes can be
grown as profitably acre for acre as the golden leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Net profit on an acre of tobacco is about $1,200 in Surry
County, according to Charles Boles, agricultural instructor at the
local community college. The potential profit for grapes is about
$1,300 to $1,500 an acre.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, more than 125 farmers are growing some 1,200 tons of
grapes for sale as wine, juice and fresh fruit, according to the
North Carolina Grape Council.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hobson is harvesting 60 acres of tobacco, he and his
wife, Lenna, already have adopted RagApple Lassie as the name of
their fledgling vineyard and the winery they hope to start. They
plan to do it alone, or set up a cooperative winery with other
farmers, and hire a winemaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more the better,'' Lenna said. ``They are going to feed
off one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Dobson, the largest of North Carolina's 12 wineries,
the $10 million Shelton Vineyards is preparing to harvest its first
crop of grapes and bottle its first wine next summer.
</P>
<P>
   At least for the next few years, Shelton Vineyards intends to
buy grapes from local growers as it expands its own harvest from 60
acres to 250 acres. The anticipated need for workers trained in
grape production prompted the vineyard's owners, millionaire
brothers Ed and Charlie Shelton, to approach Surry Community
College about starting the viticulture curriculum. They've
committed $50,000 to the program over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see more wineries in the area,'' said Ed
Shelton, 59. ``It adds credibility to our opinion that this is a
good area to make wine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious they grow here,'' said Sean McRitchie, 37,
driving slowly past row after row of Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot and
other varieties, on farmland that once raised cattle and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   He relocated to Dobson from Oregon with his family two years ago
to start the Sheltons' vineyard and winery.
</P>
<P>
   Just recently, Surry Community College hired McRitchie's father,
Bob, also an Oregon winemaker, as its ``resident viticulture
expert'' and viticulture instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Other family members are involved. Sean McRitchie's wife, Patty,
a lawyer, does legal work for the vineyard. Aside from raising
three children, they care for the vineyard's two Labrador
retrievers.
</P>
<P>
   The black one is named Cabernet, the blond one Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
