<HEADER>
A9778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SOUTHERN-TOBACCO0813-     08-12 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-TOBACCO0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco farmers see future up in smoke
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERSET, Ky. _ Wearing a New Holland baseball cap on his head
and despair on his sleeve, farmer Jack DeBord knows money doesn't
grow on trees. It grows on tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Raising beef cattle pays some bills in the valleys between
Kentucky's rocky outcrops. But tobacco, DeBord said, ``That's how
we make our living.''
</P>
<P>
   For generations of Southerners, tobacco has been golden. The
shimmer comes from a 67-year-old federal price-support program that
guarantees farmers minimum payments for their tobacco in exchange
for production limits _ the highly revered quota.
</P>
<P>
   Grow a good crop, and you're in the money. It's what DeBord's
father and grandfather did. Tobacco shaped farm culture for decades
in Kentucky, North Carolina, Georgia, Tennessee, Virginia and South
Carolina. Nine pounds of every 10 harvested in this country comes
from those states.
</P>
<P>
   But a string of anti-smoking settlements _ including July's $145
billion Florida jury verdict against the nation's largest tobacco
companies _ is forcing farmers to find other ways to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   Monday in Louisville, cigarette companies, farmers, members of
Congress and scientists will gather for a ``tobacco summit'' to
exchange ideas on how to cushion the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to try everything,'' said DeBord, whose family has
farmed for 100 years. ``It's very somber and distressed.''
</P>
<P>
   With Big Tobacco trying to cover legal bills, cigarettes cost
more. Fewer people are smoking. Imported leaf is rising. As a
result, tobacco quota has fallen faster than a two-legged cow.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida judgment likely faces a lengthy appeal. Still,
farmers wonder whether it's the straw that has broken Joe Camel's
back. So while they're flexing their muscles in the fields, they're
fixing their eyes on the future. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee and Kentucky, freshwater shrimp ponds and catfish
farms are replacing tobacco fields. There also are fresh crops of
blueberries, herbs and tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, growers are experimenting with genetically modified
tobacco intended for pharmaceutical products. CropTech, a
Blacksburg company, inserts genes that allow the plants to make the
same kind of proteins produced by the human body.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina and Maryland, grapes are creeping into
prominence. Kentucky now has an active vineyard society.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia and elsewhere, some farmers have clamored for
permission to grow hemp, a marijuana cousin. Hemp, the country's
leading crop in the 1700s, is used to make clothing, rope, paper
and candy, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   When flue-cured auctions opened Aug. 1 in Georgia and Florida,
farmers grumbled about low opening prices. Similar anxiety spread
as the Carolina markets opened last week.
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky and Tennessee, farmers of burley tobacco will
harvest their fields this month and next. Their auctions start the
Monday before Thanksgiving. They expect the same dim prospects as
their flue-cured brethren.
</P>
<P>
   DeBord is looking at a new kind of tobacco. In addition to his
regular burley, which cigarette companies blend with flue-cured
varieties, DeBord is growing an experimental crop.
</P>
<P>
   Star Scientific Inc. of Chester, Va., a tobacco company that's
not part of any settlement, hopes the new curing and harvesting
process will produce fewer cancer-causing chemicals. The aim is a
safer cigarette, one less prone to ignite major lawsuits that have
pushed the industry to the brink.
</P>
<P>
   DeBord is among 100 Kentucky farmers growing the new tobacco.
For their troubles, Star farmers will receive 30 cents extra per
pound come auction time.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean almost $1,800 extra for DeBord's 3 acres of
experimental tobacco. He hasn't given up on traditional tobacco.
But by working with Star, he's preparing just in case the
unthinkable day comes when regular tobacco won't pay the mortgage.
Already, he's raised cash by selling some farm frontage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the four major companies go bankrupt, we're looking at
going out of business,'' said DeBord, who won't push his 2
1/2-year-old son, Zachary, into farming. If Big Tobacco succumbs,
Star ``might be the only purchaser we have.''
</P>
<P>
   On a hot afternoon this month, fellow growers came to DeBord's
farm off a skinny asphalt road. They gathered around a concrete
pad, where a narrow barn made of gleaming silver metal recently had
been built.
</P>
<P>
   Valves, motors, pipes and propane tanks churned in the back of
the high-tech barn, which heats bales of tobacco to 250 degrees.
The curing process is designed to quickly eliminate the moisture
scientists think helps spread cancerous toxins through the burley
leaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the future,'' said 68-year-old tobacco farmer
Wendell Massengale, one of the 40 or so growers who came to tour
DeBord's experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Southern farmers got hooked on the federal tobacco program in
1933 as the Great Depression triggered farm collapses throughout
the country. Every three years, farmers vote whether to continue
the program. If they accept, production limits are set.
</P>
<P>
   Quotas cause prices to rise artificially at auction houses,
where cigarette companies bid on batches of tobacco leaf. In good
years, bid prices rise far above federal supports.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, bids have hovered near the support level.
</P>
<P>
   The bids _ and the price support _ have kept 50-year-old Roger
Quarles growing tobacco most of his life. The rich soil of
Kentucky's hilly terrain is perfect for tobacco _ but little else.
</P>
<P>
   Quarles lives in Scott County north of Lexington. He has spent
the past couple of years buying up quota from other farmers and
sharecroppers.
</P>
<P>
   But increasing tobacco imports, more lawsuits and decreasing
cigarette consumption have forced quota cuts. Since 1997, quota has
dropped 65 percent. Imagine, Quarles says, being told today your
wages would drop in half, now live with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our best-laid plans have been torn to pieces,'' Quarles
said. He figures he'll spend more time on his farm services
business that provides assistance to neighbor growers.
</P>
<P>
   Some tobacco companies are trying direct contracts with farmers,
a move some growers say signals the demise of price supports. If
the federal program ends, thousands will be flushed from tobacco
farming.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not so easy for tobacco farmers, who average 58 years
of age in Kentucky, to change careers overnight. New niche markets
are competitive, almost cutthroat. As one agricultural expert said,
it's not like a 58-year-old is going to be a farmer one day and a
water-ski instructor the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to farm in central Kentucky and farm in an
economical way and provide for your family, you grow tobacco,''
Quarles said. ``That's what you do. It's all I've ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
