u f BC-MALL-OF-GEORGIA0813-C     08-12 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-OF-GEORGIA0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Year-old Mall of Georgia changes area economic climate
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross and Don Fernandez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fletcher hangs out at the Mall of Georgia but doesn't
spend a dime.
</P>
<P>
   He is a long-haired cat with a shiny black coat who lives at
Hollister &AMP; Co., an apparel store at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   By day, Fletcher sleeps on a stack of jeans, or purrs to adoring
customers. If he tries to leave the store, his magnetic-sensor
collar sends a beeping signal to employees to fetch him. By night,
Fletcher sleeps in a cage in the stockroom, safely away from the
parrot out by the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher is a living prop at one of the newest retailers at Mall
of Georgia. The gigantic Buford mall is among the first in the
country to land Hollister &AMP; Co., a new concept by Abercrombie &AMP;
Fitch that caters to teens.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since opening, Mall of Georgia has landed dozens of
cutting-edge retailing concepts, including new prototype stores for
toy seller FAO Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   The mall, about 35 minutes north of downtown Atlanta, debuted
one year ago today with 100 specialty tenants and three anchor
department stores. Now it has close to 200. In November, Rich's is
set to open a department store between Dillard's and J.C. Penney.
The mall has also spawned surrounding retail development.
</P>
<P>
   Shopper traffic is brisk on weekends, but during the week it's
hit or miss, retailers say. There's no office development base
close to the mall _ at least not yet _ to attract workers during
weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   Mall officials say shopper visits are rising and total 11
million since opening, excluding the outdoor ``village'' area. They
have also said sales are only slightly more than the national mall
average of $323 per square foot. Vacancies remain, with the mall
about 85 percent leased. The industry average for malls open a year
or more is about 90 percent, according to the International Council
of Shopping Centers, an industry group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The established Gwinnett Place mall 12 miles south on I-85 draws
an estimated 17 million visitors annually and is 96 percent leased,
according to marketing brochures. Both malls are operated by Simon
Property Group, an Indianapolis-based mall company.
</P>
<P>
   New competition for both will come from Discover Mills, a new
off-price mall being built off I-85 between Mall of Georgia and
Gwinnett Place. It's slated for a 2001 opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discover Mills will have an impact,'' said Dave Fick, managing
director of Legg Mason Wood Walker in Baltimore. ``But long term,
Mall of Georgia is a fine asset.''
</P>
<P>
   When developers Ben Carter and Scott Hudgens envisioned the Mall
of Georgia, it was to be the ``mall of the future,'' with a design
like no other in metro Atlanta and few places nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor village consists of cafes and shops encircling a
concert pavilion. A dancing fountain draws kids.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Piassick, California Cafe's sous chef, said teens and
families hang out at the mall because there is ``not much to do''
in Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a destination,'' Piassick said. ``There's a lot of
foot traffic, but I'm not sure how many are bringing out shopping
bags.''
</P>
<P>
   The acreage where the mall is today was once considered rural
Gwinnett County. Three years ago the mall began to take shape,
replacing the forrested landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen the center rise from a hole in the ground,'' said
Scott Higley, mall marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   Most any consumable item can now be found within a half-mile of
the shopping compound.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Sprint PCS, Hi-Fi Buys, CD Warehouse, Mattress Firm
and Ulta, a cosmetics discounter, have set up shop within a stone's
throw of the complex. Nearly every nook and cranny of square
footage along the Buford Drive gateway is either hosting a convoy
of bulldozers or boasting a placard announcing imminent
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work here, and we're surprised by things cropping up,''
Higley said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the mall's location and the tight labor market make
recruiting efforts a challenge for the proliferating restaurants
and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dudley, general manager of California Cafe, said he's had
trouble finding staffers for his restaurant in the mall village.
He's currently seeking a head chef.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people that came here, came out to live,'' Dudley said,
referring to the pricey subdivisions that surround the area. ``I've
got great service staff but not enough of them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hoped that a fledgling plan to create bus service in
Gwinnett will ease the shortage of service workers.
</P>
<P>
   While the success of that project remains to be seen, the Mall
of Georgia already draws buses filled with tourist shoppers from
outside the area.
</P>
<P>
   Gwinnett officials believe that has contributed to a rise in
tourism spending in the county from $1.2 billion in 1998 to $1.6
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The main parcel of mall property will be charged $1.7 million in
property taxes this year, according to Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   The mall also contributed to a rise in sales tax revenue
returned to Gwinnett County by the state, from $51.2 million from
November 1998 through April 1999 to $59.2 million for the same
period ending this past April. Malls track sales annually, but the
figures do not include anchor stores because their sales are not
reported individually.
</P>
<P>
   Mall of Georgia's sales figures also don't reflect the impact of
new stores, such as the FAO Schwarz that opened in June. More are
coming, including Rich's and specialty retailers Petite
Sophisticate and August Max.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he's negotiating with several others, including Gap
Body and Sketchers, and two restaurants. There's room for a sixth
anchor, but that's still five to seven years out, Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By year-end, the mall will be over 90 percent leased,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-mile corridor between Gwinnett Place mall and Mall of
Georgia also is filling up.
</P>
<P>
   Several developers have proposed commercial and mixed-use
projects between Gwinnett Place and the Mall of Georgia, including
2 million square feet of office space being developed by Taylor &AMP;
Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   Those developments could spur more shopping at Mall of Georgia.
But the Discover Mills project down the interstate will also bring
new competition.
</P>
<P>
   Mills Corp., of Arlington, Va., has already broken ground on the
1.3 million-square-foot outlet and entertainment center, just off
I-85 at Sugarloaf Parkway. Known tenants include Off 5th/Saks Fifth
Avenue; Bass Pro Shops Outdoor World; F.Y.E. For Your
Entertainment, a media superstore and arcade; and Jillian's
Billiard Cafe, a dining megaplex. Discover Mills plans to have
about 200 tenants when it opens in fall 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simon is scared of Discover Mills,'' analyst Fick said.
``They're about to get cut off at the pass. Discover Mills has
better visibility and physical location.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carter maintained the Mills project will simply draw more
shopper traffic to the county, and that's ``positive'' for Mall of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
