u f BC-PHONES0813-COX     08-12 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONES0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some 90 companies are chasing BellSouth in Georgia, seeking
residential and business customers
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTAm _ Local telephone service is the rather boring Plain
Jane of communications when compared to tiny cell phones, fancy
pagers and red hot long-distance. But it has suddenly become a new
battleground.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting atop the local phone service is BellSouth, with some 5
million customers in Georgia alone. The real battling is between
the competitors that are trying to take business from the familiar
Bell company.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, according to BellSouth, some 90 companies of
various kinds are in the chase to sign up residences as well as
businesses all over Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Major players going up against BellSouth include WorldCom,
Teleport and Intermedia in the bid for commercial service. And in
the residential market, the insurgents include Georgia CommSouth,
Mpower and Knology.
</P>
<P>
   Some newcomers to the local phone service are offering their own
service. Others are ``resellers,'' companies that simply buy
BellSouth service wholesale and sell more cheaply than BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia CommSouth, a reseller, has carved out a special market
aiming at customers with poor credit or who otherwise fail to
qualify for regular phone service. It offers such customers phone
service on a prepaid basis for $29 in advance and $49 per month for
one line.
</P>
<P>
   Among these newcomers stalking residential customers, none is
more eager, ambitious or better financed than MediaOne, the metro
Atlanta cable provider that has merged with AT&AMP;T. In the last
several years MediaOne has embarked on switching its service to
interactive digital offerings, including telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   That switchover is nearly complete, and MediaOne is turning to
the job of capitalizing on its investment by offering customers a
smorgasbord that includes 200 channels of digital television, a
high-speed connection for computers and, now, telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, MediaOne is offering a package of services,
including phone service. The company expects to offer a
one-price-for-all package across the region, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne's main selling point for local phone service, a real
grabber, is that it costs 35 percent to 50 percent as much as
BellSouth, depending on phone requirements. Put another way,
MediaOne customers could have two phone lines, including one with
the fancy features, for the price of one full-featured line by
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why BellSouth would tolerate this kind of rate difference,
a MediaOne executive put it succinctly:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so small at this point, we haven't even hit their radar
screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually BellSouth is active on many fronts, including extension
of high-speed data capability and other growth areas. Moreover,
BellSouth has incentive to help the local challengers at this
point.
</P>
<P>
   Both the carrot and stick have been brought to bear on
BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   Federal legislation passed in 1996 to spur competition requires
local phone giants like BellSouth to make it easy and convenient
for local competitors to enter the area, and that's the stick.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, and more powerfully, there is the carrot: the hope and
expectation that a showing of local competition will help convince
federal regulators to look more favorably on BellSouth's bid for
long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   While BellSouth may seem almost indifferent toward the flurry of
activity in offering local service, it is deadly serious about
getting a chance to offer long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   And why would BellSouth have such high hopes for a field as
furiously competitive as long-distance?
</P>
<P>
   ed to be self-healing in many accidents or storm damage, much
like traditional phone lines that can bypass certain breaks in the
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of the cable phone service, with a year or two of
experience, report that the reliability is good.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the service started, however, can be a chore.
</P>
<P>
   This writer switched to MediaOne recently, but got stood up at
the agreed-on installation time. MediaOne explained later that the
handoff from BellSouth incurred problems, when there was some
difficulty confirming the existence of my two phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   And that, in fact, is a most common complaint from those trying
to compete _ that BellSouth doesn't smoothly handle the transition.
BellSouth says it has been addressing those problems.
</P>
<P>
   Others report a need for repeated visits to get the service
started, but generally when the connection has been made
satisfactorily, the service is what you expect from traditional
phone service.
</P>
<P>
   To allay fears, MediaOne is offering a free initial month of
service and a promise to switch you back to the original phone
company if you are not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The extra good news is that you keep your phone number, so
people who call you have no reason to notice the change. Also,
under contract with BellSouth, the familiar directory assistance
(411) continues, as well as 911.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BellSouth bolsters its case for getting into
long-distance by reporting that it has ``lost'' 10 percent of the
4.3 million lines in Georgia to various competitors. A majority of
the loss has probably taken place in metro Atlanta, where about 3
million of those lines are located.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
