<SLUG> BC-RECORDER0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD video recorder is latest in digital switch
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The trend of going from analog recording _ tape,
vinyl records, etc. _ to digital _ optical discs, computer chips,
etc. _ continues with the introduction of the Tera Optix CD Video
Recorder.
</P>
<P>
   The unit looks and works like a conventional video recorder, but
instead of recording on tape the TeraOptix machine records on CD-R
or CD-RW blank discs. The recordings are digital and can be played
on compatible DVD players, CD players and computers.
</P>
<P>
   TeraOptix is based in Singapore and their line of digital
products, including the CD Video Recorder, is only available in a
few retail outlets in the United States but can be ordered from the
company's GoTerapin.com online store.
</P>
<P>
   The TeraOptix CD Video Recorder is about the size of a VHS video
recorder. With a distinctive colored cowl and silver accents, its
retro science fiction look seems to have been plucked from an Ultra
Man soundstage.
</P>
<P>
   The TeraOptix CD Video Recorder accepts inputs from broadcast,
cable or satellite television signals, camcorders, VHS recorders,
DVDs and other audiovisual sources. It also records sound from CDs,
radios, records and other audio sources.
</P>
<P>
   The programs are recorded on 74-minute CD-R or CD-RW blank
optical discs that look like ordinary CDs. CD-R discs can be
recorded only once, but CD-RW discs are ``rewritable'' and can be
erased and rerecorded many times.
</P>
<P>
   CD-R and CD-RW discs can be purchased fairly inexpensively
wherever computer and advanced audio products or sold. TeraOptix
sells boxes of 25 CD-R discs for $29.99 or 10 CD-RW discs for the
same price.
</P>
<P>
   Once recorded, the discs can be replayed on the CD Video
Recorder or on DVD players and multimedia computers set up to play
CD-R and CD-RW discs. Audio recordings can be played on CD players.
</P>
<P>
   TeraOptix currently offers its CD Video Recorder online for
$599. To order or to get more information, log on to
www.goterapin.com, the company's online store.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
