<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-UPS0813-COX     08-12 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS set to appeal $1.8 billion Tax Court judgment
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A year after United Parcel Service Corp. set aside
$1.8 billion in one of the biggest U.S. Tax Court judgments in
history, the world's largest transportation company is preparing to
take the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   UPS lawyers are scheduled to submit written arguments Monday in
Atlanta's 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals spelling out their
reasons the 1999 ruling against them should be reversed and the
massive judgment overturned. The case is likely to take many
months, possibly years, to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   But industry experts say UPS has compelling historical as well
as financial reasons to fight to the end. Throughout its 97-year
history, the company has sought to be known as a place where
managers make moral decisions _ not just legal ones. U.S. Tax Court
Judge Robert Ruwe's stinging judgment last year assails that
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people at UPS feel that they've been acting ethically and
responsibly all along,'' said Rashad Bajarkly, transportation
analyst at Williams Capital Group in New York. ``They've already
had to endure the financial pain of putting the money aside. Now
they feel like they're obligated to fight to protect their good
name.''
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE ARM OFFSHORE
</P>
<P>
   The collision between UPS and the Internal Revenue Service was
set in motion Feb. 24, 1983, when UPS Chief Financial Officer
Walter Danielewski met in Briarcliff Manor, N.Y., with insurance
executives from UPS and Frank B. Hall Insurance Brokers Inc., one
of the largest insurance firms in the world. The discussion topic
was ``excess value charges,'' or the fees UPS collected from
shippers buying additional insurance on the packages they sent.
</P>
<P>
   EVCs in increments as small as 25 cents were projected to bring
UPS revenue of $69.9 million that year. The company expected to pay
$21.4 million in claims. After taxes, UPS stood to clear $26.1
million in EVC profits, although Hall experts believed UPS could
raise its margins far higher.
</P>
<P>
   If UPS created its own offshore insurance subsidiary, Hall
officials proposed, UPS would not have to pay federal income taxes
on EVC income and annual profits would surge to $42.2 million _ a
jump of $16 million, or 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   According to the judge's 114-page ruling, UPS executive Allen
Dougherty, in attendance at the meeting, ``suggested an alternative
whereby (UPS) would form an insurance company in Bermuda to be
owned by employees. Mr. Dougherty believed the Bermuda insurance
company ... (would) not have U.S. tax obligations on profits.''
</P>
<P>
   During the next five months, conservative and tax-savvy UPS
managers endorsed a plan to create an offshore insurance
subsidiary. On July 14, 1983, the principals at the New York
meeting reconvened in Bermuda to found UPSINSCO Ltd. (later renamed
Overseas Partners Limited) to handle revenue from EVC sales. Three
of the fledgling company's five directors elected that day,
Danielewski, Kenneth L. Johnson and Jerome D. Stein, were UPS
managers.
</P>
<P>
   OPL performed much as its founders had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years later, the IRS challenged the arrangement, and
Ruwe sided with the agency. He issued a judgment against UPS
including back taxes, penalties and interest that could reach $2.4
billion. The company put $1.8 billion in an IRS escrow account to
avoid future penalties and interest. UPS denied wrongdoing and
quickly filed an appeal in Atlanta. Company officials declined to
be interviewed for this story, however, saying they would make
their case in court.
</P>
<P>
   HOW IT WORKED
</P>
<P>
   In the early '80s, UPS package insurance worked like this: UPS
self-insured each shipment for a maximum value of $100. If
customers wanted more coverage, they paid 25 cents for each
additional $100 in declared value. UPS recorded the extra charges
on its regular pickup bills, collected the funds and deposited them
into its bank accounts. The company reported EVC revenue to U.S.
regulatory agencies and paid income tax on it.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, 1984, however, that system changed.
</P>
<P>
   UPS still marketed and collected EVCs. But instead of depositing
the money in UPS bank accounts and reporting it as income, the
company directed EVC revenue to an insurance subsidiary of American
International Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   That company transferred the money by wire to OPL, the Bermuda
firm that UPS managers founded and controlled. OPL reinsured UPS
shipments, spreading the risk among a variety of insurance
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   During OPL's first full year of operation in 1984, UPS took in
$99.7 million through EVCs and paid $22 million in claims, court
records show. The new arrangement allowed UPS to shelter more than
$78 million that formerly would have treated as taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   `SHAM TRANSACTION'
</P>
<P>
   In his written ruling, Ruwe concluded the company's
restructuring had ``no economic substance or business purpose'' and
was a ``sham transaction'' designed to avoid U.S. income tax.
</P>
<P>
   UPS cited similar Tax Court cases involving Gulf Oil and U-Haul
that had been decided in favor of the companies. UPS also argued
that it had recast its EVC business to comply with state laws
requiring all companies that sold insurance _ even self-insured
firms like UPS _ to have state insurance licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The judge dismissed that explanation, however, saying UPS
officials produced few records to show they were concerned about
state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``With nothing more than the sketchy testimony about vague
concerns by (the head of UPS' insurance department, the company)
would have us conclude that it divested itself of a very profitable
$100 million per year revenue source ... that had consistently
received approval of the federal and state governments,'' Ruwe
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe (UPS) would have (restructured) a
significant portion of its business in order to avoid a potential
state law problem without having thoroughly analyzed the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies set up foreign subsidiaries in low-tax countries
like Bermuda to gain foreign tax credits that offset income from
high-tax areas, said Ernest R. Larkins, a Georgia State University
professor specializing in international taxation. By combining the
low- and high-tax income, U.S. firms can lower their overall tax
rates. Jay Carlson, a tax expert with the Washington lobbying firm
Miller &AMP; Chevalier, said the UPS case shows Tax Court judges are
increasingly likely to reject aggressive corporate tax strategies
and disregard management testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is sending a very strong message to corporate
America,'' Carlson said. ``They're drawing a line in the sand and
saying that some business practices aren't acceptable _ and some
explanations aren't believable.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be out of character for a tradition-bound, risk-averse
company like UPS to engage in questionable tax practices, said Roy
Bahl, director of Georgia State University's Policy Research
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time imagining that a company like UPS would
intentionally put itself in that kind of position,'' Bahl said.
``Companies have been known to make mistakes _ but so have Tax
Court judges. My gut tells me this case is ultimately going to be
resolved in UPS' favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Transportation industry experts say the outcome of the UPS tax
dispute will have little practical impact on the company. UPS
brought in $27.1 billion in revenue in 1999 and posted operating
profits of $3.9 billion. In documents filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, UPS said its financial reserves are more than
adequate to meet any contingencies.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Black, transportation analyst at Blaylock &AMP; Partners in New
York, said the fact that UPS has had to set aside an amount equal
to about six months' earnings and face accusations that it has been
a tax scofflaw is intolerable for a company that has sought to be
above reproach.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS is one of the most admired companies in America _ and its
business is built on trust,'' Black said. ``It's vitally important
for the company to maintain the relationships it's built over the
years. A matter like this goes far beyond a simple financial
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
