<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9788 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-TOURNEY0813-C     08-12 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-TOURNEY0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Valhalla: Course not fit for gods
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After two such incredible main courses in 2000 _ a
U.S. Open at Pebble Beach and a British Open at St. Andrews _ here
comes the payback. It's yet another PGA Championship at Valhalla
Golf Club this week in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   A month after a major held on the sport's most hallowed ground,
the 600-year-old Old Course and presumed home of golf, comes the
year's last one, on a property that has held one major in 1996,
generating nearly as many complaints as birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything drastically wrong with Valhalla as a
golf course; it's just not Winged Foot or Medinah or Southern Hills
or anything else dripping with history, which the PGA Championship
annually needs to keep pace with the other majors. After Pebble
Beach and St. Andrews, going to Valhalla is like riding around all
summer in a Lexus and then switching to a Chevy Nova.
</P>
<P>
   But, alas, the PGA of America, which has 50 percent ownership of
Valhalla, expanding to 100 percent ownership after this year's
tournament, is saving millions in lease fees, and you need go no
further for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Playing Sahalee in Remond, Wash., two years ago and asked to
comment on returning to Valhalla in 2000, Atlanta's Billy Andrade
said, ``I just can't believe it. I thought Valhalla was awful
compared (with Sahalee).''
</P>
<P>
   In John Feinstein's book, ``The Majors,'' David Duval is quoted
as saying, ``I think Valhalla is a perfectly nice golf course _ for
a Nike Tour event. But a major championship. You have to be
kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Leonard has called Valhalla, a 1986 design of Jack
Nicklaus, ``good enough for a regular tour event'' after a bit of
tweaking since the 1996 PGA, but also said, ``Is it comparable to
Winged Foot? Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was such a relatively simple venue in 1996 that 46 players
who made the cut ended up breaking par. Mark Brooks, who beat Kenny
Perry in a playoff, has not won a tournament since.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't remember much about Valhalla from 1996, you're not
alone. Fred Couples said he can't think of anyone who can remember
three holes there.
</P>
<P>
   After blowing away everyone at Pebble Beach and St. Andrews,
Tiger Woods is again a huge favorite. And why not? Valhalla is
pretty much basic Nicklaus stuff. Generous fairways, severe
approach areas and sloped greens, favoring someone with a power
fade.
</P>
<P>
   After making a quick practice round last Tuesday in a light
rain, the defending champion came away with nothing to reduce his
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That golf course is typical Nicklaus golf course where he
gives you room off the tee, but he makes it a little more
challenging coming into the greens,'' said Woods. ``You've got to
hit some precise shots. If you're playing well, you can use the
slopes to you advantage. You can spin the ball off the slopes and
let it run an extra 10 or 15 feet. If you're playing well, the
greens become bigger because you can use the slopes to bring the
ball into the hole. If you're struggling, for some reason you tend
to catch the opposite side and the ball tends to roll away from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's Ernie Els, who is trying to change a trend that
has resulted in three runner-up finishes in the 2000 majors,
obviously handles a Nicklaus track well. He won last Sunday on
Nicklaus' Castle Pines course at The International.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can shoot real low scores on Nicklaus-designed courses if
you're on your game and everything goes your way and you get your
distances right,'' Els said. ``You can play safe and you can shoot
your even par, 1 under par pretty easily. But if you want to go
after it, you're going to take the risk, maybe shoot a very high
score. I did that at Valhalla. I shot a 68 in the second round and
I went out and shot a 79 in the third round.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few changes to Valhalla, which features a
front nine in a links-type, meadow area and a back nine through the
trees. New tees were built on No. 1, No. 2 and No. 6 and existing
tees at the 5th and 12th hole were extended _ all to encourage more
players to hit drivers. For viewers, a change at the par-5 597-yard
7th is worth noting. In 1996 an island fairway positioned in the
middle of a quarry was deemed off-limits by the PGA. This year,
much to Nicklaus' pleasure, the route will be open down the left
side, making the hole reachable in two and adding some thrills.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly considering Nicklaus' game, the course often
favors a bit of a left-to-right shot. That would also fit David
Duval, if his sore back is up to it, and a player such as lefty
Mickelson. For him, it's a draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of his greens tend run left-to-right, as opposed to
front-to-back,'' Mickelson said. ``So it's a very shallow landing
area and you need to bring the ball in high and soft.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's a unfortunate that the PGA of America has sacrificed
quality and history for dollars, when things start up Thursday, it
will all be relative. It will be Woods against the field and a
quest for three consecutive major victories. His place in history
will be more important than the place they are playing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
