<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-LOSANGELES-ART-2T     08-12 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-LOSANGELES-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WAVE OF POWER BROKERS ESTABLISHES BEACHHEAD IN LOS ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2 and NYT3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Charlie Woo is the sort of business and civic
leader one would expect to find at the head of the welcoming line
at the Democratic National Convention this week, and, in fact, he
will be, as a vice chairman of the city's host committee.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most revealing aspect of Woo's prominence and
devotion to an impressive array of community organizations is the
boards that he _ like many of the other successful people in the
city's new wave of leaders _ is not on.
</P>
<P>
   Woo will soon become the first Asian-American chairman of the
Los Angeles Chamber of Commerce, and he has helped guide groups
involved in everything from voter registration to inner-city job
development and Chinese-American political fund-raising. But even
though he is an obvious candidate, he has no involvement in the
prestigious institutions that once stood at the apex of civic life
here, the philanthropies, art museums and especially the downtown
Performing Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That represents a different world that isn't relevant to me in
the same way these things might have been in the past,'' said Woo,
a toy manufacturer. ``The power shift that is taking place here is
not just new ethnic groups rising, but a new approach to how you
get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Major public events like the Democratic convention are
opportunities for the host cities to put a well-scrubbed face
forward and for their power elite to stand on a national stage,
displaying a shared sense of civic pride and identity.
</P>
<P>
   But in Los Angeles, a sprawling concatenation of communities
with a restless multi-ethnic character, there is no single
``face,'' in the usual sense of the word. A surge of immigration
and the rapid shift toward an economy dominated by small businesses
rather than huge corporations have pushed Los Angeles into a
dizzyingly complex transition.
</P>
<P>
   The city has lost its white majority and will soon have a Latino
majority, with a swiftly growing number of Asian-Americans. But
despite these shifts, the upper crust of movers and shakers, the
power elite at the most well-recognized civic bodies, remains
heavily white and has not changed in tandem.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Performing Arts Center, formerly known as the
Music Center and once the most prestigious social prize, today has
81 board members, four of whom are minority members. There are two
minority members on the Los Angeles County Museum of Art's
39-member board, and the pattern of underrepresentation of the
city's emerging minorities is similar at some other traditionally
important boards, from the Huntington Library to the University of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   As many leaders point out, there is no single power elite here
today, but many, some of whom are just emerging and have made it
clear they have little interest in the traditional avenues for
civic involvement, which had long been closed to them. This has
long been true for Hollywood power brokers, who have historically
shown almost no interest in the standard civic groups, and now the
attitude seems to be spreading to emerging ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the host committee for the Democratic convention limped
from one crisis to another, at least partly because there was no
longer a lengthy A-list of reliable contributors to call whenever a
financing problem arose. There have been plenty of other
disappointments, from the tepid new millennium celebration to the
city's continued failure to secure a professional football team,
all considered a product of the lack of a shared vision by a
unified power group. But the most potent symbol of the decline of
the old order was the sale of The Los Angeles Times this year to
the Tribune Co. of Chicago by its controlling shareholders, the
Chandler family, which once defined civic commitment but has now
all but vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Today, few of Los Angeles' governing elites know one another
well, lunch together or golf together, or share much beyond a
conviction that the whole notion of civic leadership must be
broadened.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, in short, will be seeking to define themselves
for the new millennium in a city that has lost its unified civic
aristocracy and has yet to find a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days there was a real power structure and it was
clearly defined and you knew how to access it,'' said Gordon
Davidson, a founder and artistic director of the Center Theater
Group at the Performing Arts Center, home to many of the city's
most elite fund-raising galas. ``The sad thing now is that we don't
have it in the same way. It's a healthy sign, but it means you have
to work a lot harder.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Frankly, it's what makes being here still something
of an adventure. The question that I don't really have an answer to
is, who is setting the pace?''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Griego, an entrepreneur and a former deputy mayor, says
she grows slightly irritated when asked why the old-line boards do
not have more Latino or Asian-American or black members. In short,
she said, many elites from minority groups are frustrated that
these older organizations have not been more aggressive in courting
them. But she said that leaders who are members of minorities often
do not join those boards, even when they are invited, because their
missions did not seem to serve the ethnic population.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old aristocracy is really gone,'' said Griego, who has
served on boards as varied as hospitals, community redevelopment,
the local community college system and the city's cultural affairs
office. ``It was kind of a downtown, music-center nucleus, based on
old families and huge corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Dominic Ng, the chairman of the EastWest Bank here, said that
when he was first urged to join the high-status local board of the
United Way about five years ago, he hesitated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was, why should I join? They don't do much
for the Asian-American or even the Hispanic communities,'' said Ng,
an immigrant from Hong Kong. But he said he was persuaded that by
joining he could help alter the philanthropy's mission, and, with
the help of some committed board colleagues, he has. The United Way
has cut back on its contributions to traditional recipients, like
the American Heart Association, and poured money into programs that
will help train new immigrants for jobs and help them buy homes. Ng
is now the board's vice chairman. He serves on other boards as
well, but he said that he sees little need to join the traditional
boards of the old power elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of those organizations have asked me, but I declined,''
Ng said. ``I feel I need first to help the poor and to really help
change the community.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Economics have exerted a major influence over these trends.
Nearly all of the Fortune 500 companies that once had headquarters
in Los Angeles, from Arco and Unocal to the First Interstate Bank,
have been acquired or have moved elsewhere. Along with this shift,
the downtown district has atrophied, as the thriving new businesses
have tended to move to other parts of the city and region.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the economy is dominated by myriad small companies. And
members of minorities have found it far easier to rise in the
entrepreneurial ranks than in the old corporate hierarchies, which
has also contributed to the changing civic architecture of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we have to reach out more,'' said Joanne Corday
Kozberg, the president of the Performing Arts Center. ``We need to
reach the entrepreneurial base, and by that you really mean a lot
of people of color. You have to look at where the community is
going. We may need to focus more on trade, and we hadn't done that
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson, of the theater group, said one irony was the fact that
his staff was far more diverse than his board, in part because it
was proving far easier to find minority artists interested in
working at the theater than in finding minority business leaders
interested in setting artistic policy. That still leaves many
people here frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a disconnect between the changing face of Los Angeles
and the political, economic and civic leadership circles,'' said
Antonio Villaraigosa, a former speaker of the California Assembly
and a Democrat who is given a reasonable chance of becoming Los
Angeles' first Hispanic mayor in the election in 2001. ``Los
Angeles is the Ellis Island of the west. These civic organizations
really lag what is happening in the population.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the key to the changes and the city's future vitality
was not that some of the old elite organizations are opening their
doors, but that the more dynamic leaders are forging their own
paths, without feeling obliged to follow in the footsteps of the
elites of previous generations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Luis Nogales, a child of migrant farm laborers who was recently
named to the board of the J. Paul Getty Trust, expressed
frustration at the pace of civic change and a sobering view of the
multiple barriers that will need to fall to speed the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had too many firsts,'' said Nogales, an entrepreneur who
was the first Latino graduate of Stanford's law school and the
first Latino trustee of Stanford. ``One of the problems is that the
first step is usually for show. But I make it a point not to be the
last Hispanic member of those boards, and that takes a lot of
work.'' He added: ``It's a good start to be on a board, but it's a
start. I'm not satisfied to just get the appointment. I come with
an agenda. Making any difference means you have to work twice as
hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
