<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS SEE BRIGHT SIDE OF ODD LOSS IN FINAL SECONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ For a coach who had just watched two of his
rookies fumble away a preseason victory in the game's final
seconds, Jim Fassel did not appear too shaken in the wake of the
New York Giants' 16-13 loss here Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, when he emerged from the team's locker room he was a
bit red-faced from yelling at his charges, or perhaps just
red-faced.
</P>
<P>
   How often, after all, does a game turn in the final seven
seconds on a collision between teammates when each was trying to
protect the football and the victory?
</P>
<P>
   Leading by 13-9, team members were initially relieved when
Giants cornerback Fred Lewis, a rookie from Louisiana Tech,
intercepted a pass thrown by the Jacksonville Jaguars' reserve
quarterback Jonathan Quinn near the Giants goal line. Lewis, not
sure if he had caught the football in the end zone, started to
advance the ball up field. Running laterally across the field, he
passed Jack Golden, a rookie linebacker from Oklahoma State. Golden
said later that he wanted Lewis to fall to the ground to avoid a
fumble.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Lewis sped by, Golden reached out and tackled his
teammate, knocking the football from Lewis' grasp. It rolled into
the corner of the end zone where Jacksonville tight end Brandon
Christenson fell on it for the Jaguars' game-winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy smokes,'' Fassel said later to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   No one bothered to ask if Fassel had ever seen a finish like
that. Fassel was the offensive coordinator at Stanford in 1983 when
the University of California made its now famous lateral-laden,
marching-band-abusing kickoff return for a touchdown on the game's
final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just an amazing way to lose a game,'' Fassel said,
though it was not apparent whether he was talking about 1983 or
2000.
</P>
<P>
   If Friday had been a regular-season game, there would have been
no effort to see the bigger picture after such a bizarre loss. But
since preseason games are intended to prepare the team for the
regular season, the majority in the Giants locker room, Fassel
included, saw mostly positives from their visit here.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants starters, for example, were disheartened, but it was
far more important to them that they had again showed progress _
they won their part of the game, leaving with a 10-6 lead at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were rooting pretty hard on the sideline for the victory,
so I'm not going to stand here now and say it meant nothing,'' said
running back Tiki Barber, who had a spectacular game with 83
rushing yards and 27 receiving yards in one half. ``But you've got
to know that what happened was a freaky thing and not let it
overshadow everything else we came down here to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Giants have never played well here, and since it was
their only preseason game on the road, one of the team goals was to
play a mistake-free game in an unfriendly environment. The Giants,
now 0-2 in the preseason, wanted to be aggressive and show some
mental toughness.
</P>
<P>
   The game's conclusion hardly fit the bill, but in the first
half, the Giants were the better team and they revealed at least a
glimpse of what they would like to accomplish this year.
</P>
<P>
   The starting quarterback, Kerry Collins, was sharp, just as in
last weekend's loss to Chicago, when the starters again left with a
lead. Collins completed 10 of 19 passes for 110 yards, including a
well-executed pass to Amani Toomer for a 22-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can start to feel some things click out there,'' Collins
said. ``It's a process, but I see us making steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Barber set up a field goal and stunned the Jaguars with a
55-yard dash around right end that was all running instinct and a
pure burst of speed. Barber continues to make his subpar season of
1998 look like some kind of sophomore jinx.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie Ron Dayne had 17 carries for 66 rugged yards at
running back. Dayne broke tackles, ran well in short-yardage
situations and made the most of small openings.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the Giants' top offensive line played with unity
against an opponent known for its swarming, blitzing defense even
in preseason games. With four new members in the offensive line,
there have been a lot of questions, but for the second successive
week, Collins was not sacked and rarely even hurried.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Giants were steady, although their tackling was
occasionally slipshod. The Giants were playing without their
starting middle linebacker, Mike Barrow, who has a knee sprain, and
they also lost his backup, Pete Monty, who broke his thumb early in
the game and will miss two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of ways you can look at a game like that,''
Fassel said when he had composed himself enough to offer a thin
smile. ``You hate to lose it and I'm disappointed, but I'm going to
see the good things, too. And there were lots of good things.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the final seven seconds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
