<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-MARLINS-RISE-NYT &LR;      08-12 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MARLINS-RISE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLINS RISE FROM THEIR ASHES TO THE .500 LEVEL
</HEADLINE>
  (WITH BBO-NOTEBOOK, attached)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Aug. 13. Do you know where the Florida Marlins are?
</P>
<P>
   Around .500, that's where they are, and that's utterly
remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Rising rapidly from the bitter ashes of the 1997 World Series
championship and their fire sale, the Marlins have become a
competitive team again, if not a contender. Putting that phrase
``competitive team again'' in perspective, this is only the second
season in the Marlins' eight-year history that they have had a
winning record after the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased with where we are at this point compared with
where we've been the past couple years,'' said Dave Dombrowski, the
president and general manager, who has engineered the quick
comeback. ``We know nothing matters till you're a championship
team, and we have 50 games left in the season. But if you had told
us in spring training we'd be over .500 in August, you'd be pleased
with that. There are a lot of encouraging signs down here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Marlins will live forever in baseball infamy. The first
team to reach the World Series that had not finished in first
place, they defeated the Cleveland Indians for the championship
after wiping out an Indians' lead in the ninth inning of the
seventh game, then wiped themselves out by fiat of the then owner,
Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski, in the most painful act of his impressive career,
dutifully dismantled the champions, trading his good veteran (read:
high-priced) players or letting them go as free agents. At the
time, it might have appeared that he was giving them away, but he
was amassing a collection of talented youngsters, primarily
pitchers, who have matured enough to know how to play winning
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround becomes even more remarkable when Dombrowski's
trade itinerary is considered. He was still making trades to shed
veterans well into the 1998 season, not much more than two years
ago. And he has not created this winning team by snatching a free
agent here and there.
</P>
<P>
   Consider one of the key members of the team, Antonio Alfonseca.
He inherited the closer's role when the Marlins traded Matt Mantei
to Arizona 13 months ago, and he has performed brilliantly. He
leads the major leagues with 34 saves, and he has saved 59 percent
of the 58 victories the Marlins had at the start of the weekend.
Add his four victories, and he has figured in 66 percent of the
victories, also tops in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he had the potential to do it,'' Dombrowski said,
``but to say he'd put up the numbers he has would have been
presumptuous on our part. One characteristic he had was he had ice
in his veins. Look back at the World Series. He was pitching in
middle relief, and he came in and pitched scoreless ball'' _ three
games, 6 1/3 innings, no runs. `` He rose to the occasion, and he
has done that as the closer. He's been phenomenal for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins plucked Alfonseca from the Montreal minor league
system in 1993. Two other relievers, Armando Almanza and Braden
Looper, were acquired from St. Louis in the December 1998, trade of
Edgar Renteria. Dan Miceli came from San Diego last winter, Manny
Aybar from Cincinnati last month. Vic Darensbourg came up through
the team's minor league system.
</P>
<P>
   The relief corps has the lowest earned run average in the
majors, 3.72.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get late into a game, that's been our biggest plus,''
Dombrowski said.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching has generally been stingy in recent weeks. In the
eight games (6-2) before Saturday night, the Marlins had allowed
three or fewer runs six times, and in their last 15 games (10-5)
they had given up four or fewer runs 13 times.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Castillo has become the catalyst of the offense, holding
the National League's third-highest batting average, .357, the
third-highest on-base percentage, .442, and the most stolen bases,
46. He has driven in only nine runs, but the last third of the
Marlins' lineup does not give the second baseman many RBI
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He epitomizes what you look for in a leadoff hitter,''
Dombrowski said. ``He disrupts the other club's pitcher any time
he's on base, and he scores a lot of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Preston Wilson, the center fielder, is the team's No. 1 run
producer, driving in 88 runs before Saturday night, but he also is
the major leagues' No. 1 strikeout victim. With 146 strikeouts in
playing 114 of the team's 115 games, he is headed for the record of
189 strikeouts Bobby Bonds set in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll always be a high strikeout guy because he has that kind
of swing,'' Dombrowski said. ``But now the emphasis is on the
positive side _ RBIs, stolen bases, defense. He's a maturing young
person who keeps getting better and better. He's not the type of
guy to be affected by the strikeouts. He knows he strikes out a
lot. It's talked about a lot. But he's a very hard worker, and he
works at getting better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other developing players are first baseman Derrek Lee,
third baseman Mike Lowell and right fielder Mark Kotsay.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins have won 11 more games than they did in the
corresponding period last year and 17 more than they did in 1998,
the year after. They will not reach the playoffs this season, but
they are headed in the right direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
