<HEADLINE>
THE LOSINGEST PITCHERS; CLEMENS IS HIGHEST PAID IN HISTORY 
(WITH BBN-MARLINS-RISE) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way Joe Mays pitched in his last start, he is clearly one of
the favorites to win the race, but do not overlook Jose Lima. And
what is Mike Mussina doing there?
</P>
<P>
   It's the race no pitcher wants to win _ most losses of the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   Mays, who allowed four runs in a third of an inning last
Thursday for Minnesota; Lima, who won 21 for Houston last season,
and Steve Parris of Cincinnati are tied for the lead with 14 losses
each. Kelvim Escobar of Toronto has 13, and Mussina, struggling
with the dying Baltimore Orioles, is one of five pitchers with 12
losses each. Steve Trachsel, traded recently from Tampa Bay to
Toronto, has 11 losses. He won last year's race with 18 losses.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kingman will not be rooting for any particular pitcher to
win this year's race. He'll just root, as he did with Trachsel a
year ago, for none of them to lose 20. He was the last major league
pitcher to lose 20, in 1980, and he wants to retain the
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens Is Highest Paid in History
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees are not shouting it from the highest hill;
they're not even whispering it under the covers. But contrary to
George Steinbrenner's allergic reaction to establishing salary
standards, the Yankees have done just that by making Roger Clemens
the highest-paid player in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   That development was not mentioned Friday when the Yankees
announced that they have given Clemens a contract extension worth
$30.9 million. That's because the Yankees called it a three-year
deal. But Clemens has to play only two years to receive all of that
money so the annual average value computes to $15.45 million, and
it surpasses the $15 million average of Kevin Brown's seven-year
contract with the Los Angeles Dodgers, the previous record.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will jump up and down and insist that the two-year
computation is incorrect; they'll stamp their feet and say the
third year has to be included and that the average is really $10.3
million. But the third year is an option year _ at Clemens' option.
He can say no, thank you, not play for the Yankees in 2003 and
still collect his money for that year, $10.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Any money a player can receive for an option year that is not
exercised, either by the club or the player, is included in the
guaranteed part of the deal. The year, however, is not because it
is not known if the player will play for the team that season.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez, for example, has a six-year contract with the
Boston Red Sox that includes an option for a seventh season in 2004
at a $17.5 million salary. If the Red Sox do not exercise the
option, they will pay Martinez $2.5 million. To determine the value
of the contract, that $2.5 million buyout is added to the other
guaranteed money for a total of $75 million for six years, or an
average of $12.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The collective bargaining agreement between the owners and the
players stipulates that when it comes to free agents clubs cannot
act in concert with other clubs and players cannot act in concert
with other players. But the labor contract does not say anything
about owners acting in concert with players and their agents, and
that's what Steinbrenner has apparently done here with Randy and
Alan Hendricks, the pitcher's agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees acquired Clemens in a trade with Toronto in
February, 1999. As a player traded during a multiyear contract, the
pitcher had the right to demand a trade last November. When he did
not invoke that right even as leverage for an extension, Clemens
seemed to confirm what some baseball executives had said, that the
two sides already had an understanding about an extension.
</P>
<P>
   One person with knowledge of the Clemens development said the
contract announced Friday is a two-year deal with the $10.3 million
for the third year serving as a makeup for the lower salaries
Clemens has had in his two years with the Yankees, $8.25 million
last year, $6.35 million this. He said the two sides had reached
that understanding last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
