<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TRAFICANT-RENO-0813-C     08-12 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAFICANT-RENO-0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN YOUNGSTOWN, TRAFICANT VS. RENO IS NO CONTEST
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio _ In Teenie's Tavern just south of downtown,
screeching hard rock anthems by AC/DC play side-by-side with the
muddy harmonies of polka music.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the standard bar smoke and plume of white flour reaching
from the back room where the girls make pirogies, the retired
barber drinks his beer and revs up his opinion about Rep. James
Traficant, the combative Democrat who represents this community in
Congress. But first an agreement: no names, the barber insists. He
waves a hand, ``No names.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's doing a hell of a job,'' the 67-year-old man says
from beneath a Detroit Tigers baseball cap. ``I want to know how
many more congressmen and how many more senators have had the same
thoughts he's had but haven't had the guts to say it. About the
IRS. About Janet Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, Attorney General Janet Reno. Last week, Traficant
appeared on an evening talk show in Washington and claimed to have
``sworn affidavits'' from people accusing Reno of a spectrum of
tawdry illegalities, starting with hiring female prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations, which Traficant will not substantiate by
releasing the documents he claims to have, stirred a brief tempest
for the lawmaker who is by many accounts _ including his own _
inching simultaneously toward
</P>
<P>
   effortless re-election and a grand jury indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Traficant, who are legion in this economically
depressed area in northeastern Ohio between Cleveland and
Pittsburgh, are heartened once again by his fearlessness.
Detractors, a smaller but perhaps growing group, consider it
further evidence that Traficant is moving out of the realm of
enigmatic populist and full-throttle into the arena of shadowy
civic liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's out beyond the brink on that one,'' said state
Sen. Bob Hagan, D-Youngstown, who challenged Traficant in the party
primary last March. ``It's embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the politics of thin majority rule, where a handful of
seats determines control of the House, Traficant is no outcast. As
a Democrat who often votes with Republicans, Traficant has both
parties tip-toeing around his increasingly unpredictable behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Vindicator, Youngstown's paper, is less cautious. The paper
didn't repeat the charges Traficant
</P>
<P>
   leveled at Reno because he wouldn't provide documentation. But
in a column Friday, the paper's political writer likened
Traficant's attack to McCarthyism.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant, a former football star and sheriff who gained folk
hero status in 1983 after winning an acquittal as his own attorney
on charges he took a bribe from the mob, soldiers on. He issued a
press release days after making the charges against Reno, saying he
had submitted a Freedom of Information Act request for documents as
part of his ``ongoing investigation into corruption within the
Justice Department.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In response to the many media inquires I have received this
week,'' Traficant said at the bottom of the press release, ``I have
this to say to the media: Ask Janet Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   At her weekly news conference Thursday, Reno was asked. ``I just
consider the source,'' she said. ``I don't know where he got the
information, and since he didn't present it, I don't know anything
about it. But people say all sorts of mean things that have no
basis in fact, as these have no basis in fact, and I try to go on
and ignore them.... As Lincoln said, if I were to read everything
mean that people said about me I might as well close this shop for
business. But those were some of the meanest things.''
</P>
<P>
   A school of thought in the Mahoning Valley has it that Traficant
is simply trying to discredit his pursuers, employing the strategy
of a great offense as the best defense. By the time the grand jury
in Cleveland is ready to indict the target of the probe, an unnamed
``public official'' whom an attorney for one of the witnesses
confirms is Traficant, it will be impossible for potential jurors
not to wonder if the charges aren't retaliation for all those
``mean things'' Traficant has said.
</P>
<P>
   Or so the theory goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that argument,'' said Traficant's spokesman, Paul
Marcone. ``For years he's been a critic of the Justice Department,
that's a matter of record. This isn't something new.''
</P>
<P>
   What's new is the federal investigation into allegations that
Traficant has illegally accepted cars and other gifts from
constituents. He invoked his Fifth Amendment right against
incriminating himself when he refused to turn over subpoenaed
documents earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, contractor David Sugar pleaded innocent to
charges he provided false testimony and tampered with a witness in
connection to allegations he poured concrete at Traficant's horse
farm outside of
</P>
<P>
   Youngstown without taking payment. Sugar is accused of ordering
his secretary to draw up fake invoices to show payments for the
work.
</P>
<P>
   Pat D'Angelo, Sugar's attorney, said Traficant made a ``partial
payment,'' for the $1,000 worth of concrete but insisted there was
no quid pro quo of official favors from Traficant involved.
D'Angelo, who confirmed that
</P>
<P>
   Traficant is the public official at the center of the grand jury
investigation, said Sugar and Traficant are lifelong friends.
</P>
<P>
   The other new piece of the Traficant story is that despite his
current legal troubles, Democrats and Republicans in Washington are
trying very hard to stay on his good side. The two parties are in a
tightly fought war over control of the House, with Democrats
needing to pick up only six seats to retake control of the chamber
for the first time since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the blustery Traficant presents a problem for his party's
effort because he often votes with Republicans on issues, and more
significantly because he has promised to vote for Republican House
Speaker Dennis Hastert in the speakership election in January. That
means Democrats will need to pick up seven new seats in order to
gain enough votes to choose the speaker, who sets the legislative
agenda in Congress and appoints the chairmen of committees.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant, a delegate to the Democratic National Convention that
starts Monday, pledged his allegiance to Hastert this summer, about
the same time an emergency spending bill was approved with $25
million set aside for a new community center in Youngstown. It was
the only Democrat project included in the $200 million bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Davis, the Virginia Republican who leads the Republican
National Congressional Committee, told the Columbus Dispatch
recently that Traficant is important to the party. ``We'll take
every vote we can get at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   But this attitude hasn't been well received by the congressional
campaign of Paul Alberty, the Republican challenging Traficant this
year. Alberty is a computer systems consultant and former member of
the Poland Village Council who has gotten moral support, but so far
no money from the NRCC for his race against Traficant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if (the NRCC) came out against Traficant, but
right now they need him for some key votes,'' said Ed Crepage,
Alberty's campaign manager. ``It is frustrating for us. Right now
they're playing along with
</P>
<P>
   him, but that's politics.''
</P>
<P>
   And in politics, Traficant remains golden. Although he is said
to have slipped in popularity, he won more than 50 percent of the
vote in a three-way primary race that even opposing political
consultants concede was a ``remarkable'' performance.
</P>
<P>
   Voters like the barber in Teenies, or an industrial electronics
worker who also refused to give a name, believe in Traficant.
</P>
<P>
   They believe him when he says the Department of Justice is
corrupt and out to get him because he embarrassed them with his
acquittal in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   They believe he tells the truth that no one else has the courage
to tell.
</P>
<P>
   They believe he is doing his level best to help Youngstown out
of the economic slump it fell into with the closing of steel plants
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   And they will vote for him again in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a solid core of voters who if Traficant came by their
house and killed their mother they'd thank him for stopping by,''
said Leo Jennings, a political consultant who worked on the Hagan
primary campaign and now is working on the well-financed
independent candidacy of Randy D. Walter. ``I don't know what you
do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery can be e-mailed at scottm(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
