<SLUG> BC-FBN-PACKERS-FAVRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVRE HAS NO PLAN TO DRIVE HIS TRACTOR OUT OF TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A separate story, FBN-NOTEBOOK, is attached.) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is interesting how quickly fans forget. It was not long ago
when Brett Favre, the Green Bay Packers quarterback, could have run
for mayor in that city. Super Bowl appearances in the 1996 and 1997
seasons had revitalized football in Packersville, and Favre's
rocket arm was the biggest reason for it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on radio talk shows in Green Bay, fans and some members of
the news media are questioning if Matt Hasselbeck, the backup
quarterback, should replace Favre. Hasselbeck will indeed be a
starter in this league. He is good, but is he better than Favre?
</P>
<P>
   Will everyone please come back to this solar system?
</P>
<P>
   If the Packers are going to make a return to the Super Bowl,
their best chance is with Favre, not Hasselbeck, who has been
impressive in preseason games mostly against backup players
(against the Jets last week, Hasselbeck completed 11 of 15 passes
for 162 yards and 2 touchdowns). But he has yet to be tested on a
consistent basis during the regular season against the starters of
top defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Favre was not thrilled when he was asked about the Hasselbeck
chatter, or the status of his sore throwing elbow. There is some
mild concern in the Packers' organization that Favre will again
battle arm and hand injuries, as he did last season, when a
severely injured thumb disrupted his passing motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought much about it,'' Favre said last week of the
Hasselbeck talk. ``As far as I know I'm still the starting
quarterback, and they're paying me for it. When they stop doing
that, I've got a tractor and you all can start talking about
somebody else. I mean, there'll be another backup quarterback that
comes in and the whole phenomenon will start over again.''
</P>
<P>
   On the persistent questions about his elbow, Favre, who was
addressing reporters from a podium during his weekly news
conference, said rather testily: ``I don't enjoy all these
questions. I don't know if any of you would be standing up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again the old backup quarterback controversy is rearing its
ugly head. No matter how many Super Bowls a quarterback wins, if he
goes through a rough stretch there are always calls for the backup.
John Elway, Dan Marino, Phil Simms, Terry Bradshaw, Joe Montana _
all great throwers who at one point heard calls for the understudy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there is a reason the backup was the backup to begin
with. But perspective is always the first victim when the
controversy strikes.
</P>
<P>
   It is true tendinitis in Favre's right elbow has affected his
passes in camp, as have blisters on his hand. For now he is not
throwing with that familiar Favre zip. As a result, coach Mike
Sherman has reduced Favre's throwing repetitions to rest the elbow.
He is scheduled to play only a handful of series during Sunday's
preseason game against the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Favre maintains his elbow is fine, and that if the season began
Sunday, his passes would be as deadly as ever. For the first time
in his career, Favre is following the example of great veteran
passers like Troy Aikman, who does not overwork his arm in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to do anything to jeopardize my throwing for
when it really counts,'' Favre said. ``Nothing counts in preseason
except for guys trying to make the team. That's as clear as I can
state it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to prove anything to anybody right now,'' he
added. ``I just want to survive preseason. Five years ago, I
probably would take every snap. But I'm trying to be smart about it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Favre, whose 235 touchdown passes in the 1990s are the most of
any quarterback, has been an unparalleled leader with a chance of
being in the Hall of Fame. This is Favre's 10th season so it is no
wonder Favre is having some physical problems with his arm.
</P>
<P>
   But bench Favre? Now? The idea is silly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
