<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-WINSTON-CUP-NYT     08-12 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NADEAU PEEKING OUT FROM SHADOW OF GORDON
</HEADLINE>
 By DAVE CALDWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Jerry Nadeau first jumped into a go-cart
when he was 4, and he was hooked. He loved driving cars so much
that he often slept in one to scare up enough money to keep chasing
his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not bad when you turn the heat on,'' Nadeau said on
Saturday morning, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Now Nadeau, 29, a native of Danbury, Conn., has his own mobile
home to sleep in and his own fast Winston Cup car to drive. He has
finished fourth in two of his last three Nascar races, including
the Brickyard 400 last Saturday, and he is peeking out from the
huge shadows cast by Jeff Gordon, his Hendrick racing teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, things are starting to turn around and we're
starting to finish races,'' Nadeau said.
</P>
<P>
   With six straight victories on road courses and a three-race
winning streak at Watkins Glen International, Gordon will be a
focal point entering Sunday's Global Crossing at the Glen. Although
some road-course specialists are hired for this race, stock-car
drivers are better on road courses than they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you didn't focus on a road course,'' Gordon
said. ``You said, `That's just one we throw out the window.' Now,
for the championship, you've got to run good everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Showers on Saturday morning forced the cancellation of
qualifying, throwing an interesting wrinkle into the race for the
Winston Cup. The cars will start in order of their Winston Cup
points standing, which means the top three _ Bobby Labonte, Dale
Jarrett and Dale Earnhardt _ will be at the front of a lead pack
that will be hard to catch.
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau will start 25th, but he thinks he has a car capable of
surging to the front. He posted the third-fastest time in practice
under sodden skies on Saturday, even faster than Gordon. He posted
his best finishes here in each of his two full Winston Cup seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau's first season driving for Rick Hendrick started slowly,
with many accidents and breakdowns. Now, he said, his luck is
changing.
</P>
<P>
   He joked that he has started wearing his underwear backwards to
improve his fortunes, but added that he is doing things the same
way he did earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau has driven virtually every kind of souped-up car there
is. When he was 17 he won track championships on dirt and asphalt
at Oakland Valley Raceway in Cuddebackville, N.Y., and he once
finished second in a go-cart race on ice in that
not-so-chicken-fried racing locale, St. Petersburg, Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quick from the start,'' said Skip Barber, who runs a
racing school from which Nadeau and other drivers learned many
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   But Nadeau, Barber said, was also painfully shy. He had the
talent and the push to become a good driver _ ``a sleep-in-his-car
kind of guy,'' Barber said _ but he did not have a driver's
swagger.
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau found that, too. He won an open-wheel championship in
Barber's program in 1991, earned a scholarship, and stayed on a
roll. He took some public speaking courses and became less shy and
more well-spoken, always a plus in the eyes of publicity-hungry
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, Nadeau moved to North Carolina to try to be a Winston
Cup driver. He remembers sneaking into Hendrick's shop to pick up
some tips. Two years later, he was in a Winston Cup car. He signed
with Hendrick at the end of last season and got sponsorship from a
dot-com company that sells building materials.
</P>
<P>
   All he has to do now is win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just takes time, and then experience takes over a little
bit,'' said Tony Furr, Nadeau's crew chief. ``What's been hard for
us is that this has been a new car and a new driver. Usually, when
you make a change, you only have to worry about one of those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   It has helped Nadeau that he has had Gordon's expertise at his
disposal. But Hendrick, who also owns a car driven by Terry
Labonte, has never seen Nadeau as his third-best driver. Probably
more important, Nadeau has never seen himself that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry's stayed pretty level,'' Furr said. ``You can tell he's
confident _ I reckon that's the word for it. But he has a lot more
confidence than he had early, that's for sure.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
