<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL OBSERVER: YOUNG, IDEALISTIC AND AMBITIOUS AT YALE IN THE
'60s  
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the talk of the importance of average families in the
election this year, it turns out to be a grand year for elites. The
last time a presidential race featured a candidate from Harvard (Al
Gore), Yale (George W. Bush) and Princeton (Ralph Nader) was 1912 _
the year of Woodrow Wilson, Teddy Roosevelt and William Howard Taft
_ when the Ivy League was more clearly a place of privilege than it
is today.
</P>
<P>
   For Yale, however, it's a trifecta. With the selection of Dick
Cheney and Joseph Lieberman as vice presidential candidates, three
out of the four major-party nominees spent at least some of their
college years in New Haven. It is not a burning issue, but still
you have to wonder. What was there at Yale that helped incubate
these choices?
</P>
<P>
   With his reputation as a fun-loving fraternity president, Bush
fits into a popular stereotype of Yale, dating from old New Yorker
cartoons depicting the guy in a raccoon coat at a football game.
But what I find striking about the candidates is their echo of a
peculiar strain of political ambition combined with do-goodism
rampant at Yale in the 1960s, when I was a student along with Bush
and Lieberman and other budding politicians like Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts and Gov. George Pataki of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Back then Yale, like most campuses, was a hub of idealism,
networking and, in retrospect, more than a little sanctimony. My
years there were framed by two Kennedy assassinations and filled
with civil rights activity and anti-war protests. ``There were
moments when you weren't sure about the survivability of the
country,'' says Roland Betts, one of my class' biggest champions of
Bush. ``It was not like today, when kids go through college
planning their careers and figure that everything will be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents of Yale from that era were also moral
spokesmen. Kingman Brewster's defense of the legal rights of Black
Panthers led eventually to his departure, and Bart Giamatti, my
thesis adviser, made the study of Renaissance epic poetry into a
quest for the ideal. Everything was debated in moral terms _ not
just the war and the draft, but coeducation, teacher tenure and
whether to join a fraternity or go to law school.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lewis Lapham, editor of Harper's and a chronicler
of the American class system, Yale has been a place of moral debate
since its founding in 1701 by ministers upset that Harvard had
strayed from its religious purity. ``The argument between God and
mammon, between doing well and doing good, is always alive and well
at Yale,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, the struggle has taken place on both the left
and right. The left of my day saw Yale as a tool of the
establishment, whereas Bush says he recalls the condescension of
the liberals, just as William F. Buckley had a generation earlier.
Yet Bush is sending his daughter to Yale this fall, just as Buckley
sent his son.
</P>
<P>
   The most memorable feature of the ferment at Yale was how
Yale-like it was. There was a perverse pride in knowing that while
some Yale professors had done recruiting for the CIA and alumni
like the Bundy brothers and the Rostow brothers were helping to
prosecute the war, the anti-war movement was led by Yale graduates
like Benjamin Spock, David Dellinger and the Rev. William Sloane
Coffin Jr. I can still remember my irritation with Coffin when he
challenged a group of us to get off our rear ends _ during exam
season _ to organize a protest against Lady Bird Johnson, who was
speaking to the Political Union. We did, but the main goal, I
remember, was to make sure that the radicals didn't do something
really impolite like pull down their pants.
</P>
<P>
   The other relevant feature of life at Yale was what Gaddis
Smith, the diplomatic historian, calls the ``ethos of organized
activity.'' Smith, who is writing a book about Yale in the 20th
century, says that students have aspired to organize and lead
groups since the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of student government, Yale students joined
publications, sports teams, academic advisory boards, fraternities,
singing groups and other organizations. I was active in The Yale
Daily News and the Political Union, a campus debating society that
was sometimes ridiculed as a place of earnest and ambitious student
politicians. Pataki led the Union's Conservative Party, and Kerry
led the Liberal Party but caused a rump faction to break off in
protest against his support of the Vietnam War. Lieberman, a law
student while I was at Yale, was in a separate tradition of News
chairmen with political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, was believed to have no political ambitions.
That memory came back two weeks ago, when about 18 of his
classmates held a kind of class reunion at the Republican
convention in Philadelphia. Everyone I talked to at the party was
both proud and amazed that he had become such an extremely
effective politician. In New Hampshire earlier this year, when I
caught up with Bush, I found myself saying to him that I simply
found it incredible that he was running for president. He laughed
and said that all his classmates had the same reaction, but that it
was absurd to say he never had any interest in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, I didn't go out and join the Conservative Party,''
he said, with that familiar trace of mockery toward the Political
Union. ``But I cared about politics. Look, I'm not saying that
being president of DKE qualifies me to be president. But it shows
that I do like to accomplish things and get people to do things. I
always did.''
</P>
<P>
   To me, in running a moral crusade, Bush seems more than ever
like the child of Yale in the 1960s that he says he never wanted to
be. It sounds strained, perhaps. But it is somehow reminiscent of
Yale in the '60s that on both sides its graduates are convinced
they are trying to save the nation's soul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
