<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIAZZA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PIAZZA, MVP TALK IS SOMETHING TO IGNORE
</HEADLINE>
  By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the sixth inning on Friday night, a chant began to
grow out of the stands as Mike Piazza stood in the batter's box.
The chorus of ``MVP! MVP!'' reverberated onto the field and Piazza
stepped out of the box, as if he could hide from the unwanted
attention.
</P>
<P>
   But the chant did not die down on Friday and it will likely
follow Piazza, deservedly if early, throughout the remaining six
weeks of the season. And the questions that came one after another
in the clubhouse, wondering whether he had heard the chant and what
he felt of his chances in the National League's MVP balloting, will
certainly intensify. Especially after a night like Friday, when he
once again provided the decisive blow, a two-run homer that started
the Mets to a 4-1 victory over the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza also looked as if he wanted to slip away from his crowded
locker and off into the night, off to any place where he would not
have to answer these questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flattering,'' Piazza said. ``What can you do? You just
want to play hard and just do the best you can. That's my
philosophy. Guys that have won the award, guys that lost the award,
or finished second, third, fourth, fifth, that's the philosophy you
have to have. You don't play to win that award. You play to win. If
the award comes your way, great. But you don't really go out there
thinking about it. If it has a way of just making the team better,
then great. If it fires everyone up, great. But I'm just like,
`Whatever.'''
</P>
<P>
   The chant did not grow just from another monstrous home run from
Piazza in this game, or as a reward for the 4-for-4 performance in
Houston on Thursday that had brought the Mets home from a
successful road trip. The chant could have begun building when
Piazza won the rookie of the year award in 1993, or at least since
he joined the Mets a little more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza has twice finished second in the MVP balloting, in 1996
and 1997. While he has not been able to capture the individual
honor, he has carved out a career that is certainly bound for
Cooperstown and the Hall of Fame, reaching 30 home runs this season
for the sixth consecutive year, a feat that no other catcher in
history has approached.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, he may be hard-pressed to be denied the award,
batting .349 with 31 home runs and 97 runs batted in. And while
there are still six weeks remaining in the regular season, it might
seem frightening to think that Piazza actually could just be
heating up. While injuries have limited him to 97 games this season
out of the first 114 the Mets have played, he has come back with
fresh legs and a torrid bat, batting .539 with two home runs and
four runs scored in the last three games through Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's been great all year,'' Bobby Valentine said. ``He's got
six more weeks of the regular season to give it his best, and he
gives his best every night. That's all we ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza said of the MVP chase: ``The few times I've been through
it before, I don't really think about it. You can't. You just go
out and do everything you can to help the ball club win. I finished
second twice. I was honored with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even say in those years that I was thinking about it.
That's just the way it is. You just play ball and help the team
win. When the team wins, you're going to reach your personal
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Piazza reaches toward those personal goals, helping
the Mets toward another playoff berth, the team's success could
figure in his chances. His competition could come from San
Francisco's Jeff Kent or St. Louis outfielder Jim Edmonds, both of
whose teams are in first place in their divisions right now. Among
the teams not in contention, Colorado's Todd Helton and Montreal's
Vladamir Guererro have the statistics to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A winning team usually gets it,'' Piazza acknowledged. ``But
like I said, you can't think about it. I mean, there's just so many
things, especially now with the time left. I'm definitely not
thinking about it. It's flattering to mention it now, but you still
have a lot of games left. You have to keep that in mind, just keep
pressing on and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza strained to try to remember if it was this way when he
was with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been the same, really,'' he said. ``Going back to
when I was rookie of the year, too, everyone was saying that you
have it already when it was just halfway through the season. I
didn't think about it. I just kept playing and tried to finish
strong and that's what I did. You can't dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza paused for a moment and added with a smile, ``How many
times did I say that?''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
