u f BC-UNMARRIED-REAL-NYT &LR;      08-12 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNMARRIED-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN UNMARRIED COUPLES SPLIT UP, WHAT ABOUT THEIR JOINT PROPERTY? 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Pina Olson and her life partner decided to buy a
Manhattan apartment together in October 1998, they put money aside
to hire a lawyer to draft an agreement that would spell out what
would happen in the unlikely event that they eventually parted. As
it turned out, Olson said, the agreement was never drafted.
</P>
<P>
   The couple moved into the apartment and lived together for a
little more than a year. Then the unlikely happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved out in December,'' Olson said. ``He still lives there,
but I'm still paying half the mortgage. I can't afford not to. If
he lets it go into default, it could ruin my credit for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson, of course, is not alone. In fact, real estate lawyers
say, while life partnerships have become an increasingly common
alternative to traditional marriage, those who buy property with a
significant other should be careful to attend to legal and
practical matters first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If two people are buying property together, and they're not
legally married, they almost always need to exert some effort to
protect themselves,'' said William H. Michelson, a Plainfield,
N.J., real estate lawyer who frequently represents gay, lesbian and
unmarried heterosexual couples. ``There are two basic problems they
have to prepare for. One is to decide what happens if one of them
dies, and the other is to decide what happens if they split up.''
</P>
<P>
   The first issue is relatively simple for married couples, he
said. They generally take title to property as ``tenants by the
entirety,'' a form of ownership _ available only to married couples
_ that results in title to the property passing automatically to
the surviving spouse when the other spouse dies.
</P>
<P>
   For an unmarried couple to achieve a similar result, Michelson
said, they must specifically state on the deed that they are taking
title as ``joint tenants with right of survivorship.'' With such a
form of ownership, he said, title passes to the surviving joint
tenant on the death of the other, achieving the same result that a
married couple would get with a tenancy by the entirety. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible, Michelson said, to pass title to property
into the name of a surviving unmarried partner by taking title as
``tenants in common'' _ whereby each partner owns a 50 percent
interest in the property _ and then drawing up wills that leave
each partner's share to the other upon death.
</P>
<P>
   Michelson cautioned, however, that buying property as tenants in
common can be tricky if the partners fail to execute wills naming
each as the beneficiary of the other, or if one or both of them
executes a will and then later changes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can end up with what I call `the wicked stepsister
syndrome,''' Michelson said, referring to the possibility that a
surviving partner may end up owning the property with a relative of
the deceased partner whose relationship with the survivor may be
strained or even hostile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once heirs have inherited a deceased partner's share they can
say, `We want the property sold,' and the surviving partner is
going to be hard-pressed to stop it,'' Michelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Even that may be easier than dealing with an ex-partner who is
still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you're buying a co-op, a condo, or a house, if you're
not husband and wife, the law looks at you as if you were joint
investors,'' said Stanley Simon, a Manhattan real estate lawyer.
``And smart investors always have written agreements governing
their investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon said that regardless of how title to property is held by
an unmarried couple, it is essential that the couple have an
agreement that addresses the issues that often arise when a
relationship sours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement can be as simple or as sophisticated as the
situation dictates,'' he said, adding that at the least the
partners should agree on a way to settle issues of ownership if
they disagree. For example, Simon said, an agreement should
establish the ground rules that would be used if one party wants to
buy out the other's interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to make sure that the partner who
is selling gets his or her name taken off the note and mortgage,''
he said, explaining that in most cases, the only way to do that is
for the remaining partner to refinance the mortgage and put it in
his or her name alone. Failure to do so, Simon said, can result in
one's credit rating being damaged if the partner who remains
responsible for paying the bills pays late or misses payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the bills get paid on time, the partner who left could
still have a hard time getting a mortgage on another house because
he or she is still obligated on the previous mortgage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement should also specify that if a buyout cannot be
accomplished without the selling partner being removed from the
note and mortgage, then the property must be put up for sale to a
third party.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Bohn, a Manhattan real estate lawyer, said that a
well-drafted property ownership agreement should specify how the
property is to be valued if one partner wants to buy the other's
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties can agree to use a mutually agreed upon
independent appraiser,'' Bohn said. ``Or, if they can't agree on
that, they can agree to each get their own appraiser and then use
the average of the two appraisals.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it is also important for property-ownership agreements
to contain an acknowledgment of each partner's respective
contributions to the property, including the original down payment,
improvements and repairs, and payments on the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   This is important because whenan unmarried couple splits up they
cannot go to a divorce court, which usually seeks an equitable
distribution of assets between divorcing couples. The unmarried
couple must instead file what is known as an action for partition _
a legal proceeding whereby a court orders the property sold and the
proceeds distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a divorce court, however, the court in a partition
proceeding will typically look to the actual contributions of the
respective parties in determining how the proceeds of the sale will
be divided.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that if one party contributes all the down payment,
makes all the repairs and improvements and pays all the mortgage
payments, there's a good chance that the other party isn't going to
end up with much in a partition action,'' Bohn said.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, he said, it is critical for unmarried partners who
own property to keep accurate records of each partner's respective
contributions over the years _ even if they have a
property-ownership agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, who has toyed with the idea of filing an action for
partition against her former life partner, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first split up we tried to sell the apartment on our
own,'' she said. ``We had these young couples in love coming in to
look at it, and some of them weren't married. I wanted to pull each
of those people aside and say: Whatever you do, make sure you have
an agreement drawn up. Don't be an idiot like me. It's too
expensive a lesson to learn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
