<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9810 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-EXCLUSIVE-ART-98     08-12 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EXCLUSIVE-ART-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HIS SPEECH, GORE TO SHIFT EMPHASIS TO HIS OWN AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Pa., Tenn.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore said Saturday that in his
acceptance speech to the Democratic National Convention he would
embrace President Clinton's success in presiding over the hardy
economy but send an unmistakable message that ``I'm running on my
own agenda, on my own voice and through my own experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first extensive interview previewing the address he will
give to the delegates on Thursday _ the most momentous of his
political career _ Gore said the speech at the Staples Center here
would be loaded with policy specifics because he wanted the public
to know he had a definite agenda to lead the country.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he would pledge to connect with the American public
as president by constantly holding ``town meetings'' with ordinary
citizens that would become ``a major theme of my presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would ``speak very concretely'' in outlining his
plan for cutting taxes for middle-class families and altering the
Social Security system, his championing of the environment and his
role ``in efforts to set time limits and reform welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I'm going to take the risk of going into
specifics,'' he said, ``is that I think people ought to know the
issues that are at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed that his decision to speak in great detail,
reminiscent of Clinton's policy-laden State of the Union messages,
was a gamble because ``the modern trend has been to resort to the
vaguest of generalities and not to challenge the audience with
specifics and hard substance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go along with that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made clear that his proposal for town meetings was intended
to help address what some of his advisers say has been his central
vulnerability: that he is not personally appealing to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the centerpiece of the way I conduct an open,
continuing, candid, no-holds-barred dialogue with the American
people throughout the Gore-Lieberman administration,'' said Gore,
who was known for holding endless public sessions when he was a
young congressman from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from Pittsburgh, where he was campaigning,
Gore said he welcomed the comments last week by Clinton that the
vice president should not be tarred with any scandals of the
Clinton years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate what the president said,'' Gore said. ``He
repeated what he said in the past and what many others have said:
This campaign is about the future.'' Dismissing worries among some
Democratic officials that Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton were
looming over the proceedings here and distracting attention from
him, Gore said, ``This election is about the future. It is about
the choice that has to be made between Governor Bush and myself.
Anyone who doubts that underestimates the desire of the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some Democrats here expressed concerns that the Clintons
have hardly slipped gently into the shadows as Gore's big week
approaches. Recognizing, perhaps, that he has dominated the
coverage in the run-up to the convention, Clinton abruptly canceled
several television interviews scheduled for this weekend. And White
House officials said they called off an interview with The New York
Times because they were furious about the newspaper's coverage of
how the Clintons are the headline attractions at fund-raising
events here that competed with Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   As delegates streamed into this city Saturday for their first
convention here since John F. Kennedy was nominated in 1960, their
overriding objective of the week was to name a ticket that would
continue eight years of their party's rule in the White House. But,
thus far, Clinton's long shadow has been the talk of the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Edward G. Rendell, the general chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, said in an interview that Clinton had resisted
a Monday night speaking slot here and tried to hold out for Tuesday
because he thought it was a bigger night. Rendell, the former mayor
of Philadelphia, said he had persuaded Clinton to settle on Monday
by telling him he would draw a larger audience than on Tuesday if
he delivered his address immediately after what would surely be a
highly rated Titans-Rams football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Look, we've got to get the maximum audience because
there's nobody alive who can better explain why Al Gore should be
president than you,' '' Rendell said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said it would not be fair to compare his task to that of
Vice President George Bush in 1988, who advisers said was
essentially offering himself as the steward of a third term of the
Ronald Reagan administration. Rather than merely continue with
Clinton's achievements, Gore said his message would be that he can
build upon the economic successes of the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role that I have played in helping to shape the policies
that have continued the economic progress will, by the time I speak
at the convention, be fairly well known and understood.'' He added,
``I will make a new start to include those who have not yet fully
enjoyed the benefits of the progress we have made and upon which I
can launch this new effort to connect the American people to the
full spirit of our democracy: the open meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers said his speech would be a pivotal moment in his
stepping out from Clinton's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would mention Clinton in his address, Gore replied:
``Sure. I will say that the last eight years have been years of
such remarkable economic progress and progress in lowering the
crime rate and welfare reform, in significant measure because of
his dedication to trying to create a better future.'' Yet Gore also
said he would put forth a new vision. ``He gave us a foundation
upon which I will build, upon which I will make a new start to
include those who have not yet fully enjoyed the benefits of the
progress we have made.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said that while he would make contrasts with
Gov. George W. Bush and Dick Cheney on policy, he intended to keep
his remarks upbeat. ``It will be positive, positive, positive,''
Gore said of the speech, which he drafted largely himself. ``And it
will describe a time of tremendous hope and possibility. There will
be no negative points about Governor Bush or Cheney, either overt
or covert, either direct or implied. There will be direct
comparisons of the approach Joe Lieberman and I take to the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   His pledge to stay positive in his speech, Gore insisted, was
not rooted in any concern that the Republicans would continue to
portray him as having a relentlessly negative campaign style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the American people are beginning to tune into this
dialogue, most of them for the first time,'' he said, ``it is
imperative that we elevate the tone of the campaign on both sides.
I think there's a willingness to do that on the other side. And I
hope the other side will see this convention and this speech as an
opening of opportunities for them as well as for us. The real
question is now what we get out of it. It's what the American
people get out of my speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's assurances, several Gore advisers and convention
officials said that while they were mindful that the program should
not appear harshly negative, some speakers would not shrink from
aggressively taking on Bush and the Republicans. The wide belief
among leading Democrats is that the sharp-edge remarks against
Democrats at the Philadelphia convention, particularly by Cheney,
gave them an excuse to fire back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they have a lot of credibility left on that
anymore,'' said Robert Shrum, one of Gore's top advisers. ``The
Cheney and Bush speeches had a personally negative tone. Secondly,
I think you can very respectfully discuss issues, and the
differences you have on issues. People don't see that as a negative
at all. They see that as something they're entitled to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Republicans might trap the Democrats by goading
them into lambasting Bush, and then condemning them as too
negative, Rendell said: ``They had a chance but they blew that on
Wednesday night. If they had run a sweetness and light convention
on Wednesday night, it would have been difficult for us. We would
have had to tread gingerly to even do issues comparatives without
seeming negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining how this convention would address pressing matters
like education and health care, Shrum ridiculed the largely cheery
and temperate convention stages of the Republicans, saying, ``Look,
we're not trying to run an ersatz variety show. We're trying to run
a convention that puts a person, in a very serious way, before the
American public.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview Saturday, Gore said he was intent on reaching
back _ to far before he became vice president _ for the public to
understand what motivated him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to know that the proposals I'm making for the
future are rooted in my 24-year fight for working families,'' he
said. ``I want them to know that my proposal for regular open
meetings as president is rooted in my experience in learning from
the working families for whom I fought for 16 years in the House
and Senate. I want them to know that my passion for protecting the
environment is rooted in the battle that I've waged for almost a
quarter century.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Los Angeles said they were bracing for a livelier,
and seemingly less disciplined, gathering than the Republican
convention in Philadelphia, in part, perhaps, because of the
questions about the Clintons hovering over the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster, said Gore had more to gain
_ and, maybe, to lose _ from the convention than his opponent
because as close as the polls are, Bush is now ahead, and the vice
president needs to scramble the dynamic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
