<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SWM-QUANN-850&AMP;ADD     08-12 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWM-QUANN-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUANN, 16, MOVING UP THE LIST AND TOWARD AN OLYMPIC MEDAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ On a closet door in her bedroom, 16-year-old
Megan Quann keeps a list of the world's fastest times in the
100-meter breaststroke. As she climbs the list, she crosses off one
time, then another.
</P>
<P>
   Each night as she goes to bed, Quann lies down with a stopwatch
and swims the perfect race in her head.
</P>
<P>
   She imagines herself in the waiting room with her competitors,
marching onto the pool deck, climbing onto the starting block,
leaning forward, legs bent in a sprinter's crouch. She starts the
clock and the race begins in her mind, stroke by stroke, the
bobbing torso and froglike kick, and when she hits the stop button,
she has broken the world record.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Heyns of South Africa, the 1996 Olympic champion, has swum
1 minute 6.52 seconds, swifter than anyone, but Quann imagines
going even faster this year, 1:05.49, or even 1:04.70. She is
impatient and bulletproof with youth, while Heyns has struggled
with her confidence and her stroke. The whispers say that Heyns may
not even compete next month at the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   If Heyns does show up, she will lose, Quann said Friday night
after winning the 100-meter breaststroke in 1:07.26 at the Olympic
trials. In Thursday's preliminaries, Quann swam 1:07.12, the
fastest time in the world this year and a U.S. record. She will be
the Olympic favorite in Sydney, and she has the predatory sense
that Heyns is uncertain, vulnerable. She speaks of the Olympic
champion as if she were a milk bottle in a midway game of softball
toss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's going down,'' Quann said of Heyns. ``She's 26 or
27. I'm 16. I'm going to race my heart out and I'm going to win
that gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Quann will be a junior this year at Emerald Ridge High School in
Puyallup, Wash. She is at an age where failure is unknown and
everything is possible. The American freestyle sprinters are in
their late 20s or early 30s, but many breaststrokers have not yet
been to the prom. The outward kicking motion of their specialty
requires great flexibility, and it is the young who are most pliant
in the hips and knees.
</P>
<P>
   Success comes fast and fleeting. Anita Nall set a U.S. record in
the 100 breaststroke at the 1992 Olympic trials and finished 38th
in the semifinals of the 2000 trials. At 14, Amanda Beard won the
trials in 1996 and took an Olympic silver medal. At 18, she
finished eighth, dead last, in Friday's 100-meter final.
</P>
<P>
   At the trials here four years ago, Beard carried a teddy bear on
the pool deck as a good luck charm. This year, she showed up with a
pierced tongue and punctured innocence. Success that early _ and
blazing and brief _ left her with a dislocating convergence of
celebrity, self-induced pressure and anticlimax.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all those people watching you at the Olympics, you put a
lot more pressure on yourself to live up to everybody's
expectations,'' Beard told a Los Angeles Daily News reporter at the
trials. ``Then you think they expect you to swim the way you did in
the Olympics every time you get in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Quann is not at that stage yet. She is naive and tunnel-visioned
and fearless. It is not arrogance or cockiness in her voice, her
mother said, but rather a belief that if she makes her goals
public, she will somehow achieve them. Megan has always been
competitive, Erin Quann said of her daughter. Once, on a family
cycling trip, she had to ride a single-speed bike and pedaled
furiously to keep up with the 10-speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants to be right in there,'' Erin Quann said. ``That's
her view of the universe: `If I put it out there and say it, it's
going to happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her taste for competition, Megan said, grew out of sibling
rivalry with her older brother Michael, who is 18. Her parents,
too, are athletic. Erin Quann was a classical ballet dancer who
received a scholarship to the Joffrey Ballet. Tom Quann, an
electrical engineer, played and coached water polo at Washington
State University. Megan tried ballet for a while _ she played a bon
bon in ``The Nutcracker'' _ but preferred the pool to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   As do other swimmers, Megan lives a life of rigorous discipline,
a certain obsessiveness always attendant to greatness. Pool time is
scarce in Puyallup, so she spends two to three hours a day
traveling to and from practice in a car or a swim club van. This
past school year, she was up at 4:30 a.m. for swim practice from 6
to 8 a.m., school from 9 a.m. to 1:30 p.m., gym training from 2 to
3 p.m. and swimming again from 6 to 8 p.m.. She swims about 15,000
yards a day; one day two years ago, she said she spent 11 hours in
the pool and swam 50,000 yards, a distance longer than a marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Quann does not get home until 9 p.m., having to eat
dinner and get to bed at 10 p.m. Last school year, to prepare for
the Olympics, she reduced her course load to four classes and used
her swimming to gain credit for physical education. The principal
required her to log 90 hours of training in a semester to qualify
for credit; she turned in 543 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the principal told her 90 hours, she kind of chuckled,''
Tom Quann said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Her parents say they have raised the proper caution flags on
this race toward a gold medal. They have hired a nutritionist to
monitor their daughter's diet. Erin Quann is herself a registered
nurse and massage therapist. Because Megan will miss six weeks of
class this fall to attend the Olympics, she took four courses this
summer, including calculus, to get a head start on her junior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to cover all the bases,'' Erin Quann said.
</P>
<P>
   With family hiking trips, movies, trips to the mall, she said,
Megan balances swimming with normal teen-age diversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want her to be as well-rounded as possible,'' Erin Quann
said. ``You've got to realize this is her passion. We haven't
pushed her. Swimming is something she wanted to do. When you have
that passion, we are not going to hold her back. You've got to let
everyone live their life and experience their passion.''
</P>
<P>
   The passion that comes from climbing into bed each night with a
stopwatch, swimming the perfect race in her head, hoping to
transfer that perfection from her mind to the pool in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of a race is self-confidence,'' Megan Quann
said. ``I do the work in practice. You have to be prepared. I'm
having so much fun. This is the time of my life. I've made it to
the Olympics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
