<SLUG> BC-NY-LIVERY-RAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVERY CAB DRIVER SUSPECTED OF SEXUAL ATTACKS IN QUEENS 
</HEADLINE>
  By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since last summer, a livery-cab driver has been
preying on women leaving Irish pubs in Queens and in Manhattan, the
police say, driving them to secluded spots in northern Queens,
where he rapes or sexually abuses them.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives identified a suspect in the attacks as Cesar Vicuna,
28, a citizen of Ecuador, and released his photograph on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the six assaults took place from July to October 1999.
The attacks apparently resumed July 8, and the latest was reported
on Aug. 6. That incident involved a 25-year-old woman, who hailed
and entered a white livery cab. While in the car, the woman fell
asleep. She woke up with the driver on top of her in the back seat,
where she was raped, detectives said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks all took place between 2:30 and 4 a.m. in various
locations in Queens, a short distance from most of the bars where
the women had been. The victims ranged in age from 23 to 31.
Several were raped, the police said, and at least two were punched
and kicked.
</P>
<P>
   At O'Malley's, an Irish pub where the police say Vicuna picked
up a victim last summer, customers were upset to hear that the
crimes had started again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I want to go home, I want to go home,'' said Allison
McGready, 28. ``The cabdrivers are in full control of the car. If
one of my drivers is a lunatic, how can I stop him?''
</P>
<P>
   At a strip of Irish pubs in Queens, many women expressed
concern. ``If you can't take a cab, what's the alternative?'' said
Yvonne Wood, 22, who was sitting next to her boyfriend in Donovan's
Pub. ``There is no alternative. I would think to take a cab before
I do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the block, a half-dozen livery cabs waited outside Sean
Ogs, a crowded bar. A woman said Vicuna's photograph had been taped
onto a wall in the women's room.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Santangelo, the bartender at Donovan's, said that the bar
usually called cabs for women, but would be doing that even more
often now.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have someone preying on young women at night out here like
this is completely disturbing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9818 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-WILLIAMS-NYT &LR;      08-12 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS IS IN A RACE TO GET BACK ON THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRAD SPURGEON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Ferrari and McLaren continue their battle for Formula One
supremacy at the Hungarian Grand Prix Sunday in Budapest, the two
teams threaten to lap the rest of the field. The gap between the
top two teams in the constructors' championship is the smallest it
has been at this point in the season in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari has 102 points, and McLaren is four points behind. The
third-place Williams team is another 76 points behind _ the biggest
gap between second and third at this stage in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just astonishing,'' said Frank Williams, owner of the
Williams team. ``And it burns us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is more astonishing because in the last 20 years, Williams
has won 16 of the 40 available constructors' and drivers' titles.
McLaren has won 16, while Ferrari and Benetton have three each and
Brabham 2.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to Williams?
</P>
<P>
   ``It has happened before,'' he said. ``It happens to everybody,
and when we do get to the top again, it will probably happen again.
That wicked word competition won't go away, and that's why we're
all here trying to beat each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has not won a race since Jacques Villeneuve won the
Luxembourg Grand Prix in September 1997; it is the longest period
without a victory in the team's history.
</P>
<P>
   While Williams has been involved in the sport since the 1960s,
he founded his current team in 1977 with Patrick Head, a part owner
and the technical director.
</P>
<P>
   Head says he thinks Williams, 58, can climb back. In addition to
being an astute businessman _ a necessity in today's Formula One _
Head said Williams was ``fundamentally an enthusiastic racer.''
</P>
<P>
   The icy look Williams is seen to wear on television as he
watches his drivers race may contribute to his reputation for being
hard on drivers. But the team's titles, nine for the constructors
and seven for the drivers, also reflect his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   At McLaren, under the direction of Ron Dennis, who has a
reputation among his drivers for benevolence, the numbers are the
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said his reputation came largely because twice in the
1990s, he dropped drivers the year they won the world championship.
The contracts of Nigell Mansell and Damon Hill had ended, he said,
and they had asked to be paid too much.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that he had great admiration for drivers while
they were on the track, which comes through when he talks about the
one he admired the most of those who drove for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alain Prost never ever went quicker than he had to,'' Williams
said. ``Once or twice he had to push himself on qualifying. And
while he was always very smooth, his car, you could see it, was
dancing. It was just hanging onto the road and it was fuss-free.
When he was on, he was devastating. He had some deficiencies, but
very, very clever. And gifted.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was talking in the Grand Prix paddock in Spielberg,
Austria, propped up to a standing position in his extendible
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1986, while driving to the airport from the Castellet
circuit in the south of France, Williams lost control of his car
and had an accident that left him paralyzed from the waist down,
and with little use of his arms or hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before my accident, I was extremely energetic physically and I
was ubiquitous within the company and within the paddock,''
Williams said, his words coming out quietly and, as always, with
the appearance of great physical effort.
</P>
<P>
   He missed the 1986 season, but the team won the constructors'
title, and in 1987, when he returned, it won both titles with the
driver Nelson Piquet.
</P>
<P>
   Then followed a period of rebuilding as the team began a
relationship with Renault, which became one of the most successful
in the sport. They won the constructors' title five times in the
1990s. The team also won the drivers' title in 1992 and 1993 with
Mansell and then Prost.
</P>
<P>
   Tragedy struck in 1994 when Ayrton Senna, who had just joined
the team, was killed at the San Marino Grand Prix at Imola, the
season's third race. Williams and Head were charged with
manslaughter by the Italian justice system, which claimed the car
was faulty. After five years, they were exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Williams won the constructors' championship in the tumultuous
year of Senna's death with Hill and David Coulthard driving. Then,
in 1996 and 1997, Williams won both titles, with Hill and
Villeneuve.
</P>
<P>
   The team then lost its designer, Adrian Newey _ who joined
McLaren and designed that team's championship-winning cars of the
last two years _ and its engine supplier. This year Williams joined
up with BMW, the German engine constructor, which returns to the
sport after a 12-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll all take longer than people would like,'' Williams said.
``When it is firing on all 10 cylinders again, we will be a serious
team. Time frame, one year, two years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
