<HEADER>
A9824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DUMP-VOICES-NYT &LR;      08-12 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DUMP-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINHAUER  
</HEADLINE>
  
 OH, BABY, HAVE WE GOT PLANS FOR THIS OLD DUMP, OR WHAT? By JENNIFER c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Given enough time, fantasies about the Fresh Kills
landfill on Staten Island could overtake one's life. The space has
housed a garbage dump for 52 years, but in January the landfill is
supposed to close, and public officials, college professors and
Staten Islanders have been embroiled in debates over what to do
with the 3,000 acres left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Guy V. Molinari, the borough's president, has asked traffic
consultants to submit plans for a new highway, which would connect
to existing roads used by trash trucks, to ease congestion.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't a new roadway a little uninspired? And all the chatter
about public parks and ballfields is earnest and fine, but the city
already has a lot of those.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, how about a giant center devoted to a specific,
underappreciated art form _ say, ``Riverdance''? Or what about one
big storage space, where all New Yorkers could, for a small fee,
house all the stuff kept in what most Americans commonly refer to
as the hall closet?
</P>
<P>
   Or a giant television studio, perhaps for exclusive use by all
those really bad shows that revolve around the antics of freakishly
thin women who live in huge apartments with kitchen islands?
</P>
<P>
   There is the small problem of potential toxins _ the Sanitation
Department is required to monitor the site for 30 years after it
closes before houses can be built and people can actually live
there. But what if that problem suddenly went away? What would New
Yorkers dream of for Fresh Kills (outside of a more inviting name),
if all impediments, including horrific emissions, were somehow
removed?
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Sexton, president of the Times Square Business
Improvement District, said: ``Something many people don't know
about Fresh Kills is that hundreds of acres of it have never been
touched. At roughly four times the size of Central Park, it is a
huge, huge opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexton is on the board of the Municipal Arts Society, which is
sponsoring an international design competition to ponder these very
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Some would-be urban planners, when posed the question, demurred
_ Conan O'Brien, for example, does not do landfills, his publicist
said. Joey Buttafuco was dying to comment, his spokeswoman said,
but he had never heard of Fresh Kills.
</P>
<P>
   But here are what others who have given the issue some thought
would love to see on the Fresh Kills site of the future:
</P>
<P>
   Clark Wolf, restaurant consultant: ``A road is a boring idea. It
would be so wonderful to have organic teaching gardens, where
culinary students could see what comes from the earth. There would
be all kinds of flowers and trees and plants, but all of them
edible. And there is nothing better than compost for produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Hardin, senior vice president for creative brand management
at Saks Fifth Avenue: ``I think it is a tremendous opportunity for
a day prison for cell phone abusers. It is so well deserved for
those who use them on trains and restaurants. All we need is for
the mayor to empower us all to make citizen's arrests, and then we
would send them there. I bet you people will learn to stop this
heinous abuse,'' like the man on a commuter train he heard
hammering out divorce terms with his wife on his mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rosenberg, managing director of the Drama Department, a
theater company: ``I am seeing a giant amusement park. Instead of a
tunnel of love, there would be a tunnel of trash. The roller
coaster would go over all the stuff that people once threw away.
There would be carnival games, where people pull the bottle up from
a trash heap, or throw baseballs to break dishes. A community
garden would be sweet. But no.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Roldan, artist: ``A giant new museum for new artists _ of
course including myself _ changing every season to reflect the
weather. It would show the people in the world that New York art
can be about more than Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Liebman, chief executive of the Corcoran Group, a real
estate brokerage: ``Staten Island's newest golf course _ with
diaper ditch and trash traps. Or maybe there could be a Chelsea
Piers of Staten Island. You know, something fabulously athletic!''
</P>
<P>
   Leo Bennett, bartender at Gallagher's Steak House on West 52nd
Street: ``No more tract homes. Staten Island has enough of those. I
would like a park, like Central Park, but no zoo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
