<HEADER>
A9852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-BUSH-POLLS-NYT &LR;      08-12 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-POLLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW TUNED IN, BUT POLL SHOWS CONVENTION STILL HELPED BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even though few Americans watched two hours or
more of the Republican National Convention, a new study shows that
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas succeeded in increasing awareness that
he favors a bigger tax cut than does Vice President Al Gore and
wants prescription drugs available to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Polling conducted after the convention for the Annenberg Public
Policy Center at the University of Pennsylvania found that only
about one American in five watched two hours or more of the
convention, while 67 percent said they watched a few minutes or
none at all.
</P>
<P>
   But the combination of television watching and other news
coverage increased the knowledge of some of Bush's positions.
</P>
<P>
   Before the convention, 54 percent of the public identified Bush
as the presidential candidate who ``favors the biggest tax cut.''
After the convention, that reached 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also before the convention, 25 percent knew that Bush favored
providing vouchers to defray some of the costs of prescription
drugs for the elderly. After the convention, 31 percent said the
Republican nominee did.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also succeeded in communicating a message about Gore.
Before the Republican convention, 39 percent knew that Gore opposed
allowing workers to invest some of the Social Security taxes in the
stock market _ something Bush favors. Knowledge of Gore's position
reached 44 percent after the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But the public learned one thing that Bush may not have
intended. Although only two speakers all week used the word
abortion, the percentage of the public that said Bush wanted to
make it harder for women to get abortions increased from 52 percent
to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, director of the Annenberg center and of
its yearlong project involving about 100,000 polling interviews on
Americans' political opinions, cited this finding in particular as
evidence that news coverage and not just the convention itself
helped people learn about the candidates. Abortion figured heavily
in coverage of the Republican platform in the days before the
convention and when the platform was adopted on the first day.
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson said the increases in knowledge extended to people who
did not usually pay attention to politics. ``The convention may not
have reached many Americans directly,'' she said, ``but the event
did stimulate many to pay attention to the presidential campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
