 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Saturday, August 12, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file or has filed these stories for
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis at
213-336-1800. or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   (All sluglines include the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CONVENTION-RDP (Los Angeles) _ As the Democrats prepare to
open their first presidential nominating convention in Los Angeles
since John F. Kennedy was picked here in 1960, party leaders are
measuring how much distance President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore should seek to put between them. Obviously, Gore wants credit
for the robust economy but nothing to do with the impeachment
scandal. Picking and choosing could be difficult. Meanwhile, Rep.
Loretta Sanchez is back on the convention program after agreeing to
drop plans for a fundraiser at the Playboy Mansion. Party leaders,
nervous about any hint of salaciousness, has pressed her to find
another site. By DAN FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CELL-PHONE-PRIVACY (Washington) _ In what privacy rights
advocates say is a significant threat to civil liberties in the
digital age, the FBI may soon be able to turn the cellular phone
into a ready-made tool for nosing around in private lives. If a
federal rule stands up to a court challenge here, f ederal and
state law enforcement agencies will be allowed to track a cell
phone user's location while monitoring bank and data transactions
made with the device _ all without the need for a court-ordered
wiretap. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
