<HEADER>
A9855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-ETTLINGER-NYT &LR;      08-12 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ETTLINGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON ETTLINGER, 86, SCRIPTWRITER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif., Mich., Ill.)   By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Ettlinger, a writer for film, television and theater, died
Monday at a hospital in Nyack, N.Y. He was 86 and lived in Pomona,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Ettlinger was born in Detroit and attended Stanford University
and the University of Chicago. While still an undergraduate, he was
hired by 20th Century Fox in Hollywood and, at 21, became one of
the youngest contract writers on the Fox lot.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ettlinger's early projects, written with Karl Tunberg,
was the 1938 film ``Rebecca of Sunnybrook Farm,'' starring Shirley
Temple. With Tunberg, Ettlinger also wrote ``Shipyard Sally''
(1940), which was based on a story by Gracie Fields, Tom Geraghty
and Val Valentine, and was a writer of ``The Great American
Broadcast'' (1941).
</P>
<P>
   In World War II, Ettlinger was in the Army Signal Corps,
stationed in Astoria, Queens, where he made secret Army training
films. After the war, he wrote for radio, including the
long-running crime show, ``The FBI in Peace and War.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of television, Ettlinger worked for Studio One
and Kraft Television Theater. He was also a writer on the series
``Mama,'' which starred Peggy Wood. Some of the episodes were
written with his wife, Katrina Ettlinger, who survives him. He also
wrote scripts for soap operas, including ``Love of Life'' and ``The
Secret Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   With Anna Marie Bartow, Ettlinger wrote the libretto for
``Ambassador,'' a Broadway musical adaptation of Henry James' novel
``The Ambassadors,'' which starred Howard Keel and Danielle
Darrieux.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by his daughters, Keren
Saks of New York City and Victoria Ettlinger of Shokan, N.Y.; a
son, Mark, of Los Angeles; and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
