<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HAITIAN-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAITIANS CRY `ASSASSIN' OUTSIDE HOUSE IN QUEENS
</HEADLINE>
 By   AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ High-pitched wails and angry shouts pierced the damp
quiet of a Queens neighborhood Saturday morning as about 30 people
gathered at the home of a former paramilitary leader from Haiti to
protest his presence in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the white stucco house where the former leader, Emmanuel
Constant, has lived on and off since 1994, several women shouted
``Assassin'' and ``Murderer.'' They shook and gyrated and bent to
the ground, watched by police officers in a van and on the
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toto is a criminal,'' the women shouted, using the name by
which Constant, the former leader of the right-wing Front for the
Advancement and Progress of Haiti, is commonly known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must go,'' the crowd responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to give up,'' said Mimose Lambert, one of the
women leading the chanting. Constant's group has been accused of
killing and torturing thousands of supporters of Jean-Bertrand
Aristide in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of Haitian and human rights groups has tried to
persuade the U.S. government to extradite Constant to Haiti for
trial. And this is not the first such protest demanding his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Outrage at his presence in a mostly Caribbean neighborhood
prompted the Immigration and Naturalization Service to detain him
for a year. He was abruptly released in 1996, raising suspicions
that Constant, who has said he was a paid informer for the CIA,
struck a deal with the U.S. government: his freedom for his
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Florestal, 64, a host of Radio Soleil d'Haiti, a station
in New York, said Constant's life of relative impunity symbolized
the way the United States had too often treated Haiti and its
people. Without accountability for those who tortured, maimed,
terrorized and then fled to exile, Florestal said, the victims
could not heal.
</P>
<P>
   Later, about 20 protesters walked to Rigaud Realty, where
Constant has been employed as a licensed real estate broker. They
carried posters of Constant in a suit and tie flashing the victory
sign, and they were trailed by six cars, including one with a
poster showing a body by a pool of water and a message that the
dead person was a victim of Constant's group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame, shame, shame on you, Rigaud,'' the protesters shouted
outside the Realtor's office. The owner, Patrick Rigaud, was inside
but would not comment. A worker said Constant had not been there in
three or four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the protesters suddenly began chasing a car that
they said was driven by a man who had just threatened that he would
``be back to take care of'' them because they supported Aristide,
the priest and former Haitian president who was ousted in a coup in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Constant is not the only Haitian with ties to the country's
repressive past believed to be living in Queens. At one point
during the protest, outside Constant's home, members of the crowd
spotted a man they said had been a senator in Haiti during the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criminal,'' they yelled. ``Criminal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
