<SLUG> BC-BOATING-COUPLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAVERICK COUPLE CHRONICLE THEIR CRUISING VENTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1969, when Lin and Larry Pardey set out from Southern
California aboard the 24-foot Seraffyn, their engineless self-built
wooden cutter, they traveled on the winds of modest expectations.
``We'd never had a reasonable holiday in our working lives and we
just wanted to do something that was all about sailing,'' Larry
said. ``The thought of cruising around Mexico for a few months with
time off was just cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, the act of sailing _ and the art of
chronicling their adventures _ remains the axis around which the
Pardey's peripatetic lifestyle spins. With 11 books and four videos
to their credit and more than 100,000 miles of voyaging behind
them, Larry, 60, and Lin, 56, show no signs of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started out our motto was `As long as it's fun,''' Lin
said. ``I guess now it's `As long as we're able.' But we're still
having these crazy experiences and they're always different.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Pardeys slipped into Newport, R.I., on the
29-foot-6-inch Taleisin, which Larry built from teak and black
locust, and which the couple moved aboard in 1983. Having left the
sweltering Chesapeake Bay about a month before, the Pardeys swung
north using one of the basic guidelines that is crucial to all
their routing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't like it there,'' Larry said. ``Too hot. And we'd
been invited to a classic-boat rendezvous in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we took off and brought our home with us. How many people
can do that?''
</P>
<P>
   The Pardeys have been an inspiration to plenty of neophyte
voyagers. But their devotion to ultrasimple, cost-conscious
voyaging has also been ripe for both lampooning and criticism,
particularly from those who believe cruising boats must be equipped
with hefty diesel engines and copious electronics. ``Well, we see a
lot of people out there who spend all their time fixing their
refrigeration and stuff,'' Larry said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pardeys' writing career started when, in the early '70s and
anchored with Seraffyn among a dozen similarly modest boats near
the Panama Canal, Lin read a magazine article that stated the
perfect size for a cruising boat was 57 feet. In anger, she zipped
off a rebuttal letter. It led to the birth of a career that has
financed countless adventures.
</P>
<P>
   And Larry insists it was economics, not philosophy, that led
them to sail Seraffyn without an engine, a practice they have
continued with Taleisin. ``When we first set off we could live in
Mexico for $200 a month,'' he said. ``The way we looked at it, a
$3,000 engine cost 14 months of freedom. We never dreamed of going
cruising and being comfortable, we just dreamed of going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pardeys also have some steadfast opinions on the state of
long-distance voyaging. For navigation they carry two sextants but
forgo Global Positioning System navigation, which most mariners
insist is a necessity for contemporary cruising. And they believe
that many sailors, especially inexperienced ones, are being subtly
coerced into buying equipment they do not need.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put the word safety on some of this gear and it's like
saying the word motherhood; it's sacred,'' said Lin, who knows that
her views are controversial. ``So, some sailors can't figure out
what they need and what they don't need. And they don't set out
until they buy all the so-called safety gear they can find.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening is that people aren't being told to learn the
necessary skills to give them confidence, to learn how exciting and
safe and maneuverable a sailboat can be,'' she said. ``An extra
block and tackle to rig a preventer on the boom, a spare halyard, a
kerosene lamp if you lose electric power _ that's safety gear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pardeys are also not fans of the long-distance cruising
rallies that have become so popular in the last decade, in which
groups of boats _ for a fee _ travel the globe in packs for
security and companionship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine, but a lot of these people are in such a hurry
that they're irresponsible,'' Larry said. They get someplace, drop
the anchor and go ashore for a guided tour. Their boats are
unattended and if they drag anchor and hit someone, it's no big
deal. They have insurance. But it's a problem for the people they
run into.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, as they ease closer toward retirement age, if not spirit,
the Pardeys find themselves working about six months a year and
traveling for the balance. They are also involved in charity work
on the Chesapeake Bay, and will open their simple, remarkable boat
to the public during the U.S. Sailboat Show in Annapolis, Md., in
early October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
