<SLUG> BC-MEGAMALL-ATTRACTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPER COUNTS ON HUGE MALL TO DRAW TOURISTS (AND MONEY) TO
SYRACUSE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.Y., Tenn., Minn., Maine, Mo.)  By LESLIE EATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In many parts of the country, a proposal for a super-duper
tourist-attracting mega-mall would be greeted with howls of
protest, followed by reams of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Not in Syracuse, N.Y., where many people are embracing the mall
plan as a way to save their ailing city. Their praise, however, is
less enthusiastic than resigned; a popular sign at a public hearing
last month was, ``Do You Have a Better Alternative?''
</P>
<P>
   The mall could well become the largest shopping center in the
country. Its developers, the Pyramid Management Group, plan to
triple the size of their existing mall, the Carousel Center, and
turn it into 103 acres of stores, entertainment outlets, with
hotels, restaurants and even an aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   The current 1.6 million-square foot mall would be expanded to
4.5 million square feet; the leader in the enormous mall
sweepstakes, Mall of America outside Minneapolis, is 4.2 million
square feet, although there are plans to expand it, too. But
metropolitan Minneapolis is four times the size of Syracuse, which
has a population of only 735,000 (and fewer than 390,000 within 10
miles of the mall, while Mall of America has more than 900,000).
Minneapolis is also far more prosperous. The average household
income around the Mall of America is about $66,000, compared with
about $47,000 for households near the Carousel Center, according to
data from the International Council of Shopping Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of malls, full of movie theaters, skating rinks and other
attractions, are in the works across the country, the council
reports, but none as big as the one proposed for Syracuse. And,
almost all are being built in booming areas.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse has only recently emerged from a decadelong recession.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mall's supporters concede that Syracuse seems an
unlikely place for a mammoth mall. ``Intuition tells you this isn't
going to be that great,'' said Vito Sciscioli, the commissioner of
economic development for the city, from which the developers are
seeking tax breaks for the $900 million project. But, he said,
consultants hired by the city to evaluate the plan told him,
``You've got a hot one here.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Tourists. The mall's backers believe that millions
of tourists will go to the center, bringing lots of cash into
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Luring them, the developers say, will be stores with outdoor
themes, catering to hunters, campers and fishermen. After all, L.L.
Bean draws hordes to Freeport, Maine, and the Bass Pro Shop is
``the largest tourist attraction in the state of Missouri,'' said
Bruce A. Kenan, a partner at Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists do seem to visit giant malls, especially those that
bill themselves as theme parks. Opry Mills, which opened in
Nashville in May and attracted 100,000 people on its first day,
says that about 30 percent of its visitors are not from Tennessee.
Foreign tourists account for more than 5 percent of the visitors to
Mall of America.
</P>
<P>
   Developers must court travel agents and tour operators and
travel writers, however. They spend a lot to attract people, said
Therese Byrne, who writes the newsletter Retail Maxim. ``Is Pyramid
set up to do that?'' she asked. She added that she was a little
dubious of the hunting and fishing theme, noting that 80 percent of
shoppers are women.
</P>
<P>
   The developers themselves concede that were they not based in
Syracuse, they would not be pursuing the mega-mall project. ``If
you didn't have the emotional attachment, you wouldn't do it,''
Kenan said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment may help Pyramid calm fears expressed at the
public hearing and in letters to the Syracuse newspapers that the
mall expansion will be a windfall for Robert J. Congel, Pyramid's
founder.
</P>
<P>
   The developers said they would expand the mall in stages, with
construction beginning next spring. They say that the current mall
is already drawing 17 million visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   The mall sits on the site of an old junkyard, an area where in
the last century, water from saline springs evaporated. The land is
still so marshy that the mall does not sit on pilings but actually
floats on the soupy ground; water is pumped in or out to keep it
stable.
</P>
<P>
   Pyramid, which pays almost no real estate taxes now, has asked
Syracuse to defer levying any such taxes for 30 years. The
developer would then make payments in lieu of taxes to pay off
tax-exempt bonds, which would finance road improvements and parking
garages. Mayor Roy Bernardi and the developers have agreed on the
deal, which is now under consideration by city and county
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Syracuse have suggested that that the city would do
better to grab the real estate taxes on the current mall, rather
than give them up for three decades to help finance a bigger mall.
``Their gut reaction is that we need more property taxes to pay the
bills,'' said Minchin G. Lewis, the city auditor.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the city would get relatively little money from the
mall's property taxes, but quite a lot from sales taxes, and could
get a lot more if the mall succeeds. ``The city's being asked to
give the developer a baseball bat and hope it hits a home run,'' he
said. ``If it strikes out, we don't lose anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
