<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COLUMN-EYES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE NEW MILLENNIUM FASHION QUESTION _ `WHO DOES YOUR
EYES?' 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERGENFIELD, N.J. _ The wall is hung with pictures of the
near-famous. Newscaster Jack Ford. Yankees coach Lee Mazzilli.
Radio host Bob Grant. Golfer Jim McLean. Radio disc jockey Dan
Neer. You almost expect to see a Jackie Mason publicity shot
inscribed, ``Love That Corned Beef!!!''
</P>
<P>
   But this is no delicatessen. The menu here is all corneas. This
is the New Jersey Eye Center, home of the laser-wielding Dr. Joseph
Dello Russo, the used-eyes-made-new alchemist whose copious
advertising has helped foster one of the most surprising
developments in modern medicine: the celebrity ophthalmologist.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not since the proctologist Jeffrey LaVigne plastered New
York subways with advertisements to call 1-800-MD-TUSCH have
doctors made such a spectacle of themselves. But it is fitting.
Laser surgery has all the requisite postmodern elements _
technology, a quick fix, a sense of new beginnings, low risk. So
why not celebrity?
</P>
<P>
   Just recently, Dello Russo operated on Ford live on ``Good
Morning America.'' ``I was talking back and forth with Diane
Sawyer,'' the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   His waiting room is full of ecstatic former four-eyes. ``Every
decade has its thing,'' said Wayne Kessler, 25, after emerging from
the much-advertised ``flying spot laser.'' ``The '70s was bell
bottoms. The new millennium is getting your eyes done.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dello Russo, the late '70s and the '80s were about cataract
surgery, and lots of it. ``He was a big cutter,'' says Stephanie
Waterman, his marketing director and wife. But reimbursement rates
fell, and when doctors began correcting vision with lasers in the
early '90s, Dello Russo's office was an early test site. Like other
independent ophthalmologists, he now charges up to $5,500 for both
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   With new technology simplifying surgery and lowering risk, and
the country flush with disposable income, you can hardly turn on a
radio or open a newspaper without encountering a laser surgeon. It
might be Dello Russo, or Dr. Eric Mandel, talking about his laser
work at Harvard, or Bernie Williams touting Dr. Ken Moadel.
</P>
<P>
   It makes some ophthalmologists cringe. You don't hear it from,
say, plastic surgeons. ``Nobody says, `I do the perfect noses,' or
`I went to Dr. Miller and he gave me the cutest nose and the most
perfect nostrils,''' said Paul Orloff, a past president of the New
York State Ophthalmological Society.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, there is friction among laser luminaries. Dello Russo
said he started advertising so heavily because he was irked by
Mandel's ads about his role in laser research. ``Despite him, the
laser was developed,'' Dello Russo said. Mandel, who did have a
fellowship at Harvard, said Dello Russo's ``claim to fame is he
bought the first laser.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctors are trying to polish their credentials before the
business is swallowed by clinics that zap eyes for as little as
$999 each. ``Everyone's looking for a piece of the laser market,''
Dello Russo said. ``You need a hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Moadel got his by operating on Bernie Williams between his
fabulous 1999 season and his more fabulous current season. Williams
now endorses Moadel in advertisements, for which Moadel says he
pays a ``token amount'' that is ``less than a day's pay'' for
Williams. The center fielder makes $12.5 million a year for 162
games, so a day's pay is real money, even for a laser surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Every doctor has his big-name patients. ``We do a lot of
doctors,'' Mandel said. ``I did an obstetrician yesterday. I did a
cardiologist last week. I did a Knick last week.'' Soon, Kurt
Thomas is on the phone, reporting: ``I can read license plates! I
can see people's facial expressions!''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees general manager, Brian Cashman, praises the surgery,
which he said Dello Russo performed free in exchange for using
Cashman's name to promote his practice. Neer, the DJ, said that he
also got free surgery from Dello Russo, in exchange for reading an
ad on air, and that several relatives followed him as paying
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dello Russo says his advertising campaign, which his wife
estimates costs ``several million'' dollars a year, is intended to
emphasize his experience. He has a new office in New York and will
soon open a bigger one in Bergenfield.
</P>
<P>
   Where does it all end? ``I'm intensely goal-oriented,'' Dello
Russo said. He's setting things up for his three sons _ two are in
medical training and one is considering it.
</P>
<P>
   So, with all due respect to Mandel and Moadel, we're looking at
Dello Russos for as far as the eye can see. Which these days seems
like forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
