<HEADER>
A9877 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NYC-REAL-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      08-12 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON 14TH STREET, LESS GRIT, MORE GLAMOUR
</HEADLINE>
  By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a city where the names of some neighborhoods
bestow cachet and some addresses are dropped like royal titles,
14th Street in Manhattan has probably never achieved even a minor
peerage.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind, says Gary Gaines, an importer who is about to trade
in an apartment off Sutton Place for a loft in the Greenwich, a
cavernous former department store at 14th Street and Avenue of the
Americas. He has bought 2,150 square feet of finished but
unpartitioned space on the third floor.
</P>
<P>
   Gaines' neighbors at the Greenwich will include other migrants
from uptown, among them Brian Brooks, who sold his apartment at the
venerable Beresford on Central Park West, and Joel Solomon, who
lives on the Upper East Side at 80th Street and Third Avenue.
Solomon bought a loft for his 25-year-old son, Stephen, and a
penthouse for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will miss the seclusion and seeing Bobby Short in my
elevator,'' Gaines said, ``but I like living in the new, being part
of something happening. Fourteenth Street is on the threshold of a
major transformation, and this building is at its center.''
</P>
<P>
   People already living on or near 14th Street would probably say
that it has already crossed that threshold, starting with the
city's $3.6 million reconstruction of Union Square Park in 1983 and
the 1987 opening of the Zeckendorf Towers, a 652-apartment
condominium and office complex.
</P>
<P>
   But subsequent and future projects give weight to Gaines' notion
that another threshold has been reached.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of change are noticeable from the western end of the
street at least as far east as First Avenue, where Stuyvesant Town
dominates the landscape. (Even there, new fencing and ornamental
gate posts are planned, and new trees are to be planted.)
</P>
<P>
   These changes are giving 14th Street a new persona as a
residential boulevard, a booming retail thoroughfare and a mecca
for high-tech enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   At the western side, near 10th Avenue, art galleries, trendy
restaurants, late-night clubs and one of the city's highest-fashion
emporiums are bringing elegance and verve to the gritty
meat-packing district.
</P>
<P>
   From Eighth to Fifth avenues, new technology and dot.com
companies are clamoring for space, joining the publishers,
photographers, graphic designers and advertising agencies already
encamped there. An eyesore was removed recently when the long-empty
14th Street Armory was torn down earlier this year to make way for
two new apartment towers and a YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   On the east side of the street, further improvements are planned
for Union Square Park. The city has earmarked $2.5 million to
expand the park by 20,000 square feet at its southwest corner
between 14th and 15th streets.
</P>
<P>
   East of the park, New York University is expanding its domain,
constructing a 16-story dormitory on the site of the old Palladium
nightclub. The new building is two doors away from a 19-story NYU
dorm completed two years ago. The university has also signed a
lease for a 14-story building being put up by Alex Forkosh, a
developer, on the site of former Sahara Hotel, once a notorious
single-room-occupancy hotel and drug haven at 14th Street and Third
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   David Gmach, the executive director of both the 14th
Street-Union Square Business Improvement District and the 14th
Street-Union Square Local Development Corp., considers the
conversion of the Sahara and the demolition of the 14th Street
Armory, both of which were symptomatic of decay, to be hallmarks of
the changes that have swept across the entire street.
</P>
<P>
   Where the armory stood between Avenue of the Americas and
Seventh Avenue, two residential towers will be developed by Orda
Management Corp. and Related Companies. One will contain 60 luxury
condominiums for NYU faculty members; the other will be a rental
with 225 units, 20 percent of which will be reserved for low-income
tenants. The McBurney YMCA will occupy two floors at the base of
the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if you could find another single street
with that much going on in a two-to-three-year period,'' Gmach said
during a recent walk from 10th Avenue to Avenue B. ``There is at
least 1 million square feet of development that has either been
recently completed or is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as any artery in the city, 14th Street, which is the
dividing line between Chelsea and Greenwich Village and also
borders the Flatiron district and the Ladies Mile Historic
District, has flourished and withered and then flourished again.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, it was the cultural and political epicenter of
the city: The Academy of Music, vaudeville theaters and Tammany
Hall were all thriving. Before the rise of Fifth Avenue as a
commercial hub, 14th Street was a retail center, housing the early
quarters of Macy's, Tiffany's and Best &AMP; Co. When those stores
moved uptown, bargain emporiums like S. Klein and J.W. Mays set the
tone for the area.
</P>
<P>
   Then about 35 years ago, the area began to slide into
deterioration, its middle-class shops shuttered or replaced by
cut-rate stores with flashy merchandise displayed on the sidewalk.
Union Square became a magnet for drug dealers and derelicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mays went out, the recession came in, and so did the
junkies,'' said Alex Barbagianis, an owner of Ariston Florist,
which moved to 14th Street and Fifth Avenue nine years ago after 16
years in a location a block to the west. ``You could buy any kind
of dope here, and we had a tough time.''
</P>
<P>
   Then several significant changes took place, and a turnaround
seemed possible. The Union Square Greenmarket was established in
1976, the city refurbished the park, and Zeckendorf Towers opened
on the site of the former S. Klein store at Union Square East.
</P>
<P>
   As Chelsea became gentrified, lower Fifth Avenue acquired
national retailers and chic shops, and stores like Bed Bath &AMP;
Beyond and Barnes &AMP; Noble moved to the southern end of Avenue of
the Americas, it became all but inevitable that 14th Street would
be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``If Times Square is the crossroads of the world, then 14th
Street is the crossroads of New York, because it's where uptown and
downtown come together as a 24-hour community where people both
live and work,'' said Gmach, the BID executive. ``Everything New
Yorkers could want is at their fingertips. There is a blend of
activities and diversity here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although that assessment is widely shared, many would also agree
that 14th Street is a work in progress, and more remains to be done
to elevate it to first-class status. Some developers of residential
property, for example, still insist on giving their buildings
addresses on 13th or 15th streets. Mosbacher Properties, the
developer of the Greenwich, for example, plans to put the entrance
on 13th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteenth Street is one of the last major crosstown streets
in the city to undergo improvement,'' said David Schore, the
president of Mark Holdings, which recently bought the building at
25 W. 14th Street. ``Fifty-Seventh Street was always great, and
42nd and 34th now have a lot of new retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   If he were to measure, he said, ``Forty-Second Street is 90
percent done, 34th is 50 percent done, and 14th is 50 percent done.
There are still a lot of 99-cent and electronics stores, and those
will be squeezed out by higher rents and hopefully higher-rent
retailers. It will never be an upper Madison Avenue, but it could
be a healthy extension of lower Fifth Avenue with a lot of national
chains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
