<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LIEBERMAN-HOLOCAUST-A     08-12 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-HOLOCAUST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDACY BRINGS CHILDREN OF HOLOCAUST SURVIVORS TO THE FORE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Mass., Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They came over on merchant ships, refugees with a few valises
apiece that contained all in the world they owned.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding from scratch _ they had, after all, lost their homes
and most of their closest kin _ they worked at low-paying jobs in
dingy dress factories, luncheonettes, dry-goods stores. For many,
it was too late for any grander aspirations. Their children would
redeem their shattered lives.
</P>
<P>
   Their children more than met their expectations. But all the
pride they asserted over half a century _ quietly, so as not to
provoke the Yiddish evil eye _ seemed to crystallize this week with
special poignancy when a daughter of Holocaust survivors, Hadassah
Freilich Lieberman, stood on a platform and heard her husband, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, introduced, however prematurely,
as the next vice president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the chills when I heard about it,'' said Sonia Erlich,
who lost all but one of her 34 relatives in the Holocaust and lives
in the dwindling survivor community in Riverdale, in New York City.
``The world should know what we lost, but there is something in us
that God did not forget us. We believed something good would come
out from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden national prominence of Mrs. Lieberman has brought
into focus a largely overlooked chapter of the Holocaust story: the
lives the survivors built for themselves and their children in
America. Roughly 140,000 of them came to the United States after
World War II. Many denied themselves even ordinary pleasures _ no
movies, no dinners out, no taxis _ so that their children could be
educated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that life is gornischt, life is a feather,'' said Julia
Rosen, an Auschwitz survivor, using a Yiddish term for
``worthless.'' ``So I tried to educate my children so they should
know more than I do, because if I was an educated person I would
have run away, I would have gone to China or Italy or I would have
hid in the forest.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Rosen worked as a bakery clerk; her
husband, Andrew, drafted blueprints. But they put their three
children through good colleges and those children are now a
pharmacist, a computer consultant and a yeshiva teacher. Like
Erlich and Hadassah Lieberman's mother, Ella Freilich, Rosen lives
in Riverdale, a leafy neighborhood where survivors and their
offspring help give the neighborhood a European accent and
gentility.
</P>
<P>
   At first the refugees here barely had the confidence to remind
the world what had been done to them, let alone to protest. For
years there were no rallies, and only the flimsiest of survivor
organizations existed.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly why Rabbi Irving Greenberg, a Riverdale resident
who is chairman of the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum, saw in Mrs.
Lieberman's new stature what he called ``an incredible contrast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years ago the Jews were totally powerless,'' Greenberg
said. ``Here was the most total genocide, and they didn't have the
political clout to get the president to let Jews in. They didn't
have the clout to get the president to bomb the railroads.''
</P>
<P>
   The survivors had already felt that powerlessness in Europe,
where in countries like Poland, anti-Semitic acts were common and
it was difficult for Jews to go to high school, let alone college,
or to work for the government or enter professions.
</P>
<P>
   And so the survivors share a special gratitude to America, and
``are superpatriots as a rule,'' said William B. Helmreich, a
professor of sociology at the City University of New York and the
author of ``Against All Odds: Holocaust Survivors and the
Successful Lives They Made in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lieberman's story has familiar echoes for many survivors.
She was born in Prague, Czechoslovakia, where her mother, an
Auschwitz survivor, and her father, a slave laborer for the Nazis,
settled after the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came from hell,'' was all Mrs. Freilich wanted to say about
her wartime experience.
</P>
<P>
   The family came to the United States when Hadassah Lieberman was
3. Her father, Samuel Freilich, was trained as a lawyer and rabbi
in Czechoslovakia, but he did not speak English and he knew he did
not have time to resurrect his legal career. So he went to the
Jewish Theological Seminary in New York, looking for a rabbi's
position, and soon was in Gardner, Mass., a furniture manufacturing
center where Congregation Ohave Sholom was eager to have him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an immensely disciplined man,'' said Ary Freilich, Mrs.
Lieberman's brother, who was born in Gardner. ``He sat down with
The New York Times and a German-English dictionary and started at
the top of the page and began teaching himself English.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't earn much money, but he put Hadassah through Stern
College and Boston University and Ary through Yeshiva University.
In Boston, Hadassah Freilich met her first husband, Gordon Tucker,
the former dean of the Jewish Theological Seminary, and now a rabbi
in White Plains, N.Y. After they divorced, she lived in Riverdale
with her son, Ethan, until she met Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very appreciative of what she has,'' said Mindy Weisel,
a Washington friend of Mrs. Lieberman. ``She has not been a
princess. She doesn't take anything for granted, and that is a
keynote of her being a survivor's daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors sometimes made a mission of bearing and raising
children, and Frances Kahn, another Riverdale resident, offers a
simple explanation. She managed to emigrate to the United States
just before the war in 1939, but left behind parents, two sisters
and a brother, whom she never saw again.
</P>
<P>
   She now has three children. ``The same amount that I lost,'' she
said, ``I tried to make up.''
</P>
<P>
   In many homes, the survivors and their children maintained a
tacit silence about the wartime experiences. ``My daughter didn't
want me to talk about Auschwitz,'' Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ary Freilich, who runs a real estate company in Fort Lee,
N.J., said he had a different experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents did not speak of it often, but you don't need to
speak of it often for the words to have an impact,'' he said. ``The
absence of relatives, the pictures of small children who never made
it to be adults, were images that were present in our home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holocaust survivor families always have a little bit of
sadness in them. There is an appreciation of the fragility of life
and of the fragility of society. There is an awareness that forces
can bring a society down. But by the same token there is an immense
appreciation of life that comes from people who always lived at the
very edge.''
</P>
<P>
   And the children never seem to forget what makes them
distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Weisel said that after Mrs. Lieberman watched her husband accept
Vice President Al Gore's invitation to become his running mate, she
received an e-mail message from Mrs. Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mindy,'' it said, ``I felt I stood there for all the lost
souls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
