<SLUG> BC-NY-LONG-ISLAND-TRAFFIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTION ON LONG ISLAND DELAYS TRAFFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By AL BAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH HILLS, N.Y. _ Normally, closing any Long Island road in
the middle of summer is a sure recipe for traffic jams and driver
frustration _ never mind shutting down part of the Long Island
Expressway both ways all weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, a day that opened more like a crisp fall day
than one in August, the demolition of a bridge over the expressway
in Nassau County did not have as withering an effect on motorists
as it might have. A bitter rain, gloomy skies and a dull chill had
doused the numbers of eastbound drivers headed for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   A wrecking crew began removing the 44-year-old concrete, steel
and stone bridge Friday night as a part of the state Department of
Transportation's plans to renovate and widen the expressway between
Medford, in Suffolk County, and Queens, in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Once a new overpass opened on July 30, it was possible to start
the dismantling of the old Shelter Rock Road bridge this weekend,
said Eileen W. Peters, a spokeswoman for the department. The work
is expected to be completed by Sunday, but J.D. Posillico,
president of the contracting company doing the work, said the
project was going so well that it might finish ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Posillico said that because of the way the old arch bridge was
built, with steel rods running through the concrete rather than
with concrete slabs resting on steel frames, the whole bridge had
to be torn down at once.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 18 months, Peters said, 16 more bridges will be
refurbished or replaced in Nassau County and three of the projects
will require expressway closings similar to the one this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Peters said the tight schedule meant this weekend's work could
not be put off, because any postponement would delay the entire
project. She said that with 200,000 cars using the affected part of
the expressway on weekdays, a decision was made to disrupt weekend
traffic only.
</P>
<P>
   Some travelers on the road Saturday said they were willing to
put up with the temporary traffic snarl if the improvements would
make things less congested in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Others were angered by the work, though many said traffic was
treacherous on any day on Long Island _ with or without
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
