<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NILE-VIRUS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 TWO MORE NEW YORKERS ARE ILL WITH WEST NILE VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two more Staten Island residents, a 63-year-old woman
and a 64-year-old man, have been sickened by the West Nile virus,
bringing the number of human cases confirmed this year to three,
city health officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said that for the first time a dead crow
infected with the virus had been found in the Bronx. The two pieces
of news prompted them to announce another round of extensive
pesticide spraying to kill mosquitoes that carry the virus.
</P>
<P>
   As with the first confirmed case in a human, in which a
78-year-old Staten Island man became ill in late July, officials
said these two people had received hospital treatment and were now
recovering at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appear to have a full recovery ahead of them,'' said Dr.
Neal Cohen, the city health commissioner, who joined Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani at a City Hall press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's outbreak, centered in Queens, killed seven people
and sickened 55 others. Hundreds more tested positive for infection
but had no symptoms. People with weakened immune systems, the
elderly, and very young children are most at risk from infection.
</P>
<P>
   This year the outbreak has been centered in Staten Island. ``It
is critical that all New Yorkers, particularly the elderly and
those who live on Staten Island, take precautions to reduce
exposure to mosquitoes,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the dead bird found in the Bronx provided fresh
evidence that mosquitoes carrying the virus pose a threat across
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Staten Island has already been sprayed twice since the first
evidence of the virus was discovered there in early July. On
Saturday, Giuliani said the entire island would be sprayed from
trucks Monday night into Tuesday morning and again by air Thursday
night into Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said that a broad swath of the central Bronx, in
a two-mile radius around where the dead crow was found, would be
sprayed from trucks starting Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   All of the spraying will be conducted between 10 p.m. and 5 a.m.
Health officials said the pesticide used would be Anvil, a
relatively nontoxic chemical that the city selected to fight the
disease this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The new human cases come amid broadening evidence of
disease-bearing mosquitoes in Westchester County and in New Jersey.
The Star Ledger in Newark, N.J., reported Saturday that health
officials planned to spray the Middlesex County borough of Carteret
_ the first widespread spraying in New Jersey this year _ from 7:30
p.m. to 11 p.m. Monday and again on Thursday, as dead crows bearing
the West Nile virus were identified there.
</P>
<P>
   And officials in Somers, N.Y., told The Associated Press on
Friday that a so-called sentinel chicken _ set out as a precaution
to track infected mosquitoes _ had been infected with the virus.
But they said the area where the chicken had been placed had been
sprayed with pesticide after the infection took place, and no more
spraying was planned.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cohen said Saturday that the broadest evidence of the disease
had been obtained from mosquito traps. He said the latest analysis,
of samples taken from July 25 to July 28, found 13 cases of
infection on Staten Island and one in Central Park. But he said the
city has no plans to spray a fresh dose over Central Park, since
the park was sprayed on Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Two species of mosquitoes, one that feeds at night and another
that feeds in the day, had been found to carry the virus. Cohen
said that the latest analyses had found the virus in a third
species that feeds from dusk to dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials said that the two Staten Island residents who
most recently became sick had been infected by mosquitoes before
the island was sprayed on Aug. 4. Symptoms of the virus generally
do not become apparent until three to 15 days after the victim is
bitten.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that in the three human cases, the virus had caused a
type of meningitis, a less life-threatening illness than the
encephalitis or inflammation of the brain that killed people last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's names have not been disclosed. The officials said
the 64-year-old woman became ill on Aug. 4 and was admitted to a
hospital on Aug. 6. The 63-year-old man became ill on July 31 and
was hospitalized on Aug. 5, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
