<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTES: THEISMANN; GIANTS; BROWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theismann Still Has Arm Strength
</P>
<P>
   Joe Theismann, the ESPN analyst and former Washington Redskins
quarterback, has been friends with Baltimore coach Brian Billick
for years. So when Theismann made an appearance at training camp
last week, Billick thought he would break up the monotony by
allowing the 50-year-old to toss a few passes to Ravens receivers,
who were being covered by the secondary while running pass routes.
</P>
<P>
   Theismann's first throw was a bullet across the middle, only
several inches too high. The zip on the ball was so strong, the
Ravens players, almost in unison, shouted, ``Oooohhhhh!''
</P>
<P>
   Theismann was not done. His second throw was a perfect, tight
spiral on a deep out pattern that was caught and led to several
veterans joking that the backups had better watch out for their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite still having a strong arm, Theismann is not about to
come out of retirement. There was a time, though, when people
wished the Ravens starter Tony Banks would try another sport. But
after a dismal stint in St. Louis, Banks is entrenched as the
starter in Baltimore, and so far the move to trade for him after
the 1998 season has proven to be a brilliant one. Banks is making
better reads and decisions and this is the most comfortable he has
ever been in an offense.
</P>
<P>
   During a scrimmage earlier in camp against a good Ravens
defense, Banks completed his first 13 passes, including a 17-yard
touchdown pass to Jermaine Lewis. Over all, including last week's
preseason game against Philadelphia, he has been excellent.
</P>
<P>
   It has helped Banks that he is in the first settled situation of
his NFL career. As a professional, he has never been in the same
offensive system for two straight seasons remarkable considering
this is his fifth season. And Billick's system is extremely
quarterback friendly. Last season, Banks started the final 10
games, and finished 6-4, including a 4-0 record in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony has showed that he can run our offense efficiently,''
Billick said. ``I've said all along that Tony can step to another
level if he stayed in the same offensive system for two years in a
row.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants Considering Two Trades
</P>
<P>
   Are the New York Giants, usually conservative when it comes to
making trades, thinking about making two?
</P>
<P>
   The chances of the Giants pulling off one trade by the end of
the preseason are not as slim as one might believe, and neither is
the possibility of a second deal.
</P>
<P>
   First, several general managers have said, the team is
considering trading wide receiver Brian Alford, a third-round pick
in 1997. The Giants are deep at his position and Alford, though he
has shown flashes of talent at times in training camp this year,
will likely get little playing time during the season. That makes
him expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Those same general managers said the Giants, short on
cornerbacks, are considering trading for Jerry Azumah, currently
the third corner on the Chicago Bears' roster. The Bears may not
cut Azumah, and the Giants think they might be able to steal him
for a low-round draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have patience with players,'' said Giants general
manager Ernie Accorsi of Alford. ``This player has had no chance to
play. We have not given up on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi had no comment on Azumah, and would only say Giants
scouts are looking at a number of players.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Outperforming Arrington
</P>
<P>
   The regular season has not started yet, but it is looking more
and more like the Cleveland Browns made the right decision in
picking the defensive lineman Courtney Brown with the No. 1 overall
pick in April's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Browns officials say at times he has looked like the best player
on the field. The athleticism scouts and coaches saw when he was at
Penn State is showing on the professional level.
</P>
<P>
   Originally the team debated between choosing Brown or his
college teammate LaVar Arrington, now with the Redskins. There is
no question Arrington is going to be a good player as well. But
Brown so far has a slight edge, mainly because he has been nothing
but a true professional, while Arrington irritated coaches and
players when in June he turned a one-day excused absence from
minicamp into a four-day unexcused absence. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
