<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GOVT-HOUSE0813-COX     08-12 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVT-HOUSE0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Government gets into home building business
 &HT;    By Linda Rawls
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Big Government has become Big House Builder.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the federal government has taken over
construction of a spectacular mansion on Lake Boca Raton _ a house
commissioned by a local man who prosecutors say bilked consumers of
an estimated $200 million in one of the country's biggest swindles.
</P>
<P>
   The government intends to sell the 19,000-square-foot house when
it's completed to help compensate the victims of Equinox
International, a multilevel marketing company founded by former
Boca Raton resident Bill Gouldd. The house could sell for as much
as $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gouldd, 46, has not been charged with any criminal wrongdoing,
but in April he settled out of court with the Federal Trade
Commission and eight states that sued him in U.S. District Court in
Las Vegas, where Equinox was headquartered. The civil suit, which
accused Gouldd of running an illegal pyramid scheme, asked the
court to shut down his business, whose main product was water
filters, and seize his assets.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which put Equinox out of business and
confiscated Gouldd assets valued at up to $50 million, ended the
lawsuit _ and Gouldd's dream of lavish living on Lake Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement also put the government in the unlikely business
of building a home and trying to sell it for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this is a unique property, it is not a unique
situation,'' said Robb Evans of Sun Valley, Calif., the
court-appointed receiver who is liquidating Gouldd's assets,
including a private jet, a yacht and a car with a gold-plated
engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We typically analyze what we expect to receive by selling the
property 'as is' and what we would expect to receive if we do
certain work,'' Evans said. ``If the value added is sufficiently
greater, and if funds and time are available, we often have
undertaken substantial renovations or completion of work in
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Gouldd case, Evans determined he could get a lot more
money for the house on 150 feet of prime lakefront if he finished
it before finding a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Time and money were no problem. ``This is not a fire sale,''
said custom builder Bill Szymanski, owner of Wm. L Construction,
whom Gouldd hired to build the home in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The original house on the site, near the Boca Raton Resort &AMP;
Club, made news a month earlier when Gouldd donated it to the
Harbour Branch Oceanographic Institute. The 10,000-square-foot
house was cut into four sections and floated by barge 80 miles up
the Intracoastal Waterway to Harbour Branch, where it was
reassembled to house a library and a multimedia department.
</P>
<P>
   The receiver hasn't set an asking price yet on the house going
up in its place, but Szymanski says $16 million to $18 million is
``in the right neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   It likely will set a Boca Raton record.
</P>
<P>
   Szymanski estimates the house will cost $8 million to build. So
if it sells for its estimated minimum listing price, the government
will get $8 million for its victim compensation fund, minus real
estate fees and commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The house is full of amenities buyers in this bracket expect _
and some they might not. Besides two guest houses and an expansive
poolside entertainment area, the house has a private theater with
sofa seating and a popcorn stand, expensive Jerusalem marble
throughout and a mirror above the master bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house obviously was set up to entertain,'' Szymanski
said. ``That was a large part of his business.''
</P>
<P>
   Entertaining and showing off his flashy homes and possessions
were part of Gouldd's strategy to lure people into believing they,
too, could easily make that kind of money through Equinox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would do recruitment videos from his Colorado ranch sitting
on his snowmobile or in his Lamborghini, as if to say, 'Look at the
success I have,' '' said Tracey Brierly, Nevada's deputy attorney
general. ``That was used to draw people in.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a draw required an extraordinary house, which this is, and
so is the man who envisioned it.
</P>
<P>
   Government regulators say Bill Gouldd was a con artist, but his
supporters _ and he still has them _ see a man of vision who went
from sleeping in his car to driving Rolls-Royces. Gouldd added an
extra ``d'' to his last name when a numerologist told him his life
was unbalanced. He would later say the ``d'' stood for ``dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his supporters believe Gouldd could make others rich if
they would just ``follow the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that plan that got Gouldd into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC and the eight states that sued him _ Florida was not
part of the lawsuit _ said Equinox International was an illegal
pyramid scheme. The settlement agreement bars Gouldd for life from
participating in the kind of operation he ran. It's called
multilevel marketing in its legitimate form _ companies such as
Amway or Mary Kay Cosmetics _ and a pyramid scheme in its illegal
guise.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators and prosecutors say Equinox distributors were
duped into thinking they could make good livings by selling water
filters and health-related products out of their garages. Like all
pyramid schemes, only a very few people at the top made money.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else lost, prosecutors say, and some lost lots of
money. Others lost much more _ relationships, homes, life savings,
college trust funds, retirement nest eggs, even their sanity,
prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to this: Do people make the money by recruiting
other people into the system, or from retail sales to the public?''
said FTC lawyer Frank Gorman, who helped prosecute the civil case
against Gouldd. ``The money has to come from sales to people who
aren't members of the scheme. Otherwise, it will collapse and
people at the bottom can't make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman estimates Florida consumers lost $16.2 million in the
scam.
</P>
<P>
   Gouldd now lives in Delray Beach and has an unlisted telephone
number. He declined to be interviewed for this story through one of
his lawyers, Rob Cary of Williams &AMP; Connolly, the Washington, D.C.,
firm that represented President Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But Gouldd denied any wrongdoing in a statement he issued
through the law firm on the day of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always believed, and continue to believe that Equinox's
method of distributing products is a legitimate and unique way for
people with limited capital and means to run their own business on
their own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
