<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-R-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-ART-     08-12 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PLAY BY PLAY WITHOUT WORLD'S BIG HITTERS
</HEADLINE>
  (Repeating to correct photo numbers)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT15 and NYT16 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEL AIR, Md. _ Every minor leaguer has a major league dream.
This is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner's plane, en route from Tampa, Fla., to New
York, is forced to land at the tiny Harford County airport near
here. Impatient, feeling baseball-deprived, the Boss dials the
radio until he lands at the tiny community station, WHFC-FM 91.1.
He is mesmerized by the local game he hears, the quickness, depth,
savvy, desire, the power to use the entire field.
</P>
<P>
   He growls at an assistant, ``Who is that guy and why isn't he at
Yankee Stadium?''
</P>
<P>
   That guy, the dreamer, is Neal Conan, the 50-year-old rookie
play-by-play announcer of the Aberdeen Arsenal, a first-year
expansion club in the independent Atlantic League. Like Conan, the
players are not kids, most of them struggling to be rediscovered
after being cut from major league farm teams.
</P>
<P>
   But Conan, who gets to dream out loud, has had 23 years in the
major leagues, as an executive producer, a host, a prize-winning
foreign correspondent for National Public Radio, from which he is
on leave.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, while preparing for a live broadcast from the
Democratic convention in Chicago, his attention was caught by the
Cubs' broadcasters on his hotel television. He thought: That isn't
so different, I can do it. He began taping play-by-plays in front
of a silent TV screen. For the past three seasons, he moonlighted
as the part-time second voice of the Bowie Baysox.
</P>
<P>
   And on the night of Aug. 5, he was climbing the metal ladder to
the roof of the tiny press box at the tiny home field of the local
community college. An old friend, me, handed up his cables, mikes,
headset, Comrex Hotline, Shure mixer, Sony DAT recorder, all of
which, he explained, will ``squirt the broadcast signal down a
telephone line from the ballpark to the radio station'' and back
out to an unknown number of listeners, including Conan.
</P>
<P>
   He broadcasts with the backfeed echoing in his ears; it is the
only way he can be sure he is really on the air. Because his cell
phone is a different area code from the station's, he is not sure
that someone there will call long distance if there is a problem.
If indeed there is someone there.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this,'' I said, minutes before the game, ``seems like a
midlife crisis to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep,'' said Conan, cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   He paced the press box roof, waiting to begin his pre-game show
with a taped interview. He had melted Maleke Fowler's reserve by
dubbing the 25-year-old outfielder ``the discourager'' for having
hit a leadoff home run in the last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discourager,'' I sneered. ``Talk about ingratiating
yourself with a subject. Did you call Saddam Hussein `the heavy
hitter?' Some Bosnian jackal `the cleanup man?'''
</P>
<P>
   Conan, who was captured and held for a week by the Iraqis while
covering the Iran-Iraq war nine years ago, smiled serenely through
a graying red beard. ``It's true, I never said, `What a great
ambush.' Reportorial detachment is good, but it's nice to finally
be for something. I want these guys to win, to do well. I got
rushes covering wars and political conventions and the impeachment
hearings, but this is all by myself, filling three hours on the
radio, feeling really alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Conan screamed into his phone: ``Why aren't we on the
air? It's Neal. Pick up the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the first Lehigh Valley Black Diamond was at
the plate that the connection was made and Conan was alive again.
It was easy to imagine his clear, dryly friendly voice in a larger
market. His delivery is crisp, seamless and authoritative, if a
little forgiving; he tends to excuse overrun pop flies as lost in
the late-evening shadows. But there is no false enthusiasm and no
irony. He has also learned that it is one thing to inform listeners
that the 26-year-old pitcher Zac Stark read Updike and Hesse on the
last bus trip, another to extol someone's wife and kids back home
when that someone is dating locally.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``family entertainment'' as much as it is organized
baseball. Independent league teams, with no responsibility to
develop players, can concentrate on winning games and profitably
building a community audience. Seats are $12 and $8 (children under
5 and in Little League uniforms are free). Cal Ripken Jr., who was
raised in nearby Aberdeen, is part owner of the club and is
building a fancy ballpark with a baseball academy attached.
</P>
<P>
   Conan is thinking bigger, too; commentaries on his minor league
life are broadcast every other Friday on NPR's ``Morning Edition''
and will fuel a book, entitled ``Play by Play.'' That might get
Steinbrenner's attention.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still the bushes and far from home. His two
college-age children and wife, Liane Hansen, an NPR anchor, live
outside Washington, too far to commute. She says he looks 10 years
younger, and he says he is happy, but he has had twinges as the
political season heated up. Was he doing the right thing?
</P>
<P>
   ``But then,'' Conan said, ``a fan asked me to sign his glove.
That never happened at a convention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
