<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FLA-DEMOCRATS0813-COX     08-12 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-DEMOCRATS0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore victory essential to invigorate Florida Democratic party
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A party in steady decline for nearly a decade,
Florida Democrats come to Los Angeles today determined to hold on
to what little power they have left.
</P>
<P>
   November is crucial to the party's future. A victory by Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and losses in the U.S. Senate race and other
key Florida races could doom the party to political obscurity in
the Sunshine State for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a party in serious trouble,'' says University of
Florida political scientist Richard Scher who specializes in
Florida politics. ``They have lost touch with white, male,
middle-class businessmen and professionals who now listen to the
GOP, which gives them a moderate-to-conservative message. Democrats
are struggling with their message, and until they have something to
offer that group they will continue to struggle as a party.''
</P>
<P>
   No decade was worse for Florida Democrats than the 1990s. After
more than a century of nearly unchallenged rule, Democrats fell
apart. By 1998, they had lost control of the state House and
Senate, a majority of the congressional delegation, scores of local
offices, and in a final crushing blow, they lost the governor's
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   They managed to hang on to the governor's mansion from 1990 to
1998, but that was because of the charisma of Lawton Chiles. Some
political leaders, however, partly blame Chiles for the demise of
the Democratic Party. Chiles came from a long tradition of elected
officials who considered the party machine a useless operation
unnecessary to their own political victories.
</P>
<P>
   What Chiles and other Democratic leaders at the time failed to
notice was that Florida's Republican leadership was spending
millions to build a strong party headquarters filled with political
professionals. They also rallied around someone with star power _
Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Lawton Chiles was in office, it was like he fiddled
while the Democratic Party burned,'' says Scher, who is not alone
in that feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with the unrelenting reality that Democrats will
remain in the minority for the foreseeable future, party leaders
are counting heavily on winning this year's U.S. Senate race.
Democrats are banking on Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson who,
according to recent polls, leads Republican challenger, U.S. Rep.
Bill McCollum.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders also have high hopes for winning at least two
Republican congressional seats. One is the Orlando area seat that
McCollum is leaving, and the other is held by Republican E. Clay
Shaw of Fort Lauderdale. Shaw is getting a serious challenge in
District 22 from Democratic state Rep. Elaine Bloom of Miami Beach.
This district reaches from Miami Beach to Juno Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are in very good shape for this election,'' says
Bob Poe, the new chairman of the Florida Democratic Party. ``Two
years ago, after the 1998 election, people were telling us to turn
out the lights and bring down the flag. I think a lot has changed
since then. For us to be even competitive in these races is
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the most hopeful projections show Democrats picking up only
a handful of seats in the state House, where Republicans hold a
75-45 majority. Things are bit more hopeful for Democrats in the
Senate, where the GOP leads 23-15. Democrats hope to pick up three
or four seats there. That won't give them a majority, but it will
give them a stronger voice in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fervently want Vice President Al Gore to win Florida.
That would be a humiliating defeat for Jeb Bush and would dent the
sense of invulnerability that the Florida GOP has now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this mystique about Jeb Bush and the Republican Party
that makes them even more formidable then they already are,'' said
a GOP political adviser to Bush who did not want to be named.
``That element of inevitability can really help when you're trying
to raise money or organize.''
</P>
<P>
   Poe acknowledges that if George W. Bush wins the White House,
``Jeb Bush will really be unstoppable'' when he comes up for
reelection in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also worry that in 2002, when the legislature is
required to draw new district lines for all House, Senate and
congressional seats, they will be forced to sit back and watch as
the GOP carves up the state in ways most beneficial to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats need to start rebuilding the party from the county
level up,'' says Scher. ``It's going to take a very long time. It's
something I think they are just now starting to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the party also suffers from not having a strong
statewide leader. U.S. Sen. Bob Graham, the party's top elected
official, like Chiles, has never been deeply involved in helping
the state party. Attorney General Bob Butterworth, popular with
South Florida Democrats, has done a better job, but he will leave
office when his term ends in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Nelson wins, he is not expected to work especially hard
to rebuild the state party. ``I don't see Nelson as a great
champion of the party. He never has been in the past,'' said a
senior Democratic Party leader.
</P>
<P>
   Two years from now, when Bush faces reelection, Democrats will
be looking at a farm team of potential candidates. Political
strategists say the best Democrats can hope for in 2002 is to groom
someone to run four years later when Bush will have to leave
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any question that it has taken us a
while to understand that we are a minority party,'' says Poe. ``But
we do understand that now, and we're building the party back up. I
think in November you'll see that we are making significant
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
