<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-SABBATH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WORLD WATCHING LIEBERMAN CANDIDACY, HIS RABBI SAYS
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The vice-presidential candidacy of Sen. Joseph
Lieberman will have the world's rapt attention, Lieberman's rabbi
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a test case,'' Rabbi Barry Freundel of Kesher Israel
synagogue in Georgetown said in his Sabbath sermon to Lieberman and
other members of the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the first Orthodox Jew to run for such a high office
in the United States, was accompanied at the service by his family
and yarmulke-wearing Secret Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   Congregants serenaded the senator with a song of celebration in
Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Hadassah, and daughter, Hana, looking on from the
section of the synagogue reserved for women, Lieberman stood in a
place of honor as the Torah was read. He chanted the traditional
Hebrew blessings before and after the Torah reading.
</P>
<P>
   David Sloan, a director of the synagogue who led a portion of
the service, bestowed a blessing on Lieberman and provoked peals of
laughter when he unexpectedly blessed Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The synagogue welcomed journalists inside but admonished them
not to take notes in the sanctuary or interview worshipers during
the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   When the morning service ended just after noon, two hours after
the Liebermans arrived, they returned on foot to their home in
Georgetown, trailed by a security detail.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman's e-mail address is marks(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
