<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-DEMOCRATS13-COX     08-12 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DEMOCRATS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HISPANICS BACK END TO PLAYBOY FLAP
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hispanic officials uniformly welcomed the
successful bid to get Rep. Loretta Sanchez to move a fund-raiser
from the Playboy Mansion, Democratic leaders said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came amid a flurry of moves to project an image of
party unity on the eve of the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   _ Amid concern among officials of Vice President Al Gore's
campaign that President Clinton's five-day pre-convention schedule
here threatened to overshadow the Democratic nominee's message,
Clinton canceled a round of televised interviews Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The president instead played golf with Mayor Richard Riordan of
Los Angeles and Terry McAuliffe, the Democratic convention
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   _ Democratic general chairman Ed Rendell said that despite a
dispute over Gore's free-trade policies, labor unions would use
their political might on his behalf this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although union people disagree with us on trade, they are with
us on a whole boatload of (other) vital issues,'' Rendell said at a
breakfast with reporters. ``So they are going to go all out for
Gore in November.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Family members of former Gov. Bob Casey of Pennsylvania, who
died this year, will address the convention following the personal
intervention of Gore, Democratic national chairman Joe Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Casey, a Democrat, was denied a convention role because
his position against abortion differed sharply from that adopted in
the party platform.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, who also appeared at the breakfast, praised Sanchez and
said she remained a valued member of the party hierarchy despite
her previous insistence on holding the $3 million Hispanic Unity
USA fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about location, location, location,'' Andrew said.
Key California party figures, including several influential
Hispanics, had been tryinto get Sanchez to forgo that sexually
suggestive location, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   In return for backing down, Sanchez retained her speaking slot
before the delegates, her largely honorary title as a party
co-chair, and the continued political support of Gore, who feared
the Playboy-hosted event would detract from his plans to stress
moral family values at the convention and in the coming campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing late Friday to make the shift, Sanchez praised Lt.
Gov. Cruz Bustamante of California, who she said was instrumental
in finding an alternative site ``with the cachet we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   For a time, the controversy threatened to dim the political
fortunes of Sanchez, who was the second-highest party fund-raiser
last year _ trailing only Gore, according to Federal Election
Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   Some 600 people had already donated $5,000 each to attend the
Tuesday night event for the political action group, which Sanchez
has led for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, they will now show up at B.B. King's Blues Club at
Universal Studios' CityWalk _ even though King himself is a
Republican who backs Gore's rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Camacho, a Los Angeles businessman and Democratic
fund-raiser who runs two restaurants at CityWalk, said he helped
arrange use of King's club after being approached by other Latino
figures who were eager to settle the burgeoning controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass' e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
