<P>
   (NYT4) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 12, 2000 -- PHILLY-MOVE-AFTERMATH-1
-- There has been a scandalous epilogue to the Philadelphia MOVE
row house disaster in 1985. The gleaming brick replacement houses
for the 60 innocent homeowners on Osage Avenue and Pine Street
whose houses were destroyed when police dropped explosives on the
MOVE quarters, turned out to have been built with construction
flaws by a corrupt developer. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 12, 2000 -- DEM-LOSANGELES-2 -- Los
Angeles, the host city for the Democratic National Convention. In
Los Angeles, a sprawling concatenation of communities with a
restless multi-ethnic character, there is no single ``face,'' in
the usual sense of the word. A surge of immigration and the rapid
shift toward an economy dominated by small businesses rather than
huge corporations have pushed Los Angeles into a dizzyingly complex
transition. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 12, 2000 -- DEM-LOSANGELES-1 --
Charlie Woo is the sort of business and civic leader one would
expect to find at the head of the welcoming line at the Democratic
National Convention, and, in fact, he will be, as a vice chairman
of the city's host committee. Woo will soon become the first
Asian-American chairman of the Los Angeles Chamber of Commerce, and
he has helped guide groups involved in everything from voter
registration to inner-city job development and Chinese-American
political fund-raising. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
