<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 12, 2000 -- OLY-RUN-LOROUPE-3 -- Kenya
is favored to win its first Olympic marathon at the Games in
Sydney, Australia, next month. But the race comes with a cultural
twist. In a highly patriarchal society where women play a
subservient role, it is a woman, Tegla Loroupe, who is expected to
achieve Kenya's first gold medal in the marathon at the Summer
Games. ``Kenya has never had a woman win a gold medal at the
Olympics, so it would be great to be the first,'' says Loroupe, 27.
(Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 12, 2000 -- OLY-RUN-LOROUPE-2 -- Kenya
is favored to win its first Olympic marathon at the Games in
Sydney, Australia. But the race comes with a cultural twist. In a
highly patriarchal society where women play a subservient role, it
is a woman, Tegla Loroupe, who is expected to achieve Kenya's first
gold medal in the marathon at the Summer Games. Loroupe, 27,
appears fragile at 4 feet 11 inches and 82 pounds, yet she is an
insistent wraith, holding the world record and refusing to succumb
to the pressures of her country and her father to live a chattel
life of domestic servitude. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
