<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9924 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHINA-POET-BOS &LR;      08-12 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 CHINA DETAINS BOSTON POET AND PUBLISHER
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS GRILLO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   A Boston-based poet and publisher of a literary journal has been
detained by police in Beijing and copies of his magazine have been
seized, according to friends.
</P>
<P>
   Bei Ling, editor of Tendency Quarterly, a journal of Chinese and
Western literature, has not been seen since Friday night, when two
uniformed police officers and one plainclothes officer seized
several hundred copies of the journal from a bar near Beijing
University, his friends in Beijing said. Bei disappeared after a
forum to review the latest issue of the journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is shocking news,'' said Shirley Chang, a friend who is
staying at Bei's home while she teaches a summer course at the
University of Massachusetts at Boston. ``I spoke to him by
telephone 10 days ago, and he didn't mention any problems. I don't
understand why this happened all of a sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   But Merle Goldman, a Boston University professor who specializes
in Chinese intellectual history and dissent, said she is not
surprised by the police action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government is cracking down on anyone who
questions the Communist Party,'' she said. ``While the journal is
not political, some of the material can be interpreted as such
because it does not follow the party line of a positive view of the
People's Republic of China.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the arrest has to do with the current policies of
the regime, she said. While Tendency has been published in China 13
times since 1993, Goldman said, China's political climate today is
more repressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to this point, they have allowed the journal to be
distributed, but now there's a sense of vulnerability in the
government, and they are cracking down on the Internet and
arresting people who, they say, are spreading anti-party
messages.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said she believes that the Chinese government will
eventually release Bei but could bar him from entering the country
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can keep Bei Ling out of China, but they cannot keep the
journal from coming in from other sources. The government can't
stop the Internet and Western ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bei was being held in Beijing's university district, according
to a friend who did not want to be identified for fear of
attracting police attention. Police did not provide a reason for
the detention, the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have previously told Bei that Tendency has ``political
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe in 1994, Bei said, ``Tendency is
meant to call more attention and respect to culture and humanism,
advocates for freedom of expression, and individual creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bei, 40, moved to the United States in 1988. He is a Chinese
citizen and has a US green card.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1994, Bei was questioned for three hours in Shanghai.
A few days later in Shenzhen, on the border with Hong Kong, police
questioned him for three days, including a nine-hour interrogation
session, about ``The Post-Communist Nightmare,'' an essay by Vaclav
Havel that was included in the first issue of Tendency. Havel is
the former dissident and playwright who became the Czech Republic's
first democratically elected president.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the executive editor and cofounder of Tendency said
interference by Chinese officials will not halt the publication of
the magazine. ``No matter what happens in terms of the oppression,
we look foward to someday publishing the journal openly in China
and working toward freedom of expression,'' Meng Lang said through
a translator.
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
