<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FIRES-ARTIFACTS0813-C     08-12 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-ARTIFACTS0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fires threaten precious artifacts
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA VERDE NATIONAL PARK - Two months before a pair of wildfires
ravaged Mesa Verde National Park, archeologist Linda Towle sat in
the living room of her house in the park packing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was packing as I was watching the film from Los Alamos
(N.M.,) and I said, 'That's it,''' recalled Towle, 52, chief of
research and resource management at Mesa Verde. ``I boxed up all of
my photos, slides and family papers and I rented a storage unit in
Cortez.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Towle remembers the day: Thursday, July 20. The time was a
quarter of two. She had just settled down in an administrative
meeting to close out the year-end budget when she heard the news
that she had been dreading all summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The superintendant's secretary came in and said, ``Just want
you to know there's a fire. ... It's probably not a big deal,'''
said Towle.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something different about this fire. It was
behaving erratically, burning late into the night instead of
resting. Fire conditions were prime _ dry oak brush, pinon and
juniper trees baked in the scorching afternoon sun _ and the
brilliant blue Colorado sky provided no hint of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Towle heard the fire management officer get on the radio and
call for an evacuation of the park.
</P>
<P>
   She made the mad dash home, grabbed what she could and raced
over to the office to account for her employees, some of whom were
still out in the backcountry.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Towle found herself holed up at the Comfort Inn in
Cortez with her cat, Kiva, a stray she befriended eight years ago
after the six-week old kitten had been abandoned inside the park.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after the Bircher fire, which scorched more
than 23,000 acres inside one of the nation's largest archeological
preserves, Towle found herself in evacuation mode again. This time
a lightning strike on the Ute Mountain Ute Reservation near the
tiny town of Towaoc started another fire. It was making a run for
the opposite side of the park, sweeping up steep rugged canyons
filled with bone dry vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   The Pony fire charred more than 5,200 acres before it was
contained Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fire crews were brought in from as far away as Alaska to battle
the blaze. Aggressive air attacks obliterated the remote terrain
almost daily with water and slurry, a reddish-colored substance
made up of chemicals to douse the fire. On the ground, firefighters
carved out fire lines by hand as archeologists worked ahead of them
scouting out potential sites.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2,000 new archeological sites have been discovered
as a result of the fires, but so far no major sites have been
unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   For Towle, who struggles daily with the thought that she may not
have a home to go back to, the worst may be yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   PRICELESS ARTIFACTS AT RISK
</P>
<P>
   That's because of the Research Center, a tin building the size
of an airplane hangar. It houses a priceless collection of 2
million Native American artifacts, including some dating back as
far as 400 A.D., that has been threatened by wildfire three times
in the past four years. Each time, the fire has crept to within a
mile of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the building, irreplaceable artifacts are housed in
gun-metal gray cabinets with tracking numbers posted on each door.
Shelf after shelf provides a glimpse into the past: Navajo
basketry, ceramics and silver work; Ute moccasins; beaded Zuni
steer heads; prehistoric pottery, yucca blankets and sandal
remnants; and pot rests, brooms, farming implements and photographs
from the Gustaf Nordenskiold collection.
</P>
<P>
   There are even human remains waiting to be reburied under the
Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act of 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The artifacts are the only records left detailing the history
and habits of the Ancestral Puebloans, a lost civilization that
vanished more than 700 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   During the fires, special precautions were taken to protect the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Fire trucks circled the perimeter of the tin building like wagon
trains from the days of the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   The windows and vents were covered with reflective fire
shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters were instructed to save the building at any cost _
even if that meant using bulldozers to build a fire line, which is
against park policy unless buildings are threatened. Bulldozers
were parked and ready to go if the fire raged up lower Chapin Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created a safety zone adjacent to the Research Center
where structural fire trucks could safely stay and hose down the
center and foam it as the fire is passing over,'' said Towle.
``That would be the plan, but human safety is the highest
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   A heat-sensitive fire suppression system inside the building was
deactivated to prevent flooding.
</P>
<P>
   There is no room for error.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan had gone awry, windows could have shattered from the
intense heat, allowing the flames to creep inside. Or the roof
could have collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fire does not get inside the building, we might have
some water damage from the roof leaking as it is being foamed and
sprinkled,'' said Towle. ``If something happens and the building
were to collapse, then a lot of the (artifacts) would be damaged
and getting them out of there would be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The location of the Research Center is kept secret as a security
precaution. In May, The Daily Sentinel was allowed inside for a
rare opportunity to photograph the artifacts with the stipulation
that the location of the building not be published. But with the
intense media spotlight on the fires at Mesa Verde, the warehouse
and its contents have been widely publicized on national networks
like CNN and ABC, as well as various other print publications.
</P>
<P>
   LOOTING AFTER THE FIRES
</P>
<P>
   Once the threat of fire has passed, park officials could find
themselves dealing with another headache: artifact looters.
</P>
<P>
   Earl K. Shumway is the poster child for artifact looters.
</P>
<P>
   The self-described outlaw from Moab, Utah, is serving a 6-year
federal prison term for pilfering artifacts in southeastern Utah.
It's the longest sentence ever given for an archaeological resource
violation.
</P>
<P>
   In Mesa Verde, there is only one backcountry ranger to patrol
for pot hunters, vandals and poachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the burn, it is easy to see footprints leading off and we
will follow up on anything we see,'' said Towle. ``After the Chapin
5 fire (in 1996), we had no evidence that people were trying to get
into the burn.''
</P>
<P>
   The scuttlebutt around town is that it's easier to slip into
unauthorized areas of the Ute Mountain Tribal Park because of the
lack of security, but wildlife officers regularly patrol the area.
</P>
<P>
   The park has an estimated 25,000 archeological sites, many
pristine and untouched. Only 850 sites have been documented due to
a lack of funding.
</P>
<P>
   At the entrance to the tribal park, a weathered, white sign
reads, ``Stop: You are entering Ute Mountain Tribal Park. All
non-tribal members must be accompanied by a tribal park tour
guide.''
</P>
<P>
   A drive on the gravel road inside the park turns up no obvious
signs of security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some problems three years ago at the mouth of Mancos
Canyon,'' said Veronica Cuthair, director of the Ute Mountain
Tribal Park. ``There were some illegal excavations happening, but
they never caught them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cases are hard to prosecute due to a lack of witnesses. Once dug
up, artifacts are hard to link to a looted site. Professional
looters are sophisticated, carefully planning their illegal
excavations, studying archival and library materials and
topographical maps, according to Robert D. Hicks of Law Enforcement
Bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid detection, looters use lookouts, watchdogs and radio
scanners to track law enforcement. Others have been known to carry
false identification and forged permits. Some have even been caught
red-handed wearing fake park ranger uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Violation of the Archeological Resources Protection Act can
result in fines of up to $100,000 and five years in prison or both.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal artifacts that make their way to the black market bring
in big bucks _ upwards of a million dollars if the piece is rare
and in excellent shape. Many artifacts end up overseas where it is
a multi-million dollar business.
</P>
<P>
   A search on e-Bay, an Internet auction site, found 225 listings
for Indian artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Most items were arrowheads, pottery sherds, knives and bone
tools. A Michigan barbed axe was fetching $1,450 and the bidding
hadn't yet closed.
</P>
<P>
   Towle isn't worried about the artifact looters.
</P>
<P>
   She's more concerned about the fire danger and the long, hot
summer that still looms ahead. As the saying goes, ``Lightning
never strikes the same place twice,'' but could it strike three
times in a row?
</P>
<P>
   For now, all Towle can do is wait.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
