<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN'S CALL ROMPS IN SWORD DANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ They bought him eight years ago for
$4,000 in the hopes that he would be an athletic steeplechase
horse. They thought his name was Stuart's Affair. By the time he
became a 2-year-old, however, Thomas Voss discovered two things.
First, the colt could not jump. Second, he had the wrong horse.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out the big chestnut was really named John's Call.
Somewhere between South Carolina and the trainer's base in Maryland
the wrong horse got on the wrong truck. But John's Call was on the
right track here Saturday and splashed home a 9\-length winner in
the rain-softened bog at Saratoga in the Grade I Sword Dancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could run on broken glass,'' Voss crowed. ``He may be 9
years old but he doesn't think he's nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a gelding, John's Call, probably had. He was the oldest
horse in the field by three years. With 31 races, he was the most
seasoned. His steeplechase experience? Well, he's tried it as late
as last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When does a 9-year-old gelding who was supposed to be a jumper
win a Grade I race at a 1 { mile?'' asked Douglas Joyce, one of the
owners in Trillium Stable, which collected $300,000 for the
first-place check, before answering his own question. ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   But under Jean-Luc Samyn, John's Call laid in the back of the
pack around the first, second and third turns before pulling even
in the stretch with Aly's Alley, who had set a leisurely pace in an
attempt to steal the tour of the swampy marathon race from the
front end. ``I wasn't surprised to be on the lead. He was the speed
of the race,'' said Aly's Alley rider Robbie Davis, who held on for
second place.
</P>
<P>
   But Samyn had charted his trip around the spongy footing in
order to finish well. He stayed on the rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the rail was the place to be, and I wouldn't have moved
off it for anything,'' he said. ``Once daylight opened up, he just
took off and exploded. It was a superb race for a 9-year-old to
run. The thing I loved about it was that he was happy to do it. He
knew he had won. He was happy galloping back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the field dwindled to eight when the connections of
two millionaires _ Val's Prince and Honor Glide and three other
horses _ scratched their horses instead of taking on the tricky
footing, the old gelding was sent off as the fifth choice and
rewarded his believers with a generous $16.80 payoff for a $2 bet.
</P>
<P>
   One classy horse that stayed in the race experienced all kinds
of trouble on the soggy turf. Under Kent Desormeaux, the $1 million
earner Single Empire never got in gear and chased the top two
finishers home in third place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big effort on ground on which he is probably not his
best,'' said trainer Neil Drysdale.
</P>
<P>
   There was some valid reasons for the crowd of 24,787 to doubt
that the aging John's Call belonged at the top levels of turf
racing. Besides his steeplechase attempts, one of which he won
here, John's Call had run for as low as a $50,000 claiming price
and never had taken on such classy company. On the other hand, he
had won 13 times, placed 11 and came in third on two other
occasions which means he was near the wire in 28 of his 31 starts.
He also had an affinity for Saratoga _ winning twice and placing
second three times in seven attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Voss understood how confusing John's Call might have looked to
the public. He had often been confused himself about the old horse
he had. In 1992, the owners had bought two horses and sent them to
South Carolina to be broken. One was sent to Voss, the other to
another trainer. It wasn't until Stuart's Affair was about to race
that he noticed his identifying tattoo belonged to John's Call.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, however, they've been together. From jumps to flats.
From Delaware to Maryland to New York. From a chip in the ankle and
months on the farm, to a victorious 2:32:17 victorious gallop in a
$500,000 race. Seven years in all, one of them calling his charge
by the wrong name. So whatever happened to Stuart's Affair?
</P>
<P>
   ``He never ran a race in his life,'' Voss said. ``Isn't that
something?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
