<HEADER>
A9932 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CERABINO-COLUMN13-COX     08-12 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE DEMOCRATS' SURPRISING CONVENTION
 &HT;    By FRANK CERABINO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You can cut the excitement with a knife here.
Wait, come to think of it, that's not the excitement, that's the
air.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats picked a terrible time to come to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   It's so hot, Al Gore may just blurt out that he invented the air
conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived Saturday morning, and promptly checked in at the
Florida delegation's hotel _ which I believe is on the edge of
Runway 9 at Los Angeles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for us, the convention isn't being held at baggage
claim. It's being held at the Staples Center, which is at least
four freeways and a $36 cab ride from the hotel. If the Florida
delegation were any farther from the convention center, they'd be
at the Reform Party convention in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   What a crazy election! The Republicans paraded around
Philadelphia as if they were the Wall Street chapter of the Sisters
of Mercy. And the Democrats pretend they're not interested in sex _
canceling that Tuesday fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion here.
</P>
<P>
   I'm deeply worried that the Democrats have forgotten how to
party. I find this troubling.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when Democrats have a fund-raiser that's listed as
B.Y.O.B., it probably means Bring Your Own Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have decided to go with a ``p'' theme this
convention. They've distilled their theme into three ``p'' words:
prosperity, progress, and peace.
</P>
<P>
   I can think of a few other ``p'' words that might have been in
the running. So I'm awarding honorable mentions to ``perjury'' and
``poontang.''
</P>
<P>
   I know what you're thinking. You think I'm being nasty just
because they canceled that party at the Playboy Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you're right.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for approximately 14,595 of the 15,000 media types
here, the fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion was going to require
the kind of blanket coverage usually reserved for moon landings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, what are we going to do on Tuesday night?
</P>
<P>
   Bait Rep. Barney Frank into telling rude heterosexual jokes
about Dick Armey?
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the keynote speech from ... let's see, who's speaking
that night ... Harold E. Ford Jr.? Who is Harold E. Ford Jr.?
</P>
<P>
   He's supposedly some up-and-coming 30-year-old congressman from
Tennessee _ as if we need to hear from anybody else from Tennessee.
Al Gore's all the Tennessee I need.
</P>
<P>
   This convention needs more New Yorkers. People like ... Hillary.
She'll get to speak Monday night, just before her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Clintons will get out of town and allow the excitement
to build for Gore and his running mate, Joe Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   If that's possible. I can't imagine how.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the media will continue to emphasize that Lieberman is
Jewish, and that makes his selection a ``bold move'' by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Not bold enough, I say.
</P>
<P>
   Here's bold: Instead of calling the convention America 2000,
call it America 5760.
</P>
<P>
   As you can tell, I'm not a political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   But I am a pundit, which allows me to make reckless and
sometimes wildly inaccurate predictions. So here are 10 predictions
for the upcoming week's festivities:
</P>
<P>
   1. During his speech Monday night, the Rev. Jesse Jackson will
not rhyme the word ``Gore'' with ``snore'' or ``bore.''
</P>
<P>
   2. AFL-CIO boss John Sweeney will take a five-minute break in
the middle of his speech, as called for by contract.
</P>
<P>
   3. Somebody will speak Spanish during prime time.
</P>
<P>
   4. If it's Al Gore, real Spanish-speaking people will laugh at
his accent.
</P>
<P>
   5. Not once this week will Sen. Ted Kennedy drink a shake for
breakfast and lunch, and then eat a sensible dinner.
</P>
<P>
   6. Michael Dukakis and Walter Mondale will have obstructed-view
seating in the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   7. President John F. Kennedy will be mentioned more than a dozen
times _ not counting the mentions in speeches given by his daughter
and brother.
</P>
<P>
   8. Nearly every speaker will find it necessary to use the phrase
``this great land of ours.''
</P>
<P>
   9. The convention orchestra will not play the ``Theme From Love
Story'' to announce Gore's entrance.
</P>
<P>
   10. The convention will be marred by pushing, shoving, and a
mini-riot ... when the food is served at the media party.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
