<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0813-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Protesters begin demonstrating at convention
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceAnti-abortion protesters and immigrant
<TEXT>
rights advocates demonstrated Saturday in Los Angeles where
delegates began arriving for this week's Democratic National
Convention. Thousands of protesters are expected to descend upon
the city in the upcoming days. A few dozen demonstrators carrying
poster-sized pictures of aborted fetuses protested outside the
Staples Center, where the convention begins Monday. Meanwhile,
protesters continued making banners, picket signs and satiric
puppets at their nearby headquarters, named the Convergence Center,
to be used this week. On Friday, a federal judge ruled that police
could only enter the headquarters if they have a search warrant or
during an emergency. The decision came in response to a complaint
by the American Civil Liberties Union's citing that the Convergence
Center has been a target of police harassment.
<P>
   GORE TAKES ON BIG BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Vice President Al Gore stood on a ridge overlooking
the Allegheny River in Springdale, Pa., and claimed spiritual
kinship with the late Rachel Carson, the author of ``Silent
Spring,'' widely regarded as a founding document in the
environmental movement. Gore mocked industry advertisements showing
children walking through clouds of pesticides to demonstrate their
harmlessness, and likewise, he said, he had been the target of
similar corporate ``propaganda.'' The speech demonstrated Gore's
overall campaign strategy: blending routine rhetoric with his
larger populist theme of ``fighting for the people'' and taking on
big business. The strategy is aimed at Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush, who Gore's camp has accused of being a
captive of big oil.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the first Orthodox
Jew to run for such a high office, skipped campaigning Saturday and
observed the Sabbath by attending services at his synagogue in
Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON BACKS AWAY FROM LIMELIGHT
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton canceled a round of television interviews
Saturday after concerns were raised from Al Gore's campaign that
the president's five-day pre-convention schedule in Los Angeles
threatened to overshadow the Democratic nominee's message. The
president instead played golf with Los Angeles Mayor Richard
Riordan and Terry McAuliffe, the Democratic convention chairman.
Saturday night, the president and his wife Hillary Clinton, a
Senate candidate from New York, were to attend a fund-raiser with a
cast of Hollywood celebrities that was expected to yield $1 million
for his wife's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   GORE STILL TRAILING BUSH, POLLS SHOW
</P>
<P>
   A Newsweek poll released Saturday shows Gore trails Bush by 10
points, 48 percent to 38 percent. This is similar to a CBS News
poll released Friday that found Gore trailing Bush, 52 percent to
42 percent. An ABC News poll out Friday put Gore 9 points behind
Bush, 52 percent to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   CASEY FAMILY TO SPEAK AT DNC
</P>
<P>
   The family of former Gov. Bob Casey of Pennsylvania, who died
this year, will address the Democratic National Convention after a
personal invitation by Gore, Democratic national chairman Joe
Andrew said Saturday. In 1992, Casey, a Democrat, was denied a
convention role because his position against abortion differed
sharply from that adopted in the party platform.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION HELPED BUSH'S NOTORIETY, POLL SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   Even though few Americans watched two hours or more of the
Republican National Convention, a new study shows that Bush
succeeded in increasing awareness that he favors a bigger tax cut
than Gore, and that he wants prescription drugs available to the
elderly. Polls by the Annenberg Public Policy Center found:
</P>
<P>
   After the convention, 62 percent of voters polled said they
identified Bush as the presidential candidate who ``favors the
biggest tax cut,'' up from 54 percent before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   And 31 percent polled after the convention said they knew that
Bush favored providing vouchers to defray prescription drug costs
for the elderly, up from 25 percent before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also spread Gore's position on opposing allowing workers to
invest Social Security taxes in the stock market _ something Bush
advocates. Before the RNC, only 39 percent of voters polled were
aware of this. After the convention, 44 percent said they knew.
</P>
<P>
   GORE WINS NOD FROM LABOR GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's labor pains abated somewhat Friday, as he accepted the
long-awaited endorsement of a powerful union, the United Auto
Workers in Bridgeport, Pa. UAW President Stephen Yokich _ who once
accused Gore of ``holding hands with the profiteers of the world''
for backing a free trade agreement with China _ offered his full
support for the vice president. ``You're going to be our
candidate,'' Yokich told Gore, who pumped his fists in the air as
Yokich reported the unanimous UAW board vote to endorse Gore.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
