<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT &LR;      08-12 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS PROMISE NOT TO STEP INTO GORE'S SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT17 and NYT19 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hillary Rodham Clinton said Saturday that she and
President Clinton would stay at the Democratic National Convention
just long enough to proclaim their support for Vice President Al
Gore, and then drop completely from sight, doing nothing, she
promised, that might steal attention from the celebration
surrounding Gore's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down, we're gone, absolutely,'' the first lady announced
in an interview, sitting in a suite at the heavily secured Century
City hotel, where the Clintons are staying. ``We're going to be
staying out of sight. Really. We want there to be nothing but a
focus on the convention back in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want there to be any attention _ anywhere _ except on
Joe and Al,'' Mrs. Clinton said, referring to Joseph Lieberman, the
Connecticut senator that Gore has chosen as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who said she was speaking for herself and the
president, made her remarks at a time when Gore's supporters have
assailed them both for embarking on a vigorous schedule of
pre-convention politicking and fund-raising that has distracted
from this climactic moment in Gore's career.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton grew animated at the mention of the criticism, shaking
her head vigorously to dispute the suggestion that the Clintons
were overshadowing Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no more enthusiastic supporter of Al Gore than I
am,'' she said, adding: ``I just feel so strongly about his
candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is running for the U.S. Senate from New York,
demurred when asked to describe how she and her husband intended to
spend the rest of the week, though an aide said later that they
would be going to a friend's waterside cabin in Lake Placid, N.Y.
When asked if Mr. Clinton was aware of what the first couple was
doing once they finished their prime-time convention speeches on
Monday night, Mrs. Clinton laughed, toyed with a glass of water on
the round dining room table before her, and responded evenly,
``Yes. Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   She discussed the tangled ambitions and agendas of three of the
nation's best-known Democrats _ Clinton, Mrs. Clinton and Gore _ in
the course of an interview in which she talked at length about her
own campaign against Rep. Rick Lazio, and how she hoped the
convention in general, and her 10-minute speech on Monday night,
would provide a lift both to her campaign and Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, gazing through a plate-glass window in the
19th-floor suite at the St. Regis Hotel over Century City and
across a vast and smoggy expanse of Los Angeles, argued that Lazio
was, largely, a different kind of opponent from the one Gore faced
in Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. Lazio, she asserted, repeatedly
sought to obscure parts of his record to accommodate the Democratic
electoral terrain in New York, while Bush has run more explicitly
as a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, with an edge of frustration in her voice,
described it as a ``deliberate obfuscation of the record and the
votes that were taken, and a disclaiming of responsibility that I
find troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind having a debate in a campaign with someone who
says, you know, `I don't think we should permit HMOs to be sued,
and here are my three reasons,'' Clinton said. ``As opposed to
someone saying, `Well, I did support a patients bill of rights.'''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to Lazio's support of limited Republican
legislation to regulate HMOs, which Lazio has cited in response to
Clinton's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or you know, `I really am pro-choice _ it's just that I'm on
the conservative party line and I've given them a big wink about
what I really mean, and I won't commit to defending Roe v. Wade in
any Supreme Court nomination process in the Senate,''' she said,
continuing her remarks about Lazio. ```But, gee, take me at my
word, because I want to be all things to all people.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the Republican-conservative candidate,'' she said. ``New
York is neither Republican nor conservative when it comes to guns
and choice and education and health care and the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Dan McLagan, a spokesman for Lazio, responded to
Clinton's remarks by taking note of the amount of time the first
lady has devoted on this trip to raising campaign funds for her
race. ``It's flattering that the first lady would take time out of
her busy soft-money feeding frenzy to attack Congressman Lazio,''
McLagan said.
</P>
<P>
   The interview, one of a handful she did with New York reporters
in time for the high-circulation Sunday newspapers, came as she
continued to, in effect, use California as a base for her New York
campaign in the midst of the convention festivities. She was
scheduled to attend a fund-raiser Saturday night in Malibu that
could raise anywhere from $1 million to $4 million for her.
</P>
<P>
   That fund-raiser was one of the events that drew some
expressions of concern from Gore's supporters. Clinton, though,
asserted that she had taken pains to avoid any conflicts with
Gore's campaign during their visits here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we're doing has been coordinated with the vice
president and Tipper and top-levels of our staff,'' she said,
referring to the vice president's wife, Tipper Gore. Clinton
emphasized her point by gesturing with a hand loaded down with a
charm bracelet. Asked if that meant that she would allow Gore's
advisers to review her speech before she delivered it on Monday,
Clinton grinned and responded: ``Of course I would. I haven't
written it yet. I worked on it this morning. But you know _ if they
want to see it, I'd be more than happy to show it to them. It's
only 10 minutes long.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, she asserted there was no need for explicit
coordination on what she should say. ``We know each other so
well,'' Clinton said, leaning back in a room that was empty except
for a floral arrangement and trays of cookies and soft drinks. (She
and the president were staying on another floor).
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need to give me talking points,'' she continued.
``We know what our talking points are for this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   As to her own campaign in New York, Clinton said that Lazio was
going to great lengths to camouflage his record, and pointed to his
decision to spend a minimal amount of time at the Republican
convention. ``I think that's why he didn't want to spend a lot of
time in Philadelphia,'' she said, referring to the Republican
convention two weeks ago. ``I think he's hoping that New Yorkers
will somehow not know where he stands and what he has voted for in
the past. I think now that the campaign is into the final stretch,
that's going to be hard to avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she believed she was now entering into the a
new phase of the race, and expressed confidence that a contest that
has seemed frozen in place _ with poll after poll showing her tied
with Lazio despite her repeated attacks on his record _ would begin
to move once the conventions were over and people considered the
choice before them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of time,'' she said. ``It's a question of
issues. And people understanding what's really at stake in the
election, and what the differences between us are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
