<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES A SURE THING, BUT ALL BETS ARE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Roy Jones is betting on himself next month. He's
going to lose a bundle doing it, even though he's a sure thing to
defeat challenger Eric Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Jones considers himself the best fighter, pound for pound, on
the planet, and he may well be. He also believes he can make
millions negotiating for himself rather than working in conjunction
with his present boss, HBO. He can't.
</P>
<P>
   That HBO pays the most money in boxing to its stable of fighters
seems to be lost on Jones, who was angry at the deal HBO made with
his representative, Murad Muhammad, for a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   With one pay-per-view fight under his old contract remaining,
Jones has agreed to a Sept. 9 mandatory title defense against
Harding in New Orleans, and HBO has agreed to sell it on
pay-per-view even though no one believes anyone will buy it. They
agreed because Jones's company, Square Ring, is the promoter and
Jones is not getting a cash guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Jones will earn $15 out of every $34.95 sale, which means he
needs 60,000 buys to break even. Boxing people believe Harding will
make $650,000 and Jones will lose about $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody but (Mike) Tyson can be a free agent  &UR; today &LR;  and make
big money,'' said John Hornewer, a boxing attorney who advises many
fighters, including WBO heavyweight champion Chris Byrd, IBF
bantamweight champion Tim Austin, and occasionally Jones. ``HBO
pays the most money in the industry and everyone knows it. If you
leave them to become a free agent, where do you go?''
</P>
<P>
   That is the question Jones and Muhammad seem to want answered,
but if they take a financial bath Sept. 9, what do they have to
sell but a fighter who has done little in three attempts on
pay-per-view and will not work with promoter Don King?
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy could walk away with zip from this, but you have to pay a
price for freedom,'' says Muhammad. Perhaps so, but if Jones walks
away with zip, Muhammad may find himself in the worst of positions
_ having allowed his fighter to commit financial suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Where would Jones have to go from there? Probably back to HBO.
</P>
<P>
   HBO Sports president Seth Abraham is a wise negotiator and a guy
who has never let much of anything stand in the way of good
business. That's why it would be no surprise if he approaches Jones
after the financial bloodbath that is coming and hands him a check
and a new deal to continue the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   No one is better at allowing someone to save face than Abraham,
and after Jones gets over the shock of watching Harding earn more
than he does, he may well realize there is no free agency in boxing
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   He will if he's as smart as he thinks he is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   While Jones continues to refuse the one obvious fight he should
take, WBO champion Darius Michalczewski fights on. He is scheduled
to get in with David Telesco Sept. 9 in Germany. Jones destroyed
Telesco a while back, and if Michalczewski can do the same, it
would build interest in a fight with Jones. ``Roy Jones only dares
to open his mouth when I'm far away,'' claims Michalczewski. ``So
far, he is always hiding behind ridiculous purse demands. In the
meantime, even American journalists and fans attack him because
everybody realized that he is running from me. Jones's reproach
that I need biased judges in Germany is ridiculous. I don't need
judges at all.'' Michalczewski is 42-0 with 17 straight title
defenses . . . Shane Mosley will accept Ring magazine's award as
best pound-for-pound fighter next Sunday before the Mauricio
Pastrana-Heriberto Ruiz fight for the IBA junior bantamweight
title. Mosley is only the sixth fighter to be given this honor. The
others were Tyson, Julio Cesar Chavez, Pernell Whitaker, Jones, and
Oscar De La Hoya. The bout will be held at Harrah's in Kansas City.
Mosley, 35-0 (32 KO's), is also one of only six fighters to have
won the lightweight and welterweight titles _ Barney Ross, Henry
Armstrong, Roberto Duran, Whitaker, and De La Hoya are the others .
. . Mosley is awaiting his rematch with De La Hoya, which is
tentatively set for Jan. 20, although De La Hoya has yet to say he
is ready to fight. In fact, word is he has been concentrating on
his singing career and working on his golf game under one of the
sport's top professional trainers, and seldom thinks of boxing . .
. Reportedly, De La Hoya's father continues to protect trainer
Robert Alcazar. Many felt De La Hoya would dump his longtime
trainer after losing to Mosley. More than a few critics blamed
Alcazar for not adjusting De La Hoya's fight plan while Mosley
fought three different fights during the night. Problem with that
theory is De La Hoya made the same mistakes when Mosley fought
lefthanded that he had when he fought Whitaker. De La Hoya claimed
his trainers told him the wrong things to do the first time, which
they did. But has the guy got a memory? . . . Evander Holyfield's
trainer, Don Turner, has not been happy about rumors he will be
replaced as trainer of Michael Grant when he makes his October
comeback against Robert Daniels. According to the 61-year-old
Turner, no one has spoken to him about being replaced and Grant
has, in fact, assured him otherwise; yet the rumors persist. If
someone wants to claim Grant wasn't ready for Lennox Lewis, who
destroyed him in two rounds in April, that would be obvious, but
Turner trains the fighter, he doesn't make the fights. If Grant was
in over his head, he was put there by his managerial team. Jim
Thomas, legal adviser for Holyfield and a part of Grant's
management team, acknowledged last week that while Turner isn't
out, things may be changing after the Lewis debacle, regardless of
the fact Turner had no culpability in his fighter's meltdown.
``Mike is considering the possibility of adding someone to his
training team,'' Thomas said. ``He hasn't made a decision, but it's
a distortion for anyone to say Don is out. Don is still the head
trainer, but we know how Don is. If whoever else comes in and there
starts to be some undercutting or overcutting, it will have to be
dealt with.'' Thomas tried to compare the situation with the time
Holyfield brought in veteran Texas trainer Kenny Weldon to work the
handpads. Weldon gave the impression he was actually there for more
than that and Turner grew concerned about his position. ``Don was
upset and I went to Evander and Evander told him to get over it,''
Thomas recalled. ``He said Don was the head trainer. Michael lacks
that maturity.'' If Grant is blaming Turner for the amateurish way
he fought Lewis, he lacks sense. No trainer on earth would have
told him to charge out of his corner and start winging punches that
left him totally exposed. Worse, the day of the fight, Turner tried
to talk with Grant about the battle plan and Grant, who had
appeared to be swallowed up by the magnitude of the event all week,
walked away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits
</P>
<P>
   Byrd defends the WBO heavyweight title against Wladimir
Klitschko Oct. 14 in Germany. Klitschko is the WBC's No. 3
contender. Byrd won that title by defeating Klitschko's older
brother, Vitaly, who quit in his corner with a rotator cuff
problem. ``If they have any other brothers, Chris will fight them,
too,'' said Hornewer, Byrd's adviser . . . The latest Cuban Olympic
boxing team has been unveiled and heavyweight Felix Savon is back,
attempting to join legendary countryman Teofilo Stevenson as a
three-time Olympic gold medalist. Stevenson won in 1972, '76, and
'80. Savon won in '92 and '96 . . . Hornewer explained that Austin,
who fought Friday night, has been in King's doghouse after missing
a Showtime date eight months ago but was glad to be back working
for King again. ``You don't go to war with the Kings,'' Hornewer
said. Hornewer said that's why he felt the decision of WBA
welterweight champion James Page not to fight  &UR; last night &LR;  was
``professional suicide,'' regardless of the validity of his case.
``If freedom comes at a price, pay it, but don't lose your title
doing it. The purse bid was $112,000 (for Page) and Don was the
only bidder. I know the fight didn't come off in 60 days (as it
should have under WBA rules or a new purse bid should have been
ordered), but Page hadn't fought in a year; so what's better:
earning $112,000 or earning nothing and being stripped of your
title? If that's the purse bid, that's the purse bid.'' . . .
Johnny Tapia returns to the ring Sept. 1 on ESPN2 but has no
opponent yet. Tapia has been battling depression and on-going
promotional problems but at 48-1-2 is still hoping for a rematch
with the only man to defeat him, Paulie Ayala . . . Kostyu Tszyu's
promoter, Vlad Wharton, had a tough weekend in Phoenix even though
his fighter destroyed Chavez. First, he's short $163,000 in gate
receipts because a ticket sales office shut down two weeks after
the fight was announced and left with the cash. Second, he had
nearly $15,000 in goods stolen from his hotel room . . . Word is
circulating that Bob Arum will be fined $250,000 and put on
probation by the Nevada State Athletic Commission after admitting
to having paid $100,000 in bribes to the IBF to get Axel Schulz
rated so he could fight then-heavyweight champion George Foreman.
Rival promoter King claims a double standard after he was banned
from promoting in New Jersey simply for being indicted on several
federal charges for which he was never convicted. ``If that was me,
they'd have me in leg irons,'' King claimed last week. ``I am going
to become an abolitionist for the double standard.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local bleatings
</P>
<P>
   WBU light welterweight champ ``Irish'' Mickey Ward faces IBA
titleholder Antonio Diaz Saturday night in a 10-round non-title
fight at Foxwoods underneath WBO featherweight champion Prince
Naseem Hamed's title defense against Augie Sanchez. Ward (35-9, 26
KO's) has won 14 of his last 16; Diaz is 32-2 with 22 KO's. Diaz is
10 years Ward's junior, but at 34, Ward seems to be coming into his
own at a time when most fighters begin to fade. ``I can't wait to
fight on HBO again,'' said Ward, who stopped Sean Neary in his last
fight on HBO. ``It means a lot being there.'' . . . Promoter Lester
Bedford was irate last weekend after his fighter, James Leija, lost
a split decision to Juan Lazcano at Mohegan Sun. Bedford protested
the use of judge Steve Weisfeld, who has a longtime relationship
with Gary Shaw, president of Main Events, the promotional company
that promotes Lazcano. As the cards were read, Weisfeld's was the
swing vote, and it gave the bout to Lazcano by the widest margin.
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services, personal interviews and boxing
sanctioning bodies was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
