<HEADER>
A9958 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-GORDON-     08-12 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON IS KING OF THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past three years, Jeff Gordon's dominance on road-course
venues has grown to Tiger-like proportions over the rest of his
NASCAR Winston Cup competitors. Gordon is such a factor that his
presence makes him an overwhelming favorite to take the checkered
flag.
</P>
<P>
   He is, simply, the man to beat.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to road courses, so far, no one has.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the last six road-course races on the Winston Cup
circuit, Gordon will attempt to extend his winning streak to seven
when he starts Sunday's Global Crossing at The Glen at Watkins
Glen, N.Y. While he has made it seem effortless, Gordon admits his
impressive record has not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked really hard on my road-course driving and we stepped
up our road-course program,'' he said. ``I can't believe we've won
six in a row. I've got to hand it to this team; we haven't grown
complacent during this streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're constantly trying to improve our road-course program.
``We can't relax because the competition is so tough out here.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Gordon lost on a road course was June 1997 at
Sears Point Raceway in Sonoma, Calif., finishing second. Since
then, he has been virtually unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   So, it has begged the question: Can anyone stop him?
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Marlin, who came close to snapping Gordon's streak this
year at Sears Point, offered one unconventional suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I do have the sure-fire way of somebody else winning
on these road courses,'' Marlin said. ``All the drivers are going
to get together, take up a collection, and sponsor Jeff in Formula
One for a year. Of course, the way things have been going, he'd
probably be off that weekend for Sears Point and decide to come
back to run that one race.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gordon, a three-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion, is
eighth in the point standings, more than 400 points astern of
current leader Bobby Labonte, he has managed to win twice this
year, including at Sears Point, where he held off Marlin in the
late stages of the Save Mart/Kragen 350K to keep his streak alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it came a whole lot closer to ending at Sears Point
than people might have thought,'' Marlin said. ``We were giving it
a pretty good run there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gordon has proven Tiger-like on road courses, where he has
practically lapped the field in his six consecutive victories,
Michael Waltrip said the streak is due to run its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely, somebody will trip him up at Watkins Glen, I would
think,'' said Waltrip. ``I can't imagine him winning another one.
He does things that you can't really figure out sometimes, but I
think somebody will get him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things never go on forever. Now it's just a question as
to whether `forever' comes this week or next year at Sears Point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major moves
</P>
<P>
   On a weekend when older brother Terry's streak of 655 starts
came to an end, Bobby Labonte celebrated a milestone triumph _ one
that could very well launch him to his first Winston Cup
championship _ in last Saturday's Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis
Motor Speedway. Labonte (3,006 points) padded his lead over Dale
Jarrett by 87 points and collected a whopping $831,225 for
finishing ahead of runner-up Rusty Wallace. It was Labonte's 14th
career Winston Cup victory and his second ``major,'' after a
triumph in the 1996 Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte. ``It's definitely a
dream come true when you win any race,'' Bobby said. ``Then, when
you can win the Coca-Cola 600, the Brickyard 400 now, and every
race between the two, hopefully, from then on, too, it's just a
great feeling. You see the guys who have won this race and you just
wish you could be part of it. I guess if we had come down the front
straightaway upside down and on fire, that would have been the
ultimate. But, anyway, it's just awesome. To know the guys who have
won this race, the prestige behind this race, the amount of press
that goes on here, and the fact that they're going to have a
Formula One race here this year _ on the same track _ that's cool.
I think it's just neat. There are races that are more special and
this is definitely one of them.'' . . . Terry Labonte will sit out
Sunday's race at Watkins Glen and turn over his No. 5 Kellogg's
Corn Flakes Chevrolet to Ron Hornaday, the Busch Series driver for
Dale Earnhardt's outfit. Labonte plans to return for the Pepsi 400
a week from Sunday at Michigan Speedway after sitting out the
Brickyard 400 because of lingering dizziness from a concussion
sustained in a July 1 crash at Daytona. ``This is going to give
Terry two weeks off to rest and recuperate,'' said John Hendrick,
president of Hendrick Motorsports. ``We're grateful to Dale
Earnhardt and the DEI organization for allowing Ron to come over
and help us out this weekend. As he's shown throughout his career,
in both trucks and cars, Ron's capable of running up front every
week, regardless of the series. We think he'll do a good job in
relief until Terry rejoins us at Michigan.'' . . . Jeremy Mayfield,
who also sat out the Brickyard because of a concussion from a
violent wall crash last Friday at Indy, will miss Sunday's race.
He'll be relieved by road-racing expert Tom Hubert in the No. 12
Mobil 1 Ford Taurus. ``Especially because of where we are in the
points right now, there is no sense in taking a chance,'' said car
owner Michael Kranefuss. ``We'd rather let him rest for one more
week and be ready to go for all the key races coming up right at
Watkins Glen.'' Said Mayfield: ``Honestly, I feel fine and
everybody says everything is OK. ``I'd much rather be driving than
not driving, believe me. But everybody seems to think this will be
for the best in the long run. All I want to do is get back in the
racecar.'' . . . As has been rumored for months, CART car owner
Chip Ganassi officially entered the Winston Cup derby when he
acquired a majority stake in Team SABCO, owned by Felix Sabates.
Ganassi, whose CART team has won the last four consecutive
championships and the 2000 Indy 500 with driver Juan Montoya,
announced he will switch from Chevrolet and campaign the Dodge
Intrepid. He becomes the fourth CART owner to field a Winston Cup
team, with Roger Penske, Carl Haas, and Cal Wells. ``If you have
any competitive spirit, you can't ignore NASCAR Winston Cup
racing,'' said Ganassi. ``It's impressive to see the level of
competition, the close racing, and the way NASCAR touches the fans
every day.'' . . . The career of Indy Racing League driver Scott
Harrington has come to a perilous crossroads after he was arrested
for driving under the influence of alchohol last Saturday in
Indianapolis. It marks Harrington's third DUI offense in the last
eight months, which could carry a jail sentence of up to three
years. His latest offense comes after he reached a plea bargain on
his DUI arrests of Jan. 9 and May 27, serving 80 hours of community
service. ``I've got to get some help and deal with these
problems,'' Harrington told the Indianapolis Star. ``This is not an
isolated experience, and you don't do things like this without
having a problem. I've made some bad decisions and some serious
errors in judgment.'' Harrington will not be able to race in the
next IRL race Aug. 27 at Sparta, Ky., until he receives medical
clearance. ``I've had a lot of problems in my personal and
professional life lately, but that's no excuse,'' he said. ``I'm
not as strong as I should be, and I let it get the best of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from interviews, wire services, track publicity
departments, various race sanctioning bodies, teams, and sponsors
was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
