<HEADLINE>
CASSERLY'S HOMEWORK WILL BE COMPLETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Former Redskins general manager Charley Casserly
had just arrived in Atlanta late Friday afternoon after spending
Thursday in Pittsburgh to scout the Steelers-Panthers game. By the
time this weekend is over, Casserly, the GM of the new Houston
franchise, will have seen four games. All of this for what? His
franchise is two years away from officially existing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making decisions on players based on their history, so
the more history you have and the longer our scouting staff works
together, the better decisions we'll make when the time comes,'' he
said. ``It's important we start to work as a unit. The first
decisions we'll make on players are going to be signing street free
agents and in the expansion draft. If you can follow someone you'll
have better knowledge. An example is quarterback Trent Green. We
scouted him in college and in his first year at San Diego. We put
him on injured reserve and he sat a whole year. The next year he
threw 25 passes for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly said he'll be responsible for signing 100 players in
Houston's first season. He and his 12-man staff already are
evaluating players who may be free agents in two years. And
Casserly already is scouting players who will be available in the
college draft in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gathering all the background you can is vital in this
business,'' he said. ``The longer I'm in this business, the more
important it is that you have experienced people who can evaluate
talent. We've hired seven guys with 20 or more years in the NFL. We
have eight scouts who have had teams go to the Super Bowl. Every
one of our scouts has had a divisional championship and won at
least one playoff game. We have a group who knows how to do the
job. The challenge is meshing together.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those talent evaluators is former Patriots director of
player personnel Bobby Grier, who is the associate director of
college personnel with Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby has a lot of experience and he understands how the
process works,'' said Casserly. ``He's been in charge of a team and
to bring that type of experience into a new organization is
invaluable.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly said he has a large staff because in the beginning
there's so much work to do. There are so many players to evaluate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scouting is becoming more and more important,'' he said. ``You
can't keep your team together very long anymore because of free
agency, so you have to reload. You need different avenues to reload
your team. You can't ignore veteran free agents and you certainly
can't ignore the June market. In my final year in Washington we
brought in (fullback) Larry Centers, (defensive end) Marco Coleman,
and (offensive tackle) Andy Heck. We also signed Terry Allen out of
that market and he gave us 1,300 yards of offense two straight
years. You have to find players who aren't so expensive. You have
to save money somewhere because the core players eat up so much of
your cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly already is insisting he will take ``the best player
available'' when draft day comes in two years. ``If it's a
quarterback, that's great. If it isn't, don't panic, just build a
team and wait for a time when you can go get that young quarterback
to build around.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly has two more important positions to fill _
capologist/negotiator, which will be hired next year, and head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   He said there's no pressure to hire a coach a year in advance,
but ``if we can do that, great.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when the Arizona Diamondbacks were entering the
National League, Buck Showalter was hired two seasons in advance.
He managed the Diamondbacks' first Single A team and
``coordinated'' for a couple of years. The Diamondbacks feared
Showalter, who was the hot young manager at the time, would not be
available if they waited another year. Tom Coughlin was hired a
year in advance in Jacksonville. On the flip side, Chris Palmer
went from coordinator in Jacksonville to head coach in Cleveland
without much time to get his team together. Ditto Dom Capers, who
went from defensive coordinator in Pittsburgh to head coach in
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly claims he doesn't yet have someone in mind, though
Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher would have been the choice had he not
signed a long-term extension with the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like someone who has head coaching experience,'' said
Casserly. ``If we don't get that person, we don't get that. That
won't eliminate college coaches. You want a coach who's a leader;
when he walks in the room he's in charge. Patience, the ability to
work with young players, mental toughness, and a vision will be
very important elements.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular candidates are the same ones who surfaced when the
Patriots were looking following last season. Capers is on the list,
but he's in a great situation in Jacksonville as the Jaguars'
defensive coordinator. He's also earning head coach money from the
Panthers for a couple more years, which may ease him right into big
money in Houston. Capers could also be the heir apparent to
Coughlin if the gruff Jaguars coach has a disappointing season.
Houston native Gary Kubiak, Denver defensive coordinator Greg
Robinson, Arizona defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis, Tampa Bay
assistant head coach Herman Edwards, LSU's Nick Saban, Florida's
Steve Spurrier, Chicago offensive coordinator Gary Crowton, and
even former Patriots coach Pete Carroll are possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly and team owner Bob McNair, both personable and public
relations conscious, would also want that in their head coach. No
personality-impaired coaches would be considered.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns, who returned to the league last season, went with
the Jacksonville method of expansion by signing lesser-known,
less-experienced players. Which way will Houston go?
</P>
<P>
   ``The landscape has changed dramatically since Jacksonville and
Carolina,'' said Casserly. ``I'm not sure you have a choice. You
have to emphasize youth. We won't look pretty for a couple of
years, I'll guarantee that. Tune in a couple of years down the
road. The free agent market isn't what it used to be. The market
has dried up young players because now teams are tying them up.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is currently telling McNair and Casserly that Houston
will get the top choice in the 2002 draft and receive extra picks
in the middle of every round. Casserly and McNair believe that
should be changed. They feel their draft picks need to be moved
from the middle to the top of each round.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the subject of in which division Houston will play.
Bob Kraft, among others, agrees with McNair that Houston should be
an AFC Central team. Saints owner Tom Benson feels Houston and New
Orleans should be in the same division. But after awarding the
franchise, most owners agreed the best rivalry would be for Houston
to be in the same division as Tennessee, the team that left Houston
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Houston will unveil a nickname and logo Sept. 6. Uniforms will
follow. One thing is clear, the Houston franchise will distance
itself from anything to do with the old Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly appears to be having a ball putting this together. He's
says he's picked the brains of guys who have been through expansion
_ Capers, Bill Polian, Joe Mack, Carmen Policy, Palmer, and Dwight
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked them a lot of questions about different things and
I'll continue to ask them,'' he said. ``They're all great and all
friends. The owner here is a fabulous guy. He's given us the
resources to be the best. The key is patience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back on the job
</P>
<P>
   He was coaching from a golf cart Thursday when the Dolphins beat
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. One side of his body now has half a
kidney, but former Patriots offensive line coach Paul Boudreau, now
Miami's line coach, is just tickled he's still alive. Right before
training camp, Boudreau noticed blood in his urine, a situation
that worsened. He was told by a Miami doctor he had a cancerous
growth in his kidney and that the kidney would have to be removed.
Boudreau balked at this and began making calls. One was to Globe
columnist Will McDonough, who called his medical sources, involved
Joe Browne from the league office, and before you knew it Boudreau
was in the care of Dr. Andrew Novick of the Cleveland Clinic, the
world's top authority in kidney surgery. ``Dr. Novick has performed
3,000 of these, more than anyone in the world,'' said Boudreau, a
former assistant coach at Boston College. ``He's performed surgery
on three kings and an old broken down football coach.'' Novick
salvaged half the kidney and told Boudreau it is still viable.
Boudreau appears to be on the road back as the cancer was confined
to the golf ball-sized tumor. ``I owe a lot to a lot of people,''
said Boudreau. ``Will McDonough got the ball rolling for me. Joe
Browne helped so much. The Cleveland Browns _ Carmen Policy and
Chris Palmer _ were wonderful to me and my family and Mr. (Wayne)
Huizenga (the Dolphins' owner) flew me up there in his private
jet.'' Boudreau said Dolphins coach Dave Wannstedt has told him to
take it easy and return when he's stronger. In Boudreau's absence,
retired Buffalo line coach Tom Bresnahan has guided the offensive
line, but a still sore Boudreau returned to work Thursday and is
back performing most of his duties . . . Check out these stats:
Brian Smith, a 5-foot-11-inch, 225-pound linebacker with the Idaho
Stallions of the Arena League has made a league-record 164 tackles,
including 90 unassisted . . . Chris Canty had a rough go of it in
New England, but he's fulfilled Grier's vision and is a nickel back
with the Seattle Seahawks. Canty was asked by a Seattle reporter
what characteristic he would change about himself. He said, ``My
attitude. I don't like taking a lot of stuff from people and being
in this profession, you've got to listen to your coaches and take
criticism. That's my biggest problem, but I'm getting there. I'm
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Breath of fresh air?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Romanowski, who is facing felony charges after being
accused of using his wife's prescription drugs, obviously has an
obsession with gaining an edge. Not only was he allegedly ingesting
his wife's diet pills, which helped to speed up his metabolism, the
fiery Denver linebacker invested in a $6,000 hyperbaric chamber,
used mostly by deep sea divers to recover from surfacing too
quickly. Romanowski brought the device to the Broncos' Greely,
Colo., training camp. He would climb into the 7-foot chamber, close
the door, then breathe the rich oxygen, which supposedly improves
endurance . . . How small is this world that new Redskins teammates
Deion Sanders and Irving Fryar, who never really knew each other
but now sit side by side in the locker room, were chatting one day
about their families and realized their grandparents were brother
and sister, therefore making them cousins? . . . One supposes if
Troy Aikman has one last great gasp left and if Emmitt Smith can
still run and if their young defense comes together the Cowboys
could still be a factor in the NFC East. But they're taking hits.
Last week, cornerback Kevin Smith, suffering from nagging hamstring
problems, left the team. He's contemplating retirement. Also
thinking about calling it quits is right tackle Erik Williams. They
are two players who are hard to replace. The worst thing is Kevin
Smith would count $1.5 million against the cap. There have been
reports the Jaguars are trying to trade for Williams given they've
lost seven offensive linemen to injuries, but Williams appears
serious about hanging it up . . . The Dolphins have been written
off by a lot of people, but their defense, which ranked fifth last
season, could be the best in the NFL. The consensus among the
players is that all they need is to be consistent. Last season, the
Dolphins held opponents to fewer than 21 points in eight of the
first 11 games, but failed to achieve that in four of the last
five. The Dolphins say that with another year to jell, watch out.
And their offense might be better than we thought. They beat the
Buccaneers, 15-13, Thursday. Granted, all the points came on Olinde
Mare field goals, but there were good signs, like 76 yards rushing
in the first half, six third-down conversions in that span, and 18
minutes of possession time in the first half. It means Miami's
running game and offensive line aren't as bad as we thought, even
going up against one of the best defenses in football. The Dolphins
even showed a bit of razzle-dazzle by using receiver Bert Emanuel
(a former option quarterback at Rice) at quarterback for two
third-down attempts. He converted both, one on a handoff, the other
on a keeper. Damon Huard fumbled and threw an interception in the
red zone, but he did move the offense. Why would the Dolphins use
Emanuel at quarterback while the Patriots don't appear ready to do
that with Michael Bishop? Because Huard is Huard and Drew Bledsoe
is Drew Bledsoe. When you have an unproven quarterback like Huard,
you can pull it off. When you have a Pro Bowler, doing such a thing
would be embarrassing to the star player and mess with Bledsoe's
confidence. Now you wonder how good the Dolphins might have been
had they been able to obtain Barry Sanders from the Detroit Lions
in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still a ways away
</P>
<P>
   Week 5 for Doug Flutie? That's what he thinks. He tore his groin
in training camp and the recovery will take at least that long.
Flutie said he doesn't feel any pain just walking around, but when
he tried to side-step a trash can at a mall near the Bills'
training camp last week, he felt a twinge. In the meantime, the
Bills will go, as planned, with talented Rob Johnson at
quarterback. Interesting to hear some of the younger Buffalo
veterans trashing the departed Thurman Thomas, Andre Reed, and
Bruce Smith, hinting that perhaps they did not provide the
leadership everyone assumed they had . . . Offensive line injuries
are killing teams, particularly Jacksonville, which has lost those
seven linemen, including tackle Leon Searcy. That's why the Jets
just begged Jumbo Elliott to come out of retirement. Now the Jets
can match the Patriots' experience at left tackle . . . Do you keep
believing that Kordell Stewart can be a force in the NFL or do you
just throw up your hands and admit that he's not a No. 1
quarterback? Who knows whether the Steelers have or will reach that
crossroad. In two exhibition games, and we remind all they are just
exhibitions, Stewart, who was one of the lowest-rated passers in
football a year ago, is 6 for 22 for 101 yards. The Steelers, who
must generate offense, are getting none from the man who needs to
do the generating. Plan B would be the immobile Kent Graham, who
has been an efficient 10 for 18 for 95 yards in two part-time
stints. Graham, a former starter with the Giants, is a guy veteran
players like to play around. He's considered the consummate
teammate and players have faith he can move the offense . . .
Robert Brooks, the former sensational receiver with the Green Bay
Packers who was forced to retire because of neck injuries, had an
excellent workout last week for the Broncos. Brooks is also being
pursued by the Raiders and Seahawks and though they're denying it,
the Eagles have their eye on him . . . John Hannah, who was voted
the Patriots Player of the Century, was enshrined in the College
Football Hall of Fame this weekend in South Bend, Ind. Hannah
(Alabama) joined 21 others, including Herschel Walker (Georgia),
Billy Kilmer (UCLA), Greg Pruitt (Oklahoma) and Willie Lanier
(Morgan State), as inductees . . . Just as Chargers quarterback
Ryan Leaf was beginning to make a comeback he felt a pop in his
surgically repaired shoulder in practice last week. Leaf, 24, has
been a bust compared with the quarterback taken one spot ahead of
him in 1998, Peyton Manning. But with all of his problems on and
off the field, there had been a feeling lately that Leaf might
salvage what many believed was going to be an illustrious career,
even better than his predecessor at Washington State, Bledsoe . . .
Slowly but surely, many of agent Tank Black's clients have begun to
find other representation. Black, who is serving time in federal
prison for money laundering, took some clients for thousands of
dollars. One former client is Allen, who now is represented by Gary
Uberstine. Allen is still interested in resuming his career. At
this point, Allen would only be added to a team's roster because of
injury. ``I have ongoing talks with teams, but it's mostly a case
where if a running back gets injured Terry would be able to resume
his career,'' said Uberstine. ``He's kept in shape and he's ready.
He's just waiting for a call.'' Uberstine spoke to the Patriots
about Allen, but there was no interest . . . Uberstine also is
gearing up for talks with the Patriots regarding tackle Chad Eaton,
who can become an unrestricted free agent after this season. If
Eaton has a good year, and so far he appears on that path, he could
demand a big paycheck next season . . . Antonio Langham is one of
the feel-good stories in Patriots camp, a guy whose career hit rock
bottom but who now feels he can get it back. ``Sometimes it takes
you to come down here from up here, to get back here,'' he said,
moving his hand from his waist to his head. ``A lot of people look
at it like you're only playing for the minimum after making money.
Right now, it's not a concern of money. Right now, I want to get my
game to the level it can be. Wherever I have to come from, I'll
come from. I think it's come a long way. I feel the drive and
intensity and willingness to compete again. Sometimes situations
take the drive out of you, but you go someplace else and you get
that back. This situation has brought the drive back. I never
questioned my physical ability because I always felt I had that.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
