<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BLACKHAWKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKHAWKS BRASS INVITES FACEOFF WITH FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Come one, come all. Such was the open invitation the Blackhawks
extended to their fans late last month, swinging wide the United
Center doors for Hawks followers to attend what could have been
billed as a hockey fan's midsummer dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New England town meeting is the concept,'' said Hawks
general manager Mike Smith, who makes his permanent home on
Martha's Vineyard, where his wife owns and operates an antiques
shop. ``Once a year, the citizens have the right to sit down and
talk to town officials.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they came, more than 550 Hawks fans, to fire questions at
Smith, new head coach Alpo Suhonen, and Peter Wirtz, representing
his father, Bill Wirtz, longtime owner of the bedraggled franchise.
By Smith's count, nearly 70 percent of the questions were directed
his way, with disgruntled fans quizzing him about what he's going
to do to bring fortune back to a club that has missed the playoffs
three straight seasons and hasn't won a Cup since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never what I'd call contentious,'' said Smith, who held
similar town meetings when he was the GM in Winnipeg and proposed
one two years ago when he was working in Toronto _ only to have it
shot down, he said, by Leafs boss Ken Dryden. ``People aren't going
to come in there and call you a jerk in front of all these other
people. In fact, there was some humor to it.''
</P>
<P>
   One citizen of Hawkville, said Smith, stood at the microphone
and flatly stated the club wouldn't improve until the GM dealt Eric
Daze. Later in the proceedings, another fan asked Smith which
player(s) he would deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I asked for volunteers,'' said Smith. ``And of course, from
back in the crowd I hear, `Eric Daze!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Based on his experience in Winnipeg, where the open mike
sessions eventually brought as many as 1,500 Jets fans to the
arena, Smith expects the crowds in Chicago to grow over the years.
In order to get a true pulse of the fans, he said, the meetings
can't be restricted to season ticket-holders.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's just for season ticket-holders,'' he said, ``that's
nothing more than a marketing ploy. Let's say the Bruins had a town
meeting. Well, the guy who can't afford to come to the FleetCenter
to see every game should have the same right to have his feelings
heard as the guy who can be there every game. We are selling
accountability. There comes the point, I think, where you have to
put yourself out there and be held accountable. A true town hall
meeting is for all citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Bruins fans would relish the chance to sit down and
talk shop with Messrs. Harry Sinden, Mike O'Connell, club owner
Jeremy Jacobs, and head coach Pat Burns. Based on the venom spewed
on talk radio here over the decades, it quite likely would turn
contentious, if not downright combustible. The Bruins have missed
the playoffs two of the past four seasons, and the Cup hasn't been
waltzed through City Hall Plaza since 1972. Fans of the once-proud
franchise constantly complain about high ticket prices and repeated
postseason failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said ticket prices are high _ which they
are,'' Smith said. ``One guy said, `These guys are way overpaid.'
Then later a guy gets up and says, `Until you spend another $8
million in salary, you're not going to be any good.' I don't agree
with what he said, but the two statements show the contradiction:
if you're going to spend on salary, it has to be reflected in the
ticket prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Lending an ear to vox populi won't change a club's fortunes one
point in the standings. If, say, Bill from Everett were to stand up
and assail Sinden and O'Connell with epithets, then it no doubt
would make for sensational film at 11 and great sound clips for
shocktalk radio. But it wouldn't squeeze another assist out of
Andrei Kovalenko in 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, given that Jacobs is an absentee owner, that
regular-season results have fallen off badly, that icon Ray Bourque
is now in the Rockies, that there hasn't been a high-profile free
agent signing since Kevin Stevens, that the last trip to the Cup
finals was in 1990, it sure would be one fun night to watch and
listen if the paying saints of Bruins Nation came marching to the
Vault to have their say.
</P>
<P>
   Just for one night, close the accounting room and swing wide the
doors of accountability.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Market crash
</P>
<P>
   Reports out of Philly have it that ex-Bruin Stevens agreed to a
one-year deal with the Flyers that will pay him only $400,000 _ a
paycut of some $2.8 million from his 1999-2000 salary with the
Rangers. But, remember, Stevens is returning after his January
arrest on possession of crack cocaine, and he said in an interview
with the Globe in the spring that, if necessary, he would accept as
little as an invitation to an NHL camp to prove that he can still
play. The Flyers, obviously, offered more. On top of the dough,
Stevens also will have veteran Rick Tocchet by his side to help
him, shall we say, skate his lane. Good for the Flyers, and good
for Stevens. Word around the league is that Wayne Gretzky, included
in the prospective ownership group of the Coyotes, desperately
wanted to bring Tocchet back to Phoenix. But the slow sales
transaction in Arizona has left the Great One little more than an
interested _ and somewhat peeved _ spectator, for now . . . Alexei
Yashin, showing no signs of relenting and returning to the Senators
for at least one more season (at $3.6 million), is back in Finland,
training under the watchful eye of Russian Olympic coach Vladimir
Yurzinov . . . Brad McCrimmon, who 21 years ago this September came
to Bruins training camp with fellow first-round pick Bourque
(McCrimmon was picked 15th overall, seven slots below Bourque),
signed on as assistant coach with Calgary last week, to work under
Don Hay. Often forgotten around here: McCrimmon was on the Flames'
backline when they won their Stanley Cup in '89 . . . Randy
Hillier, another ex-Boston blueliner from the early '80s, joined
the Pittsburgh staff as an assistant coach under Ivan Hlinka,
joining Bruins short-timer Joe Mullen and Rick Kehoe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jobs wanted
</P>
<P>
   There's less than a month to go before the start of training
camp and Bay State goalies Garth Snow and Tom Barrasso are still
looking for work. Snow had a tickle from the Thrashers, but GM Don
Waddell opted for Czech backstop Milan Hnilicka (2 years/$1.1
million), former property of both the Isles and Rangers. Early
summer rumors had the Red Wings inking Barrasso to a deal,
reuniting him with Scotty Bowman (both ex-Sabres), but right now
the former Acton-Boxboro standout remains shut out of work . . . A
recent USA Today story revealed that In the Game, a company that
produces NHL trading cards, cut up the goaltending pads of the
immortal Georges Vezina as part of a marketing ploy, inserting
minute portions of the desecrated goods into a memorabilia set of
cards. As part of the set, the company also carved up a Terry
Sawchuk blocker, gloves from Turk Broda and Jacques Plante, a
Vladislav Tretiak sweater, and Johnny Bower sticks. ``All this has
a precedent in the relics of religion, specifically Catholicism,''
said Dick Johnson, curator of the Sports Museum of New England.
``In Catholicism _ and I'm Catholic _ people talk about the
splinters of the true cross, and various relics of the saints.
Well, what these card companies do is nothing short of vandalism.
Cutting up a stick, I guess you could say is splinters of the truly
crass.'' Johnson's solution: card manufacturers could insert
scratch tickets, allowing one lucky winner to collect, say,
Sawchuk's blocker, or Vezina's pads, etc. ``Please,'' exorted
Johnson, ``deliver us from these empty marketing suits!'' . . . Ed
Carpenter, Boston University's longtime sports information
director, recently made the vigil to Windsor, Nova Scotia,
considered by many puckologists to be the place where hockey was
first played in North America. Windsor farmer Howard Dill, grower
of giant pumpkins (600-plus pounds), owns a stretch of land that
includes Long Pond, the humble kettle where a wooden puck allegedly
was first dropped. ``My wife and I sat on a bench at one end of the
pond,'' said Carpenter. ``The setting is just unbelievable. If
someone wrote the whole thing as a script, people would say,
`C'mon, who are you trying to kid?' '' It's a long way to Windsor,
but it's worth the trip, just to sit where the Carpenters sat,
never mind the added benefit of Dill's rich storytelling. Don't
dare die a hockey fan without getting there. It's as close to
Cooperstown as hockey gets, with barely a trace of commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They were free to leave
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes will start 2000-01 with no fewer than 10 veterans
deleted from their lineup, including Paul Coffey and Kovalenko,
both of whom bolted to the Bruins as free agents. Others not
returning: Gary Roberts, Robert Kron, Sean Hill, Nolan Pratt,
Curtis Leschyshyn, Sandy McCarthy, Mark Fitzpatrick, and Paul
Ranheim. Notice how the Canes threw $25.5 million to Sandis
Ozolinsh, acquired from Colorado, after staging a monumental
tug-of-war last season with franchise center Keith Primeau? A
recent report in New York had Isles GM Mike Milbury categorizing
the change in the Canes' philosophy as ``managerial
schizophrenia.'' . . . In case you missed it, Al Coates, knocked
off the job as GM in Calgary, was hired by Glen Sather to run the
Rangers' AHL franchise in Hartford. Sather also retained Don
Maloney as assistant GM and brought in Tom Renney, onetime bench
boss in Vancouver, as director of player personnel . . . No one
from City Hall has called to ask me, but it says here the perfect
solution for Fenway Deux would be a land swap with BU, including
the three West Campus towers, Walter Brown Arena, Nickerson Field
(nee Braves Field), and, if needed, the ancient Armory. BU would be
left with space for new dorms and various athletic facilities
(including a new rink) where Fenway now sits. No eminent domain. An
access ramp off the Mass. Pike, right into the Commonwealth Ave.
grounds. And, no doubt, far less tax money burned up for private
enterprise. Put Mike Eruzione in charge tomorrow and stop the
insanity. ``Sounds great,'' said Eruzione, the ex-Olympic hero
whose mission at BU these days is to gain funding for a campus
sports complex. Miracle Mike: ``We'd love to do it. And if someone
wants to build our facility for us, that would clinch it.'' . . .
Will Peter Popovic be an upgrade behind the Boston blue line?
Jacques Demers, his former coach in Montreal, once projected him
for NHL stardom, but that never happened. But at 6 feet 6 inches,
235 pounds, if he grows into the job here in the Hub, we can call
him the Boston Pops . . . Now that Molson Inc. has dimmed the
lights for last call with the Canadiens, wouldn't it be a hoot if
Budweiser, already with bleu, blanc et rouge in its logo, bought
the Habs? Cheers. Don't be surprised, says one source, if Delaware
North Companies _ the Jacobs empire _ enters the bidding for the
Molson Centre, if the team and the building are sold as separate
entities.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
