<HEADLINE>
BODYSUITS ARE A FASHION TREND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Nobody knows exactly how much faster the new
neck-to-ankle bodysuits make a swimmer (3 percent is the guess).
But now that they've been declared legal, nobody wants to be
without one. More than four-fifths of the competitors (everybody
but the breaststrokers, who find them constrictive) at the US
Olympic trials here took the blocks in one version or another of
the form-fitting Lycra blend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wear it till I die,'' vows Tom Malchow, who set
the world record in the 200-meter butterfly in June wearing a
bodysuit. ``Do I think it helped me get the world record? Yes. Do I
think I would have gotten it without it? No. Do I think I would
eventually get the world record without it? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a bodysuit, swimmers say, is like changing skins with a
Great White. ``It feels like you're sliding through the water,''
says Malchow. ``You feel like I imagine a shark does.'' Except that
a shark doesn't have to put it on. ``It's like pulling on nylons,''
groans Kristy Kowal. ``Only 10 times worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are there more than twice as many swimmers (1,300) at these
trials as there were in 1996 (570)? Because USA Swimming scrubbed
its usual summer nationals and invited everybody here for a taste
of Olympian pressure. That made for jammed warmup lanes, but they
were roomy compared with the overcrowding at the recent masters
worlds in Munich. ``There were 7,000 swimmers there,'' says former
US Olympic coach Peter Daland. ``That was a big meet.''
</P>
<P>
   How could a swimming record that stood for 18 years (Mary T.
Meagher's 57.93 in the 100-meter butterfly) be surpassed eight
times in less than a year? Could be what track people called the
Roger Bannister effect, the shattering of the mental barrier of the
four-minute mile. Once Jenny Thompson went 57.88 last August, 57.93
seemed routine. Inge de Bruijn of the Netherlands went under it
twice in May and July, and Thompson and Dara Torres did it five
times in two days here. Torres set an American record of 57.58 in
Wednesday's prelims, where Thompson did 57.89. Thompson went 57.59
in the semis, then 57.78 in the final, where Torres did 57.86. The
world mark, held by de Bruijn, is now 56.64.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short program
</P>
<P>
   The selection committees that will choose the final three women
and two men for the US Olympic gymnastics team at the FleetCenter
next weekend will be working with a loudly-ticking clock. Not only
will the spectators be twiddling their thumbs waiting for the
six-member teams to be marched out, NBC will be waiting, too. Not
that the committees won't have been conferring all week, but the
obvious picks will already have made the team based on their
scores. The federation has promised that the process will be quick.
If it's longer than 15 minutes, the selectors are going to need
earplugs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they're hoping for a specialist's spot on the team, the
three women (Shannon Miller, Jeanette Antolin, Amanda Stroud)
looking for injury waivers into the trials will have to show their
competitive readiness on all four events (bars, beam, floor, vault)
before the selection committee on Tuesday. ``It's an all-around
meet,'' declares federation president Bob Colarossi, who says that
any specialist chosen would have to have a major impact on one
event. That would mean either a medal possibility on one apparatus
or the ability to jack up the team score significantly. Only one of
the three has that ability _ Miller, who won gold on the beam in
Atlanta. Miller, still recovering from a cracked shinbone, pulled
out of last month's nationals after competing only once on bars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Play ball
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that the extended dispute over the makeup of the US
women's softball team was much ado about nothing. The last in a
line of arbitrators ruled that the original 15 players picked last
fall will play in Sydney after all. Julie Smith, who was left off
the team after winning a gold medal last time, challenged the
selection process, which led to a repicking, then another. By then,
after months of acrimony, Smith said she wouldn't take a spot even
if it was awarded her. Eight Atlanta veterans, including
38-year-olds Dot Richardson and Sheila Douty, made the team . . .
US Olympic women's soccer coach April Heinrichs isn't worried about
her team's combined 2-4-2 record this year against Norway and
China, the first two opponents at the Games. More important, she
says, was that the Americans crossed an ocean last month to play
three games in seven days against the Norwegians, Chinese, and
Germans and came out 2-0-1. ``It was a simulated Olympic experience
for us,'' Heinrichs says. ``We felt it was important for us to
advance after the first three games with 6 points and we came away
with 7. We are pleased about that.'' . . . There's only one new
face in the men's lightweight four on the US Olympic rowing team _
Harvard grad Greg Ruckman, who won a gold medal in the lightweight
eight at last year's world regatta. The returnees are Tom Auth,
Marc Schneider, and Paul Teti, whose older brother Mike coaches the
US men's sweep team . . . Nice showing by the US rowing team at the
recent world championships for non-Olympic events in Croatia. The
men's lightweight eight retained its gold medal (with seven new
people in the boat), as did the coxed pair. The men's coxed four
and women's lightweight pair (with Cambridge's Catherine Humblet)
won silvers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spiked out
</P>
<P>
   Could be the end of the Olympic road for volleyball legend Karch
Kiraly, who dislocated his right shoulder spiking on the final
point of a match in Belgium last week and may be done for the year.
Kiraly, who has won three gold medals (two indoors, one beach), was
in good shape to grab the second spot on the US beach team with
Adam Johnson. Even if they end up with enough points to edge Dain
Blanton and Eric Fonoimoana, odds are that Kiraly won't be fit to
compete in Sydney next month. If so, Johnson would have to go with
another partner . . . Tough Olympic draw for the US men's indoor
volleyball squad, which gets the world's top two teams in Italy and
Russia, plus defending bronze medalist Yugoslavia. If the Yanks
beat Argentina, they'll get to the quarterfinals, but a medal will
be a tall order . . . Rough tuneup road for the US men's water polo
team, which went winless at the recent Italian Trophy tournament
without main man Chris Humbert. Then they pulled out of a major
event in Yugoslavia featuring eight of the 12 Olympic qualifiers
after the US State Department advised them that the Americans might
be targets after the US bombing of Kosovo. Half a dozen members of
the 1996 team (Humbert, Gavin Arroyo, Dan Hackett, Chris Oeding,
Wolf Wigo, Kyle Kopp) will be in Sydney. On the squad, too, is
swimmer Brad Schumacher, who won two relay gold medals in Atlanta.
Schumacher also qualified for the swimming trials, but scratched.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Going, going . . .
</P>
<P>
   The incredible shrinking Yugoslav team, down from six republics
to two, probably will be down to one after the Sydney Games.
Montenegro wants to compete under its own flag, which leaves only
Serbia under the Yugoslav banner. Croatia, Bosnia, Slovenia, and
Macedonia all compete under their own names . . . Even though the
US women's field hockey team failed to qualify for Sydney, coach
Tracey Belbin has been rehired through 2004. Since she didn't sign
on until January of last year, Belbin had little time to shape up a
squad that was rebuilding from Atlanta and the federation
understood that . . . Who are James Morrison, Human Nature, Julie
Anthony, John Farnham, Olivia Newton-John, Vanessa Amorosi, and
Tina Arena? They'll be the star entertainers at the opening
ceremonies in Sydney. All of them are Aussies and all except
Newton-John are strangers to most of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services, personal interviews, the US Olympic
Committee, international federations, and national sports bodies
was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
