<HEADER>
A9963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-WOODSMA     08-12 1874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-WOODSMANIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER PHENOMENON NOTHING SHORT OF RUTHIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Calcavecchia was playing a practice round with Tiger Woods
at St. Andrews a few weeks ago when they began talking about major
championships. The British Open, suggested Woods, would be the one
he would win the most.
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia looked at Woods with surprise. ``I told him I
thought he'd win the US Open the most,'' and Calcavecchia explained
his reasoning that that tournament demanded more of a player in
terms of being long, straight, deft with the short game, and deadly
with the putter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me, and said, `Hmmm, maybe you're right,' '' said
Calcavecchia.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the structure of the pro golf world these days that most
players can only dream of winning one major (David Duval? Colin
Montgomerie? Phil Mickelson? Take your pick for the lead man in the
``Best Player Never to Win a Major'' category) while Woods can
seriously ponder which leg of the grand slam he will win the most.
</P>
<P>
   We are in the midst of something truly remarkable, for Woods is
giving us a glimpse of what it must have been like to have been
around in the days of Babe Ruth. That is not going overboard,
folks; the kid is that good.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, others have gone on major tears before in golf _ Ben Hogan
won eight majors in 11 starts from 1950-53; Arnold Palmer won five
majors in 11 starts from 1960-62 _ but no one ever has blown away
the competition the way Woods has. Even Jack Nicklaus conceded that
he never won touranments by the incredible margins Woods has, a
point that has prompted people to claim that the competition today
isn't what it was in the '60s, '70s, and '80s when the Golden Bear
was on the prowl.
</P>
<P>
   That is simply not true, but it's an argument that will rage
forever. However, to involve yourself in it is to chance losing
sight of the phenomenon going on before our eyes _ Woods. He faces
superb talent week in and week out, and his skills are so superior
it is frightening how inferior the opposition looks.
</P>
<P>
   Woods will bring his magic to Valhalla Golf Club in Louisville
this week to try to win his second straight PGA Championship. If he
succeeds, he will join Hogan as the only players to win three legs
of the grand slam in one year (Hogan did it in 1953). It also would
give Woods victories in four of the last five majors and would have
to make you wonder: How in the name of Bobby Jones did Woods not
win the Masters in April?
</P>
<P>
   Some will choose to bemoan the fact nobody can compete with
Woods. I'll choose to marvel at a young man who is taking us on a
most incredible ride. Just like the Babe did many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A real crowd pleaser
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to think of a victory that was received with more open
arms than Lorie Kane's last Sunday at the Michelob Light Classic.
After finishing second four times in 1997, once in '98, three times
a year ago, and once in 2000, the personable native of Prince
Edward Island was more than due for her first win. No one had
smiled through more disappointment than Kane, who is arguably the
most popular player in women's golf. When, in her 122d start on the
LPGA Tour, Kane held off a host of challengers, including Karrie
Webb, she was greeted at the 18th hole by many of her colleagues.
This just never happens at pro tour stops when most players are on
to the airport five minutes after that scorecard is signed . . .
Her college season ended in bitter disappointment _ a round of 85
to plunge into her a tie for 34th at the NCAA Championships as her
Duke Blue Devils, the overwhelming favorites, stumbled to a
stunning 14th-place finish _ and there have been signs that more
polish is needed, but Beth Bauer feels otherwise. Thus, the
long-heralded youngster is forgoing her final two years at Duke to
turn pro. Her amateur farewell was not what she would have wanted
as she got ousted in the third round of the US Women's Amateur when
Marcy Newton rattled off six straight birdies to fuel a 3-and-2
triumph. Bauer will make her pro debut at the State Farm Rail
Classic Sept. 2-4, but has already played in four LPGA Tour stops
this year. She missed the cut twice and finished T-35 and T-38 in
the others, and barring a near-miracle, Bauer knows she'll have to
go through Q School . . . While Bauer leaves, Duke coach Dan Brooks
prepares to welcome Leigh Ann Hardin, so the rich stay rich. Hardin
was medalist at last week's US Women's Amateur, though she got
knocked out in the third round . . . Dottie Pepper skipped the du
Maurier this weekend, still bothered by that sore back that forced
her to withdraw from the US Women's Open a few weeks ago. Grace
Park was another WD in Canada, citing a rib injury . . . People
have made a big deal out of Woods's appearance at this weekend's
Buick Open, claiming it is because of an endorsement deal. But why
begrudge Buick its ace, particularly when it holds in its hand
three guys drifting far, far down the marquee list. We're talking
Ben Crenshaw, Chip Beck, and Steve Elkington, all of them big Buick
guys. In the Buick Invitational and the Buick Classic, those three
players combined to miss four cuts, withdraw once, and post
finishes of T-21 and T-63 . . . This weekend, Crenshaw (78-77) and
Beck (76-74) again missed the cut, but Elkington did not play . . .
Woods three times has played the week before a major, 1997, 1998
and this weekend _ all preceding the PGA Championship. But for what
it's worth, the only time he didn't play the week before the PGA
was a year ago, and he won at Medinah . . . Shockingly, Lee Janzen
(73-72 at the Buik) has just one top-10 finish in 17 starts. He's
missed six cuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A double-double
</P>
<P>
   A round of applause for Eric McPhail of Sandy Burr and Brendan
Hester of Pleasant Valley CC, both of whom last week nailed down
berths in the US Mid-Amateur Championship, one week after securing
spots in the US Amateur. Considering the depth of talent and the
scarcity of spots, it's quite an accomplishment. McPhail survived a
playoff at Olde Barnstable to earn his way to Baltusrol (Aug.
21-27) for the amateur, but made it more easily at Oak Ridge GC,
shooting 70 to finish second and get a pass to The Homestead (Sept.
9-14) for the Mid-Am. As for Hester, it was a pair of extra-inning
victories as he survived playoffs at Salem CC (US Amateur) and Oak
Ridge to make the national tournaments . . . McPhail has something
more immediate on his plate _ the MGA Public Links Championship
Monday and Tuesday. The 1998 winner of this event, McPhail figures
to be in the thick of things at William J. Devine GC, known to all
as Franklin Park, though his competition will no doubt include
former champions Bob Bradley, Jon Fasick, Kevin Murphy, and Kevin
Hanlon, as well as young guns such as Tom Giles (Stow Acres), Kenny
Lewis (Dennis Pines), Michael Carbone (Dennis Pines), Josh Hillman
(CC of Greenfield), and veteran forces such as Bruce Carter
(Cyprian Keyes), Michael Fecteau (Rowley), Carter Fasick (Indian
Meadow), Rick Cunha (Plymouth), and Tom McManus (Cyprian Keyes).
The MGA should be commended for bringing this Public Links
Championship to Franklin Park, a course that is the epitome of
``public.'' The place is a true melting pot, and few courses in the
country can match its history, which includes Willie Campbell's
days as pro, Bobby Jones's visits, Donald Ross's redesign, and
Woods's visit for a junior clinic in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Going full cycle
</P>
<P>
   One of the players in the Francis Ouimet Scholarship Fund golf
marathon Wednesday at Stow Acres was Michael Zmetrovich, who
represented Tedesco CC in Marblehead. Ironic that the fund-raiser
was being held opposite the MGA Junior Amateur because 15 years ago
Zmetrovich reigned as winner of that tournament. Back then, he
said, ``I thought for sure I'd play golf the rest of my life,'' a
thought that now makes him laugh. Though it sounds as if he were a
naive young man, Zmetrovich's life these days very much involves
golf _ not as a player on the course, but as one within the Jack
Nicklaus business empire. The Haverhill native is senior vice
president of Golden Bear Club Services with offices in North Palm
Beach, Fla., and in Beverly. In that capacity he is involved with
the running of some of the country's premier golf clubs, from
Muirfield Village in Dublin, Ohio, to the brand new Bear Club in
Palm Beach, to Pasadera, Nicklaus's breathtaking club in Monterey,
Calif., to Vermont National CC, which just opened last year. ``The
Ritz of the golf business,'' is how Zmetrovich, 32, describes the
work he is brought into contact with because of Nicklaus. ``The
best part of the job is being part of a quality organization and
being around these great clubs. You can have the influence on how
to open these clubs and create things that will be there for a long
time.'' Zmetrovich graduated from Florida International University
in 1989 and came in touch with Nicklaus's group while working as an
asset management consultant to a group looking into golf course
properties. ``I was involved in strategic planning. I would help
solve problems and make recommendations. But I never had the
satisfaction of seeing something through start to finish,'' a
problem that has not surfaced since he joined the Nicklaus team
four years ago. As for his week of glory that summer 15 years ago
at Kernwood CC in Salem, Zmetrovich said, ``I remember hitting
balls on the practice tee area the morning of the qualifying rounds
and hitting the ball almost better than I ever had in the past.''
He had finished second in the New England Junior Amateur a few
weeks earlier, but at Kernwood he made it to the top. Proving that
champions never really leave the game, Zmetrovich 15 years later
was out playing 120 holes to help a charitable effort . . . Another
of the hardy souls who took part in the Ouimet fund-raiser was
Harry Rose, the assistant pro at Needham GC. Of course, marathons
are nothing new to the 46-year-old Rose; he has run 18 marathons
throughout the country. Rose, one time, needed just 19 minutes to
play nine holes at Needham GC . . . The official tally for the
Ouimet fund-raiser was $230,000 . . . Among those who failed to get
through US Amateur qualifiers in our area were a pair of Division 1
golf coaches _ Buddy Alexander of the University of Florida (at
Salem CC), and Mike Moraghan of the University of Virginia (at
Crestview CC) . . . Finally, what have our local golfers been
eating (and can I get some, too?), because they have defied the
laws of reality. We are told that the odds of making two
holes-in-one in the same round are astronomical, something like
70,000,000-1, yet it has happened twice within a three-week span.
First, Christine Barrie made a pair of aces at her home club, The
International in Bolton, and now Bill Pierce has done the
near-impossible. Playing at Wollaston GC in Milton during a
fund-raiser for the Boston College Club, Pierce last Wednesday aced
the sixth hole, then did it again at the 12th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services, personal interviews, and golf
sanctioning organizations was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
