<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SAIL-AMCUP-AMERICAONE     08-12 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMCUP-AMERICAONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAONE IS ON COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Cayard is a pragmatic man.
</P>
<P>
   He does not sail in the America's Cup unless he has a decent
shot at winning.
</P>
<P>
   He does not jump into competition without a thorough analysis of
his strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks he may be good enough to beat one of the new
billionaires, but not four of them.
</P>
<P>
   So, the worst kept secret of Cup 2003 _ Cayard will join his
AmericaOne sailing syndicate with Oracle billionaire Larry Ellison
_ has come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Cayard announced Ellison bought the assets of the
2000 AmericaOne syndicate, forming a new syndicate combining the
sailing prowess of AmericaOne with the bottomless cash of Ellison,
who is a newly impassioned enthusiast of sailboat racing.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison joins three other such campaigns around the world _
Italy's Patrizio Bertelli, Switzerland's Ernesto Bertarelli, and
Seattle's Craig McCaw _ that have the advantage of starting without
financial constraints.
</P>
<P>
   More important to them, perhaps, than the $80 million bottom
line, is the upfront money that assures them a place in the
professional sailor/designer free agent market the Cup has
developed into.
</P>
<P>
   The other known player, at this point, is the New York Yacht
Club, which, just as it seemed resigned to sit out 2003, announced
a deal with Team Dennis Conner after two previous attempts over the
past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Conner brings his own management skills and a sailing team that,
on a shoestring budget in Auckland, made a strong run at the
semifinals with Newport's Ken Read at the helm and player-coach Tom
Whidden calling tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The exact proportions of New York's budget are unknown, but far
from the $80 million of the big four. Still in the rumor mill is
talk that Jim Clark (Netscape) and even Bill Gates _ both a
presence in Auckland _ are considering a dive into America's Cup
waters.
</P>
<P>
   But what is clear as time ticks away is that there is more money
out there than experienced Cup sailing talent, and that most of the
latter is already committed. New Zealand, ravaged by Bertarelli's
Swiss entry, which snapped up Russell Coutts and Brad Butterworth,
is going through the motions of trying to keep what remains of its
once powerhouse team by holding a national fund-raising drive to
pay sailors signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard does not blame Coutts and Butterworth for jumping ship.
``Russell Coutts is not only a two-time America's Cup winner, he
was an Olympic gold medalist in Finn Class,'' said Cayard. ``He's a
very accomplished sailor. And he probably was earning a tenth of
what (Italian skipper) Francesco deAngelis got paid last time. So
now New Zealand sees it needs to compete with the billionaire
challengers. On the other hand, with Coutts and Butterworth in
Switzerland, now the Swiss have a potentially very potent team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard thinks the broadening of the talent base and the infusion
of money only improves the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '20s and '30s, the Vanderbilt, Sopwith, Lipton sagas
were common to the event,'' said Cayard. ``The America's Cup has
always taken men of wealth to put it together. They were
industrialists, and now the leaders of high-tech have the capital
to play this game. It suits them because it is a high-tech game.
There may be fewer challengers (in 2003) than last time, but this
is the kind of thing great stories are made of. It will be
incredibly exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cayard announcement, made from his San Francisco compound,
throws the next Cup into two distinct tiers: at least four teams
are freed from constant fund-raising; and all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to be realistic,'' said Cayard, noting that selling
``our child (AmericaOne)'' was a tough choice. ``But I feel good
about what we have done to find a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem seeking that solution, said Cayard, is that
AmericaOne, engaged in the drag of constant fund-raising, would
have a budget of around $30 million, not enough to compete with the
super syndicates. So the choices were to fold AmericaOne, let the
time pass until they were out of options, or make a proactive move.
The Ellison deal became a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard would not disclose what Ellison paid for his syndicate,
but said the deal was good for both sides. ``AmericaOne has a lot
to offer anyone who would want to enter the America's Cup. We have
two great boats, a lot of good energy that went into them. The base
in New Zealand is a work of art. So I think we had a great platform
to offer the (Ellison) team, and we were fairly compensated for all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard's role in the new syndicate is still at question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am personally evaluating what I want to do. Some days I wake
up and say it's a lot of hard work to be the best skipper in the
world, and I want to spend time with my family. So I'm not going to
take a front-line position on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then there are other days I go to the gym and lift more
weight than I ever lited before, and say `Hell, I'm only 41 years
old. I can do it. I'm going to dedicate the time to be the best
sailor.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With designs due in November, Cayard noted that Prada and the
new Ellison teams will have the early advantage, since both
syndicates already have proven designs to work from.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, so does Team New Zealand, which at this point may
still be their trump card.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
