<HEADER>
A9965 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-BBNOTES-SHOWALTER     08-12 2400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-SHOWALTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS APPEAR TIRED OF THIS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're not supposed to judge a man by the clothes he wears, but
in Arizona, you could lose your job for telling another man how to
wear his socks.
</P>
<P>
   Buck Showalter, who signed a seven-year, $7-million deal with
the Arizona Diamondbacks two years before the D-Backs even started
playing, was under fire last week because his players reportedly
are fed up with his rule-for-every-occasion approach. That includes
a stipulation that the D-Backs wear their socks with the ``A''
facing up.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter's need for control extends to off-field stuff, too,
according to the East Valley Tribune, the Arizona newspaper that
reported Showalter ordered video scoreboard operators to stop
showing the American League's home run leaders because former
Diamondback Tony Batista was on the list and that reflected badly
on the club.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Republic columnist Pedro Gomez created the latest furor
with a column last Tuesday. ``They can't wait around for Showalter
and his paranoid personality to change his ways,'' Gomez said.
``Ownership needs to seize the moment while there's still a moment
to be had.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy could have ended there, but Arizona players did
little publicly to shoot down the column, and D-Backs boss Jerry
Colangelo, while saying he thought Showalter was doing a ``very
good job,'' left himself some wiggle room to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I felt there were changes that needed to be made, I would
have done it,'' Colangelo told reporters. ``My feelings are kept to
myself and I respond when I feel it's necessary to respond, one way
or another. And right now, I'd rather just concentrate on this team
playing good baseball, getting healthy, and winning games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A question has been raised. Some might come to a conclusion or
opinion. But from my standpoint, I don't need any advice from
anyone. I've been around too long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, despite the acquisition of Curt Schilling to
pair with Randy Johnson as two 300-strikeout men at the top of
their rotation, have barely played .500 baseball over the last
couple of months. They haven't gotten the production they received
last year from veterans Matt Williams and Jay Bell, but it appears
to go deeper than that.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter, a winner with the Yankees until he clashed one too
many times with George Steinbrenner, is a demanding boss who can
irk friend and foe alike. No one said a word last season when the
D-Backs won 100 games in just their second year of existence, but
with the club falling behind the Giants in the NL West, his style
is coming under increasing attack.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter is one of the most meticulously prepared managers in
the game, one who is Joe Kerrigan-like in his devotion to studying
charts and tendencies and the like. His people skills, however,
have always been questioned, much like Dan Duquette in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine this: The Giants, D-Backs, and Dodgers are running 1, 2,
3, in the West, and all three teams could have new managers next
season. The Giants want to keep Dusty Baker, but he is a free agent
after the season and could be in great demand. Showalter is under
the gun, and Davey Johnson's bosses at Fox are not satisfied with
the way the Dodgers have hovered just over the .500 mark.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Checking out
</P>
<P>
   Rico Brogna still enjoys coaching basketball as much as ever,
but the Watertown (Conn.) High School freshman coach has put his
career on hold for a couple of years so that he can spend more time
with his daughter, Alexa, who turns 3 in October. Brogna coached
seven years at Watertown. ``I had a 12-5 record my last year,''
Brogna said with a smile. ``I guess I wanted to go out on a winning
note.'' Brogna said he also has written three or four football
playbooks for use by high school teams . . . Rod Beck, on the huge
turnover in the Sox clubhouse: ``There are a lot of veteran dudes
that I crossed paths with at some point. It only takes a couple of
minutes to remember a couple of at-bats I had against 'em. I know
when I first came up I used to think it was weird that big Don
Robinson would be standing next to the batting cage in every city
we played, talking to guys. I used to think, `How the hell does he
know all those guys?' Now I know. You just have to be around long
enough.'' How does the constant turnover affect clubhouse
chemistry? ``Chemistry comes in a lot of forms,'' Beck said. ``As a
player, I've been asked maybe 100 times to describe what it is. It
changes from clubhouse to clubhouse, and can change from year to
year. I can't put my finger on the word to describe it. It's not
like if you have X and Y you have clubhouse chemistry. It has a lot
to do with winning. Winning solves a lot of problems. Win a few
games, a team starts to jell.'' . . . When Beck was with the
Giants, he played with Deion Sanders, now a full-time football
player with the Washington Redskins. ``I genuinely liked and
respected Deion. He once told me he could fall out of bed and cover
a guy in football, but he had to work at this. And he did. Every
day I'd be on my way to the bullpen and Deion would be in front of
a mirror, working on his swing. He took balls off the bat in
batting practice in the outfield, and he worked on his base
running. You have to respect someone who respects the game like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not worth it
</P>
<P>
   Count Red Sox outfielder Darren Lewis among those who are
concerned about the use of protein and muscle-enhancing
supplements, not to mention the use of illegal steroids.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed at the large number of players on the disabled list
as evidence that some players are breaking down because of the use
of supplements. ``Guys are adding 15 to 20 pounds on frames that
just weren't made for it,'' he said. ``That's why you see so many
hamstring and other muscle pulls. You look at the number of games
we play, and the fact that we're traveling more than ever, the body
breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't use any of that stuff. I make my living this way, the
way that I am. I'm not all of a sudden going to hit 20 home runs. I
try to keep my weight stable, get my rest and will continue to play
as long as my legs are good.''
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of the supplements, Lewis believes, stems in
part from the vast rewards available to athletes at an increasingly
younger age. ``You look at Venus Williams in tennis, who is barely
20 years old, Kevin Garnett, Kobe Bryant, Darius Miles. You can
beome a millionaire before you're 20. You're willing to take risks
(with your body).''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, on how baseball is changing: ``This is just my opinion,
but we're seeing more and more of the same player. The guy who hits
20 home runs and drives in 80 to 100 runs, but his flip side is he
doesn't know how to bunt, he can't hit and run, and stealing a base
has become almost obsolete. You don't have the Willie McGee type
player anymore. To me, it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cox using mirrors?
</P>
<P>
   One National League general manager on the Atlanta Braves,
bidding for their ninth straight division title: ``For the last
three years, we, like everybody else, have said the Braves are
vulnerable to this and that. But this year, Bobby Cox has had no
closer, his team has really been banged up, they're not
overpowering offensively, and they're still the best team in our
league. I think Bobby Cox has done his best job ever of managing.
He's done an amazing job. He gets slammed when the Braves don't win
the World Series, but I think he's one of the best.'' . . . Carl
Everett's agent, Larry Reynolds, was successful in persuading Frank
Robinson that his client did not head-butt umpire Ronald Kulpa. In
1990, when Roger Clemens was ejected from Game 4 of the American
League Championship Series against the Oakland A's for his run-in
with umpire Gerry Cooney, the lawyers in charge of his appeal were
prepared to use a deaf woman from the New York Institute of the
Deaf who was an expert in lip reading to testify on Clemens's
behalf. The woman specialized in lip reading from videotape, and
had been used in the movie industry to recreate scripts. She was
prepared to tesify with ``100 percent certainty,'' according to one
source, that what Cooney claimed Clemens yelled at him, Clemens
didn't say, and that Clemens was 99 percent precise in his version
of what he said. But commissioner Fay Vincent refused to hear an
appeal after then-AL president Bobby Brown gave the Rocket a
five-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That didn't take long
</P>
<P>
   Did you notice that Jeff Frye is already out of the Rockies'
starting lineup? Manager Buddy Bell has elected to go with Todd
Walker, picked up from the Twins, with Frye limited to pinch hiting
. . . Left off the list of home runs hit to end marathon games: On
June 24, 1962, Jack Reed hit a two-out home run in the 22d inning
to end the longest game in Yankees history, a 9-7 win at Detroit.
Reed, a seldom-used backup outfielder, played for the Yankees from
1961-63, appearing in 222 games. In 129 big-league at-bats, that
was his only home run. Thanks to reader Bob Interato for that gem .
. . Former Sox pitcher Earl Wilson has been named CEO of the
Baseball Assistance Team (BAT), the organization founded to help
out former players in need. Wilson succeeds Joe Garagiola . . .
Jimy Williams makes it a rule not to talk about his family _ it's a
privacy issue for him _ but kudos go to his daughter, Monica, who
swam in the US Olympic trials after being named team MVP at Texas
A&AMP;M in a vote by her teammates. Monica Williams swam the
second-fastest time in school history in the 200 freestyle and
ranks third on A&AMP;M's all-time list in the 100 freestyle . . . Bell
on Brian Rose, after the former Sox righthander won his first start
for the Rockies, allowing a run in six innings: ``I was impressed
with his command more than anything, and his ability to make big
pitches when he needed them. Brian is a competitor. He throws
strikes. He's got an idea what he's doing.'' . . . The Giants'
starting rotation seems set for the foreseeable future after they
signed lefthander Kirk Rueter to a three-year, $15.6 million deal
that included a $3.35 million signing bonus. Rueter, eligible for
free agency after the season, almost certainly could have commanded
more on the open market _ he's 29 and had won 44 games in the three
seasons prior to this one _ but he said he wanted to stay with the
Giants. He is the senior member of a collection of young guns that
includes Livan Hernandez, 25; Russ Ortiz, 26; Shawn Estes, 27; and
Joe Nathan, 25. Injuries can wreck the best-laid plans, of course,
but it would seem the Giants are in a position to be competitive
for some time to come . . . Chipper Jones has yet to sign a new
deal reported to be for six years and $90 million, but Sammy Sosa
is already salivating about what it means for him. Sosa, who now
says he wants to finish his career with the Cubs, still aims to be
the game's highest-paid player, though it's debatable whether the
Tribune Company will give Sosa more than the $15 million annual
average of Jones's contract, which reportedly will also include two
option years. ``My value is going to go up, seeing the way they
took care of Chipper,'' Sosa said . . . After beating the Cubs
Friday, the Reds have gone 115 games without being shut out this
season. The only team to go an entire season without being blanked
is the 1932 Yankees, the team for which Babe Ruth supposedly called
his shot in the World Series against the Cubs . . . Jones's Atlanta
teammate, Greg Maddux, said he struggled the first year after he
signed a big contract with the Cubs. ``After a while,'' he told
Bill Zack of the Morris News Service, ``you start to realize the
money doesn't change the player. The only difference is you can buy
two of everything instead of one.'' . . . Are the White Sox hearing
footsteps? They were 14-14 since the All-Star break entering play
Saturday. Rocky Biddle Thursday became the fourth White Sox pitcher
to make his big-league debut since July 4, joining Jon Garland,
Mark Buehrle and Lorenzo Barcelo. Little wonder manager Jerry
Manuel is hoping the White Sox pick up another veteran pitcher . .
. Ex-Sox righthander Pat Rapp could be available. The Rapper has
won just three of his last 18 starts and is expected to be traded
or released by the Orioles . . . Another Bird in free fall is
Albert Belle, who has hit just three home runs in his last 37 games
and was 12 for his last 68 entering the weekend. Belle has a
painful hip injury, but it hasn't been bad enough for manager Mike
Hargrove to yank his slugger out of the lineup . . . Derek Bell,
Everett's Tampa buddy, was fined the other day by Mets manager
Bobby Valentine for showing up at 5:40 p.m. for a 7 o'clock game.
``I got caught in traffic and there was nothing I could do about
it,'' said Bell, who last month ran in from right field while
Everett was throwing his nutty . . . Everett, who was a perpetual
late arrival all season, was among the early birds all last week.
One veteran player on another club suggested it was unfair to
single out Everett for his tardiness. ``Nowadays, stars push the
rules moreso than they used to,'' the player said. ``But rules are
rules. Why should Manny Alexander be on time when Pedro (Martinez)
and Carl Everett are not. That shows a lack of respect for
teammates. From what I hear, Jimy Williams has three rules: Be on
time. Play hard. Dress code on the road. That's it. What's so hard
about that?'' Why doesn't Nomar Garciaparra stretch the rules?
``Nomar has respect for his teammates and the game,'' the player
said . . . The Yankees, with Roger Clemens poised to sign a
reported extension for three years and $30 million, have Clemens,
Denny Neagle, Andy Pettitte and Orlando Hernandez under their
control for the next three seasons . . . The Phillies have gotten
rid of five of the nine players in their Opening Day lineup:
pitcher Andy Ashby, first baseman Rico Brogna, second baseman
Mickey Morandini, shortstop Desi Relaford, and outfielder Ron Gant.
They also dumped ace Schilling. Who says the Phils are in
rebuilding mode?
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
