<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-PEACH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY CARRIES ON MAN'S DREAM OF PEACH ORCHARD CROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A breeze doesn't blow in a peach orchard.
</P>
<P>
   The trees seal off the wind like a long, green oven door.
Inside, leaves don't move. Peaches hang still. Sweat rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Wall picks until a half-bushel box is full, then reaches
for another. Her 12-year-old son and another boy pick other trees.
</P>
<P>
   It's midafternoon in this orchard southeast of Kansas City.
They've been at it since early morning. Horseflies buzz around
them. Grasshoppers fly past their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Wall stops, takes off her glasses and uses her shirt to
wipe sweat from her face. She doesn't dare look down the row. For
there waits her husband's dream.
</P>
<P>
   This is the summer his peaches came.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,500 trees, peaches thick as ornaments on Christmas
trees at Macy's. Prettier even. Red and gold, like balls of sunset.
</P>
<P>
   And Cheryl Wall, 45, is determined to pick them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part,'' she said, ``is knowing he will never see
any of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Marion Wall died unexpectedly April 1 at age 55, leaving his
wife and son to tend the orchard. All told: 3,200 peach, apple,
pear, cherry and plum trees. And some grape vines.
</P>
<P>
   They could have moved back to the city. Cheryl Wall sure didn't
know how to run an orchard. Curtis, her son, was only a
sixth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   But they're learning. Picking, pruning and mowing. Twelve hours
most days. Carrying boxes, fighting bugs and wiping sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl does it for her husband, a man she described as being
hardworking, giving and with a laugh that came from his toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel him when I'm out there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And while many 12-year-olds spend summer days at the pool or
watching MTV, Curtis works alongside his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make this orchard work...for my dad.'' Nurturing a
dream
</P>
<P>
   They came from Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Wall worked construction there. Cheryl was a surgical
scrub nurse.
</P>
<P>
   But after 20 years of life in the city, they had a calling for
the country. During a 1994 visit to relatives in Missouri, they
happened upon a farm for sale, east of Garden City just across the
Cass County line into Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   They fixed up the place and started raising cattle. Later, came
the idea for the orchard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me it had always been his dream,'' Cheryl said.
</P>
<P>
   Marion kept his old job, commuting to Oklahoma City and
returning home on weekends to catch up with farm work.
</P>
<P>
   He was a spontaneous sort. One day, when he and Cheryl decided
the fireplace made the house too dark and a large window would be
better, Marion grabbed a 20-pound sledge and started pounding away.
</P>
<P>
   Life was good. The farm was beautiful. The trees were growing.
Marion and Cheryl had morning coffee in the gazebo that sits in the
yard.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter, Shandra, was married in that gazebo. Neighbors
came to the wedding in everything from overalls to suits. Marion
smoked ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Then came April 1 this year, a Saturday. Marion and Cheryl ran
errands that morning. They went to the feed store. Later, in what
would seem a quirk of fate, friends started dropping by.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like everybody he knew was coming to visit,'' Cheryl
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, Marion was burning a brush pile. He came to the
house and coughed a cough Cheryl had never heard the likes of. He
said he didn't feel good. He was ashen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm hurts,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get in the truck,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The white Ford pickup flew down gravel roads and blacktops
toward the hospital in Harrisonville. As always, he gave her
pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful now, you know that cow's always in the road along
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't talk,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch for that cop that sits up there,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you just relax?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles farther, she looked over and knew he was gone. She
pulled into a driveway and yelled for help. Folks came out and
helped Cheryl pull Marion out of the truck.
</P>
<P>
   A heart attack had killed her husband of 18 years, a man who had
never shown a sign of heart trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just worked himself to death,'' Cheryl says now.
``Driving back and forth to Oklahoma, cramming in all the work he
did here on weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't grieve long. There wasn't time. Marion's peaches were
coming, and they would have to be her income. She had spraying to
do and trees to prune.
</P>
<P>
   But first, she had to learn how. She went to a longtime peach
grower and told him of her plans to run the orchard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure you want to do this?'' Bill Baxter, 73, asked.
</P>
<P>
   He knew how much work an orchard was _ and he had only 350
trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Marion's dream,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But is it your dream?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   She just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Baxter, who runs a retail stand along Missouri 7 in Cass County,
gave her a crash course. He told her what sprays to use and when to
use them, how to prune and how to tell when the peaches were ready
to pick.
</P>
<P>
   Friends came to help in the orchard.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, she said. In a big city where you live on a crowded
block, you don't have that many close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``But out here, where nobody lives within a mile of you, friends
come from all over to help,'' Cheryl said.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, she hopes to go to the house where her husband died and
thank the people who tried to help her that day. But she can't _
not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``God will tell me when it's time.'' `The mominator'
</P>
<P>
   ``Duck!'' Curtis yells.
</P>
<P>
   And they all duck just as the branch whips above their heads. A
little six-wheeler truck is zipping between rows of peach trees.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, riding in the back, frowns and shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gotta start prunin','' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His 13-year-old friend, Josh Hastings, rides beside him _
helping, as always, without pay. Booker, an Australian shepherd,
runs alongside. Cheryl, whom the boys call the ``mominator,'' is
driving the six-wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   It's early afternoon. The boys haven't had lunch yet, but a
truck is coming at 3:30 p.m. to pick up 27 boxes of peaches. Later,
she will need to deliver 24 boxes to Bill Baxter's stand.
</P>
<P>
   Just another day in the orchard.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl is up around daybreak and not back into the house 'til 9
p.m. Then there's cooking and cleaning and laundry to do.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Scott, a wholesaler who buys from Cheryl, calls her the
workingest woman he's ever seen in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most wives in her place would have sold this place and moved
to town in a minute,'' Scott said. ``There ain't no quit in her.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl puts it this way: ``It doesn't get done if you just think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   She won't hire help. Not until she learns what she's doing.
Anyway, she feels a need to do it herself this summer.
</P>
<P>
   They started harvest July 8 and are now more than halfway done.
</P>
<P>
   The days are long for Curtis, but he knows what's at stake. He
was 6 when he helped his father plant the trees, ``shoveling dirt
and sweatin' like a pack mule.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, it seems that just about the time they get the
orchard mowed and the trees tended, it's time to do both again.
</P>
<P>
   But he still finds time to fish and hunt, and not just for
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my mom the more wild game I bring back, the less we
have to go the grocery store,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl calls this her learning year. Next year will be easier.
She plans on turning her barn into a retail stand.
</P>
<P>
   A family friend, Pam Huff, thinks Cheryl is holding up, though
maybe the work is a way of putting off the grieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lives in that orchard...the peaches are what keeps her
going,'' Huff said.
</P>
<P>
   And, to fulfill her husband's dream, Cheryl Wall has been going
as hard as she can.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a peach falls to the ground, it may just have to lay there
because I've done the best I can do,'' she said this week as she
filled her pickup with boxes overflowing with Biscos and Summer
Pearls.
</P>
<P>
   It is a great summer for peaches.
</P>
<P>
   It is the summer Marion Wall had waited for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
