<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, Aug. 13, and thereafter. The Daily News is continuing its
extensive coverage of the Democratic National Convention and
related issues with today's stories. For questions on any stories,
contact Michael McGarr at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   DNC-STREETS (Los Angeles _ The streets of Los Angeles filled
Saturday as delegates, journalists and protesters scrambled to find
hotel rooms, access passes and the first public events of the
weeklong Democratic National Convention. Demonstrators protested in
front of the Federal Building downtown, a small precursor to what
are expected to be massive demonstrations through Thursday's
nomination night. By Alexa Haussler and Bhavna Mistry. (Will move
in the ``a'' national, ``n'' California and ``p'' political news
files.)
</P>
<P>
   DNC-USC (Los Angeles) _ Magic Johnson and Danny Glover may be
used to being upstaged by a teammate or a co-star, but by a
congresswoman? U.S. Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Los Angeles, brought the
house down Saturday at a pre-convention symposium of prominent
African-American leaders held at the University of Southern
California campus. By Heather MacDonald. (Will move in the ``a''
national, ``n'' California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DNC-MEDIAPARTY (Los Angeles) _ One of the biggest parties of the
DNC week is Saturday night, when 10,000 to 15,000 media members
converge on downtown for free food, drinks and the chance to mingle
with politicos and celebrities. (Will move in the ``a'' national,
``n'' California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DNC-TOURLA _ Snapshot of Los Angeles: The famous schnozz of
Jimmy Durante imprinted in cement at Mann's Chinese Theatre in
Hollywood; rippling hunks at the Muscle Beach body-building pit at
Venice Beach; Brad Pitt and Jennifer Aniston sharing a hug at Spago
in Beverly Hills. Forget the Liberty Bell, Statue of Liberty and
other nationally recognized historic sights, for out-of-towners
jumping into - and out of - the DNC next week, L.A.'s famed glitz
and celebrity are the got-to-get scrapbook savers. By Dana
Bartholomew. (Will move in the ``a'' national, ``n'' California and
``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DNC-SPRUCEUP (Los Angeles) _ The DNC isn't just about Staples
Center. At the Venice Pier, city workers painted the rest rooms and
trimmed palm trees (500 of 'em). At the Cabillo Marine Aquarium,
they painted the bathrooms, put up a new, $1,000 carved-wood sign
and painted the exteriors of all the buildings. And that's just the
sprucing along the beach; money was spent across the city for a
brighter, cleaner look for the DNC. (Will move in the ``a''
national, ``n'' California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LASTORY-REINVENT (Los Angeles) _ How to reinvent yourself,
L.A.-style, in five days: personal trainer at sexiest gym;
spiritual counselor; plastic surgery on discreet body parts on
Monday and Tuesday and a full face lift on Friday, with a week to
recuperate in a Santa Barbara weight-loss resort. By Jane Robison.
(Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
