<SLUG> BC-CVN-SANCHEZ-PLAYBOY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DEMOCRATIC LEADERS APPLAUD MOVE OF FUND-RAISER AWAY FROM PLAYBOY
PALACE &HT;    By JUDY HOLLAND
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democratic leaders applauded Rep. Loretta Sanchez
Saturday for canceling her plans to hold a fund-raiser for Hispanic
politicians at the Playboy Mansion. Her retreat followed weeks of
pressure from party officials and Catholic and Latino leaders, who
said that such an event there would hurt Vice President Al Gore's
efforts to paint his candidacy as pro-family.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday party leaders warned Sanchez that unless she gave
up the Hugh Hefner pleasure palace near here, they would revoke the
California congresswomen's speaking slot at next week's Democratic
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, 40, finally caved in Friday and announced she was
moving the fund-raiser to B.B. King's Blues Club at Universal
Studios' CityWalk, a touristy street of restaurants and shops. In
return, Democratic leaders restored her speaking slot for this
Thursday and canceled their threats to consider ousting her as the
highest ranking woman in the Democratic Party. Sanchez is co-chair
of the Democratic National Committee, along with Detroit Mayor
Dennis Archer.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign chairman, William Daley, said Saturday that he
would never go to the Playboy Mansion and that hosting an event at
the site of bacchanalian revelry where scantily clad women are
pursued by pajama-wearing suitors would ``send the wrong message''
about Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that she changed her mind,'' Daley said on CNN.
``There were many people in the Democratic Party who thought that
that location sent the wrong signal to Democrats and to America
about what the Democratic Party is all about. It's a location that
is used often for chaity events but (it) has also historically been
used for things that don't exactly highlight women.''
</P>
<P>
   Party Chairman Joe Andrew said on NBC that ``we're very happy to
have (Sanchez) back and to continue our work to make sure that all
voters, particularly Latino voters, know this is their party.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew dismissed Republican charges that Democrats are
hypocritical in accepting about $60,000 from Playboy for Democratic
federal campaigns since 1991 while condemning Sanchez for wanting
to hold her fund-raiser at the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people give us money, they're endorsing our cause, our
vision, our candidates, not the other way around,'' Andrew told
reporters. ``That is an important distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Hefner, the founder of Playboy magazine, had also called Gore
and other party leaders hypocrites for attacking the mansion while
soliciting campaign contributions from Playboy executives.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew, however, said that since Sanchez is a top party oficial,
the party should have some say about where she chooses to hold
fund-raisers. ``It's location, location, location here as well,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   DNC general chairman Edward G. Rendell, said that if Sanchez had
not been a high-ranking party official, they wouldn't have become
involved. ``Had she been doing this on her own as a congresswoman,
it might have been a wholly different scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who will formally accept his party's nomination for
president Thursday at the convention, had also pressed for
relocation of the benefit for Sanchez's political action committee,
Hispanic Unity USA.
</P>
<P>
   The controversey delighted Republicans, who were preparing to
use it as a campaign issue in a year when polls show that moral
values are a key area of concern for voters.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez's Republican opponent in November's election is Gloria
Matta Tuchman, who jumped on the isue last week, saying the
congresswoman ``has embarrassed her party and embarrassed the
people of the 46th congressional district.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez became a hero to Democrats in 1996 when she narrowly
defeated a Republican hardliner incumbent, Robert Dornan, for an
Orange County congressional seat. She beat him again overwhelmingly
two years later.
</P>
<P>
