</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MONICA LEWINSKY'S SHADOW HANGS OVER CONVENTION &HT;    By DAN FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL
 &HT;    c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As bomb-sniffing dogs and security officers combed
the Democratic National Convention hall, party leaders on Saturday
dismissed as ``bizarre'' a contention by Republican candidate
George W. Bush that Vice President Al Gore should repudiate
President Clinton for his affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to counter Bush's effort to revive the Lewinsky
matter, Democratic chairman Edward G. Rendell insisted the Nov. 7
election is about the future, not the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was bizarre,'' Rendell told reporters, referring
to Bush's comments. ``These guys want this election to be about
Monica Lewinsky. Well, we have news for them. The American people
are not going to ... risk the quality of life of their families for
Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell said Gore ``has made it clear that he in no way
sanctioned the president, that he was disappointed in the
president. That's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bush told reporters that Gore should forcefully
condemn Clinton's conduct with Lewinsky, an affair that led to the
president's impeachment for obstructing justice and near-removal
from office last year. Clinton will speak Monday night in his last
convention as president and is expected to stress the Clinton-Gore
record on the economy, crime and welfare. He also is expected to
respond to claims by Bush and GOP vice presidential nominee Dick
Cheney that Clinton and Gore squandered eight years in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell confirmed that the timing of Clinton's convention speech
had been switched from Tuesday to Monday to put more distance
between the president and the convention's grand finale _ Gore's
acceptance speech on Thursday night. Clinton ``absolutely
understood,'' the need to give Gore the spotlight, Rendell said.
Clinton and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton plan to depart
Tuesday for a symbolic handoff to Gore at a campaign stop in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell said Clinton will talk about his accomplishments in
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody needs to remind this country ... where we were on
Jan. 1, 1993 (just before Clinton took office) and where we've come
today,'' Rendell said. ``On all the things important to Americans,
we've come light years _ and it's no accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell also said it was likely that Clinton will touch on the
Lewinsky scandal and handle it in much the same manner as he did
earlier this week at a meeting of ministers outside Chicago.
Clinton said then that ``surely, no fair-minded person would blame
(Gore) for the mistakes I've made.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic national co-chair Joseph Andrew took a shot the
Republican convention in Philadelphia earlier this month. ``They
had an `illusion of inclusion' convention where you saw a lot of
pretty pictures,'' Andrew said. ``We're having a convention based
on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the Democratic confab, polls showed Bush
continuing to lead Gore. Four surveys, including three that focused
on registered voters, showed Bush's margin over Gore ranging from 9
percentage points in a Newsweek survey to 14 percentage points in a
survey for Cable News Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making a claim we're not behind,'' Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell was more blunt. ``Polls are worthless,'' he said, adding
they are ``snapshots'' of an electorate in which no one is focusing
on the election.
</P>
<P>
   Although polls show voters ``care about character and
leadership,'' Andrew said, they also show ``they care about
character and leadership on the issues they think are most
important. They don't just want a leader. They want a leader on the
issues they think are (important) to them and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Communicating Gore's leadership qualities on those issues is
``our job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gore and Bush clashed on the campaign trail over the
future of environmental cleanup efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore visited the Springdale, Pa., home of Rachel Carson, author
of the ``Silent Spring'' that helped spawn the environmental
movement, to underscore his pledge to fight corporate polluters and
the oil industry to clean the nation's air and water and reduce
dependence on foreign oil with energy-efficient vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made great strides,'' Gore declared, ``but I'm here to
tell you, you ain't seen nothing yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the Clinton-Gore administration had orchestrated the
cleanup of 500 toxic waste sites in the last seven years _ three
times as many as during the 12 years of the Reagan-Bush
presidencies.
</P>
<P>
   On his way to the Pittsburgh airport by motorcade, Gore
repeatedly bounded out of his armor-plated limousine into adoring
crowds. At one impromptu stop, Gore asked the groom's permission
and offered a newly-married bride a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas, Bush's campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett
challenged the Clinton-Gore administration's ``failure'' on toxic
waste cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett said the so-called Superfund toxic waste site cleanup
program ``has benefited trial lawyers more than the environment,''
adding that despite more than $30 billion in federal spending it
still takes an average of eight years to clean up a site.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid charges from the Gore camp that he was hogging the
limelight, Clinton had a low-profile Saturday, cancelling a series
of scheduled television interviews and choosing to play golf
instead with Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan, a Republican, and
Clinton's chummy campaign finance whiz, Terry McAuliffe. Clinton
was scheduled to join his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, Saturday
night for a fund-raising concert and tribute to his presidency that
was designed to raise as much as $4 million for the first lady's
New York Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to her husband, who ducked the limelight, Mrs.
Clinton stepped eagerly forward, telling the Associated Press in an
interview that she had shouldered a substantive role at the White
House framing legislation for Clinton-Gore administration policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted people to know that because if someone is going to
claim I sat around eating bonbons for the last five or six years, I
think it's only fair that the truth come out,'' Clinton said. Her
opponent in the race to succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., has accused Clinton of
doing nothing for New York as first lady. Clinton said her
prime-time nationally televised address at the Democratic
convention on Monday night would focus on efforts to help America's
children ``to try to give every child a chance.'''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's vice presidential running mates were in the news
for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes defended the $20 million
stock paying that the energy services firm Halliburton Corp., is
paying GOP vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney. ``The American
people should be pleased they have a vice presidential nominee who
has been successful in business,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton's board voted to reverse contract language with
Cheney that had called for him to forego stock options if he left
his job at the Dallas-based firm before age 62. Cheney is 59.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lieberman made good on his pledge to continue
honoring the Orthodox Jewish Sabbath on Saturday by ceasing all
work. Lieberman, wearing a prayer shawl and a yarmulke on his head,
attended services in Reassignment, D.C., with his wife, Hadassah.
The couple's rabbi, Barry Freundel, urged the Liebermans' fellow
congregants not to act ``triumphant'' as a result of Lieberman's
selection as the first American Jew on a major party ticket. ``This
is a test case,'' Freundel said. ``We could squander this
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman and Stewart M. Powell can be reached at
213-336-1800.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
