<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-DUMAURIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LORIE KANE SHOOTS A 71 TO TIE ANNIKA SORENSTAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By LISA D. MICKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AYLMER, Quebec _ Lorie Kane is down to her last red shirt. The
Canadian golfer's timing is impeccable, since the du Maurier
Classic's championship is Sunday and she is tied for the lead with
Annika Sorenstam after 54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to sleep with the lead, but I know that Annika is a
fierce competitor,'' said Kane, who managed a one-under-par 71
Saturday and tied Sorenstam at six-under-par 210 when Sorenstam
bogeyed the final hole. ``Today was an under-par round,'' Kane
said, ``but it was a shaky one.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kane was not the only one who had a shaky round at Royal Ottawa
Golf Club. Sorenstam wobbled in at even-par 72. Diana D'Alessio,
the first-round leader, finished with a one-over-par 73 after
incurring a one-stroke penalty on the 13th green for a moving-ball
violation on top of what turned into a triple-bogey seven. She
stands tied for third at 213 with Meg Mallon, who shot a 72.
</P>
<P>
   Juli Inkster, who charged up the leader board on Friday to put
herself into contention, never seemed to recover from her own
triple-bogey misfortune on the fifth hole. Inkster lost her uphill
approach shot in some trees, was forced to take a lost-ball
penalty, found a bunker and quickly gave away three shots to the
field. Inkster was last seen Saturday walking off the 18th green,
shaking her head and mumbling after a 74 left her four strokes off
the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Karrie Webb, the tournament's defending champion, took a tumble
from seventh place after 36 holes to a six-way tie for 15th (219)
after a round of 76. Webb, who has won the Nabisco Championship and
the United States Women's Open this year, lost four shots on her
last five holes Saturday to damage her bid for a third major
championship this year.
</P>
<P>
   With Royal Ottawa's small greens drying in the August sun, the
third round became one of defensive maneuvering. Sorenstam, who
normally plays with the precision of a sharpshooter, appeared out
of sync. In a highly uncharacteristic showing, the Swedish golfer
stumbled on the back nine holes with three of her four bogeys, and
only one of four birdies. It was even more uncharacteristic for
Sorenstam to yank her drive left off the tee on the 552-yard,
par-five 18th hole. Sorenstam then punched out from under a tree,
laid up with a 5-iron on an improbable 250-yard approach to the
stamp-sized green, bumped a sand wedge from 75 yards to within six
feet of the pin and nearly saved par. The putt veered left, and
Sorenstam gratefully took the bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have mixed feelings right now,'' said Sorenstam, a
five-time winner this year. ``It's a downer to bogey 18, but the
positive thing is I'm still in good shape for Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Kane has the momentum, coming home to Canada a week after her
long-awaited, career-first victory, which came in the Michelob
Light Classic in Eureka, Mo. She also has the overwhelming and
unabashedly biased support of her fellow Canadians in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   But Sorenstam has another weapon that most others in the field
covet. She has held a final-round lead 25 times in her career, and
has won 16 of those tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger is another factor and Kane, who was a runner-up nine
times before winning, does not want to be the tour's perennial
bridesmaid. What's more, in what appears to be the final staging of
the du Maurier Classic, every red shirt on the property knows that
only one other Canadian, Jocelyne Bourassa, has ever won the event.
She did it in 1973 at the tournament's predecessor, La Canadienne,
before it became a major championship. Canadian government
anti-tobacco legislation has banned cigarette advertising at sports
and cultural events, affecting the tournament's title sponsor,
Imperial Tobacco, and Sunday's final round is likely to be this
tournament's last hurrah. Tournament organizers have yet to find a
new sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to deliver at the du Maurier Classic for Jocelyne
would mean the world to me,'' Kane said, ``and I hope that
corporate Canada also is sitting out there watching to know what
this tournament means to this country. It's an exciting time for
me, but it's also a sad time. And I have a lot of work to do
tomorrow.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
