u s BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT &LR;      08-12 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTOUT LOOMS IN BUICK OPEN INSTEAD OF A WOODS RUNAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND BLANC, Mich. _ The huge crowd that flocked to the Buick
Open Saturday had plenty to watch, and not just Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry, shooting a third-round 65, snatched the lead
boldly, like a house guest taking the biggest steak at a summer
barbecue. Phil Mickelson, who also shot a 65, and Woods, who shot a
67, birdied themselves into contention. Woody Austin, who started
the day with a two-stroke lead, struggled to a 73 and was
overtaken. Meanwhile, proven winners like Hal Sutton, Vijay Singh
and Paul Azinger remained within an eyelash of the lead, ready to
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's final round at Warwick Hills Golf and Country Club
should be birdie-filled and intense, an exciting prelude to next
week's PGA Championship. Perry ended Saturday at 15-under-par 201,
one stroke ahead of Rocco Mediate, who had a two-under-par 70.
</P>
<P>
   The list of players with a realistic chance to win was at least
15 deep. Sutton and Austin were tied for third at 13 under par;
Azinger and Joe Ozaki were 12 under; Singh, Brad Faxon, Dudley
Hart, Skip Kendall and Mickelson were 11 under; and Paul Goydos and
Jeff Maggert were 10 under. Woods was tied at nine under par with
four players _ Fred Couples, Jeff Sluman, Robin Freeman and Kenny
Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could predict what would happen Sunday. But instead of a
Woods runaway, the final round should be shootout.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you shoot a 72 tomorrow, you're not going to win the
tournament,'' said Perry, who won the 1998 B.C. Open, his only
career victory on the PGA Tour. ``There are a lot of high-profile
players on the leader board, so somebody is going to shoot a low
number. Anybody five or six back has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, fans will come, because Woods will be
there. While the tournament does not keep an official attendance
count, Saturday's crowd was estimated at 50,000, by far the largest
ever at the Buick Open. Many came to see the marquee twosome, Woods
and Mickelson, with fans packed shoulder to shoulder outside the
gallery ropes, craning their necks to get a glimpse of the action.
</P>
<P>
   Other players felt somewhat ignored, including Austin and
Mediate, who played in the final twosome and teed off almost two
and a half hours after Woods. By the time Austin and Mediate played
their final three holes, many fans had left because Mickelson and
Woods were finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the weirdest final group I've every played in,''
Mediate said. ``Tiger took all the fans with him. It was eerie. We
got to the 17th hole, and there was hardly anybody there.''
</P>
<P>
   But earlier in the day, the atmosphere was like a state fair.
With cheers and yelling echoing through the trees, the electricity
surrounding the Woods-Mickelson pairing resembled a major
championship, and both players rose to the occasion. Mickelson
birdied the first four holes and put himself in position to win for
the fourth time this year. While some players are rattled playing
with Woods, Mickelson fed off the energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy playing with Tiger,'' said Mickelson, who
stopped Woods' six-tournament winning streak in February by winning
the Buick Invitational. ``What he goes through every day, I can
take in small doses. I don't know how he does it. It's so loud and
there is so much hoopla, I can't even hear. It was just all a blur.
On the first hole, it took me five minutes after hitting into the
trees to get people out of the way so they were not in danger to
hit another shot. You basically need to keep it in play when you
play with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mickelson kept his head, and he forced Woods to keep up.
Woods did not make his first birdie until the fifth hole, but then
he proceeded to birdie Nos. 7, 9, 10, 13 and 14 to reach 10 under
par. Woods made a double-bogey at the par-4 No.15, however, hitting
a tee shot into the trees, his second shot into the front bunker, a
bad bunker shot 15 feet past the cup and a chip 4 feet past the
hole, followed by a missed putt.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods does not win, he will lament that hole as a turning
point. But the big picture for Woods this week is to prepare for
the PGA Championship. Based on his ball-striking and performance
Saturday, he appeared headed in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt if I could make a few birdies, I could feed off of
Phil,'' Woods said. ``If not, I was going to get left high and dry.
I finally made a few, but I could have made a few more.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the crowd _ some fans chanted Woods' name between
shots and others chanted Mickelson's name, not to mention other
comments _ Woods smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty interesting, huh?'' said Woods, whose announcement that
he would be playing more than doubled ticket sales. ``They're the
biggest crowds I've ever seen here. And when the noise gets between
the trees, it starts to echo.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods will be paired with Goydos on Sunday, while Perry and
Mediate will be in the final group. Perry, the son of the former
baseball pitcher Jim Perry and the nephew of the Hall of Fame
pitcher Gaylord Perry, is 39th on this year's money list and is
ranked No.24 in the world, so this week's performance is hardly a
shock. Yet, while Perry contends regularly, he has had trouble
finishing the job. Perry hoped to change that Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to play like I'm three or four strokes behind
tomorrow,'' said Perry, who shot 31 on the back nine, including an
eagle at No.14. ``I'm looking forward to the challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
