<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TORRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRES DIVES BACK IN AT 33 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ So this girl comes up to Dara Torres at a swim
meet this year and says something nasty about Torres taking away
her spot on the Olympic team. ``I'm like, whatever,'' Torres said.
``Who are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Who are these kids who were still in diapers when Torres won her
first gold medal 16 years ago? Did they even know her as a swimmer?
Or just as the high priestess of Tae-Bo workouts on cable TV?
</P>
<P>
   Who is this 33-year-old with an 18-year-old body who stays out
of the water for seven years and thinks she can just show up at the
trials and make the Olympic team again? And not just make it, but
make it in a half-dozen events?
</P>
<P>
   Torres already has made it in the 100-meter butterfly, which is
the event she does for fun. She's favored to make it in Monday
night's 100-meter freestyle, which would guarantee her a place on
the 4 x 100 freestyle relay and probably on the 4 x 100 medley
relay, too. And if she's still humming a month from now, the
coaches could put Torres on the 4 x 200 freestyle relay, even
though she pulled out of the 200 freestyle here with uterine cramps
after the Friday prelims.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody her age has ever left this lung-busting sport, come back
two quadrennia later, and been faster than before. Nobody. Dara
Torres is simply too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the whisperers are saying. Just too good to be true.
Just like the East Germans in the 1970s. Just like the Chinese in
the '90s. Just like Michelle Smith, the Irish swimmer who won three
gold medals in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It just doesn't happen that way. Not in this sport. ``Are you
insinuating that people think I'm on drugs because I swim fast?''
Torres said last week when the subject of raised eyebrows came up.
</P>
<P>
   Just because she has set American records in the 50 freestyle
and 100 butterfly this year at an age when most swimmers have
retired to motherhood doesn't necessarily mean Torres is on the
wrong side of the doping lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking with (US coach) Richard Quick about this the
other day,'' Torres said. ``We talked about Lance Armstrong and how
people were insinuating that he was (on drugs) because he made this
miraculous comeback in cycling. And you see someone like (Dutch
swimmer) Inge de Bruijn and people are insinuating her and you
know, it's too bad. Why do people have to emphasize drugs because
someone does something really fast? I don't have words to describe
it. It just infuriates me. The bottom line is everyone has a
conscience. And for me, I know that I've done everything I can to
get where I am the right way _ and I'm ready to swim fast.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot of things, Torres said. It's technique and
conditioning and stretching and nutrition and diet supplements and
maturity _ and talent. It's not like she was a former mediocrity,
like Smith, who came out of nowhere to win a fistful of medals.
</P>
<P>
   Torres held the world mark in the 50 free for three years before
it was an Olympic event. She won relay medals in three consecutive
Olympics and captained the US team in Barcelona in 1992. When she
made her comeback, her time was still ranked among the US top five
in the 100 free. It's not as if Torres was some age-grouper who had
to make a deal with the devil to get to Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no swimmer has ever left the pool for seven years and
come back anywhere near competitive. Most struggle to make two
Olympic teams in a row. Summer Sanders won four medals in 1992 and
didn't come close to making the 1996 team. Amy Van Dyken won four
gold medals in Atlanta and will be lucky to make a relay this time.
Beth Botsford won the Olymoic gold medal in the 100 backstroke four
years ago. She was last in the final here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Too many things work against a reprise _ age, injury, illness,
marriage, children, diminished motivation. Only one other American
woman (Jill Sterkel in 1976-80-84-88) has ever made four Olympic
swimming teams. And until the middle of last year, Torres had no
intention of even trying for this one.
</P>
<P>
   She went to Atlanta four years ago and watched everything but
the swimming. ``I had no idea who was competing, what was going on,
nothing. I had no desire to watch it, no desire to be involved in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That life was over. Torres was modeling and doing TV work. If
she wore a swimsuit, it was alongside the supermodels in Sports
Illustrated's annual issue. Then, suddenly, she was craving
chlorine again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody egged me on,'' Torres said. ``Planted a seed in my
head and the seed just grew. I couldn't get it out of my head. So I
said, OK, I'd better do something about this.''
</P>
<P>
   So Torres called Quick, who coaches Stanford, and asked if she
could train with the varsity. She was in the middle of her first
workout, cruising along (or so she thought), when Quick tossed a
kickboard into her lane. ``Dara,'' he informed her, ``we don't swim
that way anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven years might as well have been 700, everything was so
different. But Torres had several things going for her. She had the
ideal sprinter's body _ 5 feet 11 inches, 145 pounds. She was still
in terrific shape from her Tae-Bo workouts. She'd been a
world-class swimmer and knew what it took. ``I've been there,'' she
said. ``I've done it before.'' And she still had a sprinter's
competitive heart.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that she and training partner Jenny Thompson, who had
won three gold relay medals in Atlanta, ended up having to work
apart from each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're training for the same events every single day, twice
a day, and both of you are going for the same thing and there's
only one of those things out there,'' Torres said, ``you know it
can get very intense.''
</P>
<P>
   With Van Dyken coming off shoulder surgery, Thompson had become
America's new sprint queen. She owned the world titles in the 100
freestyle and 100 butterfly and anchored the freestyle relay. Last
year, she had broken Mary T. Meagher's world mark in the 100 fly
that had stood for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now came Torres, back to her Olympian form in five months. She
went to spring nationals this year, won the 50 and 100 free, and
posted seven lifetime bests. She broke the US record in the 50 that
Van Dyken had set winning the Olympics. Torres wasn't just faster
than she'd ever been. She was faster than almost everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that people thought it was drugs rankled her. It was a
complex blend, Torres said. It was nutrition. ``I eat a lot more
protein now,'' she said. ``When I was younger, I used to carbo-load
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It was months of demanding workouts. It was the modern technique
she'd picked up. It was the coaching of Quick, who has a knack with
sprinters. It was her special stretching routine, something called
Meridian Resistance Flexibility. Two trainers ``mash'' her before
each race, walking all over Torres's body and legs to relax the
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   It was the new Lycra bodysuits everyone's wearing. It was the
wisdom that comes with age. ``I know not to waste my energy
worrying about what other people are doing,'' she said. It's the
two dozen supplements like creatine, amino acids, proteins, and
multivitamins that she and Thompson and other elite swimmers take
to help them, as Thompson said, ``beat the cheaters without
cheating''.
</P>
<P>
   It was all that, Torres claimed, and no more. ``If I ever
thought an athlete of mine was possibly cheating,'' Quick insisted
last week, ``I wouldn't coach them for one more second.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, who says that a woman is washed up at 33 these days?
Maureen O'Toole is 39. She's on the US water polo team for Sydney.
Carol Skricki is 38. She's on the rowing team. Both Dot Richardson
and Sheila Douty are 38. They're on the softball team.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what happens in Monday's 100 free, the Americans
could have a sprint relay at Sydney that averages 30. By that
standard, Dara Torres is in the prime of life. Like Forrest Gump's
father, she's merely been on vacation. ``I think I just needed a
seven-year taper,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
