<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BROWN-BOS     08-12 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN WILL HELP CELTICS IN SEVERAL WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a steak dinner at Abe &AMP; Louie's, point guard Randy Brown
met with Celtics coach Rick Pitino for the first time. There were a
few phone calls between the player and coach before Brown signed a
free agent contract for the $2.25 million exception, but no
face-to-face conversations until the meat and potatoes. The meal
followed the official announcement of the deal Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino gave Brown plenty to digest over dinner, specifically
what sounded like ``30,000 stories'' to the newest Celtic. The men
discussed basketball and leadership, road games and buzzer-beaters,
and the playoffs for about two hours. ``We talked about me being
his voice in the locker room,'' said Brown. And by the time player
and coach left the restaurant, Brown had a copy of Pitino's latest
book on leadership in hand, having ``begged him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Chicago preparing for training camp with weightlifting
and conditioning drills, the 6-foot-2-inch, 191-pound Brown is also
working his way through ``Lead to Succeed: 10 Traits of Great
Leadership in Business and Life.'' Brown gives the book a
respectable review. ``It's good,'' he said. ``But it's different
from what I thought it was going to be by looking at the cover.''
</P>
<P>
   First impressions and free agents make an interesting
combination. Sometimes you get just what you expect. Sometimes a
little more. Sometimes a little less.
</P>
<P>
   Since exception-level players come wrapped in very few
exaggerated claims, it's not too hard to read Brown. Unable to snag
a more valued free agent, the Celtics got a 32-year-old backup
point guard for $7.5 million over three years (he makes the
mid-level exception this season and holds the option for the third
year).
</P>
<P>
   Brown comes with three championship rings, two surgically
repaired ankles, and the veteran leadership qualities Pitino has
pined for. (``You look at our basketball team and we've been void
of mature leadership,'' said Pitino. ``It's evident that he has
it.'') Brown purposely chose a situation where he would be a backup
to cut down on wear and tear and sustain his NBA career as long as
possible. He left his hometown of Chicago because the uncertainty
of rebuilding with the Bulls wasn't what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Brown believes his role with the Celtics is clearly defined:
Give starting point guard Kenny Anderson a rest in the middle of
games so he can be strong in the fourth quarter, help the second
unit sustain leads built by the starters, share the experience
gained during nine years in the NBA, lead whenever necessary. No
more. No less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to come in and throw these championship rings in
their faces,'' said Brown. ``I don't think they need to see that.
I'm just going to come in and be positive, give criticism where
it's needed, and get them in the frame of mind that every game is a
winnable game.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me being 32 and getting a chance to be a free agent
again, it was real important that I get a chance to venture out in
the NBA and get to know some new players and get to know a new
system. That's a challenge that's going to be put in front of me
(with the Celtics) and I'm a person that's always loved challenges.
Once I was (in the NBA), I made a vow that I was never going to be
kicked out. Each year I've tried to improve. I want to go out on my
own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   While he hopes his new situation in Boston will energize him and
prolong his career, the decision to leave Chicago and the team he
grew up rooting for was difficult for Brown. (Fellow Chicagoan
Antoine Walker called Brown and welcomed him to the Celtics.) His
first run through free agency allowed Brown to leave Sacramento,
which drafted him 31st overall in 1991, and return to Chicago in
1995. His family regularly attended games in the Windy City and he
fulfilled a childhood dream as part of the Bulls' championship
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Brown credits playing Chicago high school ball with giving him
the toughness that's helped his NBA career last. As a ``blue-collar
city,'' Brown said Chicago instills mental toughness and a strong
work ethic in its players. The city has produced an impressive list
of talented point guards, including Isiah Thomas, Quinn Buckner,
Tim Hardaway, Doc Rivers, and Maurice Cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in Chicago, you learn to be tough,'' said Brown.
``You learn to fight through adversity and hard times. When you're
a point guard and you make it out of Chicago, it means you've
fought through a lot of adversity and done some good things. If you
can survive Chicago basketball, you can survive anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   While playing in Chicago's Public League at Collins High School
may have been about survival, competing for the Bulls was more
about learning. In fact, Brown admits that some of his basketball
development may have been slowed as a member of the championship
teams with Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I signed with Chicago, I knew I was going to become a
role player,'' said Brown. ``But when you're playing with Michael
Jordan and Scottie Pippen, how many points do you have to score?''
Instead of scoring, Brown watched and learned how Jordan cultivated
a winning attitude among his less-talented teammates, getting
everyone to maximize their effort in games.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing little on offense, Brown was tagged a defensive
specialist. And it's a label he doesn't like. He would rather be
considered ``an athletic player who can score when needed and is
good on defense.'' If Brown had to choose a label, it would be ``a
basketball player who goes out and plays off energy.'' Over nine
years in the NBA, Brown has averaged 5.1 points per game, 2.2
assists, 1.1 steals, and 1.8 rebounds in the regular season. In 47
playoff games, the statistics drop dramatically (1.6 points per
game, 0.5 assists, 0.6 rebounds, 0.3 steals).
</P>
<P>
   Although he experienced the Bulls dynasty in the 1990s, Brown
doesn't dare compare it with the Celtics' tradition, noting his new
team is ``on a different wavelength.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes without saying that (the Celtics) have had some great
players,'' said Brown. ``It shows what type of players they've had
because I can't even get a number to go on my jersey right now.
Every number that a basketball player dreams of putting on is up in
the rafters. Maybe I'll wear the year I was born, '68, or
something. I don't think there's another organization in the NBA
that's going to have a problem with guys picking out numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Brown, the big numbers will stay on the jersey. He is
comfortable with his role as a backup with a big voice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
