<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL IS NO. 1 OF BIG FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A game of 20 questions with an NFL geek:
</P>
<P>
   Q. It's obvious you're worked up over something. What's your
agenda?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm out to prove that football makes more sense than any of
America's four ``major'' pro sports. It's not even close. I don't
know who started this chatter about the poetry of baseball _
probably Bob Costas _ but football is the country's true national
pastime.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you saying you don't like baseball, basketball, and
hockey?
</P>
<P>
   A. Typical reporter. Putting words in my mouth. No wonder Carl
Everett doesn't talk to you losers.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My bad. I'll rephrase the question: Do you like the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. What I don't like is carrying around a glossary so I can
understand why a trade did or did not happen. All I've heard about
this summer is base-year compensation guys, sign-and-trade guys,
and midlevel-exception guys. No fan wants to hear that. We want to
hear about the next great point guard splitting defenses as if he
were a metaphorical Moses splitting the Red Sea. But when NBA
general managers talk, they all sound like CPAs.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about hockey?
</P>
<P>
   A. They make you wait until you're 30 for no-strings-attached
free agency. You can lose five first-round picks if you sign
certain ``free'' agents. Who did they consult when they came up
with that system? Fidel Castro? Come on. Next question.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's your problem with baseball?
</P>
<P>
   A. It's for rich boys only. You always see the same names
(Yankees, Indians, Braves) on the World Series RSVP list. And at
the beginning of the season, you always have a group of teams
(Twins, Expos, Royals) who essentially declare themselves out of
championship contention. That would never happen in football,
America's true pastime.
</P>
<P>
   Q. That's a tough argument to make in Boston. Don't you know
this is a baseball town?
</P>
<P>
   A. Dude. You are so late 1980s in your view of the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you mean?
</P>
<P>
   A. Maybe it used to be that simple. Now, people in Boston and
everywhere else love football. Small example: On Aug. 4, the
Patriots and Red Sox went head to head on television. The Patriots
were playing the Detroit Lions in a boring exhibition game. The Sox
were playing the sad Royals, but it was an August game, meaning it
had pennant-race implications. The Patriots easily won in the
ratings, 10.7 to 7.8.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You're not going to anoint football as the region's/nation's
primary sport based purely on ratings, are you?
</P>
<P>
   A. Settle down, Sam Donaldson. As I told you before, I like
football because it almost always makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Could you give an example?
</P>
<P>
   A. I love how the sport constantly corrects itself. It gave us
instant replay and it was slow. Replay was junked. When replay
demands were renewed, the system returned, much cleaner and
quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But where was the clean and quick replay when Tennessee rode
what appeared to be an illegal pass all the way to the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   A. I know you ask the questions, but a better question is this:
Where was Buffalo's special teams coverage?
</P>
<P>
   Q. What else?
</P>
<P>
   A. I like that players receive 63 percent of revenues and that
owners have a hard salary cap. I like that well-managed teams _ not
well-bankrolled teams _ are rewarded. I like the fact that you can
see evolution happen before your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Evolution?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yeah. Ten years ago, you didn't see a 280-pound linebacker
(Levon Kirkland) who could drop back into coverage. As recently as
five years ago, there were no Jevon Kearses. Soon, you'll see guys
like Michael Vick and Donovan McNabb turn the sport upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does that include NFL broadcasting, which gave us Howard
Cosell and now Dennis Miller?
</P>
<P>
   A. Maybe. But it would have been more innovative if ABC had a
different commentator each week working with Al and Dan. I would
vote for a rotating roster that had the likes of Miller, Eminem,
Camille Paglia, Chris Rock, Alan Keyes, Alanis Morissette, Cornel
West, Mr. Lif, and Cedric the Entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   Q. More than 100 million Americans watch at least one NFL game
every weekend. Why is that?
</P>
<P>
   A. America loves the little guy. Green Bay, the smallest city in
the NFL, can win the Super Bowl. One reason is that the league has
the best TV deal in sports. When the current contract expires, each
team will have received $500 million over eight years. That
eliminates the ``Sorry, we're broke'' defense from owners and makes
them accountable to their fans.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you saying NFL teams can't lose money?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. If they lose money, it's in ``taxable losses.'' To me,
losing money is when you place a $50 bill on a desk, leave the
room, and come back to find it gone. That's losing real money. NFL
owners don't lose real money.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Exactly. So why did owners such as Georgia Frontiere, Art
Modell, and Bud Adams move their teams, claiming they couldn't make
it in Los Angeles, Cleveland, and Houston?
</P>
<P>
   A. Because they're either greedy or bad owners. In Modell's
case, he was both. All of them could have stayed in their
respective cities; they simply saw an opportunity to make more
money elsewhere and left. That's as American as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I see some inconsistencies in your money talk. How do you
explain the Washington Redskins?
</P>
<P>
   A. Tremendous talent. Strange owner. Racist nickname. Could go
anywhere from 8-8 to 11-5.
</P>
<P>
   Q. No. I mean, how do you explain their manipulation of the
salary cap?
</P>
<P>
   A. Washington is not cheating. The organization has simply
decided to try to win now, knowing that it will have major cap
problems in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I find it interesting that you haven't mentioned the NFL's
alleged and convicted criminals. Where's the next expansion team
going to be? Sing Sing?
</P>
<P>
   A. You could say the same for any sport. The NFL just receives
more attention. And it's going to receive attention because it is,
clearly, the pastime. First game is three Sundays from now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Fair enough. But NFL coaches, as a rule, give awful press
conferences. Can you defend that?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. I said the sport makes more sense than all the others. I
didn't say it was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
