<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-FOLO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD TIME IS NOT THE CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Patriots started the exhibition season with the lowly San
Francisco 49ers, lifted the bar against the Detroit Lions, and
Friday night played the highly regarded Washington Redskins. They
next face the Tampa Bay Buccaneers and complete the slate with a
slightly easier game against the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots probably felt facing good teams would better
prepare them for the regular season, during which they play nine
games against playoff teams and have the fifth-toughest schedule in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   New England rolled past the weak 49ers (20-0), had a tough time
against the average-to-above-average Lions (13-10), and was
outplayed by what appeared to be a better team in Washington
(30-20). It's only the exhibition season, but does this show the
Patriots will handle the weak teams, evenly battle the average
teams, and struggle against the tough teams?
</P>
<P>
   So far, the same problems that plagued the team a year ago are
still there. Third down continues to be a nightmare on both sides
of the ball. The offense went 2 for 9 on third-down conversions
Friday night, and the defense allowed a couple of successful
third-and-long plays by the Redskins, who finished 9 for 17 on
third down.
</P>
<P>
   Time of possession also was a problem. The offense spent fewer
than 20 minutes on the field, the defense played more than 40.
There also were special teams breakdowns and fumbles. If this is a
more disciplined team than last year's, where's the proof?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a period of growing pains when you put in
something new, even though you're practicing it you're seeing it
live at a different speed,'' said Patriots coach Bill Belichick.
``That's part of it, but I don't want to make an excuse. That's
reality. Also reality is some of the stuff we've been practicing
for a long time we're missing a little timing too often.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick said the offense needs to improve, but he's weighing
the breakdowns on defense and special teams as well.
</P>
<P>
   The coach didn't point the finger at quarterback Drew Bledsoe's
lack of protection, in fact he characterized it as ``reasonably
good.'' However, on the first play of the game, Bruce Smith turned
Jason Andersen inside-out and nailed Bledsoe. That didn't set a
great tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had expected things to be better in all three areas,'' said
Belichick after studying video of the game. ``I told the players
it's a combination of things. We need to coach better and players
need to play better. We're going to make it happen on the field, so
collectively we need to make it better. We have to pull together
and get things tightened up.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been more talk about Bledsoe's mechanics, with some
believing he's throwing off his back foot again, and about the
receivers running sloppy routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say we have to improve the passing game, I mean the
throwing, the catching, the route-running,'' said Belichick. ``I'm
talking about the precision of the routes, so that if the ball
doesn't go to one player then he effectively carries that coverage
out of the way so it opens it up somewhere else. We need to run the
routes at the right depth, with the proper execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple of dropped balls. We had a couple of throws
that could have been better and we had a couple of protection
problems, a bad snap and all that. Several logs on the fire created
a situation where we need to tighten up a lot of screws. It would
be more of a concern if it was the same thing every time, if
protection broke down every time we tried to throw. But it seemed
that three or four things were pretty good and one thing was
missing, a different thing every time, which affected the success
of the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is it wasn't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick lauded the play of Kevin Faulk, who was the primary
back in the multiple-receiver sets and had two 40-yard-plus kick
returns.
</P>
<P>
   The coach also said something that was eerily similar to Pete
Carroll of last year: ``I thought we had a good week of practice.
We were crisp. Our Wednesday practice was probably the crispest
practice we've had all year. We pretty much hit everything. We were
sharp on everything, though all that counts is how you do it when
the lights go on. Everybody felt real good coming off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie McGinest and Chad Eaton continue to excel on the
defensive line, Lawyer Milloy and Ty Law (who had an interception)
in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think overall defensively it's been respectable,'' Belichick
said. ``The thing we haven't done a good job on is third down.
We're staying on the field too long. If we can get off the field on
third down that leads to more first downs and more time of
possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively we're hurting our offense by not creating better
field position for them. If we can get the third-down situation
cleared up, it'll go a long way for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belichick didn't believe rookie running back J.R. Redmond was
ready to play Friday night, even after he'd had a few days of
practice . . . Belichick held out linebacker Tedy Bruschi, who has
a broken right hand, but the coach believes Bruschi likely won't be
restricted by the cast when the regular season starts . . .
Belichick had the players in Smithfield, R.I., for film work and a
workout Saturday, but camp is officially over and the team shifts
back to Foxborough for the remainder of the season. Belichick
wasn't sure if he would reduce the workouts to one a day because
``we have a lot of things to cover and I want to make sure we have
the time to get it all in.'' . . . The Patriots are looking for a
defensive end. One veteran still on the free agent market is Neil
Smith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
