<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ONBASEBALL-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS' STRATEGY IS PITCHER FRIENDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For many Red Sox fans, there has been nothing
more aggravating to watch this summer than teams running at will on
catchers Jason Varitek and Scott Hatteberg.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are close to a stolen-base-a-game pace against the Sox,
with 108 steals in 111 games entering Saturday night's contest
against Texas. The Rangers didn't steal a base in the series opener
Friday night, but that's only because they are one of the league's
most plodding teams, swiping just 45 bases, a total not surpassed
only by the 28 by the Sox (of course) and the 27 by the A's, a team
built along beer-league dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek, who threw out 26 percent of the runners who ran on him
a year ago (40 of 152), has succeeded in throwing out just 16 of 94
base runners this season, 17 percent. Of regular AL catchers, only
Greg Zaun (8 of 51, 15.7 percent) has a worse percentage, in far
fewer chances.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg has caught just 5 of 35 base stealers, or 14.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to look at the numbers,'' Varitek said recently.
``All I know is I'm doing everything I can.''
</P>
<P>
   You watch Varitek, and most of his throws are strong and on the
mark. Hatteberg, who had elbow surgery last year, doesn't have the
same arm strength, but he still can sling it.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jimy Williams where Varitek ranks among the league's
catchers in terms of his arm, and the Sox manager puts him near the
top. ``He has a very good arm,'' Williams said. ``He throws a
stream of milk down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek has mentioned that he throws to second in 1.9 seconds,
which should give him a better than fighting chance against most
stealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a clock guy,'' Williams said. ``I've never had a
stopwatch. I've been watching these catchers throw. I have my own
clock.''
</P>
<P>
   So if it isn't the catchers, then what's the problem? Williams
offers a simple explanation. Red Sox pitchers, with runners on
base, don't use the slide-step, the technique designed to cut down
on their leg kick and thus shorten the time in which they deliver
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   A dumb move? Hardly. Williams pulls out a sheet of paper listing
the league's pitching statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are we in ERA?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   First, with a 4.14 ERA, almost a full percentage point under the
league average (4.97).
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we rank in walks?''
</P>
<P>
   First. They've walked just 339 batters, 22 fewer than the next
closest team, Detroit, with 361.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are we in wild pitches?''
</P>
<P>
   You know the answer. First, with 19. And by now, you've probably
figured out that the opposition batting average of .257 is the
lowest in the league, 19 percentage points below the league average
of .276.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pitcher has a better chance of misfiring when he uses the
slide-step,'' Williams said. ``The slide-step can affect both stuff
and location.''
</P>
<P>
   But, but . . . but what about all those stolen bases?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it,'' Williams said, ``you can't steal
first.''
</P>
<P>
   He makes a compelling argument, of course. If all those steals
were leading to more runners crossing home plate, then the Sox
would have to adjust. And late in the season, especially in
October, when the games generally are lower-scoring and every run
becomes more precious, the Sox' inability to shut down the
opposition's running game could become magnified.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, the decision to abandon the slide-step was not made
lightly by Williams. The supposed seat-of-the-pants manager
carefully has weighed the pluses and minuses, and his way works.
</P>
<P>
   There's another reason he's down on the slide-step. ``As long as
I'm here, I want our pitchers to have the longest career they
possibly can have, and with the slide-step you can't do it. You
have a better chance of hurting yourself when you slide-step. First
of all, it's not normal. You're asking a pitcher to change his
delivery, and when you do that, you increase the chance he might
hurt his shoulder or elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Pedro Martinez two years ago, `Pedro, I want you to
pitch a long time. I don't want you to ever feel that I asked you
to do something that might hurt you.' I'd rather have a guy steal a
base. I really would.''
</P>
<P>
   With Martinez, Varitek has thrown out just one of eight
attempted base stealers. With Derek Lowe on the mound, Sox catchers
are 0 for 6, not unusual when a closer is in the game and focusing
all of his attention on getting the batter out. John Wasdin left
this as his legacy. All 12 runners who attempted to steal when
Wasdin was in the game succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   And with Tim Wakefield, the knuckleballer on the mound, only 1
of 24 would-be stealers have been caught.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time you turn to the guy on the next barstool and
complain that Sox catchers couldn't throw out 80-year-old Johnny
Pesky, have a little compassion for the Sox' masked men. It's not
their fault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
