<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-RUIZ-FIGHT-BOS &LR;      08-12 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUIZ-FIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWERS KNOW TRUTH ABOUT RUIZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ One in the Boston crowd marveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny and Stoney and Gabe all went out to Smith &AMP; Wollensky's
(steakhouse) the other night on the Strip,'' the story began.
``Just the three of 'em. And the bill? It was $364 . . . for just
the three of 'em. Give all of us $364 to eat and we'd be eating
three squares for a week and still come back at you with change.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   Once again.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the boxing world can call Saturday night's heavyweight
fight a scam and a charade, because despite being considered the
World Boxing Association's No. 1 contender, Evander Holyfield's
opponent still goes by the extra-long name ``Someone Named Johnny
Ruiz.'' And doesn't the whole world know that Lennox Lewis is the
heavyweight champion regardless of what happens here?
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Just a body to put in the ring. Just a body to ensure that
promoter Don King once again pulls off a scam, in the meantime
praising the stars and stripes and saying _ perhaps for the 50th
time in the last hour _ that no country on the face of the earth
can compare to America. ``Isn't America great?'' bellows King.
</P>
<P>
   But there are others here, from Chelsea and Somerville and
Cambridge, Mass., others who've watched for years and years from
2,500 miles away the glitter and glitz and kitsch of a title fight
in Las Vegas. Perhaps with envy. But now they are here, part of the
entourage of Johnny Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   And, for them, this is no charade. This is no scam. This is
living.
</P>
<P>
   They saw their man, Ruiz, stand up at the weigh-in and then
heard him say afterward, ``I feel great. I feel comfortable. I feel
ready for the big fight.''
</P>
<P>
   About 500 of them bought their tickets for the fight directly
from the Somerville Boxing Club, Ruiz's gym, and once word got out
about the big crowd headed out to the desert, approximately 500
more bought tickets. ``The sales went off the chart,'' said Norman
Stone, ``Stoney,'' Ruiz's manager. ``Just imagine . . . 500 from
our gym alone.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to remind any of them that the reputation _ nay,
redemption _ of Boston heavyweights was in Ruiz's hands. ``We know,
we know,'' said Tony Cardinale, Ruiz's lawyer. ``We all know about
Peter (McNeeley). Johnny's no Peter. Don't even mention them in the
same breath.''
</P>
<P>
   And they lingered around as Gabe Mari, Ruiz's trainer, said he
has seen Ruiz go ``from a 1 to a 9 1/2'' on a scale of 10 since
Mari started working with Ruiz. ``And he'll be a 10 once he knocks
off Holyfield,'' said Mari.
</P>
<P>
   They wandered around the new and plush Paris Hotel and swapped
stories. One in the Boston entourage buttonholed one and then
buttonholed all, saying he had heard that Lou Duva was at a boxing
card last week in Connecticut ``and Lou says Johnny's got a shot.
That's what Lou Duva says. Johnny's got a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   And when any skeptical souls from outside of Massachusetts
mentioned the name David Tua, and how Ruiz had gotten knocked out
by Tua after a mere 17 seconds of the first round, all had their
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years ago,'' the Bostonians said. ``And Johnny's a lot
smarter since then. Johnny made a big mistake when Tua knocked him
into the ropes. He bounced right back off the ropes and into Tua's
punch. If he didn't bounce off the ropes, Johnny maybe survives.
Now Johnny knows what to do if he's hit into the ropes . . . but
Holyfield's not going to hit him into the ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   When skeptical talk by outsiders centered back on how Lewis is
the only true heavyweight champion, the Bostonians would gather
around King, the bombastic promoter, for verbal nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis wouldn't fight the WBA's No. 1 contender, ``so I went to
federal court to have Lewis's WBA title taken away from him. And
one of the great jurists of the age, a judge that even Louis
Brandeis could not equal in his wisdom, the most honorable Judge
Lewis Kaplan, ruled that no one is above the law. Isn't America a
great country when our judges are so wise?'' King said with a
straight face.
</P>
<P>
   And Ralph Palmacci wasn't missing a beat of it. Palmacci, 81,
who is from Cambridge and goes to the Somerville gym as often as
possible, was basking in every moment of the week. And don't dare
say a negative word about Ruiz in Palmacci's presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of detractors in the beginning,'' said
Palmacci, ``and you know what'd they say? And they'd say, `He has a
jab . . . that's all he has.' '' The ultimate putdown for a
heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   Just around the corner from Palmacci, workmen were putting up
the final staging for the grandstand in a huge ballroom of the
Paris Hotel. The boxing ring looked so out of place on a deep
carpet in the middle of a room ornate with gold. But, still, this
was for the title, no matter where it was being held, and Palmacci
was in the spirit of the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of great fighters in my time,'' Palmacci was
saying, ``and I've never ever seen one with the concentration of
Johnny. The concentration he has when he works out . . . he just
seems to wipe everything else out of his mind. Then I hear people
ask what kind of strategy is he going to have against this guy
Holyfield. And I say Johnny's going to be doing what he's been
doing all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is?
</P>
<P>
   ``Working the jabs . . . a right cross . . . stepping over . . .
12-punch combinations he throws without missing a punch.''
</P>
<P>
   A 12-punch combination?
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it in one of his fights and I counted the punches . . .
12 of 'em,'' said Palmacci. ``Twelve that finally knocked him down
and knocked him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmacci's brother-in-law is Red Priest, one of the better
middleweights in New England from several generations ago (``He's
got Alzheimer's now, real bad''), and Palmacci went into detail
about how his brother-in-law ``filled up the (Boston) Garden three
or four times. So I've been around the game a long time. A lot of
years. It's a disease, this boxing game, but I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmacci spent his life as a roofer when he wasn't boxing and
now, being in Las Vegas for a title bout for a fighter he has seen
grow and grow for the last dozen years, is as close to paradise as
can be found on earth for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I say,'' Palmacci said again, ``boxing's a disease, and I
got it bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
