<HEADLINE>
MO TAKES BLAME HEAD-ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif _ When it comes to taking responsibility for the
welfare of his team, very few come close to the Angels' Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   After a 4-2 loss Wednesday to former team, the Red Sox, Vaughn
made it clear he was taking responsibility. In the game he went 0
for 4, stranding six baserunners, including four in scoring
position. He made the final out of the inning each time he left
runners on.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Vaughn sat quietly at his locker, staring
straight ahead, ice pack on his left biceps.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter approached, and before the reporter could utter a
word, Vaughn said: ``Wait. I only want to do this once. Let's get
everybody over here first.''
</P>
<P>
   A few other reporters wandered over and Vaughn was ready. But no
question was asked. Unprovoked, Vaughn started in on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take this game on my shoulders, on my back,'' he said. ``You
want to be a big-league hitter and hit third, you don't leave 10
runners on base. I'm hitting .190 against left-handers! That's the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has always prided himself on being able to hit
left-handers. Going into this season, he was hitting .299 against
them in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting left-handers has always been a part of my game,'' he
said. ``It's always been an asset. This has got to stop. It will
stop. I've got to make adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous. I've had too many opportunities all season.''
</P>
<P>
   TICK, TICK, TICK: Is Boston's Carl Everett another ticking time
bomb waiting go off?
</P>
<P>
   Everett served his suspension for head-butting umpire Ron Kulpa,
and on the day he was to return, Everett got into a heated argument
with Red Sox manager Jimy Williams. The subject: During his
suspension, Everett left the team during a road trip for a day
without telling anybody or asking permission.
</P>
<P>
   Williams explained to Everett how that was not acceptable, and
the argument followed. How will the Red Sox deal with a hothead?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make some adjustments in regards to that
behavior,'' Red Sox GM Dan Duquette said. ``And certainly Carl
will, too.''
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLE STANDARD: In a recent game between the Blue Jays and
Mariners, three Blue Jays were hit by pitches. Yet it was Blue Jays
pitcher John Frascatore who was thrown out of the game for throwing
inside to Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez. The pitch did not hit
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi was not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't pitch (Rodriguez) inside, and three of my guys
get hit and the umpires don't do a thing ... it's absolute B.S. by
the umpires,'' Fregosi said.
</P>
<P>
   BRONX REVIVAL: What is it about the Yankees and ex-Angels? The
Yankees always seem to have an interest in ex-Angels, from Chili
Davis to Chad Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Again this season, the Yankees have quite a few _ reserve
catcher Chris Turner, infielder Luis Sojo, outfielder Luis Polonia
and relievers Jason Grimsley and Allen Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Rudy Meoli is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   RESTLESS IN SEATTLE: Mariners manager Lou Piniella recently
hired an agent to negotiate for him at the end of the season when
his contract is up. Piniella is in his eighth season with Seattle,
and could command big money if the Mariners win the American League
West and play well in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about a contract extension over the winter, but with
a new general manager (Pat Gillick), I thought it would be best to
wait and see how things worked out,'' Piniella said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
