<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MAY FIND OFFSEASON ARM SHORTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Dodgers look to re-tool a pitching staff
that could need anywhere from one to three quality starters next
season, expect them to go the free-agent route.
</P>
<P>
   But just how many high-end pitchers will be available when the
free-agency market opens in November is open to debate.
</P>
<P>
   As it's turning out, the class of the free-agent market will be
Baltimore right-hander Mike Mussina and Mets lefty Mike Hampton.
But a baseball official said he expected the Mets to make a hard
run to re-sign Hampton before the free-agent market opens, and
added that Baltimore would do everything in its power to re-sign
Mussina.
</P>
<P>
   The market already was slimmed down this week when San Francisco
signed left-hander Kirk Rueter to a three-year, $15.6 million
contract extension. Rueter, who is 8-7 with a 3.36 ERA,
acknowledged he signed for below market cost, but added that he
wanted to stay in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to them and said, 'I want to stay here. What will it
take to keep me here?'`' said Rueter's agent, Tommy Tanzer. ``They
offered him a contract and he took it. There were very little
negotiations for me. It's a great deal for the Giants. Kirk is very
happy. This is what he wanted to do. This opens up a can of worms,
in my mind. They were a little leery of dealing directly with a
player. (But) it's a deal they couldn't refuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were reportedly working on a deal to keep lefty
Denny Neagle and sources said the Dodgers will work hard to keep
right-hander Darren Dreifort. It could leave Mets right-hander Rick
Reed as one of the few mid-range pitchers available.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY MAKEOVER: Philadelphia went into the All-Star break with
one look but a month later they're a very different team. And one
that is built to be competitive in two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   It began with the trading of Andy Ashby to Atlanta for
left-hander Bruce Chen, but the big deal was Curt Schilling to
Arizona for pitchers Omar Daal, Vicente Padilla and Nelson Figueroa
and first baseman Travis Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies also sent Desi Relaford to San Diego for David
Newhan and got Kent Bottenfield from the Angels for free
agent-to-be Ron Gant and dropped $1.3 million of payroll when
Boston claimed Rico Brogna off waivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of things that would have been done at the end of
the season,'' GM Ed Wade said. ``Curt was the wild card. It was the
most difficult decision. There was no guarantee Curt was going to
open that window (i.e. waive his no-trade) again. So we were
looking at two scenarios. No.1, extend him for three or four years;
or No.2., lose him to free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   DRIVING MR. NO ONE: The Dodgers open a three-game series at
Florida on Monday, and one way to tell just how dire the situation
is for the Dodgers is to look at whether Luis Castillo drives in a
run. Castillo is challenging the dubious mark of failing to drive
in runs. He entered Saturday with nine RBI, leaving him on a pace
for 13. The mark for fewest RBI by a player with 450 at-bats or
more is 12, established by Enzo Hernandez in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he's been absolutely paralyzed by it. It'll be a relief
when it's over,'' Marlins manager John Boles said. ``He wants to be
a complete player. He doesn't want that infamous record.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Cubs rookie right-hander Ruben Quevedo threw 133
pitches in a complete-game win against the Dodgers last Monday. The
reason he threw so many pitches? Pitching coach Oscar Acosta had
him with only 112 pitches. ... Colorado right fielder Larry Walker
has a no-trade clause in his contract, but the Rockies may look to
move him after the season because he's owed $12.5 million a year
through 2005. But Walker didn't want to talk about being traded
because he didn't want to give the wrong impression. ``Don't make
it sound like I'm asking to be traded because I'm not,'' Walker
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
