<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MATTHEWS-LOCAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTHEWS JR. USED TO BIG TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As long as he's not playing against Barry Bonds,
Gary Matthews Jr. feels like a veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always one of my favorite players when I was younger,''
Matthews said of the San Francisco Giants outfielder. ``When I play
against him, I always get a kick out of it. It's sort of a weird
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Being overwhelmed or in awe of the major-league experience is
rare, though, for the 25-year-old Granada Hills (Calif.) High
graduate, who has less than a season's worth of experience at this
level.
</P>
<P>
   As a reserve outfielder for the Chicago Cubs, he plays alongside
Sammy Sosa, but being around the game's elite was something
Matthews got used to years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tagging along with his dad, whose career included time with the
Cubs in the mid-80s, made Matthews feel comfortable in major-league
surroundings at an early age, leaving him focused and ready to work
when he became a major-leaguer himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably one of the biggest reasons I've been able to get
over the period of being nervous or intimidated,'' Matthews said of
his dad's career. ``That's something I really didn't go through,
that adjustment period. It didn't take me as long to get over it as
maybe some of the other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around the game a while. And growing up as a kid,
you're in the clubhouse with guys like Pete Rose, Mike Schmidt,
Ryne Sandberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The list goes on as far as guys my dad played with. So just
coming here with guys like Sammy Sosa or (Mark) Grace, it's
different players today, but it's the same thing. I'm not really in
awe, it's a place of business. But it's a lot of fun, it seems
normal to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews appeared in 23 games last season with San Diego before
being traded to the Cubs this spring. He began the season in
Triple-A Iowa, but was recalled June 2, making him the sixth son of
a former Cub to also play for the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream come true for me being here,'' Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
   He welcomed the fresh start, realizing he would probably still
be in Triple-A if he stayed in the Padres organization.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Cubs coaching staff admit they questioned
Matthews' potential when he arrived. After all, he had spent four
years at the Single-A level and had a .263 career batting average
in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing how hard Matthews works, combined with his strong arm,
speed and good range in the outfield, helped change his new
employers' minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary works with me more than anyone,'' said Cubs hitting coach
Jeff Pentland. ``He's a tremendous worker, he knows what it takes
to play at this level.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came here. I didn't realize how good of an athlete we
were getting. It'll be a while before his hitting is as good as the
rest of his game, but he's definitely improving. He has a future
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews is also encouraged by his progress. Even though he
entered this weekend's series against Cincinnati batting just .206
with four RBI, he is adjusting to changes Pentland is making in his
swing. He also has made key defensive contributions, including two
highlight-reel catches in a recent game against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good so far,'' Matthews said. ``I'm beginning to
prove I can play at this level and that I belong here. Ever since I
was kid I thought I belonged here, so it's nice to see it
happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
