<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC TALKING BIG, READY TO BACK IT UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC quarterback Carson Palmer talks about
playing for the national championship. Linebacker Zeke Moreno says
the Rose Bowl is not the ultimate goal, because the Trojans want to
play in the Orange Bowl, site of college football's title game.
</P>
<P>
   Even coach Paul Hackett says he's never been more excited about
a group of players, and this could be a ``special'' year.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like something straight out of the 1970s, or a tone
more appropriate from the mouths of today's Florida State players.
</P>
<P>
   But this is actually USC, today, and the attitude and
expectations are high. No one is talking like they belonged to any
of the previous four teams that went 26-22 and made just one bowl
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   There's an unbridled optimism that hasn't been present since
1996, when, like this season, the Trojans opened the year in the
Kickoff Classic against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people on the team in their fourth and fifth
year here, and they're fed up with what happened in the past,''
senior defensive end Sultan Abdul-Malik said. ``It's time to start
winning, and dominating and getting back to the Rose Bowl. We're
seeing the type of guys we have and the chemistry and what can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he feels so good about the Trojans precisely
because of the senior leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the senior group has given me the indication this team
will be different than the last two teams,'' Hackett said. ``It's
not depending on a freshman quarterback (Palmer) or a maverick wide
receiver (R. Jay Soward).''
</P>
<P>
   The players are also feeding off Hackett's enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he realizes what we're capable of,'' Moreno, a senior,
said. ``He's excited about the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno said he is completely prepared to defend his remarks
about the Trojans, because he has never felt so confident in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some think I'm crazy but I'm not saying it for them,'' Moreno
said. ``I'm saying it because I believe it. It's not for attention.
It's what I think we're capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who is usually low key about almost everything, thinks a
national championship is realistic. He said the Trojans' mental
outlook was part of last season's downfall, and believes the
strength of this team will be its belief in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just weren't very confident last year,'' Palmer said.
``Things are different now. We feel pretty confident about the team
and our schedule. We want to shoot for the highest goal. It's a
solid chance.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a danger, of course, with such lofty predictions. If
the Trojans lose to Penn State on Aug. 27, they could lose all the
confidence and momentum they accumulated during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in 1996. The Trojans were ranked seventh in the
Associated Press Top 25 preseason poll, then lost to Penn State
24-7 and went on to a disappointing 6-6 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see no similarities,'' senior Eric Denmon said. ``I see a
lot of leadership and guys busting their behinds this year. I can
remember we were ranked seventh in the nation, and guys thought
since they were seventh, they didn't have to work as hard. I think
we took that too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was too much bickering between the units. At that time,
we didn't have leaders. Guys were just being individual players. We
have leaders on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Moreno is taking an aggressive role to ensure
things don't go sideways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my turn to step up and take control in situations,'' he
said. ``If I see a problem, I will address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Antoine Harris has also been more vocal and Palmer
said he is willing to share responsibility because of the
importance of being the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the team has become a tighter group, spending the
summer socializing instead of going their separate ways once summer
workouts concluded.
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason for Hackett's underlying confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've teased people before and won some games and then lost
our discipline,'' Hackett said. ``But I feel there's enough
maturity with the seniors to say they have a shot to do something
and they will respond. The difference is players are talking about
how good we can be as a team. Usually you hear players say 'How
good can I be?'''
</P>
<P>
   That mindset has even permeated down to the incoming freshmen.
Although there are several high school All-Americans, there haven't
been any early displays of ego.
</P>
<P>
   `I see a lot of young guys with accolades willing to come here
with a clean slate,'' Denmon said. ``We have no individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Added strong safety Matt Grootegoed, one of the most decorated
freshmen: ``No one's cocky out here.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to the Penn State game. USC is a 3-point underdog, and
if the Trojans lost, wouldn't it suck away all their bravado and
ruin the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see us reacting that way because I don't think it will
happen, whatever the outcome of the Penn State game,'' Moreno said.
``And I don't see us losing. You don't think about it. It's just
something if it happens, it happens.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
