<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BRAVES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADDUX SHUTS DOWN LIFELESS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This high-powered offense that's carried the Dodgers
through the first two months of the season is nowhere to be found.
For the past two weeks, even rumors of how good the offense was at
one point are now unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to Atlanta isn't exactly a great way to break free. Going
against Greg Maddux is even worse.
</P>
<P>
   With Maddux working magic with his fastball that tails back over
the plate _ or relatively close _ the Dodgers hitters never stood a
chance in a 4-1 loss to Atlanta on an otherwise comfortable
Saturday afternoon at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' sixth loss in seven games came in a familiar way _
with the offense doing absolutely nothing _ and the players have
absolutely no idea what to do next to break the drought. All left
fielder Gary Sheffield knows is the blame shouldn't fall on manager
Davey Johnson, whose seat gets hotter with each loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were slated to play Saturday night, but at the time
of the Dodgers' loss they dropped to six games out of first in the
National League West, the same number by which they trailed at the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managers are hired and fired because of us,'' said Sheffield,
who doubled in four at-bats. ``Davey's doing his job and we're not
doing ours. He lets us play. Guys are complaining when they're not
playing and they're struggling. Let him do his job and we'll do
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Maligned Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes did his required
duty, putting the shellacking he took against Milwaukee last
weekend behind him to pitch six solid innings. Valdes (2-6) allowed
three runs (two earned) in six innings, but a lack of offense made
it moot.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux (13-6) allowed seven hits in 61/3 innings and relievers
Mike Remlinger and Kerry Ligtenberg pitched 22/3 innings of hitless
relief. During a 14-game stretch in which the Dodgers are 5-9,
they're batting .227 and averaging 3.36 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we had our opportunities in the game and we didn't
capitalize,'' Dodgers center fielder Devon White said. ``It's part
of the game. You have to roll with it and hopefully we don't sink
too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the energy that was once part of the clubhouse has
disappeared. White was asked if it was time to worry about falling
too far behind in the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not me,'' White said. ``I'm not going to do any worrying. I'm
going to do the best I can. Sometimes these things work themselves
out and sometimes they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, though, the offense is doing very little to ease
the burden and pressure being felt by many.
</P>
<P>
   The best Dodgers chance Saturday came in the first inning, when
Mark Grudzielanek singled with one out and Sheffield doubled. But
Maddux struck out Shawn Green looking, then got Eric Karros to line
out to right field to thwart the early threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, whose lineup produced huge days regularly during
the first two months of the season, got three runners to second
base after the first inning. The only one to score was Green, on a
Karros double in the sixth that pulled the Dodgers within 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, whenever a team comes to Atlanta the topic of a
struggling offense (ital) has to (endital) turn to just how many
calls the Braves' pitchers get off of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the last guy you want to run into when you're struggling
at the plate,'' said Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley, who went 1 for 2
with two walks. ``On TV, they look like good pitches. But when
you're hitting, they're not on the plate. When I watch it go by,
it's off the plate. But whenever it comes back, it's a few inches
on the plate when it hits the catcher's glove. It's an unhittable
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   After scoring in double digits 11 times in the first 45 games,
the Dodgers have reached 10 runs three times in the past 70 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone in here still believes we have an
opportunity,'' Karros said. ``I've seen a lot of frustration. I
think everyone in here believes we can get something going although
it may not appear that way from the outside.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
