<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAL STATE NORTHRIDGE LIKES ITS CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Cal State Northridge quarterback Marcus
Brady is back. The Matadors defense is being billed as an improved
unit. And the goal of winning the school's first Big Sky Conference
title _ CSUN's final chance _ is very real.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who will move to the Big West as an independent
team next season, open football practice Monday with two-a-days at
CSUN. Second-year coach Jeff Kearin couldn't be more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had a better offseason or summer workout period,''
Kearin said. ``It's really been a fabulous offseason. It's been a
fabulous offseason academically, and it's been a credit to the
kids. When (last) season ended they said, `We've got to win this
championship. We're stronger, we're bigger and faster than we've
ever been.' I'm real excited to go Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   And ready to put out of his mind the NCAA sanctions brought on
by former coach Ron Ponciano. Allegations of cheating that rocked
the program were upheld over the summer by the NCAA, which banned
CSUN from postseason play for a year and put it on probation for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin said he is so focused on winning the Big Sky he hasn't
yet discussed the NCAA sanctions with players. Not that it hasn't
been a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been such a hectic and disruptive and distracting
offseason,'' Kearin said. ``We've lost a couple of kids to that but
that's OK. We'll go to battle with the guys that are here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the kids are so resilient and focused as far as
keeping their eye on the ball, so to speak. We certainly can't win
a national championship, but that's all right. We can win a
conference championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors finished 6-5 last year and 4-3 in the Big Sky. On
the field, CSUN went 5-6 but Northern Arizona forfeited its win for
using an ineligible player.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge's offense was explosive, averaging 450.3 yards per
game, and six starters return. Running back Jaumal Bradley _ who
ran for 932 yards and seven touchdowns _ is gone, leaving the
position up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore wide receiver Drew Amerson, who had a team-leading 71
receptions, figures to be Brady's favorite target again.
</P>
<P>
   Brady passed for 3,326 yards and 24 touchdowns but also threw 15
interceptions. Kearin believes this year's offense _ despite a
young and inexperienced line _ can be even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brady's arguably one of the best quarterbacks in the
country,'' Kearin said. ``Probably his biggest improvement is his
feeling of leadership on the team. He's more of a quiet leader, not
a screamer. But everybody's looking to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was less than careful with the ball _ (15) turnovers.
That's devastating. He feels he has to throw fewer interceptions.
That goes without saying. But to be honest, I take a lot of
responsibility for the turnovers. I inherited the group two weeks
before the season started, and I didn't have a firm grasp of the
offense. We've tweaked and adjusted and changed some things, and I
understand it better. We'll be more efficient as a coaching
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   And hopefully for the Matadors, more effective on defense. The
defense has just three returning starters in camp, but Kearin is
impressed with the speed of rookies and transfers. Newcomers
started camp Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Cos Abercrombie returns to the linebacker corps, which Kearin
calls the most improved unit on either side of the ball. The
Matadors surrendered 431.1 yards per game last season, a trend
Kearin hopes to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we're certainly much more talented and much
faster as a defensive unit,'' Kearin said. ``We have a scheme in
place that is really effective. ... The young kids have developed,
and I think Ron Ponciano and ourselves have recruited some good,
young defensive players. We were not very strong last year as a
defensive front. We've filled some holes, and young guys have
developed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
