<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY DREIFORT MEANS EVERYTHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dodgers manager Davey Johnson has done his best to
protect Darren Dreifort. He's limited Dreifort's innings and rested
him a few extra days when off-days made it possible, all in hopes
of keeping him strong during the last month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dodgers will pay particular attention to how Dreifort
performs during the last month of the season. And if he performs.
If the tough right-hander doesn't have arm problems and is able to
finish strong, the Dodgers will try hard to re-sign the
free-agent-to-be, sources said. Dreifort's eligible for free agency
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to the Dodgers' decision, more so than the way
Dreifort performs over the final 47 games, is his health.
</P>
<P>
   The club has already decided Dreifort can be the dominating
starter that so many scouts predicted he would be. He enters his
start today against Atlanta with a career-high five-game winning
streak and a 2.67 ERA since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from his two months of inconsistency earlier in
the season, when he was 1-6 with a 7.03 ERA in 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``His delivery is more consistent,'' Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone said. ``He's repeating the same delivery, which allows
him to have better control and better command. It looks like he's
found it. His stuff has always been there, but he's found a
consistent delivery that allows him to throw the ball with more
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, who is 9-7 with a 4.51 ERA, has gone through these
spells of dominance before, but the the Dodgers' brass remains
guarded about his durability. Johnson thought about pushing
Dreifort's next start back to Tuesday, giving him a few more days'
rest because the Dodgers had Thursday off.
</P>
<P>
   However, after consulting with Dreifort, the decision was made
to start him today and go with right-hander Matt Herges in Florida
on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to make sure (Dreifort) was feeling good,'' Johnson
said. ``Sometimes he won't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season Johnson said he would try to limit Dreifort
to between 90 and 100 pitches as a precaution for his arm. In each
of the past two seasons _ Dreifort's first two as a starter with
the Dodgers _ he experienced arm troubles and didn't pitch for much
of September.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort is also nearing a career high in starts. Today will
mark his 23rd of the season. He established his career best last
season with 29. Dreifort's career high is only 180 innings, which
he achieved in 1998. He's thrown 131 innings this season.
</P>
<P>
   2001 SCHEDULE: Major-league clubs have received a tentative
schedule for the 2001 season, and plenty of them are unhappy with
it. Include the Dodgers in that mix.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule has the Dodgers opening the season April 2 in
Milwaukee, then traveling back to Los Angeles for their home
opener, a baseball source said. It would also mean the Dodgers
would open up Milwaukee's new ballpark. The Brewers, in turn, would
then go on the road after the one game.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Dodgers and Milwaukee have expressed displeasure at the
schedule, but it might be tough to get around, the source said. A
by-product of the unbalanced schedule next season is that teams
will have to stop in a city for one game. The tentative schedule
also calls for Atlanta to play one game in Cincinnati to begin the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are also continuing to explore options of playing
exhibition games outside the United States before the regular
season begins. One of the areas being researched by the Dodgers is
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Because switch-hitting Devon White was 4 for 14
with a homer and two RBI against Atlanta right-hander Greg Maddux,
he got the start in center field. The left-handed-hitting Tom
Goodwin, who's platooning with White in center field, was 0 for 8
against Maddux. ... Third baseman Adrian Beltre was fine despite
getting hit in the head with the ball on a stolen base in the
second inning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
