<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-12 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-DILBECK-COLUMN-LA     08-12 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DILBECK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, LET'S BREAK UP THE YANKEES LOVEFEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Come on, together we can do this. We need to
do this.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, life just hasn't been the same since the Yankees
became so, so ... (ital) respectable (endital).
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that hurt. Growing up in my little Southern California
tract home, we were taught never to use the word ``hate,'' unless
of course referring to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Then all manner of vile, repulsive vitriol was not only
acceptable, but absolutely encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking the damn Yankees. They were just so New York. Like
the entire baseball world began and ended in pinstripes. The
original ``best team money could buy.'' Team Smug.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, they had this irritating habit of beating the
snot out of the Dodgers every World Series.
</P>
<P>
   One of the truly great moments in Los Angeles sports history
came when the Dodgers not only beat the Yankees in the 1963 World
Series, but swept them in four games. It still warms the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Then when the Dodgers became good again and finally got past the
Big Red Machine, who was there to thwart them the first two times
they reached the Fall Classic but the Bronx Blowfish.
</P>
<P>
   Now they brought all kinds of new reasons to despise them. They
were owned by George M. Steinbrenner III, who offered a
never-before-seen personal catalog of egomania.
</P>
<P>
   His free-agency spending spree brought Reggie Jackson, the King
of Pompous. Some dictators were easier to love. It was always close
who offered the most disdain, you for Reggie, or Reggie for you.
OK, Reggie for you.
</P>
<P>
   They were managed, depending on the month, by hard-living Billy
Martin, a Napoleonic creature who always walked around like he was
looking for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   These were golden days for Yankees detesting. They made it so
easy. Lord, I miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Because now the Yankees are again America's dominant baseball
team, and what is up? They've won three of the past four World
Series. They are ripe for the ripping, and instead are almost
beloved.
</P>
<P>
   This is all very wrong. America is missing out. We need someone
in a black hat. We crave a bad guy. It's hard enough we don't have
the Soviets to get worked up over anymore, but now the Yankees are
admired?
</P>
<P>
   Willie Randolph, the longtime Yankee, brief Dodger and current
Yankees third-base coach, maintains the country remains full of
those eager to vilify the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may hate us, but right now you don't want to show your
face,'' Randolph said. ``You only talk trash when you can get away
with it. You can't do too much cracking when we're winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, that's exactly when you're supposed to have your fill of
N.Y. This is when you need to dust off your finest anti-Yankee
jibes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we practically get testimonials. Where is the
tradition? Where is the venom? All across the land, fans who once
jeered the Yankees, embrace them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' said Angels coach Alfredo Griffin. ``Times
change.''
</P>
<P>
   To wit: These Yankees are nice guys. They willingly play their
roles. Their egos are in check. They put the team ahead of the
individual. They don't always overwhelm you with power, but do all
the little things right. They are a real team.
</P>
<P>
   Their leaders are Bernie Williams, Derek Jeter and Tino
Martinez, pillars of the baseball community. They're managed by Joe
Torre, an honest, helpful, caring man.
</P>
<P>
   This is Steinbrenner's team?
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time people really hated the Yankees was when they
had Reggie,'' said Irv Kaze, a former Yankees public relations
director who now hosts a sports show on KIEV-AM in Los Angeles.
``These really aren't people you dislike.
</P>
<P>
   ``People respect them for what they've done. They're not
controversial. None of them makes any news off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Making this animosity thing more difficult is that the Yankees
have had to undergo more than their share of personal tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees won the first of their three most recent titles
in 1996, Torre lost one brother to a heart attack and had another
undergo heart surgery during the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, outfielder Darryl Strawberry came down with colon
cancer and three players _ Paul O'Neill, Scott Brosius and Luis
Sojo _ lost their fathers. Last year, Torre battled prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees have pulled at our hearts, not ripped them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to respect the character of this team,'' Randolph
said. ``You need individuals to hate. This team really doesn't have
anyone to hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Steinbrenner did add Jose Canseco lately, so at least
there's somebody to boo again. It's a start.
</P>
<P>
   There is still plenty to get worked up over. They remain the
ultimate example of big-market excess. Their payroll is now a
record-breaking $112.3 million. Players keep going down, and
Steinbrenner just adds more bodies _ David Justice, Denny Neagle,
Glenallen Hill, Luis Polonia, Canseco.
</P>
<P>
   And they blend in and keep winning. It's absolutely disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core of this group is pretty flexible when it comes to
change,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable how they extend their arms to anyone new and
make them feel welcome. On most clubs, new people have to prove
themselves. They're very unusual, very unique in that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Very irritating, when you're trying to work up a good
anti-Yankees lather. Maybe the whole anti-Manhattan thing has
become passe.
</P>
<P>
   You seldom even hear a New York accent around here anymore,
unless you're trying to listen to L.A. sports radio.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, but it's not too late. It doesn't matter if Williams plays
the classical guitar, Jeter calls his mother every day or Martinez
helps little old ladies across the street.
</P>
<P>
   These are the Yankees. You are not allowed to admire them. It's
un-American. Work on it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
