<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COL-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, CAMPO FLAWLESS IN REPLACING THE HAT AND HAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hair has been tinted a bit to take out the gray, plus
cropped shorter. When laser surgery wasn't possible, the old
moon-eyed frame on his glasses gave way to designer snazziness. His
ride of pride had been a Trans-Am. Now it's a Cadillac. And for
street-wear, the wardrobe went from off the rack at any-old-place
to the best Neiman-Marcus has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   A down-home guy from Connecticut is promoted to his dream job,
and what's the first thing everybody attempts to do?
</P>
<P>
   Make him ``look'' like the head coach of the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Campo is not alone. Makeover artists are in big demand
these days. ``W'' is being told not to smile. To look presidential.
Al is being told to smile more. To show a personality.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, however, has already assumed a higher office than those
two.
</P>
<P>
   So have you gotten cozy yet with the idea that he's now the man?
Can you come to grips with Campo suddenly holding the same job that
once belonged to The Hat and The Hair?
</P>
<P>
   His football credentials are in perfect order, but take another
look tonight. When the TV cameras zoom in on the Texas Stadium
sidelines, could you pick Campo out of a crowd of fifty-something
sportswriters or at a reunion of former Central Connecticut State
shortstops?
</P>
<P>
   Campo's best friend growing up was John Ellis, a member of the
Rangers in the 1970s. To this day, Ellis is considered the toughest
player ever in Arlington, plus he had the ``look.'' If Hollywood
had been asked to cast the head coach of the Cowboys, it would be
John Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jerry Jones gave us Ellis' little pal.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, how has Campo handled the assignment thus far?
</P>
<P>
   ``Flawlessly,'' was the answer from Brad Sham last week in
Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   That's just an opinion, although as a longtime Cowboys radio
voice, Sham speaks with qualifications. He knows where all the
bodies are buried, including his own after Sham once told the truth
(on the air) about a former pseudo head coach.
</P>
<P>
   At Valley Ranch, the football stuff is by far the easiest part
of this job. Between ``handling'' Jones, and the largest army of
media in professional sports, and the largest collection of spoiled
fandom in pro sports, and the blimp-sized egos in the locker room,
Campo can also keep everybody happy by winning a minimum of 12
games a season and going to three Super Bowls in the next four
seasons. Oh, yeah. It'd be best to win at least two of those Super
Bowls. And have a darn good alibi for the third.
</P>
<P>
   Given the job back in January to something less than rave
reviews, Campo has been laying down his head coaching foundation
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Without a game being played, how does Campo currently stack up?
</P>
<P>
   Flawlessly. (There's an echo in here).
</P>
<P>
   Without a game being played, this has been a perfect debut in
all areas. No names, please, but I know one guy who didn't think
Campo should have gotten the job, and now the same guy screams at
peaheads who wonder why Campo doesn't ``look'' like the head coach
of the Cowboys is supposed to look? What does being short and
normal have to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   How tall is short? I don't know. I never asked Campo for his
height when he was defensive coordinator. Why is it important now?
</P>
<P>
   This just in from the Cowboys' media relations department:
</P>
<P>
   Campo is as tall or taller than the winning coaches of the first
four Super Bowls (Lombardi, Lombardi, Ewbank and Stram).
</P>
<P>
   This just in from Troy Aikman:
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you read the new book about Lombardi?''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read it. Part of it ties in with what Dave is going through.
It took Lombardi forever to get his first head coaching job because
it was said he didn't project the presence of a head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Campo?
</P>
<P>
   ``He has established himself as the leader of this football
team, if that's what you mean,'' Aikman said. ``If we win, Dave is
going to look like a head coach and I'm going to look like a
quarterback. If we don't win, both of us will look like...''
</P>
<P>
   Valid points, Troy.
</P>
<P>
   But while they dress him, groom him and put him in Cadillacs,
Campo just grins, good-naturedly. He also knows what you are
thinking. He knows winning can change your mind, and he knows Brad
Pitt wouldn't survive around here without the winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell me I should now attempt to have the conservative
look of a successful executive,'' said Campo, shrugging. Actually,
it was his kids who ordered dad to ditch the out-of-style eye-wear,
and his wife wanted the shorter hair. The other look was fine for
one of the best defensive coordinators in the NFL. But as the head
coach of the Dallas Cowboys, well...
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing, however, is changing about me,'' Campo said. ``I'm
always going to be the same ol' guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Attaboy, coach. Stand tall.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
