<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-WATKINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARELY USED RULE SETS NASCAR LINEUP AT WATKINS GLEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Bobby Labonte has the pole. Brett Bodine
figures he and Scott Pruett got the shaft.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Winston Cup interlopers Ron Fellows and Todd Bodine
landed two controversial starting spots yesterday at Watkins Glen
International, where a second day of unsettled upstate New York
weather prompted NASCAR to invoke a seldom-used rule to fill out
the grid for today's Global Crossing at The Glen.
</P>
<P>
   Postponed by showers Friday afternoon, Winston Cup pole
qualifying was 11 cars deep yesterday morning when showers began
pelting the back portion of the 2.45-mile, 11-turn road course.
Anticipating a lengthy additional delay, and mindful of a TV
commitment to a Busch North Series race, NASCAR officials canceled
the remainder of Cup qualifying and went to the rulebook.
</P>
<P>
   The starting lineup for today's 90-lap/220.5-mile event was
determined by Section 9-5 of that book. The top 35 positions were
set by car owner's points, meaning native Texan Labonte and points
runner-up Dale Jarrett will be sharing the front row in the cars
owned by Joe Gibbs and Robert Yates, respectively. Section 9-5
provides that the 36th position be awarded to a past Cup champion _
a spot filled by three-time champion Darrell Waltrip for owner Carl
Haas.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Article No. 8 of Section 9-5 provides that the next
positions be assigned according to the random draw for qualifying.
That opened the door for Cup regulars Mike Bliss, Kyle Petty and
Rick Mast, who drives for Texan A.J. Foyt. Also making the cut at
40th via the draw was road-racing specialist Fellows, in a
Chevrolet owned by Cup regular Joe Nemechek, and Busch Grand
National driver Todd Bodine, 43rd and last in the No. 34 I Love NY
Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   Purely by the luck of the draw, Fellows and Todd Bodine knocked
Cup regulars Pruett and Brett Bodine out of the starting lineup.
And neither of the latter was a happy camper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My race team commits to attempt to race every weekend in the
Winston Cup Series,'' said an agitated Bodine, whose wife, Diane,
owns the No. 11 Ralphs Supermarkets Ford Taurus. ``Evidently, that
doesn't mean anything, because there are teams that are going to
start this race that haven't even attempted to make one race this
year. I just do not see the logic in that procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine is 38th in points, having qualified for 16 of 20 races to
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to start this race because I wasn't lucky in
what number I drew in my qualifying order,'' Bodine said outside
his hauler. ``How can luck of the draw override hard work,
determination, dedication and commitment to something?''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine's primary sponsorship reportedly is worth $5 million a
year. That is only half of what Tide reportedly is paying to fund
rookie Pruett in the No. 32 Tide Ford owned by Cal Wells III.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me. I've been here 33 years and I'm out of here,''
said veteran Dave Marcis, who has only qualified for 10 races this
season but was a victim of the draw. ``Cal Wells, what's he got on
the line? He's out of here. I'm sure the CEO or whoever's in charge
of their sponsorship will call up NASCAR next week and ask, `How is
this place run?' I don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Pruett, 39th in points but coming off his first
career top-10 finish at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a rookie, I don't understand all the ins and outs of the
rules,'' Pruett said, ``but I think NASCAR should take a close look
at that rule. If you base it on speed and you're not fast enough to
get into the race, fair enough; you don't deserve to be there. But
if you are fast enough to get into the race and you've been
committed to the sport all year long, and are going to be committed
to the sport like we are for the rest of the season, we shouldn't
be one of those guys going home.''
</P>
<P>
   Road-racing hired guns Boris Said and Brian Simo also were sent
packing. But not before Said, driving a car entered by Cup regular
Jimmy Spencer, vented his frustration to Mike Helton, NASCAR's
senior vice president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mad at NASCAR,'' said Said, who posted the fastest speeds
in both practices in the No. 23 Ford. ``I went up to Mike Helton
and I said, `Hey, you're killing me over here. I've got 300 people
from Federated Auto Parts coming, one of the best sponsors I've
ever had.' They probably made the right decision, but I'm still mad
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton said he understood the angst of the five drivers who will
miss the season's second and final road race.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the procedure is laid out in the rulebook, and everybody
knows going into the year what the procedure is,'' Helton said.
``We tried the best we could to qualify, but circumstances wouldn't
permit us to do that. Then somebody goes home.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that can happen anywhere. We've had our share of
\Rweather\S problems everywhere, including Texas.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
