<SLUG> BC-RAC-IRWINDALE-NHRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWINDALE BREAKS GROUND FOR DRAGSTRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Irwindale is once again Drag City.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 23 years after Irwindale Raceway was closed to make room
for the Miller Brewery, officials of two-year-old Irwindale
Speedway broke ground Saturday for an eighth-mile drag strip that
will be used primarily for National Hot Rod Association junior
dragsters and street-legal cars.
</P>
<P>
   The Irwindale Dragstrip will be the first Southern California
drag racing facility built since 1974 and the first NHRA-sanctioned
facility since the now-defunct Orange County Raceway was
constructed in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of a dream come true for us,'' said Irwindale
Speedway CEO Jim Williams, who was joined at the ground-breaking
ceremony by NHRA founder Wally Parks and other racing dignitaries.
``When we build Irwindale we kind of had something like (a drag
strip) in the back of our minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody asks, 'Is this an afterthought?' It certainly wasn't
an afterthought, we just didn't think we would be able to pull it
off as fast as we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The strip, half the length of the traditional quarter-mile, will
be located on the southeastern corner of the track property. It
will cover roughly 1,400 feet from a burnout area to shutdown area.
The track surface will consist of a 220-foot concrete launching
pad, which is used for increased traction. There will be
grandstands for 1,000 spectators and a timing and scoring tower.
</P>
<P>
   It's expected to be ready by the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's a dream come true,'' Parks said. ``We have waited
so many years to add a drag-racing facility to this part of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we once had about a dozen tracks operating (in the
area), we now have two _ Pomona Raceway and (Los Angeles County
Raceway) in Palmdale. So there is just a tremendous need for young
people who like acceleration racing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Irwindale Dragstrip comes into play. Following
an agreement earlier this year between NHRA, Los Angeles County
Fairplex officials and La Verne city officials, the NHRA
street-legal program will be nonexistent at Pomona Raceway
beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened at Pomona wasn't part of our plan,'' Williams
said. ``It's ironic that they are closing (the street legal
program), so we're going to fill the void.''
</P>
<P>
   And Parks, who founded the Glendora-based NHRA in 1951, doesn't
think using an eighth-mile circuit will hurt. In fact, he thinks it
may enhance the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I approve and am in favor of the eighth-mile racing distance
as opposed to the standard quarter-mile,'' Parks said. ``I think
eighth-mile racing is going to be more and more of a popular form
of competition. And this one at Irwindale will provide our best
chance for a showcase.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-12-00 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000812.0252 </DOCNO>
