A0189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SWM-TRIALS-NYT &LR;      08-12 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWM-TRIALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEUSCHER WINS 200 MEDLEY, AND A SECOND TRIP TO THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ By her sophomore year of high school, Cristina
Teuscher was an elite international swimmer. Her graduation present
in 1996 was a gold medal in the 800-meter freestyle relay at the
Atlanta Olympics. She could have attended any of the major swimming
powers, such as Stanford or Southern Cal, which were more than
willing to give her a full-scholarship ride through college.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Teuscher chose to stay close to home, attending
Columbia University and shelling out $34,000 a year. Do not worry
about cost, her father, Enrique Teuscher, a psychiatrist in New
Rochelle, N.Y., had told her. Just be happy. So she remained close
to her parents, balancing the academic rigors of an Ivy League
education with the demands of a high-level swimming career, minus
the pressures of having to justify her scholarship by leading her
team to national collegiate titles.
</P>
<P>
   She chose a road not often taken in the swimming world, and her
career has benefited demonstrably. Teuscher now has a degree in
psychology, four individual collegiate titles and yet another spot
in the Olympics, having qualified Saturday night for the Summer
Games in Sydney, Australia, by winning the 200-meter individual
medley at the Olympic trials in 2 minutes 13.36 seconds, her career
best by nearly a second. Gabrielle Rose, who competed for Brazil at
the 1996 Games, finished second Saturday night in 2:14.95.
</P>
<P>
   Teuscher had been a favorite last Wednesday in the 400-meter
individual medley, but apparent complacency and tentativeness took
her out of the race immediately and she finished third. Only two
swimmers qualify for the Olympics in each event. Saturday night,
not wearing a high-tech body suit because it constricts her
breaststroke, she swam much more aggressively, drawing away
steadily from her competition and winning by more than a second and
a half, a huge victory in a race that can be decided by hundredths
of a second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to prove to myself that I could get up after
being down,'' the 22-year-old Teuscher said.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 200-meter butterfly, Tom Malchow of St. Paul,
Minn., was nearly a half second faster than his world-record pace
after 150 meters, but he perhaps went out too fast. He still won
easily in 1:56.87, but did not threaten record of 1:55.18. In
finishing second in 1:57.48, 15-year-old Michael Phelps of
Baltimore became the youngest American male swimmer to qualify for
the Olympics since 1932.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can put together two great swims and dominate
this event,'' Malchow said.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Benko of Elkhart, Ind., won the women's 200-meter
freestyle in 2:00.45, ahead of Owen Rada (2:00.54) of Arlington,
Va. In the semifinals of the men's 100-meter freestyle, Neil
Walker, who finished second on Friday in the 100-meter backstroke,
posted the fastest time of 48.55 seconds. Gary Hall Jr., the 1996
Olympic silver medalist, posted the second-fastest time in 48.92
seconds. Hall has been found to have diabetes since the Atlanta
Games, and was an uncertain presence before the trials began. He is
now a serious contender in Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 200 individual medley, Teuscher said that her
choice to remain close to home for college had been long validated
and did not depend on a victory Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see people go off to college and have difficulty balancing
academics and the responsibilities of a college scholarship,''
Teuscher said. ``They are away from home and their defenses are
always up. I'd rather be in a comfortable setting, around people I
know who would give me unconditional love. I could let my guard
down.''
</P>
<P>
   She won the first two collegiate swimming titles for Columbia in
1998, then stunned her competitors by leaving the national meet
early to go home and study. While in school, she trained in the
morning at Columbia with Coach Diana Caskey and in the afternoons
at Lehman College in the Bronx with John Collins, her longtime
coach at the Badger Swim Club in Larchmont. Grants from the United
States Olympic Committee and the national swimming federation
helped defray tuition costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the best of both worlds with a female and male coach,''
the 6-foot-1-inch, 150-pound Teuscher said. ``I hate to generalize,
but a woman coach seems more in tune about how I feel. I'm an
emotional person. John really knew what I needed physically to be
in shape. The mixture was perfect for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Caskey said, ``I think this allowed her to develop her own sense
of self-confidence and maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlanta Games, Teuscher, then 18, said she was in a
``catatonic state,'' unnerved by the crowds of 18,000 people at
Georgia Tech. After winning the 200-meter freestyle at the 1996
trials and finishing second in the 400 freestyle, her best
individual finish at the Olympics was sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was like a scared rabbit,'' Collins said. ``Some people
step up in those kind of situations. With Cristina, it didn't work
that way at all. I'm proud that she was able to recover to get a
gold medal in the relay.''
</P>
<P>
   Attending Columbia provided a sort of protective cocoon, Collins
said, allowing Teuscher to rebuild her confidence and to gain a
broader world view in a rigorous academic environment. Team
swimming was stressed, relieving the pressure of individual
accomplishment. Four years later, she entered the 2000 trials
relaxed and self-assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said I looked like a five-year-old on TV, ready to
cry,'' Teuscher said with a laugh about her performance in Atlanta.
``I felt all the pressure on my shoulders. I think I've learned to
brush that off and just get in the pool and swim. I've definitely
come a long way since then. The secret to it is to be relaxed and
have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   She may have been too relaxed in the 400 individual medley after
a superb early season, Collins said. He said the third-place finish
had the effect of waking up a somnolent Teuscher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she concentrated enough to be to do what she had
to do to win,'' Collins said. ``It was a wakeup call. Everyone
needs that once in a while, but it came at an inopportune time.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday night's race, Teuscher spoke to Jenny Thompson,
a five-time Olympic gold medalist, and to Summer Sanders, who won a
silver medal in the 200 individual medley and a bronze in the 400
at the 1992 Summer Games in Barcelona, Spain. She also covered
herself with ladybug stickers as sort of good-luck charms.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson told her to remain controlled and Sanders said, ``Just
have fun and go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you need to hear that from people beside your family
and coach,'' Teuscher said. ``I was really more aggressive. I
wasn't taking any chances.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
