<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA SHUFFLES ANGELS' LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ With an eye toward beefing up production
against left-handed pitching, Angels manager Mike Scioscia gave his
lineup a good shuffle Saturday night, the most notable change the
shift of third baseman Troy Glaus to the No.2 spot for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll give us a little boost against left-handed pitching,''
Scioscia said before the Angels went up against New York Yankees
lefty Denny Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No.2 hole is a lot different in the American League (which
employs the designated hitter) than it is in the National League
(where pitchers generally bat ninth),'' Scioscia explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, Troy is both a table-setter and a run producer,
and this gets him up there in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, who started the night hitting .273 with a team-leading 32
home runs and 70 RBI, has hit No.6 in the lineup in 102 games, No.5
in eight games and No.4 in three games. But never No.2.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia also shifted right fielder Tim Salmon from the clean-up
spot, where he'd started 108 games, to No.3 for just the third
time, and moved first baseman Mo Vaughn from third to fourth for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get caught up in who's batting fourth, fifth, sixth,
whatever,'' Scioscia said. ``It's who's hitting behind or in front
of someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've struggled a little against left-handers with our run
production.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus, a right-handed batter, has hit lefties well _ .355 going
into Saturday night's game _ and so has center fielder Garret
Anderson, a left-handed batter (.353). But Vaughn was hitting only
.199 against lefties, and Salmon .216.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo isn't close to his recent career numbers against
left-handers,'' said Scioscia, noting that Vaughn hit .336 against
left-handers last year. ``You rarely see that much dropoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to juggle some things.''
</P>
<P>
   STRESS NOT ALL BAD: Disabled Angels left-hander Jarrod Washburn
is treating the diagnosis of his sore left shoulder _ a stress
fracture _ as a good news, bad news situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's welcome news,'' Washburn said. ``No surgery.
The biggest thing was finding out what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn is on the Angels' disabled list for the third time this
season. He came off the DL on Monday night to start against the
Chicago White Sox. By the end of the night he was back on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll be able to come back and help the club this
season,'' said Washburn, who's 7-2 _ tied with reliever Shigetoshi
Hasegawa for most wins on the staff _ with a 3.74 ERA. ``As soon as
the pain goes away the doctors say I can pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, right now I'm pretty much doing nothing. I can't even
play catch yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Tim Belcher is also cautiously optimistic,
explaining, ``I feel like I'm on the mend.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher is disabled because of a strained flexor muscle, which
was operated on in December. He threw well in the bullpen Friday,
said he felt fine Saturday and plans on throwing again before this
evening's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``No date, no time ... we'll see,'' is how the 38-year-old
Belcher left it.
</P>
<P>
   RELIEF HARDER TO COME BY: The loss of Angels reliever Mike
Fuyrie because of inflammation in his right elbow leaves the
bullpen on the wobbly side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big hit,'' Scioscia said of Fuyrie, who faced two
batters Friday night before coming out. ``He's been a pleasant
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuyrie appeared in 25 games and had a 2.28 ERA, best on the
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said the most likely scenario to replace Fuyrie is the
combination of Juan Alvarez, Lou Pote and Eric Weaver, who was
summoned from Triple-A Edmonton to take Fuyrie's spot on the
roster.
</P>
<P>
   TOMMY'S IN TOWN: Former Dodgers manager Tom Lasorda dropped by
the ballpark and had quite a reunion _ in both clubhouses.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, the Angels' manager, and three of his coaches, Mickey
Hatcher, Ron Roenicke and Alfredo Griffin, all played for Lasorda,
and so did Yankees infielder Jose Vizcaino and Yankees coach Willie
Randolph. Lasorda also visited with his longtime pal, Yankees coach
Don Zimmer, and onetime managerial rival Joe Torre, the Yankees'
pilot, as well as former Yankees and Angels great Reggie Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   No word whether Lasorda talked Reggie into playing for the U.S.
Olympic team, which Lasorda will manage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
