<HEADLINE>
RUNNING BACKS ACTIVE IN TROJANS' SCRIMMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC coach Paul Hackett wanted to emphasize the
running game in Saturday's first football scrimmage at UC Irvine,
and if one thing is apparent early, there will be plenty of
substituting in the backfield this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans alternated sophomore Sultan McCullough, junior
Malaefou MacKenzie and senior Petros Papadakis in the 84-play
scrimmage, and each had their moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the deepest position on the team,'' Hackett said.
``We're not going to be a team that has two backs and just plays
two backs. We want to play three guys and hopefully wear a team
down by bringing in a fresh guy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough had 85 yards in 12 carries, including a 48-yard run.
MacKenzie had 35 yards in seven carries while Papadakis had 40
yards in seven carries and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all did well,'' running backs coach Kennedy Pola said.
``That just makes it harder (to pick a starter). But I'm glad to be
going with a full load rather than no depth at all.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough would seem to be the likely starter, but Pola said he
would like to assess the tailbacks after the first two or three
games. And even if McCullough did start, MacKenzie could see more
playing time because of his value as a receiver and power runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy that will play no matter what is Malaefou,'' Pola
said. ``Because he is so key in different personnel (formations).''
</P>
<P>
   Even true freshman Chris Howard played Saturday and had 16 yards
in five carries.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Carson Palmer had a solid scrimmage, completing
eight of 14 passes for 135 yards. Senior Mike Van Raaphorst
completed six of seven passes for 50 yards and a touchdown, while
freshman Matt Cassel of Chatsworth was 4 for 12 for 33 yards with
an interception by sophomore Kevin Arbet.
</P>
<P>
   The scrimmage did seem to raise the stock of several players.
Notably, junior Faasea Mailo seems to have taken the lead over
freshman Jacob Rogers for the starting right tackle position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a heck of a week,'' Hackett said. ``He might have a
little bit of an edge at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   And junior David Newbury is the solid frontrunner in the kicking
battle, after going 4 for 5 in the scrimmage with a long of 47
yards. Freshman John Wall of Birmingham High was 3 for 5 with a
long of 44, and senior David Bell was 1 for 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Newbury took a step ahead,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   If any freshman made an impression, it was strong safety Matt
Grootegoed, who made six tackles, including several hard hits that
drew gasps from the 1,000 or so fans.
</P>
<P>
   Grootegoed knocked Howard out of the game with a strong hit,
although Howard later returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ability to absorb our defense in a week is remarkable,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Many key players did not participate in the scrimmage to nurse
minor injuries, including wide receiver Kareem Kelly, linebacker
Markus Steele, tight end Antoine Harris, strong safety Troy
Polamalu, defensive tackles Ennis Davis and Ryan Nielsen and
defensive end Shamsud-Din Abdul-Shaheed. It's anticipated they will
return Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Zeke Moreno played only one series so Hackett could
look at other players at his position.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive guard Trevor Roberts is expected to be out this week
with a sprained foot. Freshman Lenny Vandermade will fill in until
Roberts returns.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Harris, the tight end position received increased
exposure, as sophomore Doyal Butler and freshmen Gregg Guenther
(Taft) and Alex Holmes (Harvard-Westlake) all caught passes.
Guenther had a scrimmage-high three receptions for 42 yards,
including an 8-yard touchdown pass from Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   In a familiar note to last season, the Trojans had 12
penalties. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
